{"title_page": "Sadiq Khan", "text_new": "{{about|the Mayor of London since 2016|the 18th-century Persian Shah|Sadeq Khan Zand|the suicide bomber|Mohammad Sidique Khan|the 17th-century Sylheti faujdar|Sadeq Khan}}\n{{Pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{short description|Mayor of London and British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = Sadiq Khan\n|image            = Sadiq Khan 2017.jpg\n|caption          = Khan in 2017\n|office           = [[Mayor of London]]\n|deputy           = [[Joanne McCartney]]\n|term_start       = 9 May 2016\n|term_end         =\n|predecessor      = [[Boris Johnson]]\n{{Collapsed infobox section begin|[[Shadow Cabinet]] positions}}\n|office2          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Justice]]<br />[[Shadow Lord Chancellor]]\n|leader2         = [[Ed Miliband]]\n|term_start2     = 8 October 2010\n|term_end2        = 11 May 2015\n|predecessor2    = [[Jack Straw]]\n|successor2      = [[Charles Falconer, Baron Falconer of Thoroton|The Lord Falconer of Thoroton]]\n|office3          = [[Minister for London|Shadow Minister for London]]\n|leader3          = [[Ed Miliband]]\n|term_start3      = 16 January 2013\n|term_end3        = 11 May 2015\n|predecessor3     = [[Tessa Jowell]]\n|successor3      = ''Vacant''\n|office4          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]]\n|leader4          = [[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Ed Miliband]]\n|term_start4      = 14 May 2010\n|term_end4        = 8 October 2010\n|predecessor4     = [[Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis|The Lord Adonis]]\n|successor4       = [[Maria Eagle]]{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n|office5          = [[Minister of State for Transport]]\n|primeminister5   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start5      = 9 June 2009\n|term_end5        = 6 May 2010\n|predecessor5     = The Lord Adonis\n|successor5       = [[Theresa Villiers]]\n|office6          = [[Department for Communities and Local Government|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]\n|primeminister6   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start6      = 5 October 2008\n|term_end6        = 9 June 2009\n|predecessor6     = [[Parmjit Dhanda]]\n|successor6       = [[Shahid Malik]]\n|office7          = [[Chief Whip|Assistant Government Whip]]\n|primeminister7   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|1blankname7      = [[Chief Whip of the Labour Party|Chief Whip]]\n|1namedata7       = [[Geoff Hoon]]\n|term_start7      = 2 July 2007\n|term_end7        = 5 October 2008\n|office8          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]]\n|term_start8     = 5 May 2005\n|term_end8        = 9 May 2016\n|predecessor8    = [[Tom Cox (British politician)|Tom Cox]]\n|successor8     = [[Rosena Allin-Khan]]\n|birth_name       = Sadiq Aman Khan\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1970|10|8}}\n|birth_place      = [[Tooting]], [[London]], England\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Saadiya Ahmed|1994}}\n|children         = 2\n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|nationality      = British\n|alma_mater       = [[University of North London]]<br />[[University of Law]]\n|website          = {{Official website|http://www.sadiq.london/}}\n|awards=[[Nishan-e-Pakistan|Sitara-e-Imtiaz]] (2018)}}\n'''Sadiq Aman Khan''' ({{IPAc-en|s|\u0259|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|k|_|\u02c8|k|\u0251\u02d0|n}}; born 8 October 1970) is a British politician who has served as the [[Mayor of London]] since [[2016 London mayoral election|2016]]. He was previously a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]] from 2005 until 2016. A member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], Khan is on the party's [[soft left]] and has been ideologically characterised as a [[Social democracy|social democrat]]. \n\nBorn in [[Tooting]], [[South London]], to a working-class [[British Pakistanis|British Pakistani]] family, Khan earned a [[law degree]] from the [[University of North London]]. He subsequently worked as a solicitor specialising in human rights issues and chaired the [[Liberty (advocacy group)|Liberty]] advocacy group for three years. Joining the Labour Party, Khan was a [[Councillor]] for the [[London Borough of Wandsworth]] from 1994 to 2006 before being elected MP for [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]]. Under Labour Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]], Khan was appointed [[Department for Communities and Local Government|Minister of State for Communities]] in 2008, later becoming [[Minister of State for Transport]]. A key ally of the next Labour leader, [[Ed Miliband]], he served in [[Shadow Cabinet of Ed Miliband|Miliband's Shadow Cabinet]] as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Justice]], [[Shadow Lord Chancellor]] and [[Minister for London|Shadow Minister for London]].\n\nAs the [[London Labour Party|London Labour]] candidate, Khan was elected Mayor of London at the [[2016 London mayoral election|2016 mayoral election]], defeating [[London Conservatives]] rival [[Zac Goldsmith]] and then resigning as an MP. In office, he has frozen all [[Transport for London|TfL]] fares for [[London Buses|bus]], [[Tramlink|tram]] and single pay-as-you-go [[London Underground|Tube]] and [[Docklands Light Railway|DLR]] travel, introduced the Hopper fare for unlimited bus and tram journeys for an hour, the Toxicity Charge (T-Charge) on older and more polluting vehicles in [[Central London]],<ref name=\"t-charge\">{{cite web|author=Chapman, Ben |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/t-charge-what-is-it-london-emissions-charge-how-affect-will-pay-congestion-car-diesel-a8014976.html |title=T-charge: What is the new London emissions charge and how will it affect you? |work=The Independent |date=23 October 2017 |accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> and the 24/7 [[Ultra Low Emission Zone]] (ULEZ) fee on all but the cleanest vehicles in Central London,<ref name=\"ulez\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/apr/06/london-prepares-for-launch-of-ultra-low-emissions-zone|website=The Guardian|title=London prepares for launch of ultra-low emissions zone|date=6 April 2019|accessdate=18 January 2020|last=Topham|first=Gwyn}}</ref> backed expansion at [[London City Airport]] and [[Gatwick Airport]], and focused on uniting the city's varied communities. He was a vocal supporter of the unsuccessful [[Britain Stronger in Europe]] and [[People's Vote]] campaigns for [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|the UK to remain]] in the [[European Union]] and a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|second referendum]] on [[Brexit]], respectively. As well as having a strained relationship with former Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]], whose [[socialism|socialist]] platform Khan thought unelectable, he attracted international attention for his [[Twitter]] arguments with United States President [[Donald Trump]].\n\nHe has been included in the [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]] list of most influential people in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sadiq Khan: The World's 100 Most Influential People|url=http://time.com/collection/most-influential-people-2018/5217530/sadiq-khan/|website=[[Time 100]]|publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|year=2018|accessdate=22 April 2018|language=en-us}}</ref> Khan has been praised for promoting mutual tolerance among London's varied communities, making transport more accessible, and reducing the number of polluting vehicles in Central London;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cityam.com/sadiq-khans-ulez-charge-cuts-polluting-vehicles-by-over-a-third-and-bags-tfl-51m/|website=CityAM|title=Sadiq Khan's Ulez charge cuts polluting vehicles by over a third and bags TfL \u00a351m|last=Rogers|first=Alexandra|date=17 September 2019|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/futurelondon/cleanair/high-pollution-levels-detected-by-40-of-londons-air-quality-sensor-networks-a4196811.html|website=London Evening Standard|title= London pollution: High levels detected by 40% of capital's air quality sensors|last=Bayley|first=Sian|date=23 July 2019|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> however, he has been criticised for the rise of [[knife crime]] and his response to [[Crime in London]].\n\n==Early life==\nKhan was born on 8 October 1970 at [[St George's Hospital]] in [[Tooting]], [[South London]] to a working-class [[Sunni Muslim]] family.<ref name=\"pugilist\">{{cite web|last1=Eaton|first1=George|title=The pugilist: Sadiq Khan's quest to become mayor of London|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/03/pugilist-sadiq-khan-s-quest-become-mayor-london|work=New Statesman|accessdate=11 March 2016|quote=His grandparents emigrated from India to [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]] following Partition; his parents emigrated from Pakistan to London shortly before his birth.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312070742/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/03/pugilist-sadiq-khan-s-quest-become-mayor-london|archivedate=12 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=observer-20150531>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/31/sadiq-khan-aspiration-labour-leadership-overused-blair|title=Sadiq Khan says 'aspiration' will be Labour leadership race's most overused word|author=Rowena Mason and Simon Hattenstone|newspaper=The Observer|date=31 May 2015|accessdate=1 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150601002649/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/31/sadiq-khan-aspiration-labour-leadership-overused-blair|archivedate=1 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://next.ft.com/content/8c974c8e-1379-11e6-bb40-c30e3bfcf63b|title=Victory for Sadiq Khan highlights tolerant face of London|work=[[Financial Times]]|date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626155723/https://next.ft.com/content/8c974c8e-1379-11e6-bb40-c30e3bfcf63b|archivedate=26 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His grandparents migrated from [[Lucknow]] in [[United Provinces (1937\u201350)|United Provinces]], [[British India]] to [[Pakistan]] following the [[partition of India]] in 1947.<ref name=\"pugilist\"/><ref name=\"London Evening Standard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/sadiq-khan-makes-historic-border-crossing-on-foot-from-india-to-pakistan-a3712026.html|title=Sadiq Khan makes historic border crossing from India to Pakistan on foot|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=6 December 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207035206/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/sadiq-khan-makes-historic-border-crossing-on-foot-from-india-to-pakistan-a3712026.html|archivedate=7 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nHis father Amanullah and mother Sehrun arrived in London from Pakistan in 1968.<ref name=\"London Evening Standard\"/>{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=14}} Khan was the fifth of eight children, seven of whom were boys.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=14}} In London, Amanullah worked as a bus driver and Sehrun as a [[seamstress]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=14\u201315}}<ref name=\"pugilist\"/>\n\n[[File:ErnestBevinSchool.jpg|thumb|left|[[Ernest Bevin College]] in Tooting]]\nKhan and his siblings grew up in a three-bedroom [[council flat]] on the Henry Prince Estate in [[Earlsfield]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=15}} He attended Fircroft Primary School and then [[Ernest Bevin College|Ernest Bevin School]], a local [[comprehensive school|comprehensive]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=15}} Khan studied science and mathematics at [[A-level]], in the hope of eventually becoming a dentist. A teacher recommended that he read law instead, as he had an argumentative personality. The teacher's suggestion, along with the American television programme ''[[L.A. Law]]'', inspired Khan to do so. He read Law at the [[University of North London]] (now [[London Metropolitan University]]).<ref name=\"pugilist\"/> His parents later moved out of their council flat and purchased their own home.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=15}} Like his brothers, Khan was a fan of sport, particularly enjoying football, cricket, and boxing.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=15}}\n\nFrom his earliest years, Khan worked: \"I was surrounded by my mum and dad working all the time, so as soon as I could get a job, I got a job. I got a paper round, a Saturday job\u2014some summers I laboured on a building site.\"<ref name=\"pugilist\"/> The family continues to send money to relatives in Pakistan, \"because we're blessed being in this country.\" He and his family often encountered racism, which led to him and his brothers taking up boxing at the Earlsfield Amateur Boxing Club.<ref name=\"pugilist\"/> While studying for his degree, between the ages of 18 and 21, he had a Saturday job at the [[Peter Jones (department store)|Peter Jones]] department store in [[Sloane Square]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Cooper |first=Goolistan |title=Sadiq Khan recounts life lessons learned working at Chelsea department store |date=1 February 2016 |website=GetWestLondon |url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/news/west-london-news/sadiq-khan-recounts-life-lessons-10811540 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602221552/http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/news/west-london-news/sadiq-khan-recounts-life-lessons-10811540 |archivedate=2 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nBefore entering the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in 2005, Khan practised as a solicitor.<ref name=Grauniard31May15/>\nAfter completing his law degree in 1991, Khan took his [[Law Society]] [[Final examination|finals]] at the [[University of Law|College of Law]] in [[Guildford]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=16}}<ref name=PoliticsCo>{{citation|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/sadiq-aman-khan|title=Sadiq Khan, biography|website=www.politics.co.uk/|date=2015|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604043218/http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/sadiq-aman-khan|archivedate=4 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1994 he married Saadiya Ahmed, who was also a solicitor.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=15}}\n\nIn 1994 he became a trainee solicitor at a firm of solicitors called ''Christian Fisher'';<ref name=Grauniard31May15/> the firm undertook mainly legal aid cases.  The partners were Michael Fisher and [[Louise Christian]].<ref name=LAGDec15/>  Khan became a partner in 1997,<ref name=Grauniard31May15/> and like Christian, specialised in human rights law.<ref name=\"pugilist\" />  When Fisher left in 2002, the firm was renamed ''Christian Khan''.<ref name=Grauniard31May15>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/31/sadiq-khan-london-mayor-tony-blair-aspiration|publisher=The Guardian|title=Sadiq Khan: 'Ruthless? No. Decency can get you to the top in politics'|access-date=25 May 2017|date=31 May 2015|first1=Simon|last1=Hattenstone|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505182605/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/31/sadiq-khan-london-mayor-tony-blair-aspiration|archivedate=5 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=LAGDec15>{{citation|url=http://www.lag.org.uk/magazine/2015/12/claims-that-sadiq-khan\u2019s-former-human-rights-firm-\u2018was-worth-millions\u2019-queried-by-lawyers.aspx|title=Claims that Sadiq Khan's former human rights firm 'was worth millions' queried by lawyers|publisher=Legal Action Group|last1=Bawdon|first1=Fiona|date=December 2015|work=Legal Action magazine|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117214943/http://www.lag.org.uk/magazine/2015/12/claims-that-sadiq-khan%E2%80%99s-former-human-rights-firm-%E2%80%98was-worth-millions%E2%80%99-queried-by-lawyers.aspx|archivedate=17 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=LAGMay15>{{citation|url=http://www.lag.org.uk/magazine/2015/05/dear-sadiq-khan-when-you-left-christian-khan-to-become-an-mp,-you-said-you-could-bring-about-more-change-as-a-politician-than-a-lawyer-what-happened.aspx|publisher=Legal Action Group|title=Dear Sadiq Khan. When you left Christian Khan to become an MP, you said you could bring about more change as a politician than a lawyer. What happened?|last1=Christian|first1=Louise|date=May 2015|work=Legal Action magazine|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626162250/http://www.lag.org.uk/magazine/2015/05/dear-sadiq-khan-when-you-left-christian-khan-to-become-an-mp,-you-said-you-could-bring-about-more-change-as-a-politician-than-a-lawyer-what-happened.aspx|archivedate=26 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Khan left the firm in 2004, after he became the prospective Labour candidate for the [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]] parliamentary constituency.<ref name=Grauniard31May15/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiankhan.co.uk/ViewNews.asp?NewsID=35|title=Departure of Sadiq Khan \u2013 ::Imran Khan and Partners Solicitors, London, UK|author=Imran Khan and Partners Solicitors|publisher=christiankhan.co.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007132021/http://www.christiankhan.co.uk/ViewNews.asp?NewsID=35|archivedate=7 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring his legal career, he acted in actions against [[employment law|employment]] and [[discrimination law]], judicial reviews, inquests, the police, and crime, and was involved in cases including the following:\n* Bubbins vs The United Kingdom (European Court of Human Rights&nbsp;\u2013 shooting of an unarmed individual by police marksmen)<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1468-2230.2006.00583_1.x |title=Bubbins v United Kingdom: Civil Remedies and the Right to Life \u2013 Martin \u2013 2006 beav|publisher=[[Wiley Online Library]]|date=24 February 2006|journal=Modern Law Review|volume=69|issue=2|pages=242\u2013249|first=Neil|last=Martin}}</ref>\n* HSU and Thompson v [[Metropolitan Police Service|Met Police]] (wrongful arrest/police damages)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/law-report-juries-to-be-given-guidance-on-awards-against-police-1281004.html|location=London|work=[[The Independent]]|first1=Paul|last1=Magrath|title=Law report: Juries to be given guidance on awards against police|date=28 February 1997|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206135857/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/law-report-juries-to-be-given-guidance-on-awards-against-police-1281004.html|archivedate=6 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Reeves v Met Police (duty of care to prisoners)<ref>{{cite web|author=Law Lords Department|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199899/ldjudgmt/jd990715/reeves01.htm|title=House of Lords \u2013 Commissioners of Police for the Metropolis v. Reeves (A.P.) (Joint Administratix of the Estate of Martin Lynch, Deceased)|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719062219/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199899/ldjudgmt/jd990715/reeves01.htm|archivedate=19 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Murray v CAB (discrimination)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/uk-workers-go-to-work-when-ill-fewest-sick-days-survey-70-per-cent-a7737031.html|title=Latest British Employment Law News|first=Zlata|last=Rodionova|newspaper=Independent|date=7 June 2011}}</ref>\n* Ahmed v [[University of Oxford]] (racial discrimination against a student)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emplaw.co.uk/content/index?startpage=data/2003733.htm|title=Latest British Employment Law News |publisher=emplaw.co.uk|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n* Dr Jadhav v Secretary of State for Health (racial discrimination in the employment of Indian doctors by the health service)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/rajen/Jadhav-v-SS/index.htm |title=Jadhav v Secretary of State for Health |publisher=Homepage.ntlworld.com |accessdate=7 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024053506/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/rajen/Jadhav-v-SS/index.htm |archivedate=24 October 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* CI Logan v Met Police ([[racial discrimination]])<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3266581.stm|work=BBC News|title=Black officer's 'six figure sum' payout|date=13 November 2003}}</ref>\n* [[Ali Dizaei|Supt Dizaei]] v Met Police (police damages, discrimination)<ref>[[Ali Dizaei]]</ref>\n* Inquest into the death of David Rocky Bennett (use of restraints)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiankhan.co.uk/ViewNews.asp?NewsID=15 |title=David 'Rocky' Bennett Inquiry Report. News from Christian Khan Solicitors, London UK |publisher=Christiankhan.co.uk |date=5 February 2004 |accessdate=7 June 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311181602/http://www.christiankhan.co.uk/ViewNews.asp?NewsID=15 |url-status=live |archivedate=11 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* Lead solicitor on [[List of demonstrations against corporate globalization#2001|Mayday demonstration 2001]] test case litigation ([[Human Rights Act 1998|Human Rights Act]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lexisweb.co.uk/cases/2009/January/Austin-and-another-v-Metropolitan-Police-Commissioner |title=Austin and another v Metropolitan Police Commissioner \u2013 [2009&#93; All ER (D) 227 (Jan) |publisher=Lexisweb.co.uk |date=28 January 2009 |accessdate=7 June 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311181723/http://lexisweb.co.uk/cases/2009/January/Austin-and-another-v-Metropolitan-Police-Commissioner |archivedate=11 March 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* [[Farrakhan v Home Secretary]] (Human Rights Act): in 2001, Khan represented the American [[Nation of Islam]] leader [[Louis Farrakhan]] in the High Court and overturned a ban on him entering the United Kingdom, first imposed in 1986. The government subsequently won on appeal.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=19}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1467587.stm|work=BBC News|title=Farrakhan UK ban overturned|date=31 July 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111054640/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1467587.stm|archivedate=11 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* In February 2000, Khan represented a group of Kurdish actors who were arrested by Metropolitan Police during a rehearsal of the [[Harold Pinter]] play ''[[Mountain Language]]'', securing \u00a3150,000 in damages for the group for their wrongful arrest and the trauma caused by the arrest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/pound150000-for-police-raid-on-kurdish-pinter-play-726752.htm |location=London |work=The Independent |first=Robert |last=Verkaik |title=\u00a3150,000 for police raid on Kurdish Pinter play |date=2 February 2000 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/628257.stm |archivedate=8 November 2012 }}</ref>\n* McDowell and Taylor v Met Police: Leroy McDowell and Wayne Taylor successfully sued the [[Metropolitan Police]] for assault and [[false imprisonment]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/analysis-officers-fear-of-being-branded-racist-has-done-little-to-reduce-bias-over-suspects-608687.html|location=London| work=The Independent|title=Analysis: Officers' fear of being branded racist has done little to reduce bias over suspects|date=8 November 2002}}</ref>\n* Represented [[Maajid Nawaz]], Reza Pankhurst and Ian Nisbet in Egyptian court when they were arrested on charges of trying to revive [[Hizb ut-Tahrir]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/2597335.stm|title=BBC NEWS {{!}} UK {{!}} England {{!}} Egypt trial Britons' case resumes|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2017-06-06|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923101310/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/2597335.stm|archivedate=23 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/2002/10/43243.html|title=6 months since the detention of British men --in Egypt \u2013 UK Indymedia|website=www.indymedia.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-06-06|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806202337/https://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/2002/10/43243.html|archivedate=6 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n===First term: 2005\u20132010===\n[[File:Sadiq Khan, September 2009 cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|Sadiq Khan in 2009]]\nBefore entering Parliament, Khan represented [[Tooting]] as a Councillor for the [[London Borough of Wandsworth]] from 1994 to 2006, and was granted the title of [[Title of honor|Honorary]] [[Alderman]] of [[Wandsworth]] upon his retirement from local politics.<ref>[http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/sadiq-aman-khan http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/sadiq-aman-khan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604043218/http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/sadiq-aman-khan |date=4 June 2016 }}, politics</ref>\n\nIn 2003, [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]] [[Constituency Labour Party]] decided to open its parliamentary selection to all interested candidates, including the incumbent MP since 1974, [[Tom Cox (British politician)|Tom Cox]]. This prompted Cox, then in his mid-70s, to announce his retirement rather than risk de-selection. In the subsequent selection contest, Khan defeated five other local candidates to become Labour's candidate for the seat. He was elected to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]].\n\nKhan was one of the Labour MPs who led the successful opposition to Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]]'s proposed introduction of 90 days' detention without charge for those suspected of terrorism offences.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=20}} In recognition of this, ''[[The Spectator]]''\u2014a right-wing magazine then edited by [[Boris Johnson]]\u2014awarded him the \"Newcomer of the Year Award\" at the 2005 Parliamentarian of the Year Awards.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=20}} The magazine's editorial board stated that he had received the award \"for the tough-mindedness and clarity with which he has spoken about the very difficult issues of Islamic terror\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/archive/features/14489/part_2/parliamentarian-of-the-year.thtml?SelectedIssueDate=19%20November%202005 |date=19 November 2005 |title=Parliamentarian of the Year |work=[[The Spectator]] |accessdate=27 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090616124012/http://www.spectator.co.uk/archive/features/14489/part_2/parliamentarian-of-the-year.thtml?SelectedIssueDate=19%20November%202005 |url-status=dead |archivedate=16 June 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> In August 2006, he was a signatory of an open letter to [[Tony Blair]] that was signed by prominent Muslims and published in ''[[The Guardian]]''. The letter criticised [[Foreign policy of the United Kingdom|UK foreign policy]] and in particular the 2003 invasion of Iraq, stating that Blair's policies had caused great harm to civilians in the Middle East and provided \"ammunition to extremists who threaten us all\".{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Minister criticises Muslim letter |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/4787119.stm |date=12 August 2006 |accessdate=27 March 2009 |work=[[BBC News]] |archivedate=8 November 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108143352/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/4787119.stm |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sadiq Khan and Yasmin Qureshi talk to British troops in Kabul (2473583886).jpg|thumb|left|Khan meeting with British troops stationed in Kabul, Afghanistan in 2008]]\n\nKhan had to repay \u00a3500 in [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|expenses]] in 2007 in relation to a newsletter sent to constituents featuring a 'Labour rose', which was deemed to be unduly prominent. While the content of the newsletter was not deemed to be party political, the rose logo was found to be unduly prominent which may have had the effect of promoting a political party. There was no suggestion that Khan had deliberately or dishonestly compiled his [[Expense management|expenses claims]], which were not explicitly disallowed under the rules at that time. The rules were retrospectively changed disallowing the claim, which had previously been approved by the House of Commons authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200708/cmselect/cmstnprv/182/182.pdf|title=Microsoft Word \u2013 Baker-Bruce-Khan \u2013 CRC Rep.doc|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013064730/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200708/cmselect/cmstnprv/182/182.pdf|archivedate=13 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/london/7142779.stm |title=Minister's rose emblem broke rule |work=BBC News |date=13 December 2007 |accessdate=15 December 2010 |url-status=live |archivedate=17 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101017175350/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/london/7142779.stm |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 3 February 2008, ''[[The Sunday Times]]''<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Gillard|author2=Jonathan Calvert|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/crime/article3295393.ece|title=Police bugged Muslim MP Sadiq Khan|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=3 February 2008|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516004326/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/crime/article3295393.ece|archivedate=16 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> claimed that a conversation between Khan and prisoner [[Babar Ahmad]]&nbsp;\u2013 a constituent accused of involvement in terrorism&nbsp;\u2013 at [[Woodhill Prison]] in [[Milton Keynes]] had been [[bugging|bugged]] by the [[Metropolitan Police Anti-Terrorist Branch]].<ref name=kwbi>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7224786.stm |title=Khan welcomes 'bugging' inquiry |work=BBC News |date=3 February 2008 |accessdate=7 June 2011 |archivedate=25 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325035405/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7224786.stm |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> An inquiry was launched by the [[Secretary of State for Justice|Justice Secretary]], [[Jack Straw]].<ref name=kwbi/> There was concern that the bugging contravened the [[Wilson Doctrine]] that police should not bug MPs. The report concluded that the doctrine did not apply because it affected only bugging requiring approval by the Home Secretary, while in Khan's case the monitoring was authorised by a senior police officer.  The Home Secretary, [[Jacqui Smith]], then announced a further policy review and said the bugging of discussions between MPs and their constituents should be banned.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/feb/22/uksecurity.police?gusrc=rss&feed=uknews |title=Bugging of MP on prison visit did not break the rules, inquiry finds |first=Vikram |last=Dodd |date=22 February 2008 |accessdate=4 July 2009 |location=London |newspaper=The Guardian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831203539/http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2008/feb/22/uksecurity.police?gusrc=rss&feed=uknews |archivedate=31 August 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, Blair stood down as both Prime Minister and Labour Party leader, to be replaced by [[Gordon Brown]]. Brown thought highly of Khan, who moved up the parliamentary ranks under Brown's Premiership.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}} Brown made Khan a party whip, who was therefore charged with ensuring that Labour-sponsored legislation made it through the parliamentary process to become law.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}} In July 2008, Khan helped push through a government proposal to permit the detention of those suspected of terror offenses for 42 days without charge.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}} For his part in this, Khan was criticised by Liberty's [[Shami Chakrabarti]] and others, who claimed that Khan had contravened his principles on civil liberties issues.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}}\n\n[[File:Rt Hon Sadiq Khan MP at Has Labour lost the plot on crime?.jpg|thumb|right|<center>Sadiq Khan speaking in 2011</center>]]\n\nOn Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]]'s [[Cabinet reshuffle]] of 3 October 2008, Khan was appointed [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] [[Department for Communities and Local Government|for Communities and Local Government]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}}<ref name=PUSSCALG>{{citation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081126155329/http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/corporate/pdf/707527.pdf|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/corporate/pdf/707527.pdf|title=Ministerial Team|publisher=[[Department for Communities and Local Government]]|website=www.communities.gov.uk|archive-date=26 November 2008<!-- archive date guessed from URL -->|url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=theyworkforyou>{{citation|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/11878/sadiq_khan/tooting#profile|title=Sadiq Khan, Former MP, Tooting, profile|publisher=TheyWorkForYou|website=www.theyworkforyou.com|access-date=21 May 2017|df=dmy|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525055553/https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/11878/sadiq_khan/tooting#profile|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\nIn 2008, the [[Fabian Society]] published Khan's book, ''Fairness Not Favours''. In this work, Khan argued that the Labour Party had to reconnect with British Muslims, arguing that it had lost the trust of this community as a result of the [[Iraq War]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=27\u201328}} He also said that British Muslims had their own part to play in reconnecting with politicians, arguing that they needed to rid themselves of a [[victim mentality]] and take greater responsibility for their own community.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=28}} In the House of Commons in January 2009, Khan criticised [[Pope Benedict XVI]] for the rehabilitation of [[Richard Williamson (bishop)|Bishop Richard Williamson]] following his remarks about [[the Holocaust]], a move he described as \"highly unsavoury\" and of \"great concern\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Prince |first=Rosa |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/4388359/Minister-criticises-Pope-for-pardoning-Holocaust-denial-bishop.html |title=Minister criticises Pope for pardoning Holocaust denial bishop |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=29 January 2009 |accessdate=29 January 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114024511/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/4388359/Minister-criticises-Pope-for-pardoning-Holocaust-denial-bishop.html |archivedate=14 November 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009 he was promoted to [[Minister of State for Transport]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=28}}<ref name=theyworkforyou/><ref>{{cite news |first=Eleanor |last=Harding |title=Tooting MP Sadiq Khan named first Muslim cabinet minister in Gordon Brown's reshuffle |url=http://www.wandsworthguardian.co.uk/news/4424355.Sadiq_Khan_named_first_Muslim_cabinet_minister/ |work=The Wandsworth Guardian |date=6 June 2009 |accessdate=6 June 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090609074816/http://www.wandsworthguardian.co.uk/news/4424355.Sadiq_Khan_named_first_Muslim_cabinet_minister/ |archivedate=9 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In what was believed to be a first for an MP, Khan used his Twitter account to self-announce his promotion.<ref>{{cite web |last=Banerjee |first=Subhajit |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/scienceandtechnology/technology/twitter/5467688/MP-Sadiq-Khan-announces-his-Transport-Minister-appointment-on-Twitter.html |title=Minister appointment on Twitter |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=7 June 2009 |accessdate=7 June 2011 |url-status=live |archivedate=11 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611012324/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/scienceandtechnology/technology/twitter/5467688/MP-Sadiq-Khan-announces-his-Transport-Minister-appointment-on-Twitter.html |df=dmy }}</ref>  Though Khan was not a member of the [[Brown ministry|cabinet]], he attended meetings for agenda items covering his policy area,<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/politics/domestic_politics/factcheck%2Ban%2Ballwhite%2Bcabinet/3394202.html|title=FactCheck: an all-white cabinet?|date=20 October 2009|author=By Channel 4 News|publisher=Channel 4|access-date=21 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131125170053/http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/politics/domestic_politics/factcheck%2ban%2ballwhite%2bcabinet/3394202.html|archivedate=25 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> thus becoming the first Muslim to sit in on the British Cabinet.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=28}} As Transport Minister, Khan supported plans to expand [[Heathrow Airport]] with [[Expansion of Heathrow Airport|the addition of a third runway]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=30}}\n\nDuring this period, Khan served as chairman of the socialist [[Fabian Society]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fabians.org.uk/executive-committee-mainmenu-64/executive-committee |title=Executive Committee \u2013 The Fabian Society \u2013 where the British left thinks |publisher=Fabians.org.uk |accessdate=7 June 2011 |url-status=live |archivedate=11 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011113227/http://www.fabians.org.uk/executive-committee-mainmenu-64/executive-committee |df=dmy }}</ref> remaining on its Executive Committee. In 2009, he won the Jenny Jeger Award (''Best Fabian Pamphlet'') for his writing \"Fairness not Favours: How to re-connect with British Muslims\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fabians.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/FairnessNotFavours.pdf|title=Fairness not Favours How to reconnect with British Muslims (full text)|first1=Sadiq|last1=Khan|first2=Hannah|last2=Jameson|first3=Sunder|last3=Katwala|year=2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029020452/https://www.fabians.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/FairnessNotFavours.pdf|archivedate=29 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/sep/17/religion.islam|title=Fairness, not favours, for Muslims (opinion)|first1=Sadiq|last1=Khan|work=The Guardian|year=2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219223931/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/sep/17/religion.islam|archivedate=19 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, Khan publicly stated that for a second successive year he would not be taking a pay rise as an MP or Minister, declaring \"At a time when many people in Tooting and throughout the country are having to accept pay freezes I don't think it's appropriate for MPs to accept a pay rise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/minister-all-mps-should-give-up-their-1000-pay-rise-6707031.html |title=Minister: All MPs should give up their \u01411,000 pay rise |newspaper=London Evening Herald |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=7 June 2011 |url-status=live |archivedate=24 October 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024103045/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/minister-all-mps-should-give-up-their-1000-pay-rise-6707031.html |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Second and third term: 2010\u20132016===\nIn [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]], Khan was re-elected as the MP for Tooting despite a swing against his [[Labour Party (UK)|party]] of 3.6% and a halving of his previous majority.<ref>https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/rivals-attack-nasty-campaign-as-sadiq-khan-survives-6466885.html</ref> His campaign in Tooting had been supported by [[Harris Bokhari]], who reportedly used anti-Ahmadiyya sentiment to mobilise Muslim voters at a mosque in Tooting to vote for Khan instead of the rival [[Ahmadiyya]] candidate, Nasser Butt.<ref name=newyorker>https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/07/31/sadiq-khan-takes-on-brexit-and-terror; https://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/8451614.election-race-infected-by-anti-ahmadiyya-hate-campaign/</ref> In 2019, Bokhari was appointed to join Khan's new Diversity, Equality and Inclusion Advisory Group.<ref>https://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/debbie-weekes-bernard-chair-new-board-inequality</ref> In the subsequent [[2010 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election]] Khan was an early backer of [[Ed Miliband]], becoming his [[campaign manager]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Harding |first=Eleanor |place=Wandsworth |url=http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/local/wandsworthnews/8167355.EXCLUSIVE___I_m_backing_Ed___says_MP_Khan/ |title=EXCLUSIVE: 'I'm backing Ed Miliband', says Sadiq Khan MP |newspaper=[[Your Local Guardian]] |date=15 May 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315074031/http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/local/wandsworthnews/8167355.EXCLUSIVE___I_m_backing_Ed___says_MP_Khan |archivedate=15 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> In the wake of Labour's [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 election defeat]], Acting Leader [[Harriet Harman]] appointed Khan [[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Exclusive: 'Bitter-sweet' promotion for Sadiq Khan MP |date=14 May 2010 |work=Wandsworth Guardian |url=http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/local/wandsworthnews/8167341.EXCLUSIVE___Bitter_sweet__promotion_for_Sadiq_Khan_MP/ |accessdate=17 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301145559/http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/local/wandsworthnews/8167341.EXCLUSIVE___Bitter_sweet__promotion_for_Sadiq_Khan_MP/ |url-status=live |archivedate=1 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Khan orchestrated [[Ed Miliband]]'s successful campaign to become Labour leader,{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=29}} and was appointed to the senior roles of [[Shadow Lord Chancellor]] and [[Shadow Secretary of State for Justice|Shadow Justice Secretary]].<ref name=\"parliament.uk\">{{cite web|title=Rt Hon Sadiq Khan|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/sadiq-khan/1577|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=11 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707033528/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/sadiq-khan/1577|archivedate=7 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ed Miliband conference speech in Manchester, September 2010.jpeg|250px|left|thumb|Khan orchestrated Ed Miliband's successful campaign to become Labour Leader and later served in Miliband's Shadow Cabinet.]]\n\nIn April 2010 it was revealed that Khan had repaid falsely claimed expenses on two occasions, when literature was sent to his constituents. The first incident concerned letters sent out before the 2010 General Election which were ruled to have the \"unintentional effect of promoting his return to office\", the second a \u00a32,550 repayment for Christmas, [[Eid al-Fitr|Eid]], and birthday cards for constituents, dating back to 2006.<ref>{{cite news|location=London |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7579476/General-election-2010-Transport-minister-Sadiq-Khan-in-election-expenses-row.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=General election 2010: Transport minister Sadiq Khan in election expenses row |last=Kirkup |first=James |date=12 April 2010 |accessdate=25 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123210912/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7579476/General-election-2010-Transport-minister-Sadiq-Khan-in-election-expenses-row.html |url-status=live |archivedate=23 November 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Under House of Commons rules, pre-paid envelopes and official stationery can only be used for official parliamentary business.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/8192570/MPs-expenses-17-MPs-were-re-elected-after-secret-deals-on-expenses.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Martin |last=Beckford |title=MPs' expenses: 17 MPs were re-elected after secret deals on expenses |date=9 December 2010 |accessdate=11 December 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113022531/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/8192570/MPs-expenses-17-MPs-were-re-elected-after-secret-deals-on-expenses.html |archivedate=13 November 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/8192581/MPs-expenses-the-secret-deals-revealed.html |first=Martin |last=Beckford |title=MPs' expenses: the secret deals revealed |date=10 December 2010 |accessdate=11 December 2010 |archivedate=14 December 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101214062821/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/8192581/MPs-expenses-the-secret-deals-revealed.html |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/dec/09/secretly-resolved-mps-expenses-cases-made-public |location=London |work=The Guardian |title='Secretly' resolved MPs' expenses cases made public |date=9 December 2010 |accessdate=11 December 2010 |archivedate=13 December 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101213011233/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2010/dec/09/secretly-resolved-mps-expenses-cases-made-public |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> Khan's claim for the greetings cards was initially rejected, but he presented a new invoice no longer identifying the nature of the claim, and this was accepted. Khan attributed the improper claim for the cards to \"inexperience\" and human error and apologised for breaking the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|expenses rules]].<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7063316.ece|location=London|work=The Times|first=David|last=Brown|title=Transport Minister Sadiq Khan repays 2500 wrongly claimed on expenses|date=16 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8569397.stm |work=BBC News |title=Minister repays \u00a32,500 expenses |date=15 March 2010 |accessdate=15 December 2010 |url-status=live |archivedate=23 March 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323063009/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8569397.stm |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn early 2013, Miliband appointed Khan as the [[Shadow Minister for London]], a position that he held in addition to his other responsibilities.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=31}}<ref name=\"parliament.uk\" /> In December 2013, the Fabian Society published a collection of essays edited by Khan that was titled ''Our London''.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=31}} Khan was also tasked with overseeing Labour's campaign for the [[2014 London local elections]],{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=30}} in which the party advanced its control in the city, gaining hold of twenty of the thirty-two boroughs.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=32}} By this point, there was much talk of Khan making a bid for the London Mayoralty in 2016, when incumbent Mayor Boris Johnson would be stepping down.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=31}} His options were affected by the outcome of the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]; if Labour won, then he would be expected to become a government minister, but if they lost then he would be free to pursue the Mayoralty.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=31}} In December 2015, Khan voted against the Cameron government's plans to expand the bombing of targets in the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=96}}\n\nPolls had suggested that Labour could be the largest party in a [[hung parliament]] following the 2015 general election, but ultimately the Conservatives secured victory.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=32\u201333}} In the vote, Khan was returned for a third term as MP for Tooting, defeating his Conservative rival by 2,842 votes.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=33}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wandsworth.gov.uk/info/200327/election_results/1991/parliamentary_election_results_may_2015/3|title=Tooting Constituency \u2013 Parliamentary election results May 2015|publisher=Wandsworth Council|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416175632/https://www.wandsworth.gov.uk/info/200327/election_results/1991/parliamentary_election_results_may_2015/3|archivedate=16 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was one of 36 [[List of Labour Party (UK) MPs|Labour MPs]] to nominate [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as a [[Endorsements in the 2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|candidate]] in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election of 2015]], but has said that he was \"no patsy\" to Corbyn and would stand up to him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-leadership-election|title=Who nominated who for the 2015 Labour leadership election?|work=New Statesman|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705074349/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-leadership-election|archivedate=5 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35412680|title=Londoners should not let Corbyn 'experiment' with city \u2013 PM|work=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204044633/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35412680|archivedate=4 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He later stated that he nominated Corbyn to \"broaden the debate\" but did not then vote for him.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why won't Labour's Sadiq Khan say he supports Jeremy Corbyn? |last=Deacon |first=Michael |date=4 April 2016 |website=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/04/why-wont-labours-sadiq-khan-say-he-supports-jeremy-corbyn/ |ref=harv |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611113423/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/04/why-wont-labours-sadiq-khan-say-he-supports-jeremy-corbyn/ |archivedate=11 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2016, Khan resigned as an MP by his appointment to the ancient office of [[Chiltern Hundreds|Crown Steward and Bailiff of The Three Chiltern Hundreds]], a customary practice in the UK. This triggered a by-election in [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]] to be held in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2016/may/sadiq-khan-resigns-as-mp-for-tooting/|title=Sadiq Khan resigns as MP for Tooting|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]|date=10 May 2016|accessdate=10 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511133538/http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2016/may/sadiq-khan-resigns-as-mp-for-tooting/|archivedate=11 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Simon|first1=Harris|title=Sadiq Khan resigns triggering Tooting by-election|url=http://www.itv.com/news/london/update/2016-05-09/sadiq-khan-resigns-triggering-tooting-by-election/|website=ITV News|publisher=ITV News|accessdate=9 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511131758/http://www.itv.com/news/london/update/2016-05-09/sadiq-khan-resigns-triggering-tooting-by-election/|archivedate=11 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe is regularly named among the Top 100 [[Politics of England#Greater London Authority|London politicians]] in the ''[[London Evening Standard]]''{{'}}s annual poll of the 1,000 most influential Londoners<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=7 June 2011 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/standard-home/londons-1000-most-influential-people-2010-politics-6536029.html |title=London's 1000 most influential people 2010: Politics |newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=26 November 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024200001/http://www.standard.co.uk/standard-home/londons-1000-most-influential-people-2010-politics-6536029.html |url-status=live |archivedate=24 October 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> and is an Ambassador for [[Mosaic Network]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mosaicnetwork.co.uk/about/our-supporters/ambassadors|title=Ambassadors|work=Mosaic|accessdate=7 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508081539/http://www.mosaicnetwork.co.uk/about/our-supporters/ambassadors/|archivedate=8 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> an initiative set up by [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]].\n\n==Mayor of London==\nIn 2016, Sadiq Khan ran to become the [[mayor of London]] and was elected with 57% of the vote. He is London's first Muslim mayor and first [[ethnic minority]] mayor.<ref name=\"khaleeli\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/06/sadiq-khan-victory-islamophobia-mayor-london|title=Sadiq Khan's victory won't end Islamophobia, but it offers hope|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Homa Khaleeli|date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204052217/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/06/sadiq-khan-victory-islamophobia-mayor-london|archivedate=4 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Khan was officially sworn in as Mayor in a multi-faith ceremony held in [[Southwark Cathedral]] the following day.<ref name=\"warmwelcome\"/> His first act as mayor was his appearance at a [[Holocaust]] memorial ceremony in a rugby stadium in North London,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish/news/1.718546|title=Sadiq Khan Attends Holocaust Memorial as First Official Mayoral Act|work=Haaretz|accessdate=9 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508214236/http://www.haaretz.com/jewish/news/1.718546|archivedate=8 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> although due to delays with the results of the election, he officially took office on 9 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1691893/sadiq-khan-vows-to-be-mayor-for-all-londoners|title=Sadiq Khan Vows To Be 'Mayor For All Londoners'|publisher=Sky News|date=7 May 2016|accessdate=9 May 2016|quote=But because of the processes involved, he won't be technically in office until just after midnight on Monday.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509012751/http://news.sky.com/story/1691893/sadiq-khan-vows-to-be-mayor-for-all-londoners|archivedate=9 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n===2016 candidacy===\n{{Main|2016 London mayoral election}}\n\n{{Quote box|width=25em||align=right|quote=\"An affordable and secure home to rent or buy, more jobs with higher wages for the lowest paid, making it easier to set up and run a successful business, reducing the cost of commuting, and making London's environment safer, healthier and less polluted.\"|source=Khan's priorities as Mayor.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=74\u201375}}}}\n\n====Nomination as Labour candidate====\nAfter Labour's defeat at the 2015 general election, Khan resigned from the Shadow Cabinet.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=35}} He then announced himself as a candidate to be the Labour nominee for the London Mayoral elections of 2016.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=35}} Khan soon gained the support of prominent figures in the party, including former Mayor of London [[Ken Livingstone]], who was on Labour's leftist, socialist wing, and [[Oona King]], who was on its centrist, [[Blairism|Blairite]] wing.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=37\u201339}}  He also received the backing of the Labour-affiliated [[GMB (trade union)|GMB]] and [[Unite the Union|Unite]] unions,{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=40}} and the nomination of 44 of Labour's 73 parliamentary constituent parties in London, leaving him as one of the top two contenders.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=40}}\n\nKhan's main rival was Conservative candidate [[Zac Goldsmith]]; Khan described him as a spoiled dilettante who \"never finishes anything he starts\".{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=103}} A [[YouGov]] poll for [[LBC]] suggested that while the other main contender to be the Labour nominee, [[Tessa Jowell]], would defeat Goldsmith in a mayoral election, Khan would not.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=62}} In hustings, Khan placed an emphasis on his working-class origins, which would play against Jowell's wealthier upbringing, and argued for the need for change in London, thereby insinuating that Jowell would represent too much continuity with the outgoing Johnson administration.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=42\u201343}} In September 2015, Khan was announced as the winning nominee.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=73\u201374}} He gained 48,152 votes (58.9%) against Jowell's 35,573 (41.1%).{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=73\u201374}}<ref name=\"Lab elects\">{{cite web|last1=Wintour|first1=Patrick|title=Sadiq Khan elected as Labour's candidate for mayor of Londo|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/sep/11/sadiq-khan-elected-as-labours-candidate-for-mayor-of-london|work=The Guardian|accessdate=11 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911222641/http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/sep/11/sadiq-khan-elected-as-labours-candidate-for-mayor-of-london|archivedate=11 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was the favourite candidate in all three voting categories; Labour Party members, members of affiliated trade unions and organisations, and registered supporters who had paid \u00a33 in order to vote.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=74}}\n\n====Campaign====\nKhan vowed that if elected, he would freeze public transport fares in London for four years.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=103}}<ref name=\"Evening Standard\">{{cite web|title=Sadiq Khan pledges four-year freeze of all fares if elected Mayor|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-pledges-fouryear-freeze-of-all-fares-if-elected-mayor-a3111856.html|work=London Evening Standard|accessdate=11 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115173321/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-pledges-fouryear-freeze-of-all-fares-if-elected-mayor-a3111856.html|archivedate=15 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He claimed that this would deprive [[Transport for London]] (TfL) of \u00a3452 million, but TfL stated that it would deprive them of \u00a31.9 billion, taking into account projected population growth over this period.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=127\u2013128}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-35443206|title=Sadiq Khan's fare freeze would cost \u00a31.9bn, says TfL|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408090139/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-35443206|archivedate=8 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Although he had previously backed Heathrow expansion, he now opposed it, instead calling for expansion at [[Gatwick Airport]]; he was likely aware that supporting the former was a vote loser in London.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=47}} Aware of the severe housing shortage in London, he also spoke of clamping down on foreign property investors,{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=52\u201353}} and proposed the establishment of both a \"London living rent\" tenure and a not-for-profit lettings agency that could undercut commercial operators in order to ease the high cost of renting in the city.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=53}} He also called for house building on land owned by TfL, insisting that at least 50% of those constructed should be \"genuinely affordable\".{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=131\u2013133}}\n\nThe YouGov poll had revealed that 31% of Londoners stated that they would not be \"comfortable\" with a Muslim mayor.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=62}} Aware that many voters were suspicious regarding the loyalties of British Muslims to the British state, Khan emphasised his commitment to liberal social values.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=82}} As part of this, he declared his opposition to [[homophobia]],{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=83}} and said that he would have \"zero tolerance for anti-Semitism\".{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=82\u201383}} He openly condemned Islamic extremism and called on the Muslim community to take a leading role in combating it, although at the same time acknowledged the [[Islamophobia]] that many British Muslims faced.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=94\u201395}} He also distanced himself from Corbyn,{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=81\u201382}} rebuking Labour's socialist leader for his links to armed anti-Israel groups,{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=79\u201380}} and criticising him for not singing the [[God Save the Queen|national anthem]] at an event commemorating the [[Battle of Britain]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=79}} Concerned that Corbyn's socialist platform was alienating many of London's businesses, Khan declared that he would be \"the most pro-business mayor ever\",{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=84}} and met with groups such as the [[Federation of Small Businesses]] and [[City of London Corporation]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=109}} He also ensured that his campaign was run entirely separate from Corbyn.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=116\u2013117}} Conversely, Goldsmith's Conservative campaign emphasised connections between Khan and Corbyn.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=98}} Both the Conservative campaign and several Conservative-aligned newspapers sought to tar Khan as an apologist for, or even sympathiser with, Islamic extremism.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=93}}\n\nInternational press sources often focused on his religious identity,<ref>{{cite news |last=Henley |first=Jon |title=Global press reaction to Sadiq Khan a mix of curiosity and ignorance |date=6 May 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/06/london-mayor-global-press-reaction-sadiq-khan-curiosity-ignorance |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103095517/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/06/london-mayor-global-press-reaction-sadiq-khan-curiosity-ignorance |archivedate=3 January 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> with many right-wing American media outlets reacting with horror at his election.<ref>{{cite news |last=Millward |first=David |date=7 May 2016 |title=Sadiq Khan's victory as London Mayor alarms American right as US liberals say result will resonate far beyond City Hall |website=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/07/sadiq-khans-victory-as-london-mayor-alarms-american-right-as-us/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707035448/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/07/sadiq-khans-victory-as-london-mayor-alarms-american-right-as-us/ |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nKhan won the election with 57% of the vote. The 1.3 million votes he received are the largest any UK politician has personally received to date.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Sadiq Khan won the London mayoral election|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/05/how-sadiq-khan-won-london-mayoral-election|publisher=[[New Statesman]]}}</ref> Various press sources noted that Khan's election made him the first actively affiliated Muslim to become mayor of a major Western capital.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|last1=James|first1=William|last2=Piper|first2=Elizabeth|title=Labour's Khan becomes first Muslim mayor of London after bitter campaign|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-britain-politics-election-london-idUKKCN0XX1W4|accessdate=7 May 2016|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507140517/http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-britain-politics-election-london-idUKKCN0XX1W4|archivedate=7 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"warmwelcome\">{{cite web |last1=Hooper |first1=Ryan |last2=Hughes |first2=David |title=Warm Welcome as Sadiq Khan is Sworn in as Mayor of London |date=7 May 2016 |url=http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/warm-welcome-as-sadiq-khan-is-sworn-in-as-mayor-of-london/ar-BBsK5SB?ocid=spartanntp |website=Press Association |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602141517/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/warm-welcome-as-sadiq-khan-is-sworn-in-as-mayor-of-london/ar-BBsK5SB?ocid=spartanntp |archivedate=2 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n[[File:London mayoral election by borough 2016 map.png|thumb|right|Map of Greater London boroughs showing those that voted for Khan (red) and Goldsmith (blue) in the 2016 mayoral election]]\n\n===Mayoralty===\nIn the buildup to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum on the UK's continuing membership]] of the [[European Union]] (EU), Khan was a vocal supporter of the 'Remain' camp.<ref>{{cite news |website=The Telegraph |date=9 June 2016 |title=Sadiq Khan warns Labour has a 'responsibility' to win EU referendum remain vote |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/08/sadiq-khan-warns-labour-has-a-responsibility-to-win-eu-referendu/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615071545/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/08/sadiq-khan-warns-labour-has-a-responsibility-to-win-eu-referendu/ |archivedate=15 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He agreed to attend a [[Britain Stronger in Europe]] campaign event with the Conservative Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] to demonstrate cross-party support for remaining within the EU,<ref>{{cite news |last=Sparrow |first=Andrew |title=David Cameron and Sadiq Khan plan pro-EU joint appearance |website=The Guardian |date=30 May 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/29/david-cameron-and-sadiq-khan-plan-pro-eu-joint-appearance |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160904042739/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/29/david-cameron-and-sadiq-khan-plan-pro-eu-joint-appearance |archivedate=4 September 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=PM hails 'extraordinary coalition' as he joins Sadiq Khan in EU campaign |website=Business Insider |date=31 May 2016 |url=http://business-reporter.co.uk/2016/05/31/pm-hails-extraordinary-coalition-joins-sadiq-khan-eu-campaign/#sthash.eufpzs2X.dpuf |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601150311/http://business-reporter.co.uk/2016/05/31/pm-hails-extraordinary-coalition-joins-sadiq-khan-eu-campaign/#sthash.eufpzs2X.dpuf |archivedate=1 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> for which he was criticised by Labour Shadow Chancellor [[John McDonnell (politician)|John McDonnell]], who claimed that sharing a platform with the Conservatives \"discredits us\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Hughes |first=Laura |title=Labour splits as John McDonnell attacks Sadiq Khan for sharing a platform with David Cameron |website=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/31/labour-splits-as-john-mcdonnell-attacks-sadiq-khan-for-sharing-a/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704214127/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/31/labour-splits-as-john-mcdonnell-attacks-sadiq-khan-for-sharing-a/ |archivedate=4 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> After the murder of MP [[Jo Cox]] during the campaign, Khan called for the country to \"pause and reflect\" on the manner in which the Leave and Remain camps had been approaching the debate, stating that it had been marred by a \"climate of hatred, of poison, of negativity, of cynicism\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Mason |first=Rowena |date=17 June 2016 |title=Sadiq Khan calls for more respectful tone in EU referendum debate |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/17/sadiq-khan-calls-for-more-respectful-tone-in-eu-referendum-debate |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126142410/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/17/sadiq-khan-calls-for-more-respectful-tone-in-eu-referendum-debate |archivedate=26 November 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the success of the 'Leave' vote, Khan insisted that all EU citizens living in London were welcome in the city and that he was grateful for the contribution that they made to it.<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnston |first=Chris |website=The Guardian |date=25 June 2016 |title=Sadiq Khan tells London's Europeans they remain welcome |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/25/sadiq-khan-tells-londons-europeans-they-remain-welcome |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160824045529/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/25/sadiq-khan-tells-londons-europeans-they-remain-welcome |archivedate=24 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Elledge |first=Jonn |date=24 June 2016 |title=London mayor Sadiq Khan to EU citizens: \"You are welcome here\" |website=City Metric |url=http://www.citymetric.com/politics/london-mayor-sadiq-khan-eu-citizens-you-are-welcome-here-2201 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625123521/http://www.citymetric.com/politics/london-mayor-sadiq-khan-eu-citizens-you-are-welcome-here-2201 |archivedate=25 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He endorsed the Metropolitan Police's 'We Stand Together' campaign to combat the rise in racial abuse following the referendum,<ref>{{cite news |last=Sleigh |first=Sophia |title=Sadiq Khan launches crackdown on Brexit vote hate crime |date=8 July 2016 |website=London Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-launches-crackdown-on-brexit-vote-hate-crime-a3291331.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714234210/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-launches-crackdown-on-brexit-vote-hate-crime-a3291331.html |archivedate=14 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and later backed the 'London is Open' campaign to encourage businesses, artists, and performers to continue coming to the city despite Brexit.<ref>{{cite news |last=Razaq |first=Rashid |date=22 July 2016 |title=Jessie Ware joins Sadiq Khan's call to show #LondonIsOpen in music showcase |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/jessie-ware-joins-khan-s-call-to-show-londonisopen-in-music-showcase-a3302171.html |website=London Evening Standard |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725143526/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/jessie-ware-joins-khan-s-call-to-show-londonisopen-in-music-showcase-a3302171.html |archivedate=25 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n[[File:Pride in London 2016 - Matthew Barzun, Sadiq Khan and senior members of Pride in London.png|thumb|Khan at [[Pride in London]], June 2016]]\nWhile fasting for the Islamic holy month of [[Ramadan]] in 2016, Khan declared that he would use the period as an opportunity to help \"break down the mystique and suspicion\" surrounding Islam in Britain and help to \"get out there and build bridges\" between communities, organising [[iftar]]s to be held at synagogues, churches, and mosques.<ref>{{cite news |last=Crerar |first=Pippa |date=6 June 2016 |title=Sadiq Khan: I'll use Ramadan to help build bridges between communities |website=London Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-i-ll-use-ramadan-to-help-build-bridges-between-communities-a3264506.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160613153311/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-i-ll-use-ramadan-to-help-build-bridges-between-communities-a3264506.html |archivedate=13 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mortimer |first=Caroline |website=The Independent |date=5 June 2016 |title=Ramadan 2016: Sadiq Khan wants to use Islamic holy month to reduce suspicion of Muslims |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/ramadan-2016-sadiq-khan-wants-to-use-festival-to-reduce-suspicion-around-islam-a7066756.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909185742/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/ramadan-2016-sadiq-khan-wants-to-use-festival-to-reduce-suspicion-around-islam-a7066756.html |archivedate=9 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He then appeared at a [[Trafalgar Square]] celebration of [[Eid al-Fitr]], endorsing [[freedom of religion|religious freedom]] and lambasting \"criminals who do bad things and use the name of Islam to justify what they do\".<ref name=\"Eid\">{{cite news |last=Hill |first=Dave |title=Sadiq Khan speaks for peaceful Islam at Trafalgar Square Eid festival |date=10 July 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/davehillblog/2016/jul/10/sadiq-khan-speaks-for-peaceful-islam-at-trafalgar-square-eid-festival |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716063611/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/davehillblog/2016/jul/10/sadiq-khan-speaks-for-peaceful-islam-at-trafalgar-square-eid-festival |archivedate=16 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]], Khan attended a vigil in [[Old Compton Street]], [[Soho]], and insisted that he \"will do everything in [his] power to ensure that LGBT Londoners feel safe in every part of our city\";<ref>{{cite news |last=Khan |first=Sadiq |title=Sadiq Khan: I'll work to preserve London's record of being LGBT-friendly |date=14 June 2016 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/comment/comment/sadiq-khan-i-ll-work-to-preserve-london-s-record-of-being-lgbtfriendly-a3271101.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629165948/http://www.standard.co.uk/comment/comment/sadiq-khan-i-ll-work-to-preserve-london-s-record-of-being-lgbtfriendly-a3271101.html |archivedate=29 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> later that month he marched in the LGBT [[Pride London]] parade.<ref>{{cite news |work=BBC News |date=25 June 2016 |title=Thousands join Pride parade in London |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-36628793 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625220438/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-36628793 |archivedate=25 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, Khan declared his support for [[Owen Smith]]'s bid to oust [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as Leader of the Labour Party. Although describing him as a \"principled Labour man\", Khan said that Corbyn had failed to gain popularity with the electorate and that Labour would not win a general election under Corbyn's leadership.<ref>{{cite news |last=Syal |first=Rajeev |title=Jeremy Corbyn supporters dismiss Sadiq Khan's criticisms |work=The Guardian |date=21 August 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/21/jeremy-corbyn-supporters-dismiss-sadiq-khan-criticisms-labour |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161214112850/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/21/jeremy-corbyn-supporters-dismiss-sadiq-khan-criticisms-labour |archivedate=14 December 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Transport and housing policies====\nOn transport, Khan immediately announced the introduction of a \"Hopper\" bus ticket which would allow a passenger to take two bus and tram journeys within an hour for the price of one; it was intended to benefit those on low incomes most.<ref>{{cite news |last=Crerar |first=Pippa |title=Sadiq Khan confirms new \u00a31.50 one-hour 'hopper' London bus ticket |website=London Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khan-confirms-150-onehour-hopper-london-bus-ticket-a3244331.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614225833/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khan-confirms-150-onehour-hopper-london-bus-ticket-a3244331.html |archivedate=14 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tfl.gov.uk/info-for/media/press-releases/2017/september/gla---over-100-million-journeys-made-on-hopper-fare|title=GLA - Over 100 million journeys made on \u2018Hopper\u2019 fare|website=Transport for London|date=11 September 2017|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> In January 2018, this was ugraded into unlimited journeys, also now allowing travel on Tube or rail services in between.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tfl.gov.uk/info-for/media/press-releases/2018/january/gla---unlimited-hopper-fare-launches-this-mon|title=GLA - Unlimited Hopper fare launches this month|website=Transport for London|date=2 January 2018|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> In June 2016, Khan announced that his electoral pledge to prevent transport fare rises would only apply to \"single fares\" and [[Pay-as-you-go tax|pay as you go]] fares, and not daily, monthly, weekly, or yearly railcards; he was widely criticised for this, including by the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[Caroline Pidgeon]], who accused him of having broken his promise.<ref>{{cite news |last=Speed |first=Barbara |date=9 June 2016 |website=New Statesman |title=Has Sadiq Khan already broken his promise of a fares freeze? |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/devolution/2016/06/has-sadiq-khan-already-broken-his-promise-fares-freeze |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701231809/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/devolution/2016/06/has-sadiq-khan-already-broken-his-promise-fares-freeze |archivedate=1 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cowburn |first=Ashley |title=Sadiq Khan accused of breaking flagstone electoral promise to freeze London transport fares |date=8 June 2016 |website=The Independent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/sadiq-khan-accused-of-breaking-election-promise-to-freeze-london-transport-fares-a7070496.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231063433/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/sadiq-khan-accused-of-breaking-election-promise-to-freeze-london-transport-fares-a7070496.html |archivedate=31 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> That same month, he ordered TfL to ban any advertising on its network that was deemed to engage in [[Anti-fat bias|body shaming]] and the demeaning of women.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Kayleigh |date=13 June 2016 |title=Body-shaming adverts to be banned on London transport by Sadiq Khan |website=The Independent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/body-shaming-adverts-banned-london-transport-tube-sadiq-khan-a7079591.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923231647/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/body-shaming-adverts-banned-london-transport-tube-sadiq-khan-a7079591.html |archivedate=23 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In July he urged the government to allow TfL to take control of the failing [[Southern (train operating company)|Southern]] rail service,<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnston |first=Chris |date=20 July 2016 |website=The Guardian |title=Sadiq Khan seeks Transport for London takeover of Southern |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/20/sadiq-khan-southern-rail-transport-for-london-takeover |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725181438/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/20/sadiq-khan-southern-rail-transport-for-london-takeover |archivedate=25 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mortimer |first=Caroline |title=Sadiq Khan says Southern Rail should be placed under Tfl control after months of commuter misery |date=20 July 2016 |website=The Independent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/sadiq-khan-southern-rail-commuter-train-cancelled-chaos-strike-rmt-gtr-a7147111.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820194707/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/sadiq-khan-southern-rail-commuter-train-cancelled-chaos-strike-rmt-gtr-a7147111.html |archivedate=20 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and in August launched the 24-hour [[Night Tube]] service on Fridays and Saturdays, an idea initially proposed by Johnson two years previously.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Weaver |first=Matthew |title=Sadiq Khan to launch London's night tube service |work=The Guardian |date=19 August 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/aug/19/sadiq-khan-launch-london-night-tube-service |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829124935/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/aug/19/sadiq-khan-launch-london-night-tube-service |archivedate=29 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn his first weeks as Mayor, Khan criticised foreign investors for treating homes in London as \"gold bricks for investment\", instead urging them to invest in the construction of \"affordable homes\" for Londoners through a new agency, Homes for Londoners, which would be funded by both public and private money.<ref>{{cite news |last=Booth |first=Robert |title=Sadiq Khan condemns foreign investors' use of London homes as 'gold bricks' |date=25 May 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/may/25/sadiq-khan-condemns-foreign-investors-london-homes-gold-bricks-housing-policy |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622095306/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/may/25/sadiq-khan-condemns-foreign-investors-london-homes-gold-bricks-housing-policy |archivedate=22 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, in contrast to a pre-election statement, he revealed that he no longer supported rent freezes in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last=Foster |first=Dawn |title=Sadiq Khan attacks empty luxury flats, but his housing policies are also void |date=27 May 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/housing-network/2016/may/27/sadiq-khan-empty-luxury-flats-housing-policy |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920224616/https://www.theguardian.com/housing-network/2016/may/27/sadiq-khan-empty-luxury-flats-housing-policy |archivedate=20 September 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Insisting that he would \"oppose building on the Green Belt, which is now even more important than when it was created\", Khan vetoed the construction of a football stadium and two blocks of flats on Green Belt land in [[Chislehurst]], after the plan had already been supported by [[Bromley Council]].<ref>{{cite news |last=May |first=Luke |title=Sadiq Khan rejects football stadium plans to protect Bromley's green space |website=Bromley Times |date=22 June 2016 |url=http://www.bromleytimes.co.uk/news/sadiq_khan_rejects_football_stadium_plans_to_protect_bromley_s_green_space_1_4587938 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624192156/http://www.bromleytimes.co.uk/news/sadiq_khan_rejects_football_stadium_plans_to_protect_bromley_s_green_space_1_4587938 |archivedate=24 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nKhan backed expansion of [[London City Airport]], removing the block on this instituted by Johnson's administration; environmentalist campaigners like [[Si\u00e2n Berry]] stated that this was a breach of Khan's pledge to be London's \"greenest ever\" mayor.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Crerar |first=Pippa |title=Sadiq Khan's help for London City Airport expansion 'breaks green pledge' |website=London Evening Standard |date=11 May 2016 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khans-help-for-london-city-airport-expansion-breaks-green-pledge-a3245396.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821155407/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khans-help-for-london-city-airport-expansion-breaks-green-pledge-a3245396.html |archivedate=21 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nOpposing expansion at [[Heathrow Airport]], he urged Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] to instead support expansion at [[Gatwick Airport]], stating that to do so would bring \"substantial economic benefits\" to London.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Crerar |first=Pippa |title=Sadiq Khan urges Theresa May to back Gatwick Airport expansion with second runway |website=London Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khan-urges-theresa-may-to-back-gatwick-airport-expansion-with-second-runway-a3296501.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725021415/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khan-urges-theresa-may-to-back-gatwick-airport-expansion-with-second-runway-a3296501.html |archivedate=25 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nKhan launched a \"No Nights Sleeping Rough\" taskforce to tackle youth homelessness in London in October 2016.<ref name=\"lescrerarlaunchestaskforce\">{{cite news|last1=Crerar|first1=Pippa|title=Sadiq Khan launches taskforce to help young people sleeping rough in London|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/sadiq-khan-launches-taskforce-to-tackle-young-people-sleeping-rough-in-london-a3362401.html|accessdate=6 October 2016|work=London Evening Standard|date=6 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007184547/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/sadiq-khan-launches-taskforce-to-tackle-young-people-sleeping-rough-in-london-a3362401.html|archivedate=7 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the COVID-19 outbreak in 2020 Khan was criticized for closing stations and reducing services on the tube network resulting in overcrowding and putting Key workers travelling to work at risk.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/19/london-tube-to-close-many-stations-because-of-coronavirus</ref>\n\n==== Air pollution ====\n[[File:Jasvir Singh OBE accompanying the Mayor of London Sadiq Khan to the Golden Temple in Amritsar, India.jpg|thumb|right|Khan on a visit to Amritsar, India in 2018]]\n\nKhan has called air pollution \u201cthe biggest public health emergency of a generation.\u201d<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/sep/13/londons-most-polluted-schools-to-be-given-air-quality-audits|title=London's most polluted schools to be given air-quality audits|last=Taylor|first=Matthew|date=2017-09-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914045806/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/sep/13/londons-most-polluted-schools-to-be-given-air-quality-audits|archivedate=14 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October 2017, he introduced the Toxicity Charge (T-charge); operating within the same hours and zone as the [[London congestion charge]], the T-Charge levied a \u00a310 fine on top of that for older and more polluting vehicles (typically diesel and petrol ones registered before 2006) that do not meet [[European emission standards#Toxic emission: stages and legal framework|Euro 4 standards]].<ref name=\"t-charge\"/> In that same year, he announced plans to establish a replacement: an \"[[Ultra Low Emission Zone]] (ULEZ)\" across London that would charge owners of the most polluting cars a fine of \u00a312.50 per day on top of the congestion charge.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/sadiq-khan-plans-world-s-first-ultralow-emissions-zone-with-new-daily-charges-for-swathes-of-london-a3506561.html|title=Sadiq Khan plans world's first ultra-low emission zone across huge swathe of London|work=Evening Standard|access-date=2017-09-14|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914175643/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/sadiq-khan-plans-world-s-first-ultralow-emissions-zone-with-new-daily-charges-for-swathes-of-london-a3506561.html|archivedate=14 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The all day, every day (except on Christmas Day)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tfl.gov.uk/modes/driving/ultra-low-emission-zone|title=Ultra Low Emission Zone|website=Transport for London|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> zone was introduced in 2019 in Central London, applying to diesel cars and vans whose engines aren't at the latest [[European emission standards#Toxic emission: stages and legal framework|Euro 6 standard]] as well as most petrol cars over 14 years old; in addition, non-compliant buses, coaches and lorries will have to pay \u00a3100.<ref name=\"ulez\"/> The zone will be extended to the North and South Circulars in October 2021.<ref name=\":1\" /> It resulted in a drop of the worst polluting vehicles entering the zone each day from 35,578 in March 2019 to 26,195 in April after the charge was introduced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/may/16/ulez-cuts-number-of-worst-polluting-cars-in-central-london |title=ULEZ cuts number of worst polluting cars in central London}}</ref>\n\nKhan criticised Great Britain's government in June 2017 for its lack of drive in improving general air quality.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/jun/23/sadiq-khan-michael-gove-life-and-death-air-pollution-crisis|title=Sadiq Khan: Gove must get a grip on 'life and death' air pollution crisis|last=Taylor|first=Matthew|date=2017-06-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915023727/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/jun/23/sadiq-khan-michael-gove-life-and-death-air-pollution-crisis|archivedate=15 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He stated that the government's action plan on the issue lacked \u201cserious detail, fails to tackle all emission sources, such as from buildings, construction or the river, and does not utilise the government\u2019s full resources and powers\u201d, reflecting its low prioritisation of the issue in the past.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn September, he announced that the first 50 air quality audits for primary schools in the worst-polluted areas&nbsp;of the city had been launched with the objective to reduce air pollution around public schools.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-41254593|title=Audit to protect 'pupils from toxic air'|date=2017-09-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-09-14|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914192317/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-41254593|archivedate=14 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The audits will continue until the end of 2017, with reports being published in 2018.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n====Policing====\nIn an interview with [[LBC]], Khan accepted responsibility for knife crime in London as the Police and Crime Commissioner for the city, but blamed budgetary cuts by the UK [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] Government.<ref>https://jerseyeveningpost.com/news/uk-news/2018/06/07/london-mayor-accepts-responsibility-for-crime-situation-as-he-blames-police-cuts/</ref> Khan stated that knife crime is \"rising across England & Wales\" and that it is \"clearly a national problem that requires national solutions.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kerr |first1=Chloe |title=Met police set up new task force to deal with violent crime |url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/942870/london-news-met-police-knife-crime-task-force-crime |accessdate=10 July 2019 |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=7 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref>  Following the [[2019 London Bridge stabbing]] Khan stated, \u201cYou can\u2019t disaggregate terrorism and security from cuts made to resources of the police, of probation, the tools that judges have \u2026 The key thing is we need to support the police and security service. (...) The point I am making is we can be safer, with more police and more resources.\u201d<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/nov/30/london-bridge-attack-swift-review-of-violent-sentences-pledged Justice system playing 'Russian roulette' with public, says terror expert] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\n==Political image and views==\nWriting for ''[[The Spectator]]'', the political commentator [[Nick Cohen]] described Khan as a centre-left social democrat,<ref>{{cite web|author=Nick Cohen |title=Would Jeremy Corbyn prefer George Galloway to be Mayor of London? |website=The Spectator |date=10 February 2016 |url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/would-jeremy-corbyn-prefer-george-galloway-to-be-mayor-of-london/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160211090622/http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/would-jeremy-corbyn-prefer-george-galloway-to-be-mayor-of-london/ |archivedate=11 February 2016 }}</ref> while the journalist [[Amol Rajan]] termed him \"a torch-bearer for the social democratic wing\" of the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite web |author=Amol Rajan |title=After Boris, Mayor Khan for London? |date=15 September 2015 |website=Politico |url=http://www.politico.eu/article/tooting-to-victory-london-sadiq-khan-mayor-corbyn-goldsmith-boris-johnson-bevin/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314141400/http://www.politico.eu/article/tooting-to-victory-london-sadiq-khan-mayor-corbyn-goldsmith-boris-johnson-bevin/ |archivedate=14 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The BBC describe Khan as being located on the party's [[soft left]].<ref>{{cite news |title=London mayor: The Sadiq Khan story |author=Esther Webber |work=BBC News |date=7 May 2016 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-36140479 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507141456/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-36140479 |archivedate=7 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In an article for [[Al Jazeera]], the [[Marxism|Marxist]] commentator [[Richard Seymour (writer)|Richard Seymour]] described Khan as a [[centrism|centrist]],<ref>{{cite web |author=Richard Seymour |title=Sadiq Khan's victory and free Londonistan |publisher=Al Jazeera |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2016/05/sadiq-khan-victory-free-londonistan-160507174122069.html |date=8 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615015120/http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2016/05/sadiq-khan-victory-free-londonistan-160507174122069.html |archivedate=15 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> while Matt Wrack, the General Secretary of the [[Fire Brigades Union]], characterised Khan as belonging to \"that part of the Labour Party that was in government under Blair and Brown\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Watts |first=Joe |title=Sadiq Khan faces backlash after saying Jeremy Corbyn election win is 'extremely unlikely' |website=The Independent |date=22 August 2016 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/a-counter-offensive-has-been-launched-against-sadiq-khan-after-the-london-mayor-said-a-jeremy-corbyn-a7202496.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708221128/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/a-counter-offensive-has-been-launched-against-sadiq-khan-after-the-london-mayor-said-a-jeremy-corbyn-a7202496.html |archivedate=8 July 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The journalist Dave Hill described Khan as a [[social liberalism|social liberal]].<ref name=\"100 days\">{{cite web |last=Hill |first=Dave |title=Sadiq Khan's first 100 days as London mayor: how is he doing? |date=16 August 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/16/sadiq-khans-first-100-days-as-london-mayor-how-is-he-doing |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221155635/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/16/sadiq-khans-first-100-days-as-london-mayor-how-is-he-doing |archivedate=21 February 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:London June 8 2019 (79) Eid Trafalgar Square Mayor Sadiq Khan (48026201552).jpg|thumb|left|Khan at a 2019 Eid event in Trafalgar Square, London]]\n\nKhan has described himself as a \"proud feminist\".<ref name=\"100 days\"/> In April 2019, Khan joined the [[Jewish Labour Movement]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Oster |first1=Marcy |title=London Mayor Sadiq Khan joins Jewish Labour movement |url=https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/london-mayor-sadiq-khan-joins-jewish-labour-movement#.XL8400Ai0D8 |website=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |publisher=70 Faces Media |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nKhan considers himself as a practising Muslim.<ref>Jane Onyanga-Omara, [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2016/05/06/sadiq-khan-london-mayor-muslim/84016822/ 5 things to know about London's first Muslim mayor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116015859/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2016/05/06/sadiq-khan-london-mayor-muslim/84016822/ |date=16 January 2017 }}, ''USA Today'' (May 6, 2017).</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=London elects Sadiq Khan, first Muslim mayor, after ugly campaign|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/05/06/europe/uk-london-mayoral-race-sadiq-khan/index.html}}</ref> He quotes from the [[Quran]] and [[hadith]] when discussing terrorism.<ref name=newyorker/> He received death threats from Islamic extremists after voting in favour of the [[Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013|Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=58}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/02/18/labour-mp-sadiq-khan-receives-death-threats-for-supporting-same-sex-marriage/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-04 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330023159/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/02/18/labour-mp-sadiq-khan-receives-death-threats-for-supporting-same-sex-marriage/ |archivedate=30 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was also threatened by the far-right group [[Britain First]], which in 2016 threatened to take \"[[direct action]]\" against Khan where he \"lives, works and prays\" as part of an anti-Muslim campaign.<ref>Olivia Blair, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/sadiq-khan-britain-first-london-mayor-threaten-direct-action-a7047991.html Britain First threatens to target London Mayor Sadiq Khan with 'direct action'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912193411/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/sadiq-khan-britain-first-london-mayor-threaten-direct-action-a7047991.html |date=12 September 2017 }}, ''The Independent'' (May 25, 2016).</ref>\n\nJournalist Dave Hill has said that Khan was \"savvy, streetwise and not averse to a scrap\",{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=101}} whilst also describing him as having a \"joshing, livewire off-stage personality\" which differed from the formal image he often projected while onstage.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=59}}\nKhan used to perform [[stand-up comedy]] before running for Mayor, including a ten-minute money-raising ''Stand Up for Labour'' routine. Comedian [[Arthur Smith (comedian)|Arthur Smith]] stated that Khan could become a \"good club-level comedian one day\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2016/09/05/25710/sadiq_khan%3A_i_used_to_do_stand-up|title=Sadiq Khan: 'I used to do stand-up'|work=Chortle|year=2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927083831/http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2016/09/05/25710/sadiq_khan%3A_i_used_to_do_stand-up|archivedate=27 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> During the 2016 Mayoral campaign, Goldsmith referred to Khan as \"a caricature machine politician... the sort of politician who justified peoples' mistrust in politics\", as evidence citing Khan's U-turn on supporting Heathrow expansion.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=116}}\nAnother rival in the 2016 Mayoral campaign, [[George Galloway]] of the [[Respect Party]], referred to Khan as a \"flip-flop merchant\" and a \"product of the Blairite machine\".{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=139}}\n\nThere has been an ongoing political feud between Khan and US president [[Donald Trump]] since 2016, when Khan criticised Trump over his proposed \"[[Trump travel ban|Muslim ban]]\" and Trump responded by attacking Khan a number of times on Twitter over the next several years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weaver |first1=Matthew |title=Timeline: Donald Trump's feud with Sadiq Khan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jun/03/timeline-donald-trump-feud-with-sadiq-khan |accessdate=10 July 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=16 June 2019}}</ref> Shortly before Trump's 2019 state visit to the UK, Khan compared Trump to \"European dictators of the 1930s and 40s\".<ref>{{Citation|title=It's un-British to roll out the red carpet for Donald Trump \u2013 Sadiq Khan|date=1 June 2019|website=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jun/01/donald-trump-state-visit-red-carpet-unbritish}}</ref> Upon arrival, Trump responded on Twitter by calling him a \"stone-cold loser\" and comparing him to another mayor he also targets, [[Bill de Blasio]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Trump attacks London mayor in tweets before landing \u2013 CNN Video|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/06/03/trump-tweet-sadiq-khan-uk-visit-es-vpx.cnn|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Six months after his election as the MP for Tooting, ''[[The Spectator]]'' awarded Khan Newcomer of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2005/11/parliamentarian-of-the-year/|title=Parliamentarian of the Year|date=2005-11-19|website=The Spectator|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n* Khan was nominated for the Politician of the Year Award at the [[British Muslim Awards]] in January 2013 and 2015 and won the award in February 2016.<ref name=\"asianimage\">{{cite news|url=http://www.asianimage.co.uk/news/10197507.Winners_honoured_at_British_Muslim_Awards/|title=Winners honoured at British Muslim Awards|publisher=Asian Image|date=31 January 2013|accessdate=1 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121173521/http://www.asianimage.co.uk/news/10197507.Winners_honoured_at_British_Muslim_Awards/|archivedate=21 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"asianworldnews\">{{cite news|url=http://www.asianworldnews.co.uk/business/british-muslim-awards-2016/|title=British Muslim Awards 2016|publisher=Asian World|date=17 February 2016|accessdate=1 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421220433/http://asianworldnews.co.uk/business/british-muslim-awards-2016/|archivedate=21 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* In late 2016 and 2017, Khan won and accepted the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[GQ]]\u2019s Politician of the Year Award.<ref>[https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/gallery/anthony-joshua-jared-leto-stormzy]</ref>\n* In 2017, he was awarded an Honorary Doctorate from the [[University of Law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://universitybusiness.co.uk/Article/the-university-of-law-awards-sadiq-khan/|title=The University of Law awards Sadiq Khan|website=University Business|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n* In 2018, Khan was conferred [[Sitara-e-Pakistan]] for his services to Pakistan by the Pakistani President [[Mamnoon Hussain]].<ref>{{cite news |title=President Mamnoon confers civil awards on Yaum-i-Pakistan |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1397075 |work=Dawn}}</ref>\n* In 2018, he became an Honorary Fellowship by the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architecture.com/knowledge-and-resources/knowledge-landing-page/riba-honorary-fellowships-2018-announced|title=RIBA Honorary Fellowships 2018 announced|website=www.architecture.com|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n* In 2019, Khan became an Honorary Bencher of [[Middle Temple]] Inn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.middletemple.org.uk/civicrm/event/info?reset=1&id=40086|title=Middle Temple|website=www.middletemple.org.uk|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKhan is a practising [[Muslim]] who observes the fast during [[Ramadan]] and regularly attends Al-Muzzammil Mosque in Tooting.<ref>{{cite web|title=London elects its first Muslim mayor and the journalism world rightly notes its importance|url=http://www.getreligion.org/getreligion/2016/5/8/london-elects-a-muslim-mayor-and-the-journalism-world-rightly-notes-it-as-a-new-day|publisher=Getreligion.org|accessdate=14 May 2016|date=9 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511121118/http://www.getreligion.org/getreligion/2016/5/8/london-elects-a-muslim-mayor-and-the-journalism-world-rightly-notes-it-as-a-new-day|archivedate=11 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherwood\">{{cite news|last1=Sherwood|first1=Harriet|title='This is our moment': Tooting Muslims laud Sadiq Khan victory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/07/our-moment-tooting-muslims-sadiq-khan-london-mayoral-election-victory|accessdate=14 May 2016|work=The Guardian|date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512035232/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/07/our-moment-tooting-muslims-sadiq-khan-london-mayoral-election-victory|archivedate=12 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sadiq hosts Eid celebrations|url=http://www.sadiqkhan.org.uk/sadiq_hosts_eid_celebrations|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609203340/http://www.sadiqkhan.org.uk/sadiq_hosts_eid_celebrations|publisher=sadiqkhan.org.uk|archive-date=9 June 2016|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=58}}<ref name=\"Sherwood\" /> Journalist Dave Hill described Khan as \"a moderate, socially liberal Muslim\".<ref name=\"Eid\"/> Khan has expressed the view that \"too often the people who are 'representing' the Islamic faith aren't representative, they're angry men with beards. And that is not what Islam is about.\"{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=83}}\n\nKhan married Saadiya Ahmed, a fellow solicitor, in 1994. They have two daughters,<ref name=\"pugilist\" /> both raised in the Islamic faith.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Crerar |first1=Pippa |last2=Edwardes |first2=Charlotte |title=Sadiq Khan says 'I'm like a stressed Victorian dad' in revealing interview about his family and religion |website=London Evening Standard |date=13 July 2016 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-says-im-like-a-stressed-victorian-dad-in-revealing-interview-where-he-talks-about-his-a3294436.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714151534/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-says-im-like-a-stressed-victorian-dad-in-revealing-interview-where-he-talks-about-his-a3294436.html |archivedate=14 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2016 London mayoral election]]\n* [[List of British Pakistanis]]\n<!--\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hill |first=Dave |year=2016 |title=Zac Versus Sadiq: The Fight to Become London Mayor |location= |publisher=Double Q |isbn=978-1-911079-20-0 |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sadiq Khan}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.sadiq.london/}}\n* [http://www.sadiq.london/ Sadiq Khan \u2013 Labour Candidate for Mayor of London] official site\n{{UK MP links| parliament = sadiq-khan/1577|hansard=<!--mr-sadiq-khan-->|hansardcurr=4801|guardian=8847/sadiq-khan|publicwhip=Sadiq_Khan|theywork=sadiq_khan|record=Sadiq-Khan/Tooting/272|bbc=35774.stm|journalisted =sadiq-khan}}\n* [https://twitter.com/SadiqKhan @SadiqKhan Verified Twitter Account]\n* [https://twitter.com/MayorofLondon @MayorofLondon Official Verified Twitter Account]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tom Cox (British politician)|Tom Cox]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013[[2016 Tooting by-election|2016]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rosena Allin-Khan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Parmjit Dhanda]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Communities and Local Government|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]|years=2008\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Shahid Malik]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis|The Lord Adonis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of State for Transport]]|years=2009\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Theresa Villiers]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]]|years=2010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Maria Eagle]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Jack Straw]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Justice]]|years=2010\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after={{nowrap|[[Charles Falconer, Baron Falconer of Thoroton|The Lord Falconer of Thoroton]]}}}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Lord Chancellor]]|years=2010\u20132015}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tessa Jowell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for London|Shadow Minister for London]]|years=2013\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=''None''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Boris Johnson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of London]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Chair of the [[Fabian Society]]|years=2008\u20132010|before=[[Anne Campbell]]|after=[[Suresh Pushpananthan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{Miliband Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{Labour Party London mayoral selection, 2015}}\n{{Mayors of London}}\n{{Mayors of the largest cities in the world by GDP}}\n{{Fabian Society}}\n{{Portal bar|London|Biography|Politics|United Kingdom|Socialism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Sadiq}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Advocates of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Alumni of London Metropolitan University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of North London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The College of Law]]\n[[Category:British lawyers of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Wandsworth]]\n[[Category:English Muslims]]\n[[Category:English people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:English feminists]]\n[[Category:Proponents of Islamic feminism]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) mayors]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Mayors of London]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Muhajir people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ernest Bevin College]]\n[[Category:Social democrats]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:Chairs of the Fabian Society]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Sitara-e-Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Mayor of London since 2016|the 18th-century Persian Shah|Sadeq Khan Zand|the suicide bomber|Mohammad Sidique Khan|the 17th-century Sylheti faujdar|Sadeq Khan}}\n{{Pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{short description|Mayor of London and British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = Sadiq Khan\n|image            = Sadiq Khan 2017.jpg\n|caption          = Khan in 2017\n|office           = [[Mayor of London]]\n|deputy           = [[Joanne McCartney]]\n|term_start       = 9 May 2016\n|term_end         =\n|predecessor      = [[Boris Johnson]]\n{{Collapsed infobox section begin|[[Shadow Cabinet]] positions}}\n|office2          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Justice]]<br />[[Shadow Lord Chancellor]]\n|leader2         = [[Ed Miliband]]\n|term_start2     = 8 October 2010\n|term_end2        = 11 May 2015\n|predecessor2    = [[Jack Straw]]\n|successor2      = [[Charles Falconer, Baron Falconer of Thoroton|The Lord Falconer of Thoroton]]\n|office3          = [[Minister for London|Shadow Minister for London]]\n|leader3          = [[Ed Miliband]]\n|term_start3      = 16 January 2013\n|term_end3        = 11 May 2015\n|predecessor3     = [[Tessa Jowell]]\n|successor3      = ''Vacant''\n|office4          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]]\n|leader4          = [[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Ed Miliband]]\n|term_start4      = 14 May 2010\n|term_end4        = 8 October 2010\n|predecessor4     = [[Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis|The Lord Adonis]]\n|successor4       = [[Maria Eagle]]{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n|office5          = [[Minister of State for Transport]]\n|primeminister5   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start5      = 9 June 2009\n|term_end5        = 6 May 2010\n|predecessor5     = The Lord Adonis\n|successor5       = [[Theresa Villiers]]\n|office6          = [[Department for Communities and Local Government|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]\n|primeminister6   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start6      = 5 October 2008\n|term_end6        = 9 June 2009\n|predecessor6     = [[Parmjit Dhanda]]\n|successor6       = [[Shahid Malik]]\n|office7          = [[Chief Whip|Assistant Government Whip]]\n|primeminister7   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|1blankname7      = [[Chief Whip of the Labour Party|Chief Whip]]\n|1namedata7       = [[Geoff Hoon]]\n|term_start7      = 2 July 2007\n|term_end7        = 5 October 2008\n|office8          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]]\n|term_start8     = 5 May 2005\n|term_end8        = 9 May 2016\n|predecessor8    = [[Tom Cox (British politician)|Tom Cox]]\n|successor8     = [[Rosena Allin-Khan]]\n|birth_name       = Sadiq Aman Khan\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1970|10|8}}\n|birth_place      = [[Tooting]], [[London]], England\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Saadiya Ahmed|1994}}\n|children         = 2\n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|nationality      = British\n|alma_mater       = [[University of North London]]<br />[[University of Law]]\n|website          = {{Official website|http://www.sadiq.london/}}\n|awards=[[Nishan-e-Pakistan|Sitara-e-Imtiaz]] (2018)}}\n'''Sadiq Aman Khan''' ({{IPAc-en|s|\u0259|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|k|_|\u02c8|k|\u0251\u02d0|n}}; born 8 October 1970) is a British politician who has served as the [[Mayor of London]] since [[2016 London mayoral election|2016]]. He was previously a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]] from 2005 until 2016. A member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], Khan is on the party's [[soft left]] and has been ideologically characterised as a [[Social democracy|social democrat]]. \n\nBorn in [[Tooting]], [[South London]], to a working-class [[British Pakistanis|British Pakistani]] family, Khan earned a [[law degree]] from the [[University of North London]]. He subsequently worked as a solicitor specialising in human rights issues and chaired the [[Liberty (advocacy group)|Liberty]] advocacy group for three years. Joining the Labour Party, Khan was a [[Councillor]] for the [[London Borough of Wandsworth]] from 1994 to 2006 before being elected MP for [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]]. Under Labour Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]], Khan was appointed [[Department for Communities and Local Government|Minister of State for Communities]] in 2008, later becoming [[Minister of State for Transport]]. A key ally of the next Labour leader, [[Ed Miliband]], he served in [[Shadow Cabinet of Ed Miliband|Miliband's Shadow Cabinet]] as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Justice]], [[Shadow Lord Chancellor]] and [[Minister for London|Shadow Minister for London]].\n\nAs the [[London Labour Party|London Labour]] candidate, Khan was elected Mayor of London at the [[2016 London mayoral election|2016 mayoral election]], defeating [[London Conservatives]] rival [[Zac Goldsmith]] and then resigning as an MP. In office, he has frozen all [[Transport for London|TfL]] fares for [[London Buses|bus]], [[Tramlink|tram]] and single pay-as-you-go [[London Underground|Tube]] and [[Docklands Light Railway|DLR]] travel, introduced the Hopper fare for unlimited bus and tram journeys for an hour, the Toxicity Charge (T-Charge) on older and more polluting vehicles in [[Central London]],<ref name=\"t-charge\">{{cite web|author=Chapman, Ben |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/t-charge-what-is-it-london-emissions-charge-how-affect-will-pay-congestion-car-diesel-a8014976.html |title=T-charge: What is the new London emissions charge and how will it affect you? |work=The Independent |date=23 October 2017 |accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> and the 24/7 [[Ultra Low Emission Zone]] (ULEZ) fee on all but the cleanest vehicles in Central London,<ref name=\"ulez\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/apr/06/london-prepares-for-launch-of-ultra-low-emissions-zone|website=The Guardian|title=London prepares for launch of ultra-low emissions zone|date=6 April 2019|accessdate=18 January 2020|last=Topham|first=Gwyn}}</ref> backed expansion at [[London City Airport]] and [[Gatwick Airport]], and focused on uniting the city's varied communities. He was a vocal supporter of the unsuccessful [[Britain Stronger in Europe]] and [[People's Vote]] campaigns for [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|the UK to remain]] in the [[European Union]] and a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|second referendum]] on [[Brexit]], respectively. As well as having a strained relationship with Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]], whose [[socialism|socialist]] platform Khan thought unelectable, he attracted international attention for his [[Twitter]] arguments with United States President [[Donald Trump]].\n\nHe has been included in the [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]] list of most influential people in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sadiq Khan: The World's 100 Most Influential People|url=http://time.com/collection/most-influential-people-2018/5217530/sadiq-khan/|website=[[Time 100]]|publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|year=2018|accessdate=22 April 2018|language=en-us}}</ref> Khan has been praised for promoting mutual tolerance among London's varied communities, making transport more accessible, and reducing the number of polluting vehicles in Central London;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cityam.com/sadiq-khans-ulez-charge-cuts-polluting-vehicles-by-over-a-third-and-bags-tfl-51m/|website=CityAM|title=Sadiq Khan's Ulez charge cuts polluting vehicles by over a third and bags TfL \u00a351m|last=Rogers|first=Alexandra|date=17 September 2019|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/futurelondon/cleanair/high-pollution-levels-detected-by-40-of-londons-air-quality-sensor-networks-a4196811.html|website=London Evening Standard|title= London pollution: High levels detected by 40% of capital's air quality sensors|last=Bayley|first=Sian|date=23 July 2019|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> however, he has been criticised for the rise of [[knife crime]] and his response to [[Crime in London]].\n\n==Early life==\nKhan was born on 8 October 1970 at [[St George's Hospital]] in [[Tooting]], [[South London]] to a working-class [[Sunni Muslim]] family.<ref name=\"pugilist\">{{cite web|last1=Eaton|first1=George|title=The pugilist: Sadiq Khan's quest to become mayor of London|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/03/pugilist-sadiq-khan-s-quest-become-mayor-london|work=New Statesman|accessdate=11 March 2016|quote=His grandparents emigrated from India to [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]] following Partition; his parents emigrated from Pakistan to London shortly before his birth.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312070742/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/03/pugilist-sadiq-khan-s-quest-become-mayor-london|archivedate=12 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=observer-20150531>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/31/sadiq-khan-aspiration-labour-leadership-overused-blair|title=Sadiq Khan says 'aspiration' will be Labour leadership race's most overused word|author=Rowena Mason and Simon Hattenstone|newspaper=The Observer|date=31 May 2015|accessdate=1 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150601002649/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/31/sadiq-khan-aspiration-labour-leadership-overused-blair|archivedate=1 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://next.ft.com/content/8c974c8e-1379-11e6-bb40-c30e3bfcf63b|title=Victory for Sadiq Khan highlights tolerant face of London|work=[[Financial Times]]|date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626155723/https://next.ft.com/content/8c974c8e-1379-11e6-bb40-c30e3bfcf63b|archivedate=26 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His grandparents migrated from [[Lucknow]] in [[United Provinces (1937\u201350)|United Provinces]], [[British India]] to [[Pakistan]] following the [[partition of India]] in 1947.<ref name=\"pugilist\"/><ref name=\"London Evening Standard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/sadiq-khan-makes-historic-border-crossing-on-foot-from-india-to-pakistan-a3712026.html|title=Sadiq Khan makes historic border crossing from India to Pakistan on foot|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=6 December 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207035206/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/sadiq-khan-makes-historic-border-crossing-on-foot-from-india-to-pakistan-a3712026.html|archivedate=7 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nHis father Amanullah and mother Sehrun arrived in London from Pakistan in 1968.<ref name=\"London Evening Standard\"/>{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=14}} Khan was the fifth of eight children, seven of whom were boys.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=14}} In London, Amanullah worked as a bus driver and Sehrun as a [[seamstress]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=14\u201315}}<ref name=\"pugilist\"/>\n\n[[File:ErnestBevinSchool.jpg|thumb|left|[[Ernest Bevin College]] in Tooting]]\nKhan and his siblings grew up in a three-bedroom [[council flat]] on the Henry Prince Estate in [[Earlsfield]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=15}} He attended Fircroft Primary School and then [[Ernest Bevin College|Ernest Bevin School]], a local [[comprehensive school|comprehensive]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=15}} Khan studied science and mathematics at [[A-level]], in the hope of eventually becoming a dentist. A teacher recommended that he read law instead, as he had an argumentative personality. The teacher's suggestion, along with the American television programme ''[[L.A. Law]]'', inspired Khan to do so. He read Law at the [[University of North London]] (now [[London Metropolitan University]]).<ref name=\"pugilist\"/> His parents later moved out of their council flat and purchased their own home.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=15}} Like his brothers, Khan was a fan of sport, particularly enjoying football, cricket, and boxing.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=15}}\n\nFrom his earliest years, Khan worked: \"I was surrounded by my mum and dad working all the time, so as soon as I could get a job, I got a job. I got a paper round, a Saturday job\u2014some summers I laboured on a building site.\"<ref name=\"pugilist\"/> The family continues to send money to relatives in Pakistan, \"because we're blessed being in this country.\" He and his family often encountered racism, which led to him and his brothers taking up boxing at the Earlsfield Amateur Boxing Club.<ref name=\"pugilist\"/> While studying for his degree, between the ages of 18 and 21, he had a Saturday job at the [[Peter Jones (department store)|Peter Jones]] department store in [[Sloane Square]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Cooper |first=Goolistan |title=Sadiq Khan recounts life lessons learned working at Chelsea department store |date=1 February 2016 |website=GetWestLondon |url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/news/west-london-news/sadiq-khan-recounts-life-lessons-10811540 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602221552/http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/news/west-london-news/sadiq-khan-recounts-life-lessons-10811540 |archivedate=2 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nBefore entering the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in 2005, Khan practised as a solicitor.<ref name=Grauniard31May15/>\nAfter completing his law degree in 1991, Khan took his [[Law Society]] [[Final examination|finals]] at the [[University of Law|College of Law]] in [[Guildford]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=16}}<ref name=PoliticsCo>{{citation|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/sadiq-aman-khan|title=Sadiq Khan, biography|website=www.politics.co.uk/|date=2015|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604043218/http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/sadiq-aman-khan|archivedate=4 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1994 he married Saadiya Ahmed, who was also a solicitor.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=15}}\n\nIn 1994 he became a trainee solicitor at a firm of solicitors called ''Christian Fisher'';<ref name=Grauniard31May15/> the firm undertook mainly legal aid cases.  The partners were Michael Fisher and [[Louise Christian]].<ref name=LAGDec15/>  Khan became a partner in 1997,<ref name=Grauniard31May15/> and like Christian, specialised in human rights law.<ref name=\"pugilist\" />  When Fisher left in 2002, the firm was renamed ''Christian Khan''.<ref name=Grauniard31May15>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/31/sadiq-khan-london-mayor-tony-blair-aspiration|publisher=The Guardian|title=Sadiq Khan: 'Ruthless? No. Decency can get you to the top in politics'|access-date=25 May 2017|date=31 May 2015|first1=Simon|last1=Hattenstone|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505182605/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/31/sadiq-khan-london-mayor-tony-blair-aspiration|archivedate=5 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=LAGDec15>{{citation|url=http://www.lag.org.uk/magazine/2015/12/claims-that-sadiq-khan\u2019s-former-human-rights-firm-\u2018was-worth-millions\u2019-queried-by-lawyers.aspx|title=Claims that Sadiq Khan's former human rights firm 'was worth millions' queried by lawyers|publisher=Legal Action Group|last1=Bawdon|first1=Fiona|date=December 2015|work=Legal Action magazine|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117214943/http://www.lag.org.uk/magazine/2015/12/claims-that-sadiq-khan%E2%80%99s-former-human-rights-firm-%E2%80%98was-worth-millions%E2%80%99-queried-by-lawyers.aspx|archivedate=17 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=LAGMay15>{{citation|url=http://www.lag.org.uk/magazine/2015/05/dear-sadiq-khan-when-you-left-christian-khan-to-become-an-mp,-you-said-you-could-bring-about-more-change-as-a-politician-than-a-lawyer-what-happened.aspx|publisher=Legal Action Group|title=Dear Sadiq Khan. When you left Christian Khan to become an MP, you said you could bring about more change as a politician than a lawyer. What happened?|last1=Christian|first1=Louise|date=May 2015|work=Legal Action magazine|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626162250/http://www.lag.org.uk/magazine/2015/05/dear-sadiq-khan-when-you-left-christian-khan-to-become-an-mp,-you-said-you-could-bring-about-more-change-as-a-politician-than-a-lawyer-what-happened.aspx|archivedate=26 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Khan left the firm in 2004, after he became the prospective Labour candidate for the [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]] parliamentary constituency.<ref name=Grauniard31May15/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiankhan.co.uk/ViewNews.asp?NewsID=35|title=Departure of Sadiq Khan \u2013 ::Imran Khan and Partners Solicitors, London, UK|author=Imran Khan and Partners Solicitors|publisher=christiankhan.co.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007132021/http://www.christiankhan.co.uk/ViewNews.asp?NewsID=35|archivedate=7 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring his legal career, he acted in actions against [[employment law|employment]] and [[discrimination law]], judicial reviews, inquests, the police, and crime, and was involved in cases including the following:\n* Bubbins vs The United Kingdom (European Court of Human Rights&nbsp;\u2013 shooting of an unarmed individual by police marksmen)<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1468-2230.2006.00583_1.x |title=Bubbins v United Kingdom: Civil Remedies and the Right to Life \u2013 Martin \u2013 2006 beav|publisher=[[Wiley Online Library]]|date=24 February 2006|journal=Modern Law Review|volume=69|issue=2|pages=242\u2013249|first=Neil|last=Martin}}</ref>\n* HSU and Thompson v [[Metropolitan Police Service|Met Police]] (wrongful arrest/police damages)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/law-report-juries-to-be-given-guidance-on-awards-against-police-1281004.html|location=London|work=[[The Independent]]|first1=Paul|last1=Magrath|title=Law report: Juries to be given guidance on awards against police|date=28 February 1997|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206135857/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/law-report-juries-to-be-given-guidance-on-awards-against-police-1281004.html|archivedate=6 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Reeves v Met Police (duty of care to prisoners)<ref>{{cite web|author=Law Lords Department|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199899/ldjudgmt/jd990715/reeves01.htm|title=House of Lords \u2013 Commissioners of Police for the Metropolis v. Reeves (A.P.) (Joint Administratix of the Estate of Martin Lynch, Deceased)|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719062219/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199899/ldjudgmt/jd990715/reeves01.htm|archivedate=19 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Murray v CAB (discrimination)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/uk-workers-go-to-work-when-ill-fewest-sick-days-survey-70-per-cent-a7737031.html|title=Latest British Employment Law News|first=Zlata|last=Rodionova|newspaper=Independent|date=7 June 2011}}</ref>\n* Ahmed v [[University of Oxford]] (racial discrimination against a student)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emplaw.co.uk/content/index?startpage=data/2003733.htm|title=Latest British Employment Law News |publisher=emplaw.co.uk|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n* Dr Jadhav v Secretary of State for Health (racial discrimination in the employment of Indian doctors by the health service)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/rajen/Jadhav-v-SS/index.htm |title=Jadhav v Secretary of State for Health |publisher=Homepage.ntlworld.com |accessdate=7 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024053506/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/rajen/Jadhav-v-SS/index.htm |archivedate=24 October 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* CI Logan v Met Police ([[racial discrimination]])<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3266581.stm|work=BBC News|title=Black officer's 'six figure sum' payout|date=13 November 2003}}</ref>\n* [[Ali Dizaei|Supt Dizaei]] v Met Police (police damages, discrimination)<ref>[[Ali Dizaei]]</ref>\n* Inquest into the death of David Rocky Bennett (use of restraints)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiankhan.co.uk/ViewNews.asp?NewsID=15 |title=David 'Rocky' Bennett Inquiry Report. News from Christian Khan Solicitors, London UK |publisher=Christiankhan.co.uk |date=5 February 2004 |accessdate=7 June 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311181602/http://www.christiankhan.co.uk/ViewNews.asp?NewsID=15 |url-status=live |archivedate=11 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* Lead solicitor on [[List of demonstrations against corporate globalization#2001|Mayday demonstration 2001]] test case litigation ([[Human Rights Act 1998|Human Rights Act]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lexisweb.co.uk/cases/2009/January/Austin-and-another-v-Metropolitan-Police-Commissioner |title=Austin and another v Metropolitan Police Commissioner \u2013 [2009&#93; All ER (D) 227 (Jan) |publisher=Lexisweb.co.uk |date=28 January 2009 |accessdate=7 June 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311181723/http://lexisweb.co.uk/cases/2009/January/Austin-and-another-v-Metropolitan-Police-Commissioner |archivedate=11 March 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* [[Farrakhan v Home Secretary]] (Human Rights Act): in 2001, Khan represented the American [[Nation of Islam]] leader [[Louis Farrakhan]] in the High Court and overturned a ban on him entering the United Kingdom, first imposed in 1986. The government subsequently won on appeal.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=19}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1467587.stm|work=BBC News|title=Farrakhan UK ban overturned|date=31 July 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111054640/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1467587.stm|archivedate=11 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* In February 2000, Khan represented a group of Kurdish actors who were arrested by Metropolitan Police during a rehearsal of the [[Harold Pinter]] play ''[[Mountain Language]]'', securing \u00a3150,000 in damages for the group for their wrongful arrest and the trauma caused by the arrest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/pound150000-for-police-raid-on-kurdish-pinter-play-726752.htm |location=London |work=The Independent |first=Robert |last=Verkaik |title=\u00a3150,000 for police raid on Kurdish Pinter play |date=2 February 2000 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/628257.stm |archivedate=8 November 2012 }}</ref>\n* McDowell and Taylor v Met Police: Leroy McDowell and Wayne Taylor successfully sued the [[Metropolitan Police]] for assault and [[false imprisonment]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/analysis-officers-fear-of-being-branded-racist-has-done-little-to-reduce-bias-over-suspects-608687.html|location=London| work=The Independent|title=Analysis: Officers' fear of being branded racist has done little to reduce bias over suspects|date=8 November 2002}}</ref>\n* Represented [[Maajid Nawaz]], Reza Pankhurst and Ian Nisbet in Egyptian court when they were arrested on charges of trying to revive [[Hizb ut-Tahrir]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/2597335.stm|title=BBC NEWS {{!}} UK {{!}} England {{!}} Egypt trial Britons' case resumes|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2017-06-06|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923101310/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/2597335.stm|archivedate=23 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/2002/10/43243.html|title=6 months since the detention of British men --in Egypt \u2013 UK Indymedia|website=www.indymedia.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-06-06|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806202337/https://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/2002/10/43243.html|archivedate=6 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n===First term: 2005\u20132010===\n[[File:Sadiq Khan, September 2009 cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|Sadiq Khan in 2009]]\nBefore entering Parliament, Khan represented [[Tooting]] as a Councillor for the [[London Borough of Wandsworth]] from 1994 to 2006, and was granted the title of [[Title of honor|Honorary]] [[Alderman]] of [[Wandsworth]] upon his retirement from local politics.<ref>[http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/sadiq-aman-khan http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/sadiq-aman-khan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604043218/http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/sadiq-aman-khan |date=4 June 2016 }}, politics</ref>\n\nIn 2003, [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]] [[Constituency Labour Party]] decided to open its parliamentary selection to all interested candidates, including the incumbent MP since 1974, [[Tom Cox (British politician)|Tom Cox]]. This prompted Cox, then in his mid-70s, to announce his retirement rather than risk de-selection. In the subsequent selection contest, Khan defeated five other local candidates to become Labour's candidate for the seat. He was elected to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]].\n\nKhan was one of the Labour MPs who led the successful opposition to Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]]'s proposed introduction of 90 days' detention without charge for those suspected of terrorism offences.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=20}} In recognition of this, ''[[The Spectator]]''\u2014a right-wing magazine then edited by [[Boris Johnson]]\u2014awarded him the \"Newcomer of the Year Award\" at the 2005 Parliamentarian of the Year Awards.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=20}} The magazine's editorial board stated that he had received the award \"for the tough-mindedness and clarity with which he has spoken about the very difficult issues of Islamic terror\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/archive/features/14489/part_2/parliamentarian-of-the-year.thtml?SelectedIssueDate=19%20November%202005 |date=19 November 2005 |title=Parliamentarian of the Year |work=[[The Spectator]] |accessdate=27 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090616124012/http://www.spectator.co.uk/archive/features/14489/part_2/parliamentarian-of-the-year.thtml?SelectedIssueDate=19%20November%202005 |url-status=dead |archivedate=16 June 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> In August 2006, he was a signatory of an open letter to [[Tony Blair]] that was signed by prominent Muslims and published in ''[[The Guardian]]''. The letter criticised [[Foreign policy of the United Kingdom|UK foreign policy]] and in particular the 2003 invasion of Iraq, stating that Blair's policies had caused great harm to civilians in the Middle East and provided \"ammunition to extremists who threaten us all\".{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Minister criticises Muslim letter |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/4787119.stm |date=12 August 2006 |accessdate=27 March 2009 |work=[[BBC News]] |archivedate=8 November 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108143352/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/4787119.stm |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sadiq Khan and Yasmin Qureshi talk to British troops in Kabul (2473583886).jpg|thumb|left|Khan meeting with British troops stationed in Kabul, Afghanistan in 2008]]\n\nKhan had to repay \u00a3500 in [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|expenses]] in 2007 in relation to a newsletter sent to constituents featuring a 'Labour rose', which was deemed to be unduly prominent. While the content of the newsletter was not deemed to be party political, the rose logo was found to be unduly prominent which may have had the effect of promoting a political party. There was no suggestion that Khan had deliberately or dishonestly compiled his [[Expense management|expenses claims]], which were not explicitly disallowed under the rules at that time. The rules were retrospectively changed disallowing the claim, which had previously been approved by the House of Commons authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200708/cmselect/cmstnprv/182/182.pdf|title=Microsoft Word \u2013 Baker-Bruce-Khan \u2013 CRC Rep.doc|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013064730/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200708/cmselect/cmstnprv/182/182.pdf|archivedate=13 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/london/7142779.stm |title=Minister's rose emblem broke rule |work=BBC News |date=13 December 2007 |accessdate=15 December 2010 |url-status=live |archivedate=17 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101017175350/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/london/7142779.stm |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 3 February 2008, ''[[The Sunday Times]]''<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Gillard|author2=Jonathan Calvert|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/crime/article3295393.ece|title=Police bugged Muslim MP Sadiq Khan|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=3 February 2008|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516004326/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/crime/article3295393.ece|archivedate=16 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> claimed that a conversation between Khan and prisoner [[Babar Ahmad]]&nbsp;\u2013 a constituent accused of involvement in terrorism&nbsp;\u2013 at [[Woodhill Prison]] in [[Milton Keynes]] had been [[bugging|bugged]] by the [[Metropolitan Police Anti-Terrorist Branch]].<ref name=kwbi>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7224786.stm |title=Khan welcomes 'bugging' inquiry |work=BBC News |date=3 February 2008 |accessdate=7 June 2011 |archivedate=25 March 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325035405/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7224786.stm |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> An inquiry was launched by the [[Secretary of State for Justice|Justice Secretary]], [[Jack Straw]].<ref name=kwbi/> There was concern that the bugging contravened the [[Wilson Doctrine]] that police should not bug MPs. The report concluded that the doctrine did not apply because it affected only bugging requiring approval by the Home Secretary, while in Khan's case the monitoring was authorised by a senior police officer.  The Home Secretary, [[Jacqui Smith]], then announced a further policy review and said the bugging of discussions between MPs and their constituents should be banned.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/feb/22/uksecurity.police?gusrc=rss&feed=uknews |title=Bugging of MP on prison visit did not break the rules, inquiry finds |first=Vikram |last=Dodd |date=22 February 2008 |accessdate=4 July 2009 |location=London |newspaper=The Guardian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831203539/http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2008/feb/22/uksecurity.police?gusrc=rss&feed=uknews |archivedate=31 August 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, Blair stood down as both Prime Minister and Labour Party leader, to be replaced by [[Gordon Brown]]. Brown thought highly of Khan, who moved up the parliamentary ranks under Brown's Premiership.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}} Brown made Khan a party whip, who was therefore charged with ensuring that Labour-sponsored legislation made it through the parliamentary process to become law.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}} In July 2008, Khan helped push through a government proposal to permit the detention of those suspected of terror offenses for 42 days without charge.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}} For his part in this, Khan was criticised by Liberty's [[Shami Chakrabarti]] and others, who claimed that Khan had contravened his principles on civil liberties issues.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}}\n\n[[File:Rt Hon Sadiq Khan MP at Has Labour lost the plot on crime?.jpg|thumb|right|<center>Sadiq Khan speaking in 2011</center>]]\n\nOn Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]]'s [[Cabinet reshuffle]] of 3 October 2008, Khan was appointed [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] [[Department for Communities and Local Government|for Communities and Local Government]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=27}}<ref name=PUSSCALG>{{citation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081126155329/http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/corporate/pdf/707527.pdf|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/corporate/pdf/707527.pdf|title=Ministerial Team|publisher=[[Department for Communities and Local Government]]|website=www.communities.gov.uk|archive-date=26 November 2008<!-- archive date guessed from URL -->|url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=theyworkforyou>{{citation|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/11878/sadiq_khan/tooting#profile|title=Sadiq Khan, Former MP, Tooting, profile|publisher=TheyWorkForYou|website=www.theyworkforyou.com|access-date=21 May 2017|df=dmy|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525055553/https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/11878/sadiq_khan/tooting#profile|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\nIn 2008, the [[Fabian Society]] published Khan's book, ''Fairness Not Favours''. In this work, Khan argued that the Labour Party had to reconnect with British Muslims, arguing that it had lost the trust of this community as a result of the [[Iraq War]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=27\u201328}} He also said that British Muslims had their own part to play in reconnecting with politicians, arguing that they needed to rid themselves of a [[victim mentality]] and take greater responsibility for their own community.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=28}} In the House of Commons in January 2009, Khan criticised [[Pope Benedict XVI]] for the rehabilitation of [[Richard Williamson (bishop)|Bishop Richard Williamson]] following his remarks about [[the Holocaust]], a move he described as \"highly unsavoury\" and of \"great concern\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Prince |first=Rosa |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/4388359/Minister-criticises-Pope-for-pardoning-Holocaust-denial-bishop.html |title=Minister criticises Pope for pardoning Holocaust denial bishop |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=29 January 2009 |accessdate=29 January 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114024511/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/4388359/Minister-criticises-Pope-for-pardoning-Holocaust-denial-bishop.html |archivedate=14 November 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009 he was promoted to [[Minister of State for Transport]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=28}}<ref name=theyworkforyou/><ref>{{cite news |first=Eleanor |last=Harding |title=Tooting MP Sadiq Khan named first Muslim cabinet minister in Gordon Brown's reshuffle |url=http://www.wandsworthguardian.co.uk/news/4424355.Sadiq_Khan_named_first_Muslim_cabinet_minister/ |work=The Wandsworth Guardian |date=6 June 2009 |accessdate=6 June 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090609074816/http://www.wandsworthguardian.co.uk/news/4424355.Sadiq_Khan_named_first_Muslim_cabinet_minister/ |archivedate=9 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In what was believed to be a first for an MP, Khan used his Twitter account to self-announce his promotion.<ref>{{cite web |last=Banerjee |first=Subhajit |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/scienceandtechnology/technology/twitter/5467688/MP-Sadiq-Khan-announces-his-Transport-Minister-appointment-on-Twitter.html |title=Minister appointment on Twitter |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=7 June 2009 |accessdate=7 June 2011 |url-status=live |archivedate=11 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611012324/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/scienceandtechnology/technology/twitter/5467688/MP-Sadiq-Khan-announces-his-Transport-Minister-appointment-on-Twitter.html |df=dmy }}</ref>  Though Khan was not a member of the [[Brown ministry|cabinet]], he attended meetings for agenda items covering his policy area,<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/politics/domestic_politics/factcheck%2Ban%2Ballwhite%2Bcabinet/3394202.html|title=FactCheck: an all-white cabinet?|date=20 October 2009|author=By Channel 4 News|publisher=Channel 4|access-date=21 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131125170053/http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/politics/domestic_politics/factcheck%2ban%2ballwhite%2bcabinet/3394202.html|archivedate=25 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> thus becoming the first Muslim to sit in on the British Cabinet.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=28}} As Transport Minister, Khan supported plans to expand [[Heathrow Airport]] with [[Expansion of Heathrow Airport|the addition of a third runway]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=30}}\n\nDuring this period, Khan served as chairman of the socialist [[Fabian Society]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fabians.org.uk/executive-committee-mainmenu-64/executive-committee |title=Executive Committee \u2013 The Fabian Society \u2013 where the British left thinks |publisher=Fabians.org.uk |accessdate=7 June 2011 |url-status=live |archivedate=11 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011113227/http://www.fabians.org.uk/executive-committee-mainmenu-64/executive-committee |df=dmy }}</ref> remaining on its Executive Committee. In 2009, he won the Jenny Jeger Award (''Best Fabian Pamphlet'') for his writing \"Fairness not Favours: How to re-connect with British Muslims\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fabians.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/FairnessNotFavours.pdf|title=Fairness not Favours How to reconnect with British Muslims (full text)|first1=Sadiq|last1=Khan|first2=Hannah|last2=Jameson|first3=Sunder|last3=Katwala|year=2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029020452/https://www.fabians.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/FairnessNotFavours.pdf|archivedate=29 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/sep/17/religion.islam|title=Fairness, not favours, for Muslims (opinion)|first1=Sadiq|last1=Khan|work=The Guardian|year=2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219223931/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/sep/17/religion.islam|archivedate=19 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, Khan publicly stated that for a second successive year he would not be taking a pay rise as an MP or Minister, declaring \"At a time when many people in Tooting and throughout the country are having to accept pay freezes I don't think it's appropriate for MPs to accept a pay rise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/minister-all-mps-should-give-up-their-1000-pay-rise-6707031.html |title=Minister: All MPs should give up their \u01411,000 pay rise |newspaper=London Evening Herald |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=7 June 2011 |url-status=live |archivedate=24 October 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024103045/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/minister-all-mps-should-give-up-their-1000-pay-rise-6707031.html |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Second and third term: 2010\u20132016===\nIn [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]], Khan was re-elected as the MP for Tooting despite a swing against his [[Labour Party (UK)|party]] of 3.6% and a halving of his previous majority.<ref>https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/rivals-attack-nasty-campaign-as-sadiq-khan-survives-6466885.html</ref> His campaign in Tooting had been supported by [[Harris Bokhari]], who reportedly used anti-Ahmadiyya sentiment to mobilise Muslim voters at a mosque in Tooting to vote for Khan instead of the rival [[Ahmadiyya]] candidate, Nasser Butt.<ref name=newyorker>https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/07/31/sadiq-khan-takes-on-brexit-and-terror; https://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/8451614.election-race-infected-by-anti-ahmadiyya-hate-campaign/</ref> In 2019, Bokhari was appointed to join Khan's new Diversity, Equality and Inclusion Advisory Group.<ref>https://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/debbie-weekes-bernard-chair-new-board-inequality</ref> In the subsequent [[2010 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election]] Khan was an early backer of [[Ed Miliband]], becoming his [[campaign manager]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Harding |first=Eleanor |place=Wandsworth |url=http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/local/wandsworthnews/8167355.EXCLUSIVE___I_m_backing_Ed___says_MP_Khan/ |title=EXCLUSIVE: 'I'm backing Ed Miliband', says Sadiq Khan MP |newspaper=[[Your Local Guardian]] |date=15 May 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315074031/http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/local/wandsworthnews/8167355.EXCLUSIVE___I_m_backing_Ed___says_MP_Khan |archivedate=15 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> In the wake of Labour's [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 election defeat]], Acting Leader [[Harriet Harman]] appointed Khan [[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Exclusive: 'Bitter-sweet' promotion for Sadiq Khan MP |date=14 May 2010 |work=Wandsworth Guardian |url=http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/local/wandsworthnews/8167341.EXCLUSIVE___Bitter_sweet__promotion_for_Sadiq_Khan_MP/ |accessdate=17 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301145559/http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/local/wandsworthnews/8167341.EXCLUSIVE___Bitter_sweet__promotion_for_Sadiq_Khan_MP/ |url-status=live |archivedate=1 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Khan orchestrated [[Ed Miliband]]'s successful campaign to become Labour leader,{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=29}} and was appointed to the senior roles of [[Shadow Lord Chancellor]] and [[Shadow Secretary of State for Justice|Shadow Justice Secretary]].<ref name=\"parliament.uk\">{{cite web|title=Rt Hon Sadiq Khan|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/sadiq-khan/1577|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|accessdate=11 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707033528/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/sadiq-khan/1577|archivedate=7 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ed Miliband conference speech in Manchester, September 2010.jpeg|250px|left|thumb|Khan orchestrated Ed Miliband's successful campaign to become Labour Leader and later served in Miliband's Shadow Cabinet.]]\n\nIn April 2010 it was revealed that Khan had repaid falsely claimed expenses on two occasions, when literature was sent to his constituents. The first incident concerned letters sent out before the 2010 General Election which were ruled to have the \"unintentional effect of promoting his return to office\", the second a \u00a32,550 repayment for Christmas, [[Eid al-Fitr|Eid]], and birthday cards for constituents, dating back to 2006.<ref>{{cite news|location=London |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7579476/General-election-2010-Transport-minister-Sadiq-Khan-in-election-expenses-row.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=General election 2010: Transport minister Sadiq Khan in election expenses row |last=Kirkup |first=James |date=12 April 2010 |accessdate=25 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123210912/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7579476/General-election-2010-Transport-minister-Sadiq-Khan-in-election-expenses-row.html |url-status=live |archivedate=23 November 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Under House of Commons rules, pre-paid envelopes and official stationery can only be used for official parliamentary business.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/8192570/MPs-expenses-17-MPs-were-re-elected-after-secret-deals-on-expenses.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Martin |last=Beckford |title=MPs' expenses: 17 MPs were re-elected after secret deals on expenses |date=9 December 2010 |accessdate=11 December 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113022531/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/8192570/MPs-expenses-17-MPs-were-re-elected-after-secret-deals-on-expenses.html |archivedate=13 November 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/8192581/MPs-expenses-the-secret-deals-revealed.html |first=Martin |last=Beckford |title=MPs' expenses: the secret deals revealed |date=10 December 2010 |accessdate=11 December 2010 |archivedate=14 December 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101214062821/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/8192581/MPs-expenses-the-secret-deals-revealed.html |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/dec/09/secretly-resolved-mps-expenses-cases-made-public |location=London |work=The Guardian |title='Secretly' resolved MPs' expenses cases made public |date=9 December 2010 |accessdate=11 December 2010 |archivedate=13 December 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101213011233/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2010/dec/09/secretly-resolved-mps-expenses-cases-made-public |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> Khan's claim for the greetings cards was initially rejected, but he presented a new invoice no longer identifying the nature of the claim, and this was accepted. Khan attributed the improper claim for the cards to \"inexperience\" and human error and apologised for breaking the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|expenses rules]].<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7063316.ece|location=London|work=The Times|first=David|last=Brown|title=Transport Minister Sadiq Khan repays 2500 wrongly claimed on expenses|date=16 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8569397.stm |work=BBC News |title=Minister repays \u00a32,500 expenses |date=15 March 2010 |accessdate=15 December 2010 |url-status=live |archivedate=23 March 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323063009/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8569397.stm |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn early 2013, Miliband appointed Khan as the [[Shadow Minister for London]], a position that he held in addition to his other responsibilities.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=31}}<ref name=\"parliament.uk\" /> In December 2013, the Fabian Society published a collection of essays edited by Khan that was titled ''Our London''.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=31}} Khan was also tasked with overseeing Labour's campaign for the [[2014 London local elections]],{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=30}} in which the party advanced its control in the city, gaining hold of twenty of the thirty-two boroughs.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=32}} By this point, there was much talk of Khan making a bid for the London Mayoralty in 2016, when incumbent Mayor Boris Johnson would be stepping down.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=31}} His options were affected by the outcome of the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]; if Labour won, then he would be expected to become a government minister, but if they lost then he would be free to pursue the Mayoralty.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=31}} In December 2015, Khan voted against the Cameron government's plans to expand the bombing of targets in the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=96}}\n\nPolls had suggested that Labour could be the largest party in a [[hung parliament]] following the 2015 general election, but ultimately the Conservatives secured victory.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=32\u201333}} In the vote, Khan was returned for a third term as MP for Tooting, defeating his Conservative rival by 2,842 votes.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=33}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wandsworth.gov.uk/info/200327/election_results/1991/parliamentary_election_results_may_2015/3|title=Tooting Constituency \u2013 Parliamentary election results May 2015|publisher=Wandsworth Council|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416175632/https://www.wandsworth.gov.uk/info/200327/election_results/1991/parliamentary_election_results_may_2015/3|archivedate=16 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was one of 36 [[List of Labour Party (UK) MPs|Labour MPs]] to nominate [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as a [[Endorsements in the 2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|candidate]] in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election of 2015]], but has said that he was \"no patsy\" to Corbyn and would stand up to him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-leadership-election|title=Who nominated who for the 2015 Labour leadership election?|work=New Statesman|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705074349/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-leadership-election|archivedate=5 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35412680|title=Londoners should not let Corbyn 'experiment' with city \u2013 PM|work=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204044633/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35412680|archivedate=4 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He later stated that he nominated Corbyn to \"broaden the debate\" but did not then vote for him.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why won't Labour's Sadiq Khan say he supports Jeremy Corbyn? |last=Deacon |first=Michael |date=4 April 2016 |website=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/04/why-wont-labours-sadiq-khan-say-he-supports-jeremy-corbyn/ |ref=harv |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611113423/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/04/why-wont-labours-sadiq-khan-say-he-supports-jeremy-corbyn/ |archivedate=11 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2016, Khan resigned as an MP by his appointment to the ancient office of [[Chiltern Hundreds|Crown Steward and Bailiff of The Three Chiltern Hundreds]], a customary practice in the UK. This triggered a by-election in [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]] to be held in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2016/may/sadiq-khan-resigns-as-mp-for-tooting/|title=Sadiq Khan resigns as MP for Tooting|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]|date=10 May 2016|accessdate=10 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511133538/http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2016/may/sadiq-khan-resigns-as-mp-for-tooting/|archivedate=11 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Simon|first1=Harris|title=Sadiq Khan resigns triggering Tooting by-election|url=http://www.itv.com/news/london/update/2016-05-09/sadiq-khan-resigns-triggering-tooting-by-election/|website=ITV News|publisher=ITV News|accessdate=9 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511131758/http://www.itv.com/news/london/update/2016-05-09/sadiq-khan-resigns-triggering-tooting-by-election/|archivedate=11 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe is regularly named among the Top 100 [[Politics of England#Greater London Authority|London politicians]] in the ''[[London Evening Standard]]''{{'}}s annual poll of the 1,000 most influential Londoners<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=7 June 2011 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/standard-home/londons-1000-most-influential-people-2010-politics-6536029.html |title=London's 1000 most influential people 2010: Politics |newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=26 November 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024200001/http://www.standard.co.uk/standard-home/londons-1000-most-influential-people-2010-politics-6536029.html |url-status=live |archivedate=24 October 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> and is an Ambassador for [[Mosaic Network]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mosaicnetwork.co.uk/about/our-supporters/ambassadors|title=Ambassadors|work=Mosaic|accessdate=7 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508081539/http://www.mosaicnetwork.co.uk/about/our-supporters/ambassadors/|archivedate=8 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> an initiative set up by [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]].\n\n==Mayor of London==\nIn 2016, Sadiq Khan ran to become the [[mayor of London]] and was elected with 57% of the vote. He is London's first Muslim mayor and first [[ethnic minority]] mayor.<ref name=\"khaleeli\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/06/sadiq-khan-victory-islamophobia-mayor-london|title=Sadiq Khan's victory won't end Islamophobia, but it offers hope|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Homa Khaleeli|date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204052217/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/06/sadiq-khan-victory-islamophobia-mayor-london|archivedate=4 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Khan was officially sworn in as Mayor in a multi-faith ceremony held in [[Southwark Cathedral]] the following day.<ref name=\"warmwelcome\"/> His first act as mayor was his appearance at a [[Holocaust]] memorial ceremony in a rugby stadium in North London,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish/news/1.718546|title=Sadiq Khan Attends Holocaust Memorial as First Official Mayoral Act|work=Haaretz|accessdate=9 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508214236/http://www.haaretz.com/jewish/news/1.718546|archivedate=8 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> although due to delays with the results of the election, he officially took office on 9 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1691893/sadiq-khan-vows-to-be-mayor-for-all-londoners|title=Sadiq Khan Vows To Be 'Mayor For All Londoners'|publisher=Sky News|date=7 May 2016|accessdate=9 May 2016|quote=But because of the processes involved, he won't be technically in office until just after midnight on Monday.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509012751/http://news.sky.com/story/1691893/sadiq-khan-vows-to-be-mayor-for-all-londoners|archivedate=9 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n===2016 candidacy===\n{{Main|2016 London mayoral election}}\n\n{{Quote box|width=25em||align=right|quote=\"An affordable and secure home to rent or buy, more jobs with higher wages for the lowest paid, making it easier to set up and run a successful business, reducing the cost of commuting, and making London's environment safer, healthier and less polluted.\"|source=Khan's priorities as Mayor.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=74\u201375}}}}\n\n====Nomination as Labour candidate====\nAfter Labour's defeat at the 2015 general election, Khan resigned from the Shadow Cabinet.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=35}} He then announced himself as a candidate to be the Labour nominee for the London Mayoral elections of 2016.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=35}} Khan soon gained the support of prominent figures in the party, including former Mayor of London [[Ken Livingstone]], who was on Labour's leftist, socialist wing, and [[Oona King]], who was on its centrist, [[Blairism|Blairite]] wing.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=37\u201339}}  He also received the backing of the Labour-affiliated [[GMB (trade union)|GMB]] and [[Unite the Union|Unite]] unions,{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=40}} and the nomination of 44 of Labour's 73 parliamentary constituent parties in London, leaving him as one of the top two contenders.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=40}}\n\nKhan's main rival was Conservative candidate [[Zac Goldsmith]]; Khan described him as a spoiled dilettante who \"never finishes anything he starts\".{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=103}} A [[YouGov]] poll for [[LBC]] suggested that while the other main contender to be the Labour nominee, [[Tessa Jowell]], would defeat Goldsmith in a mayoral election, Khan would not.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=62}} In hustings, Khan placed an emphasis on his working-class origins, which would play against Jowell's wealthier upbringing, and argued for the need for change in London, thereby insinuating that Jowell would represent too much continuity with the outgoing Johnson administration.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=42\u201343}} In September 2015, Khan was announced as the winning nominee.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=73\u201374}} He gained 48,152 votes (58.9%) against Jowell's 35,573 (41.1%).{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=73\u201374}}<ref name=\"Lab elects\">{{cite web|last1=Wintour|first1=Patrick|title=Sadiq Khan elected as Labour's candidate for mayor of Londo|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/sep/11/sadiq-khan-elected-as-labours-candidate-for-mayor-of-london|work=The Guardian|accessdate=11 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911222641/http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/sep/11/sadiq-khan-elected-as-labours-candidate-for-mayor-of-london|archivedate=11 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was the favourite candidate in all three voting categories; Labour Party members, members of affiliated trade unions and organisations, and registered supporters who had paid \u00a33 in order to vote.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=74}}\n\n====Campaign====\nKhan vowed that if elected, he would freeze public transport fares in London for four years.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=103}}<ref name=\"Evening Standard\">{{cite web|title=Sadiq Khan pledges four-year freeze of all fares if elected Mayor|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-pledges-fouryear-freeze-of-all-fares-if-elected-mayor-a3111856.html|work=London Evening Standard|accessdate=11 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115173321/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-pledges-fouryear-freeze-of-all-fares-if-elected-mayor-a3111856.html|archivedate=15 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He claimed that this would deprive [[Transport for London]] (TfL) of \u00a3452 million, but TfL stated that it would deprive them of \u00a31.9 billion, taking into account projected population growth over this period.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=127\u2013128}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-35443206|title=Sadiq Khan's fare freeze would cost \u00a31.9bn, says TfL|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408090139/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-35443206|archivedate=8 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Although he had previously backed Heathrow expansion, he now opposed it, instead calling for expansion at [[Gatwick Airport]]; he was likely aware that supporting the former was a vote loser in London.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=47}} Aware of the severe housing shortage in London, he also spoke of clamping down on foreign property investors,{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=52\u201353}} and proposed the establishment of both a \"London living rent\" tenure and a not-for-profit lettings agency that could undercut commercial operators in order to ease the high cost of renting in the city.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=53}} He also called for house building on land owned by TfL, insisting that at least 50% of those constructed should be \"genuinely affordable\".{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=131\u2013133}}\n\nThe YouGov poll had revealed that 31% of Londoners stated that they would not be \"comfortable\" with a Muslim mayor.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=62}} Aware that many voters were suspicious regarding the loyalties of British Muslims to the British state, Khan emphasised his commitment to liberal social values.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=82}} As part of this, he declared his opposition to [[homophobia]],{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=83}} and said that he would have \"zero tolerance for anti-Semitism\".{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=82\u201383}} He openly condemned Islamic extremism and called on the Muslim community to take a leading role in combating it, although at the same time acknowledged the [[Islamophobia]] that many British Muslims faced.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=94\u201395}} He also distanced himself from Corbyn,{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=81\u201382}} rebuking Labour's socialist leader for his links to armed anti-Israel groups,{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=79\u201380}} and criticising him for not singing the [[God Save the Queen|national anthem]] at an event commemorating the [[Battle of Britain]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=79}} Concerned that Corbyn's socialist platform was alienating many of London's businesses, Khan declared that he would be \"the most pro-business mayor ever\",{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=84}} and met with groups such as the [[Federation of Small Businesses]] and [[City of London Corporation]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=109}} He also ensured that his campaign was run entirely separate from Corbyn.{{sfn|Hill|2016|pp=116\u2013117}} Conversely, Goldsmith's Conservative campaign emphasised connections between Khan and Corbyn.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=98}} Both the Conservative campaign and several Conservative-aligned newspapers sought to tar Khan as an apologist for, or even sympathiser with, Islamic extremism.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=93}}\n\nInternational press sources often focused on his religious identity,<ref>{{cite news |last=Henley |first=Jon |title=Global press reaction to Sadiq Khan a mix of curiosity and ignorance |date=6 May 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/06/london-mayor-global-press-reaction-sadiq-khan-curiosity-ignorance |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103095517/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/06/london-mayor-global-press-reaction-sadiq-khan-curiosity-ignorance |archivedate=3 January 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> with many right-wing American media outlets reacting with horror at his election.<ref>{{cite news |last=Millward |first=David |date=7 May 2016 |title=Sadiq Khan's victory as London Mayor alarms American right as US liberals say result will resonate far beyond City Hall |website=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/07/sadiq-khans-victory-as-london-mayor-alarms-american-right-as-us/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707035448/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/07/sadiq-khans-victory-as-london-mayor-alarms-american-right-as-us/ |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nKhan won the election with 57% of the vote. The 1.3 million votes he received are the largest any UK politician has personally received to date.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Sadiq Khan won the London mayoral election|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/05/how-sadiq-khan-won-london-mayoral-election|publisher=[[New Statesman]]}}</ref> Various press sources noted that Khan's election made him the first actively affiliated Muslim to become mayor of a major Western capital.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|last1=James|first1=William|last2=Piper|first2=Elizabeth|title=Labour's Khan becomes first Muslim mayor of London after bitter campaign|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-britain-politics-election-london-idUKKCN0XX1W4|accessdate=7 May 2016|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507140517/http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-britain-politics-election-london-idUKKCN0XX1W4|archivedate=7 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"warmwelcome\">{{cite web |last1=Hooper |first1=Ryan |last2=Hughes |first2=David |title=Warm Welcome as Sadiq Khan is Sworn in as Mayor of London |date=7 May 2016 |url=http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/warm-welcome-as-sadiq-khan-is-sworn-in-as-mayor-of-london/ar-BBsK5SB?ocid=spartanntp |website=Press Association |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602141517/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/warm-welcome-as-sadiq-khan-is-sworn-in-as-mayor-of-london/ar-BBsK5SB?ocid=spartanntp |archivedate=2 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n[[File:London mayoral election by borough 2016 map.png|thumb|right|Map of Greater London boroughs showing those that voted for Khan (red) and Goldsmith (blue) in the 2016 mayoral election]]\n\n===Mayoralty===\nIn the buildup to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum on the UK's continuing membership]] of the [[European Union]] (EU), Khan was a vocal supporter of the 'Remain' camp.<ref>{{cite news |website=The Telegraph |date=9 June 2016 |title=Sadiq Khan warns Labour has a 'responsibility' to win EU referendum remain vote |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/08/sadiq-khan-warns-labour-has-a-responsibility-to-win-eu-referendu/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615071545/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/08/sadiq-khan-warns-labour-has-a-responsibility-to-win-eu-referendu/ |archivedate=15 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He agreed to attend a [[Britain Stronger in Europe]] campaign event with the Conservative Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] to demonstrate cross-party support for remaining within the EU,<ref>{{cite news |last=Sparrow |first=Andrew |title=David Cameron and Sadiq Khan plan pro-EU joint appearance |website=The Guardian |date=30 May 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/29/david-cameron-and-sadiq-khan-plan-pro-eu-joint-appearance |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160904042739/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/29/david-cameron-and-sadiq-khan-plan-pro-eu-joint-appearance |archivedate=4 September 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=PM hails 'extraordinary coalition' as he joins Sadiq Khan in EU campaign |website=Business Insider |date=31 May 2016 |url=http://business-reporter.co.uk/2016/05/31/pm-hails-extraordinary-coalition-joins-sadiq-khan-eu-campaign/#sthash.eufpzs2X.dpuf |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601150311/http://business-reporter.co.uk/2016/05/31/pm-hails-extraordinary-coalition-joins-sadiq-khan-eu-campaign/#sthash.eufpzs2X.dpuf |archivedate=1 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> for which he was criticised by Labour Shadow Chancellor [[John McDonnell (politician)|John McDonnell]], who claimed that sharing a platform with the Conservatives \"discredits us\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Hughes |first=Laura |title=Labour splits as John McDonnell attacks Sadiq Khan for sharing a platform with David Cameron |website=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/31/labour-splits-as-john-mcdonnell-attacks-sadiq-khan-for-sharing-a/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704214127/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/31/labour-splits-as-john-mcdonnell-attacks-sadiq-khan-for-sharing-a/ |archivedate=4 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> After the murder of MP [[Jo Cox]] during the campaign, Khan called for the country to \"pause and reflect\" on the manner in which the Leave and Remain camps had been approaching the debate, stating that it had been marred by a \"climate of hatred, of poison, of negativity, of cynicism\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Mason |first=Rowena |date=17 June 2016 |title=Sadiq Khan calls for more respectful tone in EU referendum debate |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/17/sadiq-khan-calls-for-more-respectful-tone-in-eu-referendum-debate |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126142410/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/17/sadiq-khan-calls-for-more-respectful-tone-in-eu-referendum-debate |archivedate=26 November 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the success of the 'Leave' vote, Khan insisted that all EU citizens living in London were welcome in the city and that he was grateful for the contribution that they made to it.<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnston |first=Chris |website=The Guardian |date=25 June 2016 |title=Sadiq Khan tells London's Europeans they remain welcome |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/25/sadiq-khan-tells-londons-europeans-they-remain-welcome |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160824045529/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/25/sadiq-khan-tells-londons-europeans-they-remain-welcome |archivedate=24 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Elledge |first=Jonn |date=24 June 2016 |title=London mayor Sadiq Khan to EU citizens: \"You are welcome here\" |website=City Metric |url=http://www.citymetric.com/politics/london-mayor-sadiq-khan-eu-citizens-you-are-welcome-here-2201 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625123521/http://www.citymetric.com/politics/london-mayor-sadiq-khan-eu-citizens-you-are-welcome-here-2201 |archivedate=25 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He endorsed the Metropolitan Police's 'We Stand Together' campaign to combat the rise in racial abuse following the referendum,<ref>{{cite news |last=Sleigh |first=Sophia |title=Sadiq Khan launches crackdown on Brexit vote hate crime |date=8 July 2016 |website=London Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-launches-crackdown-on-brexit-vote-hate-crime-a3291331.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714234210/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-launches-crackdown-on-brexit-vote-hate-crime-a3291331.html |archivedate=14 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and later backed the 'London is Open' campaign to encourage businesses, artists, and performers to continue coming to the city despite Brexit.<ref>{{cite news |last=Razaq |first=Rashid |date=22 July 2016 |title=Jessie Ware joins Sadiq Khan's call to show #LondonIsOpen in music showcase |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/jessie-ware-joins-khan-s-call-to-show-londonisopen-in-music-showcase-a3302171.html |website=London Evening Standard |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725143526/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/jessie-ware-joins-khan-s-call-to-show-londonisopen-in-music-showcase-a3302171.html |archivedate=25 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n[[File:Pride in London 2016 - Matthew Barzun, Sadiq Khan and senior members of Pride in London.png|thumb|Khan at [[Pride in London]], June 2016]]\nWhile fasting for the Islamic holy month of [[Ramadan]] in 2016, Khan declared that he would use the period as an opportunity to help \"break down the mystique and suspicion\" surrounding Islam in Britain and help to \"get out there and build bridges\" between communities, organising [[iftar]]s to be held at synagogues, churches, and mosques.<ref>{{cite news |last=Crerar |first=Pippa |date=6 June 2016 |title=Sadiq Khan: I'll use Ramadan to help build bridges between communities |website=London Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-i-ll-use-ramadan-to-help-build-bridges-between-communities-a3264506.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160613153311/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-i-ll-use-ramadan-to-help-build-bridges-between-communities-a3264506.html |archivedate=13 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mortimer |first=Caroline |website=The Independent |date=5 June 2016 |title=Ramadan 2016: Sadiq Khan wants to use Islamic holy month to reduce suspicion of Muslims |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/ramadan-2016-sadiq-khan-wants-to-use-festival-to-reduce-suspicion-around-islam-a7066756.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909185742/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/ramadan-2016-sadiq-khan-wants-to-use-festival-to-reduce-suspicion-around-islam-a7066756.html |archivedate=9 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He then appeared at a [[Trafalgar Square]] celebration of [[Eid al-Fitr]], endorsing [[freedom of religion|religious freedom]] and lambasting \"criminals who do bad things and use the name of Islam to justify what they do\".<ref name=\"Eid\">{{cite news |last=Hill |first=Dave |title=Sadiq Khan speaks for peaceful Islam at Trafalgar Square Eid festival |date=10 July 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/davehillblog/2016/jul/10/sadiq-khan-speaks-for-peaceful-islam-at-trafalgar-square-eid-festival |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716063611/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/davehillblog/2016/jul/10/sadiq-khan-speaks-for-peaceful-islam-at-trafalgar-square-eid-festival |archivedate=16 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]], Khan attended a vigil in [[Old Compton Street]], [[Soho]], and insisted that he \"will do everything in [his] power to ensure that LGBT Londoners feel safe in every part of our city\";<ref>{{cite news |last=Khan |first=Sadiq |title=Sadiq Khan: I'll work to preserve London's record of being LGBT-friendly |date=14 June 2016 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/comment/comment/sadiq-khan-i-ll-work-to-preserve-london-s-record-of-being-lgbtfriendly-a3271101.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629165948/http://www.standard.co.uk/comment/comment/sadiq-khan-i-ll-work-to-preserve-london-s-record-of-being-lgbtfriendly-a3271101.html |archivedate=29 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> later that month he marched in the LGBT [[Pride London]] parade.<ref>{{cite news |work=BBC News |date=25 June 2016 |title=Thousands join Pride parade in London |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-36628793 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625220438/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-36628793 |archivedate=25 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, Khan declared his support for [[Owen Smith]]'s bid to oust [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as Leader of the Labour Party. Although describing him as a \"principled Labour man\", Khan said that Corbyn had failed to gain popularity with the electorate and that Labour would not win a general election under Corbyn's leadership.<ref>{{cite news |last=Syal |first=Rajeev |title=Jeremy Corbyn supporters dismiss Sadiq Khan's criticisms |work=The Guardian |date=21 August 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/21/jeremy-corbyn-supporters-dismiss-sadiq-khan-criticisms-labour |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161214112850/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/21/jeremy-corbyn-supporters-dismiss-sadiq-khan-criticisms-labour |archivedate=14 December 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Transport and housing policies====\nOn transport, Khan immediately announced the introduction of a \"Hopper\" bus ticket which would allow a passenger to take two bus and tram journeys within an hour for the price of one; it was intended to benefit those on low incomes most.<ref>{{cite news |last=Crerar |first=Pippa |title=Sadiq Khan confirms new \u00a31.50 one-hour 'hopper' London bus ticket |website=London Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khan-confirms-150-onehour-hopper-london-bus-ticket-a3244331.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614225833/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khan-confirms-150-onehour-hopper-london-bus-ticket-a3244331.html |archivedate=14 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tfl.gov.uk/info-for/media/press-releases/2017/september/gla---over-100-million-journeys-made-on-hopper-fare|title=GLA - Over 100 million journeys made on \u2018Hopper\u2019 fare|website=Transport for London|date=11 September 2017|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> In January 2018, this was ugraded into unlimited journeys, also now allowing travel on Tube or rail services in between.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tfl.gov.uk/info-for/media/press-releases/2018/january/gla---unlimited-hopper-fare-launches-this-mon|title=GLA - Unlimited Hopper fare launches this month|website=Transport for London|date=2 January 2018|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> In June 2016, Khan announced that his electoral pledge to prevent transport fare rises would only apply to \"single fares\" and [[Pay-as-you-go tax|pay as you go]] fares, and not daily, monthly, weekly, or yearly railcards; he was widely criticised for this, including by the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[Caroline Pidgeon]], who accused him of having broken his promise.<ref>{{cite news |last=Speed |first=Barbara |date=9 June 2016 |website=New Statesman |title=Has Sadiq Khan already broken his promise of a fares freeze? |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/devolution/2016/06/has-sadiq-khan-already-broken-his-promise-fares-freeze |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701231809/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/devolution/2016/06/has-sadiq-khan-already-broken-his-promise-fares-freeze |archivedate=1 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cowburn |first=Ashley |title=Sadiq Khan accused of breaking flagstone electoral promise to freeze London transport fares |date=8 June 2016 |website=The Independent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/sadiq-khan-accused-of-breaking-election-promise-to-freeze-london-transport-fares-a7070496.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231063433/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/sadiq-khan-accused-of-breaking-election-promise-to-freeze-london-transport-fares-a7070496.html |archivedate=31 December 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> That same month, he ordered TfL to ban any advertising on its network that was deemed to engage in [[Anti-fat bias|body shaming]] and the demeaning of women.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Kayleigh |date=13 June 2016 |title=Body-shaming adverts to be banned on London transport by Sadiq Khan |website=The Independent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/body-shaming-adverts-banned-london-transport-tube-sadiq-khan-a7079591.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923231647/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/body-shaming-adverts-banned-london-transport-tube-sadiq-khan-a7079591.html |archivedate=23 September 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In July he urged the government to allow TfL to take control of the failing [[Southern (train operating company)|Southern]] rail service,<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnston |first=Chris |date=20 July 2016 |website=The Guardian |title=Sadiq Khan seeks Transport for London takeover of Southern |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/20/sadiq-khan-southern-rail-transport-for-london-takeover |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725181438/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/20/sadiq-khan-southern-rail-transport-for-london-takeover |archivedate=25 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mortimer |first=Caroline |title=Sadiq Khan says Southern Rail should be placed under Tfl control after months of commuter misery |date=20 July 2016 |website=The Independent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/sadiq-khan-southern-rail-commuter-train-cancelled-chaos-strike-rmt-gtr-a7147111.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820194707/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/sadiq-khan-southern-rail-commuter-train-cancelled-chaos-strike-rmt-gtr-a7147111.html |archivedate=20 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and in August launched the 24-hour [[Night Tube]] service on Fridays and Saturdays, an idea initially proposed by Johnson two years previously.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Weaver |first=Matthew |title=Sadiq Khan to launch London's night tube service |work=The Guardian |date=19 August 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/aug/19/sadiq-khan-launch-london-night-tube-service |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829124935/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/aug/19/sadiq-khan-launch-london-night-tube-service |archivedate=29 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn his first weeks as Mayor, Khan criticised foreign investors for treating homes in London as \"gold bricks for investment\", instead urging them to invest in the construction of \"affordable homes\" for Londoners through a new agency, Homes for Londoners, which would be funded by both public and private money.<ref>{{cite news |last=Booth |first=Robert |title=Sadiq Khan condemns foreign investors' use of London homes as 'gold bricks' |date=25 May 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/may/25/sadiq-khan-condemns-foreign-investors-london-homes-gold-bricks-housing-policy |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622095306/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/may/25/sadiq-khan-condemns-foreign-investors-london-homes-gold-bricks-housing-policy |archivedate=22 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, in contrast to a pre-election statement, he revealed that he no longer supported rent freezes in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last=Foster |first=Dawn |title=Sadiq Khan attacks empty luxury flats, but his housing policies are also void |date=27 May 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/housing-network/2016/may/27/sadiq-khan-empty-luxury-flats-housing-policy |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920224616/https://www.theguardian.com/housing-network/2016/may/27/sadiq-khan-empty-luxury-flats-housing-policy |archivedate=20 September 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Insisting that he would \"oppose building on the Green Belt, which is now even more important than when it was created\", Khan vetoed the construction of a football stadium and two blocks of flats on Green Belt land in [[Chislehurst]], after the plan had already been supported by [[Bromley Council]].<ref>{{cite news |last=May |first=Luke |title=Sadiq Khan rejects football stadium plans to protect Bromley's green space |website=Bromley Times |date=22 June 2016 |url=http://www.bromleytimes.co.uk/news/sadiq_khan_rejects_football_stadium_plans_to_protect_bromley_s_green_space_1_4587938 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624192156/http://www.bromleytimes.co.uk/news/sadiq_khan_rejects_football_stadium_plans_to_protect_bromley_s_green_space_1_4587938 |archivedate=24 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nKhan backed expansion of [[London City Airport]], removing the block on this instituted by Johnson's administration; environmentalist campaigners like [[Si\u00e2n Berry]] stated that this was a breach of Khan's pledge to be London's \"greenest ever\" mayor.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Crerar |first=Pippa |title=Sadiq Khan's help for London City Airport expansion 'breaks green pledge' |website=London Evening Standard |date=11 May 2016 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khans-help-for-london-city-airport-expansion-breaks-green-pledge-a3245396.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821155407/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khans-help-for-london-city-airport-expansion-breaks-green-pledge-a3245396.html |archivedate=21 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nOpposing expansion at [[Heathrow Airport]], he urged Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] to instead support expansion at [[Gatwick Airport]], stating that to do so would bring \"substantial economic benefits\" to London.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Crerar |first=Pippa |title=Sadiq Khan urges Theresa May to back Gatwick Airport expansion with second runway |website=London Evening Standard |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khan-urges-theresa-may-to-back-gatwick-airport-expansion-with-second-runway-a3296501.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725021415/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/sadiq-khan-urges-theresa-may-to-back-gatwick-airport-expansion-with-second-runway-a3296501.html |archivedate=25 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nKhan launched a \"No Nights Sleeping Rough\" taskforce to tackle youth homelessness in London in October 2016.<ref name=\"lescrerarlaunchestaskforce\">{{cite news|last1=Crerar|first1=Pippa|title=Sadiq Khan launches taskforce to help young people sleeping rough in London|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/sadiq-khan-launches-taskforce-to-tackle-young-people-sleeping-rough-in-london-a3362401.html|accessdate=6 October 2016|work=London Evening Standard|date=6 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007184547/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/sadiq-khan-launches-taskforce-to-tackle-young-people-sleeping-rough-in-london-a3362401.html|archivedate=7 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the COVID-19 outbreak in 2020 Khan was criticized for closing stations and reducing services on the tube network resulting in overcrowding and putting Key workers travelling to work at risk.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/19/london-tube-to-close-many-stations-because-of-coronavirus</ref>\n\n==== Air pollution ====\n[[File:Jasvir Singh OBE accompanying the Mayor of London Sadiq Khan to the Golden Temple in Amritsar, India.jpg|thumb|right|Khan on a visit to Amritsar, India in 2018]]\n\nKhan has called air pollution \u201cthe biggest public health emergency of a generation.\u201d<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/sep/13/londons-most-polluted-schools-to-be-given-air-quality-audits|title=London's most polluted schools to be given air-quality audits|last=Taylor|first=Matthew|date=2017-09-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914045806/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/sep/13/londons-most-polluted-schools-to-be-given-air-quality-audits|archivedate=14 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October 2017, he introduced the Toxicity Charge (T-charge); operating within the same hours and zone as the [[London congestion charge]], the T-Charge levied a \u00a310 fine on top of that for older and more polluting vehicles (typically diesel and petrol ones registered before 2006) that do not meet [[European emission standards#Toxic emission: stages and legal framework|Euro 4 standards]].<ref name=\"t-charge\"/> In that same year, he announced plans to establish a replacement: an \"[[Ultra Low Emission Zone]] (ULEZ)\" across London that would charge owners of the most polluting cars a fine of \u00a312.50 per day on top of the congestion charge.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/sadiq-khan-plans-world-s-first-ultralow-emissions-zone-with-new-daily-charges-for-swathes-of-london-a3506561.html|title=Sadiq Khan plans world's first ultra-low emission zone across huge swathe of London|work=Evening Standard|access-date=2017-09-14|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914175643/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/sadiq-khan-plans-world-s-first-ultralow-emissions-zone-with-new-daily-charges-for-swathes-of-london-a3506561.html|archivedate=14 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The all day, every day (except on Christmas Day)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tfl.gov.uk/modes/driving/ultra-low-emission-zone|title=Ultra Low Emission Zone|website=Transport for London|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> zone was introduced in 2019 in Central London, applying to diesel cars and vans whose engines aren't at the latest [[European emission standards#Toxic emission: stages and legal framework|Euro 6 standard]] as well as most petrol cars over 14 years old; in addition, non-compliant buses, coaches and lorries will have to pay \u00a3100.<ref name=\"ulez\"/> The zone will be extended to the North and South Circulars in October 2021.<ref name=\":1\" /> It resulted in a drop of the worst polluting vehicles entering the zone each day from 35,578 in March 2019 to 26,195 in April after the charge was introduced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/may/16/ulez-cuts-number-of-worst-polluting-cars-in-central-london |title=ULEZ cuts number of worst polluting cars in central London}}</ref>\n\nKhan criticised Great Britain's government in June 2017 for its lack of drive in improving general air quality.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/jun/23/sadiq-khan-michael-gove-life-and-death-air-pollution-crisis|title=Sadiq Khan: Gove must get a grip on 'life and death' air pollution crisis|last=Taylor|first=Matthew|date=2017-06-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915023727/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/jun/23/sadiq-khan-michael-gove-life-and-death-air-pollution-crisis|archivedate=15 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He stated that the government's action plan on the issue lacked \u201cserious detail, fails to tackle all emission sources, such as from buildings, construction or the river, and does not utilise the government\u2019s full resources and powers\u201d, reflecting its low prioritisation of the issue in the past.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn September, he announced that the first 50 air quality audits for primary schools in the worst-polluted areas&nbsp;of the city had been launched with the objective to reduce air pollution around public schools.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-41254593|title=Audit to protect 'pupils from toxic air'|date=2017-09-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-09-14|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914192317/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-41254593|archivedate=14 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The audits will continue until the end of 2017, with reports being published in 2018.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n====Policing====\nIn an interview with [[LBC]], Khan accepted responsibility for knife crime in London as the Police and Crime Commissioner for the city, but blamed budgetary cuts by the UK [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] Government.<ref>https://jerseyeveningpost.com/news/uk-news/2018/06/07/london-mayor-accepts-responsibility-for-crime-situation-as-he-blames-police-cuts/</ref> Khan stated that knife crime is \"rising across England & Wales\" and that it is \"clearly a national problem that requires national solutions.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kerr |first1=Chloe |title=Met police set up new task force to deal with violent crime |url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/942870/london-news-met-police-knife-crime-task-force-crime |accessdate=10 July 2019 |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=7 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref>  Following the [[2019 London Bridge stabbing]] Khan stated, \u201cYou can\u2019t disaggregate terrorism and security from cuts made to resources of the police, of probation, the tools that judges have \u2026 The key thing is we need to support the police and security service. (...) The point I am making is we can be safer, with more police and more resources.\u201d<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/nov/30/london-bridge-attack-swift-review-of-violent-sentences-pledged Justice system playing 'Russian roulette' with public, says terror expert] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\n==Political image and views==\nWriting for ''[[The Spectator]]'', the political commentator [[Nick Cohen]] described Khan as a centre-left social democrat,<ref>{{cite web|author=Nick Cohen |title=Would Jeremy Corbyn prefer George Galloway to be Mayor of London? |website=The Spectator |date=10 February 2016 |url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/would-jeremy-corbyn-prefer-george-galloway-to-be-mayor-of-london/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160211090622/http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/would-jeremy-corbyn-prefer-george-galloway-to-be-mayor-of-london/ |archivedate=11 February 2016 }}</ref> while the journalist [[Amol Rajan]] termed him \"a torch-bearer for the social democratic wing\" of the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite web |author=Amol Rajan |title=After Boris, Mayor Khan for London? |date=15 September 2015 |website=Politico |url=http://www.politico.eu/article/tooting-to-victory-london-sadiq-khan-mayor-corbyn-goldsmith-boris-johnson-bevin/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314141400/http://www.politico.eu/article/tooting-to-victory-london-sadiq-khan-mayor-corbyn-goldsmith-boris-johnson-bevin/ |archivedate=14 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The BBC describe Khan as being located on the party's [[soft left]].<ref>{{cite news |title=London mayor: The Sadiq Khan story |author=Esther Webber |work=BBC News |date=7 May 2016 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-36140479 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507141456/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-36140479 |archivedate=7 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In an article for [[Al Jazeera]], the [[Marxism|Marxist]] commentator [[Richard Seymour (writer)|Richard Seymour]] described Khan as a [[centrism|centrist]],<ref>{{cite web |author=Richard Seymour |title=Sadiq Khan's victory and free Londonistan |publisher=Al Jazeera |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2016/05/sadiq-khan-victory-free-londonistan-160507174122069.html |date=8 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615015120/http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2016/05/sadiq-khan-victory-free-londonistan-160507174122069.html |archivedate=15 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> while Matt Wrack, the General Secretary of the [[Fire Brigades Union]], characterised Khan as belonging to \"that part of the Labour Party that was in government under Blair and Brown\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Watts |first=Joe |title=Sadiq Khan faces backlash after saying Jeremy Corbyn election win is 'extremely unlikely' |website=The Independent |date=22 August 2016 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/a-counter-offensive-has-been-launched-against-sadiq-khan-after-the-london-mayor-said-a-jeremy-corbyn-a7202496.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708221128/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/a-counter-offensive-has-been-launched-against-sadiq-khan-after-the-london-mayor-said-a-jeremy-corbyn-a7202496.html |archivedate=8 July 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The journalist Dave Hill described Khan as a [[social liberalism|social liberal]].<ref name=\"100 days\">{{cite web |last=Hill |first=Dave |title=Sadiq Khan's first 100 days as London mayor: how is he doing? |date=16 August 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/16/sadiq-khans-first-100-days-as-london-mayor-how-is-he-doing |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221155635/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/16/sadiq-khans-first-100-days-as-london-mayor-how-is-he-doing |archivedate=21 February 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:London June 8 2019 (79) Eid Trafalgar Square Mayor Sadiq Khan (48026201552).jpg|thumb|left|Khan at a 2019 Eid event in Trafalgar Square, London]]\n\nKhan has described himself as a \"proud feminist\".<ref name=\"100 days\"/> In April 2019, Khan joined the [[Jewish Labour Movement]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Oster |first1=Marcy |title=London Mayor Sadiq Khan joins Jewish Labour movement |url=https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/london-mayor-sadiq-khan-joins-jewish-labour-movement#.XL8400Ai0D8 |website=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |publisher=70 Faces Media |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nKhan considers himself as a practising Muslim.<ref>Jane Onyanga-Omara, [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2016/05/06/sadiq-khan-london-mayor-muslim/84016822/ 5 things to know about London's first Muslim mayor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116015859/http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2016/05/06/sadiq-khan-london-mayor-muslim/84016822/ |date=16 January 2017 }}, ''USA Today'' (May 6, 2017).</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=London elects Sadiq Khan, first Muslim mayor, after ugly campaign|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/05/06/europe/uk-london-mayoral-race-sadiq-khan/index.html}}</ref> He quotes from the [[Quran]] and [[hadith]] when discussing terrorism.<ref name=newyorker/> He received death threats from Islamic extremists after voting in favour of the [[Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013|Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act]].{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=58}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/02/18/labour-mp-sadiq-khan-receives-death-threats-for-supporting-same-sex-marriage/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-04 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330023159/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/02/18/labour-mp-sadiq-khan-receives-death-threats-for-supporting-same-sex-marriage/ |archivedate=30 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was also threatened by the far-right group [[Britain First]], which in 2016 threatened to take \"[[direct action]]\" against Khan where he \"lives, works and prays\" as part of an anti-Muslim campaign.<ref>Olivia Blair, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/sadiq-khan-britain-first-london-mayor-threaten-direct-action-a7047991.html Britain First threatens to target London Mayor Sadiq Khan with 'direct action'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912193411/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/sadiq-khan-britain-first-london-mayor-threaten-direct-action-a7047991.html |date=12 September 2017 }}, ''The Independent'' (May 25, 2016).</ref>\n\nJournalist Dave Hill has said that Khan was \"savvy, streetwise and not averse to a scrap\",{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=101}} whilst also describing him as having a \"joshing, livewire off-stage personality\" which differed from the formal image he often projected while onstage.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=59}}\nKhan used to perform [[stand-up comedy]] before running for Mayor, including a ten-minute money-raising ''Stand Up for Labour'' routine. Comedian [[Arthur Smith (comedian)|Arthur Smith]] stated that Khan could become a \"good club-level comedian one day\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2016/09/05/25710/sadiq_khan%3A_i_used_to_do_stand-up|title=Sadiq Khan: 'I used to do stand-up'|work=Chortle|year=2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927083831/http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2016/09/05/25710/sadiq_khan%3A_i_used_to_do_stand-up|archivedate=27 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> During the 2016 Mayoral campaign, Goldsmith referred to Khan as \"a caricature machine politician... the sort of politician who justified peoples' mistrust in politics\", as evidence citing Khan's U-turn on supporting Heathrow expansion.{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=116}}\nAnother rival in the 2016 Mayoral campaign, [[George Galloway]] of the [[Respect Party]], referred to Khan as a \"flip-flop merchant\" and a \"product of the Blairite machine\".{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=139}}\n\nThere has been an ongoing political feud between Khan and US president [[Donald Trump]] since 2016, when Khan criticised Trump over his proposed \"[[Trump travel ban|Muslim ban]]\" and Trump responded by attacking Khan a number of times on Twitter over the next several years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weaver |first1=Matthew |title=Timeline: Donald Trump's feud with Sadiq Khan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jun/03/timeline-donald-trump-feud-with-sadiq-khan |accessdate=10 July 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=16 June 2019}}</ref> Shortly before Trump's 2019 state visit to the UK, Khan compared Trump to \"European dictators of the 1930s and 40s\".<ref>{{Citation|title=It's un-British to roll out the red carpet for Donald Trump \u2013 Sadiq Khan|date=1 June 2019|website=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jun/01/donald-trump-state-visit-red-carpet-unbritish}}</ref> Upon arrival, Trump responded on Twitter by calling him a \"stone-cold loser\" and comparing him to another mayor he also targets, [[Bill de Blasio]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Trump attacks London mayor in tweets before landing \u2013 CNN Video|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/06/03/trump-tweet-sadiq-khan-uk-visit-es-vpx.cnn|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Six months after his election as the MP for Tooting, ''[[The Spectator]]'' awarded Khan Newcomer of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2005/11/parliamentarian-of-the-year/|title=Parliamentarian of the Year|date=2005-11-19|website=The Spectator|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n* Khan was nominated for the Politician of the Year Award at the [[British Muslim Awards]] in January 2013 and 2015 and won the award in February 2016.<ref name=\"asianimage\">{{cite news|url=http://www.asianimage.co.uk/news/10197507.Winners_honoured_at_British_Muslim_Awards/|title=Winners honoured at British Muslim Awards|publisher=Asian Image|date=31 January 2013|accessdate=1 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121173521/http://www.asianimage.co.uk/news/10197507.Winners_honoured_at_British_Muslim_Awards/|archivedate=21 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"asianworldnews\">{{cite news|url=http://www.asianworldnews.co.uk/business/british-muslim-awards-2016/|title=British Muslim Awards 2016|publisher=Asian World|date=17 February 2016|accessdate=1 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421220433/http://asianworldnews.co.uk/business/british-muslim-awards-2016/|archivedate=21 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* In late 2016 and 2017, Khan won and accepted the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[GQ]]\u2019s Politician of the Year Award.<ref>[https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/gallery/anthony-joshua-jared-leto-stormzy]</ref>\n* In 2017, he was awarded an Honorary Doctorate from the [[University of Law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://universitybusiness.co.uk/Article/the-university-of-law-awards-sadiq-khan/|title=The University of Law awards Sadiq Khan|website=University Business|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n* In 2018, Khan was conferred [[Sitara-e-Pakistan]] for his services to Pakistan by the Pakistani President [[Mamnoon Hussain]].<ref>{{cite news |title=President Mamnoon confers civil awards on Yaum-i-Pakistan |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1397075 |work=Dawn}}</ref>\n* In 2018, he became an Honorary Fellowship by the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architecture.com/knowledge-and-resources/knowledge-landing-page/riba-honorary-fellowships-2018-announced|title=RIBA Honorary Fellowships 2018 announced|website=www.architecture.com|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n* In 2019, Khan became an Honorary Bencher of [[Middle Temple]] Inn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.middletemple.org.uk/civicrm/event/info?reset=1&id=40086|title=Middle Temple|website=www.middletemple.org.uk|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKhan is a practising [[Muslim]] who observes the fast during [[Ramadan]] and regularly attends Al-Muzzammil Mosque in Tooting.<ref>{{cite web|title=London elects its first Muslim mayor and the journalism world rightly notes its importance|url=http://www.getreligion.org/getreligion/2016/5/8/london-elects-a-muslim-mayor-and-the-journalism-world-rightly-notes-it-as-a-new-day|publisher=Getreligion.org|accessdate=14 May 2016|date=9 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511121118/http://www.getreligion.org/getreligion/2016/5/8/london-elects-a-muslim-mayor-and-the-journalism-world-rightly-notes-it-as-a-new-day|archivedate=11 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherwood\">{{cite news|last1=Sherwood|first1=Harriet|title='This is our moment': Tooting Muslims laud Sadiq Khan victory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/07/our-moment-tooting-muslims-sadiq-khan-london-mayoral-election-victory|accessdate=14 May 2016|work=The Guardian|date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512035232/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/07/our-moment-tooting-muslims-sadiq-khan-london-mayoral-election-victory|archivedate=12 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sadiq hosts Eid celebrations|url=http://www.sadiqkhan.org.uk/sadiq_hosts_eid_celebrations|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609203340/http://www.sadiqkhan.org.uk/sadiq_hosts_eid_celebrations|publisher=sadiqkhan.org.uk|archive-date=9 June 2016|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=58}}<ref name=\"Sherwood\" /> Journalist Dave Hill described Khan as \"a moderate, socially liberal Muslim\".<ref name=\"Eid\"/> Khan has expressed the view that \"too often the people who are 'representing' the Islamic faith aren't representative, they're angry men with beards. And that is not what Islam is about.\"{{sfn|Hill|2016|p=83}}\n\nKhan married Saadiya Ahmed, a fellow solicitor, in 1994. They have two daughters,<ref name=\"pugilist\" /> both raised in the Islamic faith.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Crerar |first1=Pippa |last2=Edwardes |first2=Charlotte |title=Sadiq Khan says 'I'm like a stressed Victorian dad' in revealing interview about his family and religion |website=London Evening Standard |date=13 July 2016 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-says-im-like-a-stressed-victorian-dad-in-revealing-interview-where-he-talks-about-his-a3294436.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714151534/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-says-im-like-a-stressed-victorian-dad-in-revealing-interview-where-he-talks-about-his-a3294436.html |archivedate=14 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2016 London mayoral election]]\n* [[List of British Pakistanis]]\n<!--\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hill |first=Dave |year=2016 |title=Zac Versus Sadiq: The Fight to Become London Mayor |location= |publisher=Double Q |isbn=978-1-911079-20-0 |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sadiq Khan}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.sadiq.london/}}\n* [http://www.sadiq.london/ Sadiq Khan \u2013 Labour Candidate for Mayor of London] official site\n{{UK MP links| parliament = sadiq-khan/1577|hansard=<!--mr-sadiq-khan-->|hansardcurr=4801|guardian=8847/sadiq-khan|publicwhip=Sadiq_Khan|theywork=sadiq_khan|record=Sadiq-Khan/Tooting/272|bbc=35774.stm|journalisted =sadiq-khan}}\n* [https://twitter.com/SadiqKhan @SadiqKhan Verified Twitter Account]\n* [https://twitter.com/MayorofLondon @MayorofLondon Official Verified Twitter Account]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tom Cox (British politician)|Tom Cox]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Tooting (UK Parliament constituency)|Tooting]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013[[2016 Tooting by-election|2016]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rosena Allin-Khan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Parmjit Dhanda]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Communities and Local Government|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]|years=2008\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Shahid Malik]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis|The Lord Adonis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of State for Transport]]|years=2009\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Theresa Villiers]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]]|years=2010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Maria Eagle]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Jack Straw]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Justice]]|years=2010\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after={{nowrap|[[Charles Falconer, Baron Falconer of Thoroton|The Lord Falconer of Thoroton]]}}}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Lord Chancellor]]|years=2010\u20132015}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tessa Jowell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for London|Shadow Minister for London]]|years=2013\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=''None''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Boris Johnson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of London]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Chair of the [[Fabian Society]]|years=2008\u20132010|before=[[Anne Campbell]]|after=[[Suresh Pushpananthan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{Miliband Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{Labour Party London mayoral selection, 2015}}\n{{Mayors of London}}\n{{Mayors of the largest cities in the world by GDP}}\n{{Fabian Society}}\n{{Portal bar|London|Biography|Politics|United Kingdom|Socialism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Sadiq}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Advocates of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Alumni of London Metropolitan University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of North London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The College of Law]]\n[[Category:British lawyers of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Wandsworth]]\n[[Category:English Muslims]]\n[[Category:English people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:English feminists]]\n[[Category:Proponents of Islamic feminism]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) mayors]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Mayors of London]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Muhajir people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ernest Bevin College]]\n[[Category:Social democrats]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u