{"title_page": "The Doon School", "text_new": "{{in use}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|Boys' boarding school in Dehradun, India}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | image                   = The Doon School.jpg\n | caption                 = Main Building at The Doon School\n | image_size              = 300px\n | name                    = The Doon School\n | logo                    = The Doon School, Dehradun - logo.png\n | logo_size               = 150px\n | colours                 = Blue & White {{color box|#005293}} {{color box|white}}\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30.333|78.030|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n | pushpin_map             = India Uttarakhand#India\n | location                = The Doon School<br>Mall Road<br>[[Dehradun]]&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;248001<br>India<br>([https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/The+Doon+School/@30.3350253,78.0298105,17z Google Map], [https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/158385701 OpenStreetMap])\n | specialist              = \n | schooltype              = Independent [[boarding school]]\n | motto                   = '' Knowledge our Light''\n | sister_school           = [[Welham Girls' School]]\n | established             = \n | founded                 = {{Start date and age|1935|09|10}}\n | founder                 = [[Satish Ranjan Das]]\n | head_name               = Founder Headmaster\n | head                    = [[Arthur Foot|Arthur Edward Foot]]\n | gender                  = Boys\n | lower_age               = 12\n | upper_age               = 18\n | headmaster              = Post vacant \n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governors\n | chair                   = [[Sunil Kant Munjal]]\n | pupils                  = c. 600\n | faculty                 = 70\n | houses                  = 5 houses + 2 holding houses\n | campus                  = 72 acres (297,314&nbsp;m\u00b2)\n | ceeb                    = 671616\n | district                = [[Dehradun district|Dehradun District]]\n | student_union           = [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n | affiliation             = [[International Baccalaureate|IB]]<br>[[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examination|CISCE]]<br>[[International General Certificate of Secondary Education|IGCSE]]\n | publication             = ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]''\n | free_label2             = Annual fees\n | free_text2              = {{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1025000}} (home students)<br>{{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1281000}} (international)\n | free_label              = Former pupils\n | free_text               = [[List of The Doon School alumni|Doscos]]\n | website                 = [http://www.doonschool.com/ www.doonschool.com]\n}}\n\n'''The Doon School''' (informally '''Doon School''' or '''Doon''') is a boys-only private, [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]] [[Selective school|selective]] boarding school in Dehradun, Uttarakhand, India, established in 1935. It was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a [[Kolkata]] lawyer, who prevised a school modelled on the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]], but conscious of Indian ambitions and desires.<ref name=\"auto\">MacDougall2006-page100</ref> Although he died in 1928, he is considered the founder of the school. The school's first [[Head teacher|headmaster]] was an Englishman, [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], who had spent nine years as a science master at [[Eton College]], England.<ref>{{cite book|year=1979|chapter=FOOT, Arthur Edward|title=Who Was Who 1961\u20131970|location=London|publisher=A. & C. Black|isbn=0-7136-2008-0}}</ref> The last headmaster was [[Matthew Raggett]], who resigned in January 2020. He was the fourth British headmaster in Doon's history and a member of [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]], [[UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/|title=The Doon School|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nDoon houses roughly 500 pupils aged 13 to 18, and admission is based on a competitive entrance examination, a group discussion and an interview with the headmaster.<ref name=\"wsj\" /> Every year in January and April, the school admits pupils aged 13 in Grade 7 (known as D-form) and aged 14 in Grade 8 (C-form) respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kapoor |first=Jaskiran |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/class-apart/601507/0 |title=Class Apart |publisher=Indian Express |date=11 April 2010 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> Doon remains a boys-only school despite continued pressure from political leaders, including former [[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]], to become [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]].<ref name=\"president\">{{cite news |last=Chopra |first=Jaskiran |title=President leads assault on Doon School heritage |newspaper=[[The Pioneer (Indian newspaper)|The Pioneer]] |date=24 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nDoon has been consistently ranked the best all-boys residential school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite news |title=3 Bangalore schools among India's best |first=Neha |last=Pushkarna |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-10-09/bangalore/30259994_1_bangalore-schools-shri-ram-school-parental-involvement |newspaper=The Times of India|publisher=The Times Group|date=9 October 2011 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?218344 |title=India's Best Schools |newspaper=Outlook |publisher=Outlook Newsmagazine |date=16 December 2002 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref> Although the school has often been cited as 'Eton of India' by media outlets such as the ''[[BBC]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02c3zgq|title=BBC World Service - Witness, India's Eton|website=BBC}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|author=STEVEN R. WEISMAN, Special to the New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/12/world/india-s-old-school-tie-harrow-by-the-himalayas.html |title=India'S Old School Tie - Harrow By The Himalayas |location=Dehra Dun (India); India |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=12 November 1985 |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/aug/13/fiction.arundhatiroy|title=The lost sub-continent|first=William|last=Dalrymple|date=13 August 2005|website=the Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Spectator]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author=Read |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/03/its-a-spartan-life-at-the-eton-of-india/# |title=It's a spartan life at 'the Eton of India' |publisher=The Spectator |date= |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/alastair-sooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html|title=The rise & rise of Anish Kapoor Inc.|first=Alastair|last=Sooke|date=2 April 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> ''[[Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Remnick |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/10/20/rajiv-gandhi-and-the-mantle-unsought/779cee82-b666-4248-8116-278d6134a002/ |title=Rajiv Gandhi And The Mantle Unsought |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1987-10-20 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> and ''[[Forbes]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/10/28/the-doon-school-grooming-ground-for-indias-wealthy-kids/|title=The Doon School: Grooming Ground For India's Wealthy Kids|first=Forbes|last=Staff|website=Forbes}}</ref> it strongly eschews the label.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Doon-of-India-wants-to-conquer-the-globe/articleshow/6800690.cms |title=\u2018Doon of India\u2019 wants to conquer the globe - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> [[Old boy network|Old boys]] of the school are commonly known as ''Doscos''.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\">{{citation|last=MacDougall|first=David|title=The corporeal image: film, ethnography, and the senses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&pg=PA107|accessdate=31 March 2012|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12156-7|pages=107\u2013108}}</ref>  Although the total number of former pupils is relatively small (estimated at 5,000 since the school's founding), they include some of India's most prominent politicians, government officials and business leaders.<ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709213757/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=For wannabe Doons, don from hills is a boon |newspaper=Times of India |date=30 December 2002 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> The best known alumnus is the late Indian Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:The Doon School main building (then FRI) - 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|Main building of Doon in 1917, when it was part of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].]]\n[[File:Main Gate, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main gate of the Doon School.]]\nDoon was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a lawyer from Calcutta and advocate-general of Bengal, who in 1927 became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council]] of [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Irwin]] on the condition that he would use the prestige of this position to raise funds for a new type of school in [[India]].<ref>''The Indian Year Book'', vol. 29 (1942), p. 419: \"Doon School&nbsp;\u2013 This school which is established in the Chand Bagh and Skinner's Estates at Dehra Doon owes its origin to the initiative and enthusiasm of the late SR Das.\"</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Rudrangshu |last=Mukherjee |authorlink=Rudrangshu Mukherjee |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1020707/editoria.htm |title=Editorial > Remains of the Past |work=The Telegraph|location=Kolkata |date=21 May 1985 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref> He decided to name the new school \"Doon\", as it was situated in the [[Doon Valley]]. He travelled widely in [[India]] with the goal of collecting {{Indian Rupee}}4&nbsp;million, but at the time of his death had raised only {{Indian Rupee}}1 million in cash and a further {{Indian Rupee}}1&nbsp;million in promises. With the money, Das formed the Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which had the objective of founding new public schools in [[India]] that would admit students regardless of caste, creed or social status. Under the IPSS, a Board of Governors supervises all matters of Doon.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 41: \"...the body founded by Das for the purposes of establishing the Doon School, the Indian Public Schools Society\"</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Das in 1928, the IPSS accomplished little, and by 1934 some of the original lenders had begun to inquire about the return of their money. To solve this problem, Sir Joseph Bhore, then Railway Minister of [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|Lord Willingdon's]] Council, became IPSS chairman and, with [[Akbar Hydari|Sir Akbar Hydari]] as secretary, worked to obtain the former estate of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] in [[Dehra Dun]] on favourable terms. Sir Frank Noyce also joined the team. [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], then President of the British Board of Education, led a selection committee that nominated [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], a science teacher at [[Eton College]], to be the first headmaster.<ref name=\"excellence\">{{cite journal|title=Excellence personified |journal=Frontline |date=12 February 2011 |volume=28 |issue=4 |url=http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313163529/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> On 27 October 1935, the [[Viceroy]], [[Lord Willingdon]], presided over the formal opening of the school. Seventy boys enrolled in the first [[Academic term|term]], and 110 more signed up for the second.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 203 (Note 12): \"...from Willingdon's inaugural address on 27 October 1935\"</ref>\n\nThe [[House system|houses]] at the new school were originally named after their respective [[housemaster]]s, but later renamed in honour of the largest presenter to the IPSS: Hyderabad House was named after Sir [[Akbar Hydari]] secured a contribution of {{Indian Rupee}} 200,000 from the [[Nizam of Hyderabad]]'s government;. [[Kashmir House]], after [[Maharajah]] [[Hari Singh]], then ruler of [[Jammu and Kashmir]], promised a contribution of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000, which was delivered in 1935;. Tata House, after the [[Tata family|Tata]] and [[Wadia family|Wadia]] Trusts promised {{Indian Rupee}}150,000, half of which was delivered in 1935;. Jaipur House, after [[Rai Bahadur]] Amarnath Atal arranged for contributions of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000 from the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] of [[Jaipur]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 197 (Appendix 1): \"Donors to the Indian Public Schools' Society prior to 1936\"</ref> No building was named after [[Rai Bahadur]] Rameshwar Nathany, since his donation of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000 was initially anonymous.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/constructingpost0000sriv |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/constructingpost0000sriv/page/224 224] |quote=rai bahadur. |title=Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School|publisher=Psychology Press |first=Sanjay|last=Srivastava |accessdate=6 March 2012|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref>\n\n===Early years:1935\u20131970===\n\n[[Arthur Foot]] had never visited [[India]] before accepting the position of headmaster. He noted that the school appeared to be surrounded by forests and close to mountains, and the possibilities of outdoor recreation and mountaineering seem to have influenced his decision as much as the chance to create a completely new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"sixtyyears\">{{cite book|title=The Doon School Sixty Years On |publisher=Doon School Old Boys' Society|date=October 1996}}</ref> Foot's first action upon being offered the position was to recruit [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J.A.K. (John) Martyn]] from [[Harrow School]] as his deputy. Doon's ethos and guiding principles were determined early in its life by Foot, Martyn, [[R. L. Holdsworth|R.L. Holdsworth]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]], who went on to become Principal of [[Mayo College]]. While these masters all came from very traditional British schools,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnathersuch.com/op_website/op_owners_text.htm |title=Ottershaw Park |publisher=Johnathersuch.com |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> they were determined to create a uniquely Indian public school rather than a transplanted British institution, and they were soon joined in their efforts by equally influential Indians such as [[Sudhir Khastgir]] (the school's first art teacher, who had trained previously in [[Santiniketan]]) and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], a pioneering mountaineer who taught at Doon for several decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =...&nbsp;By 14 he should have learnt all the ordinary principles of social behaviour. He should know how to stand up and speak to a variety of different types of people&nbsp;\u2013 to his own mother, to someone else's mother, to his father, to his schoolmasters, to servants, to Mahatma Gandhi or to the Viceroy, and to do this without any self-consciousness&nbsp;...At 17 must come another quality, less instinctive and requiring a maturer mind: he must acquire a capacity of judgement.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" />&nbsp;...\n |source = <small>Arthur Foot, 1946, ''The Objects of Education''</small>\n |align  = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\n\nIn an essay entitled ''The Objects of Education'' published in the school magazine, Foot offered a template for a complete education for boys, which included teaching them to distinguish clearly between good and evil, form a habit of choosing good over evil, think logically, express their thoughts and views clearly, and maintain a healthy body.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" /> Martyn, who was involved with Doon for several decades and became its second headmaster, acknowledged the influence of German educator [[Kurt Hahn]] in the development of the school's ethos. Although Martyn had not visited India before, he immediately accepted Foot's offer because of the opportunity it afforded to implement Hahn's ideas, which he had not been able to do at Harrow.<ref>{{cite web|author=site admin |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19851115-book-review-sumer-singh-doon-the-story-of-a-school-mady-martyn-martyn-sahib-802174-2014-01-16 |title=Where East meets West - Society & The Arts News - Issue Date: Nov 15, 1985 |publisher=Indiatoday.in |date=1985-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Martyn acknowledged Foot's leadership in the development of the school, but added that they both had similar ideas: \"I would not have been as bold as he was in trying to eliminate punishments, but we were equally keen on providing as wide a range as possible of activities that were creative and challenging&nbsp;... The problem, as we saw it, was to create an atmosphere in which boys would learn the importance of public spirit at the same time as they acquired self-confidence and initiative.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=38|quote=When John wrote to Hahn to tell him we was going to India, Hahn replied that he had been waiting to be able to offer him a place at Gordonstoun...}}</ref>\n\nFoot and Martyn, the first two headmasters at Doon, were both from elite British institutions&nbsp;\u2013 Eton College and Harrow School. They were determined to model Doon on those two schools, but both agreed that it should cater primarily for Indian boys rather than the sons of British expatriates. The public school jargon introduced by these headmasters is still in use. For example, the weekly masters' meeting, started by Foot, is called ''Chambers'', a term taken from Eton, and evening \"prep\" (the boarding-school equivalent of homework) is called ''Toye-time'', a term taken from [[Winchester College]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Charles |last1=Stevens|first2=Christopher|last2=Stray|title=Winchester notions: the English dialect of Winchester College|publisher=Athlone Press|year=1998|page=294|quote=Toy-time, or toytime recorded from 1831 as the evening hours of preparation, called 'prep' elsewhere&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB917469665815143000 |title=Language Lessons: For India's Elite English Is the Past -- and the Future\n|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Though Foot modelled Doon on Eton and Harrow (and the school is often called the \"Eton of India\" by various press agencies), he did not want Doon to be considered elitist.<ref name=\"anish\">{{cite news|last=Botsman |first=John |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturecritics/alastairsooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html |title=The Rise of Anish Kapoor|newspaper=The Telegraph, U.K. |date=1 November 2009 |accessdate=2 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"suitablejoy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/mar/27/books.guardianreview1 |title=A suitable joy|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 March 1999 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jun/09/india.kashmir2 |title=Which way now for India?|newspaper=The Guardian|date=8 June 2002 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref> Foot once said, \"our boys will join an aristocracy, but it\u2019s an aristocracy of service, not one of wealth, privilege or position\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/interview_doon-school-is-popular-for-building-an-aristocracy-of-service_1392063 |title=Doon School is popular for building an 'aristocracy of service'&nbsp;\u2013 Academy|work=DNA |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> \n\n===1970\u2013End of 20th century===\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-right:1em; font-size:85%; background:#ffc; color:black; width:20em; max-width:25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Headmasters\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n* [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], 1935\u20131948\n* [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J. A. K. Martyn]], 1948\u20131966\n* [[C. J. Miller]], 1966\u20131970\n* [[Eric Simeon|Eric J. Simeon]], 1970\u20131979\n* [[Gulab Ramchandani]], 1979\u20131988\n* [[Shomie Das]], 1988\u20131996\n* [[John Mason (Schoolmaster)|John A. Mason]], 1996\u20132003\n* [[Kanti Bajpai]], 2003\u20132009\n* [[Peter McLaughlin]], 2009\u20132016\n* [[Matthew Raggett]], 2016\u20132020 \n|}\n\nThe school's first Indian headmaster was [[Eric Simeon]], appointed in 1970. He came from a military background and laid great emphasis on disciplined living.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/schooled-for-life/32471/|title=Schooled for life - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/05/16/stories/2007051615082000.htm |title=Lt. Col. Eric Joseph Simeon dead |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> During Simeon's tenure of nine years, the school faced financial difficulties. The estate suffered as the funds were not enough to maintain buildings and facilities.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/weekly/May%2019%202007.pdf</ref> In 1979, [[Gulab Ramchandani]] became the first alumnus to be appointed headmaster. In 1988, [[Shomie Das]], another alumnus and the grandson of school founder Satish Ranjan Das, became headmaster. Das's focus was to upgrade the school infrastructure and during his tenure the Oberoi house was added to the original four houses. The next headmaster, [[John Mason (schoolmaster)|John Mason]], appointed in 1996, planned on making Doon more affordable to school pupils; the school did not raise its fees during his tenure. \n\n====Criticism of Rajiv Gandhi administration====\n\nIn the 1980s, the then [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Rajiv Gandhi]], an alumnus, drew criticism from the media for appointing many old boys to his administration. His inner circle was labelled a \"Doon cabinet\" or \"Dosco Mafia\"<ref>''Indian Tales of the Raj'' by Zareer Masani, p.152</ref> and ''Washington Post'' reported, \"The catch phrase around Delhi these days is that the 'Doon School runs India,' but that is too simple an analysis for a complex, chaotic country with so many competing spheres of influence.\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\">{{cite web|last=Bumiller |first=Elisabeth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1985/11/24/where-indias-elite-were-boys-together/0579f3d9-1835-4441-b1b1-a55e3111bdc3/ |title=Where India's Elite Were Boys Together |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1985-11-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Steven R. Weisman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/20/magazine/the-rajiv-generation.html |title=THE RAJIV GENERATION - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1986-04-20 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gandhi's reliance on Doon alumni for political advice later led Prime Minister [[Morarji Desai]] to remark, \"If I had anything to do with this place, I'd close it down\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0724/eindia.html|title=Bootstrap steps for Gandhi|date=24 July 1987|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref>\n\n===2000-Present day===\nIn 2003, [[Kanti Bajpai]] became the third old boy to become headmaster, after Gulab Ramchandani and Shomie Das. He introduced numerous punishments, notably \"yellow cards\", to control an outburst of bullying at Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03cgg70 |title=BBC World Service - Path to Power, Educating India's Elite |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1994-10-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> In 2006, Bajpai found himself embroiled in a controversy when the parents of Hindu and Sikh students complained on discovering that the school's dining hall only serves [[halal]] meat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bad-blood-over-meat-served-at-Doon-School/articleshow/1516879.cms|title=Bad blood over meat served at Doon School &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The matter was brought to light after a visiting Pakistani delegation was assured of their meal's halal status. Later, the school's board of governors called for a status quo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/doon-debates-meaty-matters/story-mQ4y1Lt1fXLI3DiW2cV3XI.html|title=Doon debates meaty matters|date=3 May 2006|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> As of 2016, the school was serving both halal and non-halal (''jhatka'') meat varieties.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2434-FINAL.pdf</ref> In 2009, [[Peter McLaughlin]], an Irish academic, was chosen to lead the school, becoming the first non-Indian headmaster in almost four decades. Shortly before taking up his appointment he said, \"We will be adhering to the school credo of engaging individuals in socially productive work, at the same time delivering on quality education.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20090526/dplus.htm#3 |work=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India|title=Dehradun Plus |date=26 May 2009 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2010 Founder's Day celebrations====\n[[File:President of India speaking at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]] speaking at the Doon School's Platinum Jubilee in October 2010.]]\n\nIn 2010, Doon celebrated its 75th Founder's Day, a three-four day event in the Autumn Term, usually October, that marks the school's founding. <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/item/40943-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doonschool.com/founders-day-celebrations |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091019061244/http://www.doonschool.com/founders-day-celebrations |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 October 2009 |title=Founder's Day Celebrations 2009 |publisher=The Doon School |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> The Founder's Day draws many ex-pupils from all parts of the world and security on campus is tight, since alumni attending the event often include senior politicians and government officials. The chief guest is usually a prominent person.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/how-indias-renowned-doon-school-is-embracing-change-to-retain-its-exclusivity/articleshow/45006985.cms?from=mdr |title=How India's renowned Doon School is embracing change to retain its exclusivity - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-11-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The event includes productions of English dramas followed by an orchestral concert given by members of the school's Music Society.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Hill Post|url=http://hillpost.in/2011/10/28/doon-school-celebrates-76-th-founders-day/33352/latest-news/bhatt |title=Doon School celebrates 76 th founders day |date=28 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Datta |first=Sravasti |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523113538/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 May 2011 |title=Life & Style / Metroplus : All boarders on board |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 February 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe 75th Founder's Day was christened ''DS-75''.<ref name=\"Doon school\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-08/news/27591639_1_celebrations-doon-school-chief-guest |title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21 |publisher=[[The Times Group]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Back to School\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/KaranThapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104092100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/karanthapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2010 |last=Thapar|first=Karan|title=Back to School |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School\">{{cite news|title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/15930-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |newspaper=Daily Pioneer|date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Among the chief guests were the then President [[Pratibha Patil]] of India, King [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]] of Bhutan and [[Kapil Sibal]], (then [[Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)|Union Minister for Human Resource Development]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bhutanjournals.com/monarchy/hms-address-at-doon-school-dehradun-india/ |title=HM's Address at Doon School, Dehradun, India|newspaper=Bhutan Journals |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Pratibha Patil, in her address, urged the school authorities to make Doon a co-educational institution. One of the main events was a discussion, dubbed the \"Chandbagh Debate\", held between alumni including [[Vikram Seth]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Manpreet Singh Badal]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] and retired headmaster Kanti Bajpai, on the topic ''Can India lead?''. It was moderated by television commentator [[Karan Thapar]], an alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+matter+of+debate+at+Doon+School+platinum+jubilee.-a0240443417 |title=A matter of debate at Doon School platinum jubilee|newspaper=[[India Today]] |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Ashvin Kumar]] made the film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'' for the celebrations, using pupils for the cast and crew. Most of it was shot in June and July during the summer break, and those scenes which required the entire student body were filmed after the school reopened in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imaginox.co.uk/course/1718 |title=Making 'Dazed in Doon' |publisher=Imaginox |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Doon School, however, objected to the film and its distribution, obtaining a court order to delay its release and labelling it \"defamatory\".<ref name=dazed>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-interviews/28271042_1_film-doon-school-ashvin-kumar|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film|newspaper=The Times of India|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=fallout>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-18/news-interviews/28230561_1_doon-short-film-ashvin|title=Doon film fallout!|newspaper=The Times of India|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=Doon-film-banned>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-03/news-interviews/28366688_1_doon-school-doon-film-dehradun|title=Doon film banned in Dehradun|newspaper=The Times of India|date=3 February 2011|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=ex-student-film>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120701125916/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 July 2012|title=Ex-student's film celebrating Doon draws school's ire|newspaper=The Times of India|date=25 December 2010}}</ref> On 22 October 2010, a commemorative postage stamp depicting the school's main building was released by the [[Indian Postal Service]] to mark the occasion of the 75th Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101009/dplus.htm#5 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016 the school announced the appointment of Matthew Raggett, principal of the [[Leipzig International School]]'s secondary department, to succeed Peter McLaughlin from the end of the summer term. In recent years, boys from the [[North Indian]] states have dominated the student demographic. To make the school more diverse, Raggett continued McLaughlin's initiative by inviting more applications from boys in [[South Indian]] cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/doon-school-looks-for-more-boys-from-south/articleshow/57725021.cms|title=Doon School: Doon School looks for more boys from south &#124; Bengaluru News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/doons-bonds-with-hyderabad/article7072329.ece|title=Doon\u2019s bonds with Hyderabad|first=R. Ravikanth|last=Reddy|date=6 April 2015|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> He also introduced a group discussion as part of the admissions process to test for critical thinking and peer interaction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/dehradun/after-8-decades-doon-school-looks-to-south-east-for-students/story-4uYQRMF8qalW61HFHuB0xM.html|title=After 8 decades, Doon School looks to South, East for students|date=3 July 2017|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> In January 2020, Matthew Raggett stepped down as the tenth headmaster citing personal reasons. In March 2020, the school was shut down and boys were sent home due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]] and [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|Indian lockdown]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/three-city-based-boarding-schools-close/articleshow/74662334.cms|title=Coronavirus scare: Three city-based boarding schools close &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Online classes are being conducted for students through video conferencing apps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-launch-online-classes-to-complete-syllabus/articleshow/74781758.cms|title=Schools launch online classes to complete syllabus in parts of Uttarakhand &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:FC Barcelona camp at Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|Main Field of the school with Kashmir and Hyderabad houses in the background.]]\n\nThe school occupies a single campus covering approximately {{convert|72|acre|m2}} flanked by Chakrata Road and Mall Road in the [[Dehradun Cantonment]] area of Dehradun city, [[Uttarakhand]], India.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114929995090170584 |title=The Andover of India? |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Anita|last=Raghavan|date=24 June 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To house the school, the IPSS acquired Chandbagh Estate in Dehradun from the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] (FRI). Part of the estate was once a deer park. The IPSS also acquired an adjoining estate, now known as Skinner's Field, from the descendants of [[James Skinner (East India Company officer)|James Skinner]]. \n\n===Architecture===\nThe construction of the Main Building, then in FRI, was carried out by Imperial Public Works Department, and finished in 1911. Its Renaissance-style architecture was inspired by [[Basilica Palladiana]] in [[Vicenza]], Italy.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\" /> Many buildings on the campus have been designed by notable Indian architects or firms.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\" /> The library was designed by Romi Khosla, the Biology block by Ram Sharma, teachers' residences by Anagram Architects, and the new Arts and Media Centre, which was inaugurated in October 2010 and shortlisted for the 2010 World Architecture News Education Award, by alumnus Sandeep Khosla <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/5-schools-india-teach-lesson-design-architecture-pune-mumbai/|title=5 schools in India that offer a quick course in sensitive design and architecture|date=10 January 2020|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sandeep Khosla, Principal Architect , Khosla Associates |url=https://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/article/1507033/making-cut |title=Making the cut |publisher=Worldarchitecturenews.com |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Arts and Media Centre houses painting, ceramic, sculpture, and textile studios, along with a lecture hall, film and photography studio, publications' room and exhibition galleries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/86476/arts-and-media-centre-at-the-doon-school-khosla-associates/|title=Arts and Media Centre at the Doon School / Khosla Associates|date=4 November 2010|website=ArchDaily}}</ref> In 2016, the school's Main Building received an \"Honourable Mention\" under the [[UNESCO Asia Pacific Heritage Awards|UNESCO Asia-Pacific Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation]], following the conservation work carried out by Aishwarya Tipnis Architects on the more than a century-old building.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/doon-school-campus-extension-anagram-architects/|title=Take a tour of India\u2019s most elite private school, The Doon School campus|date=21 March 2018|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.one.un.org/page/restoration-of-prayer-hall-at-japan-shrine-wins-top-honor-in-unesco-asia-pacific-heritage-awards/ |title=Restoration of prayer hall at Japan shrine wins top honor in UNESCO Asia- Pacific Heritage Awards - UN India |publisher=In.one.un.org |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Natural environment===\nThe Chandbagh estate is located in a green part of [[Dehradun]] and a wide variety of [[flora]] and [[fauna]] are found on the estate, including many rare trees that date back to the days of the Forest Research Institute.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\">{{cite web|url=https://fountainink.in/essay/no-common-or-garden-affair |title=No common or garden affair &#124; Fountain Ink |publisher=Fountainink.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\" /> The school has over 150 species of trees on its campus, and the formal gardens attract a variety of birds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashant |first=Shishir |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/doon-schools-etp-may-be-trendsetter/428364/ |title=Doon school's ETP may be trendsetter |newspaper=[[Business Standard]] |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1996, a book titled ''Trees of Chandbagh'' was released which provided a comprehensive account of vegetation found on Doon's campus, known as Chandbagh.<ref name=\"TreesofChandbagh\">{{cite book|last=Sahni|first=K. C.|title=Trees of Chandbagh: Doon's national heritage|year=1996|publisher=Konark Publishers|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-220-0457-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> Along similar lines, the illustrated book ''Birds of Chandbagh: A Guide To Birding at The Doon School'' was released in 2019, featuring photographs, illustrations and [[QR codes]] documenting the [[bird calls]] of the species found on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.in/BIRDS-CHANDBAGH-guide-birding-School/dp/B084HG4R87 |title=Buy BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Book Online at Low Prices in India &#124; BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Reviews & Ratings |publisher=Amazon.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has devised an Architectural and Projects Committee, which ensures that any construction taking place on campus is done without disturbing the ecological balance of the wooded school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/7-days/studies-in-style/cid/598008 |title=Studies in style |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2017-10-30 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Houses===\n[[File:TataHouseQuadinDoon.jpg|thumb|right|East wing of Tata House and the quad.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:80%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | House name and Colours\n|-\n! House\n! Colour\n! Swatch\n|-\n|Kashmir || Yellow || {{colour box|#fecb00}}\n|-\n|Oberoi || Sky blue || {{colour box|#00add0}}\n|-\n|Tata || Red || {{colour box|#c60c30}}\n|-\n|Jaipur || Green || {{colour box|#007934}}\n|-\n|Hyderabad || Navy Blue || {{colour box|#003359}}\n|-\n|Martyn || || {{colour box|#496c60}}\n|-\n|Foot || ||{{colour box|#589199}}\n|}\n\nDoon follows the [[house system]]; there are five main houses (Hyderabad, Jaipur, Kashmir, Tata and Oberoi) and two 'holding houses' (Foot and Martyn, named after former headmasters), where new students live for a year before moving to one of the main houses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/pastoral-care/boarding-at-doon/|title=Boarding at Doon|website=Doon School}}</ref> Each house is run by a housemaster or a housemistress, along with a house captain and a team of [[School prefect|prefects]]. One senior boy serves as [[school captain]], chosen by teachers and students voting in a [[secret ballot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-lad-is-Doon-School-captain/articleshow/18424444.cms |title=Ludhiana lad is Doon School captain &#124; Ludhiana News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-02-10 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Boys are assigned to houses at the time of admission and develop great loyalty to them, since all [[intramural sports]] involve fierce competition between houses.\n\nEach housemaster and housemistress is assisted by a [[matron]] known as \"The Dame\", who provides [[pastoral care]] for pupils, some of whom take several weeks to adjust fully to life in a boarding school, particularly given Doon's monastic lifestyle and strict routine.<ref name=\"outlookindia2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230938 |title=Class Up At Doon &#124; Anjali Puri |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Futehally\"> {{cite book |last1=Futehally |first1=Laeeq |title=The Last Englishman: The Life and Times of Jack Gibson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iw1CgAAQBAJ&dq=the+last+englishman+jack+gibson&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2015 |publisher=Hachette UK |location=London |language= |isbn=9789350099698 |page= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= The food and linen was the responsibility of the Dame (Matron)}}</ref> The homes of housemasters and housemistresses are adjacent or physically attached to their houses to enable close supervision and support.\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main Building of the school which houses classrooms and offices.]]\nThe school practices a five-and-a-half-day week consisting of 40 periods (or \"schools\"), each of 40 minutes. The school day begins with \"first bell\" soon after 6:15&nbsp;am. The boys have [[chhota haazri]] before doing [[calisthenics]] outdoors on the playing fields, which is then followed by classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2004-07-04/special-report/27149351_1_education-system-elite-schools-vikram-seth |title=Chhota Hazri bell tolls for desi Etons|newspaper=The Times of India |date=4 July 2004 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon pupils take the [[International General Certificate of Secondary Education]] (IGCSE) exams in [[tenth grade]], which replaced [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] in 2017, and are thereafter offered two strands for the final two years: [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) or [[Indian School Certificate]] (ISC).<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibo.org/en/school/002603 |title=The Doon School - International Baccalaureate\u00ae |publisher=Ibo.org |date=2006-08-28 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year has three terms: Spring, Summer and Autumn. New pupils (\"D-Formers or 7th Graders\") join Doon at the beginning of April. The Autumn Term runs from August to the year-end examinations in November after which the boys are promoted to the new class beginning in February. These internal examinations are known as \"trials\", while examinations leading to certificates such as the [[Indian School Certificate]] are known as \"finals\". Discipline at the school has always been strict, and the school has expelled children from well-known families. In the 1950s, Martyn's suggestion that [[Sanjay Gandhi]] finish his senior year elsewhere was accepted without question by his mother, Indira Gandhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2008/20081202/dplus1.htm |title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India&nbsp;\u2014 Dehradun Plus |work=The Tribune |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> \n\nSocial work, known formally as \"Socially Useful Productive Work\", is also part of school life. All boys of the school must complete a mandatory quota of social service hours every term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/nation-education/article/doon-school-scouts-tamil-nadu-students |title=Doon School scouts for Tamil Nadu students |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon also oversees a Panchayat Ghar teaching impoverished children, and many building projects and workshops for the local community. Pupils and alumni have frequently helped local villages of organised efforts across India to assist people affected by natural disasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roundsquare.org/educational-insights/the-doon-school-a-village-service-partnership/ |title=The Doon School: A Village Service Partnership |publisher=Round Square |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> During the [[1991 Uttarkashi earthquake]] the school's amateur radio club was used by the government for communication purposes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gautam|first=Ashutosh|title=Earthquake: A Natural Disaster|year=2008|publisher=APH Publishing|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-313-0337-5|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSbTJDwMFgAC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=doon+school+uttarkashi+earthquake#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20uttarkashi%20earthquake&f=false}}</ref>  \n\n===School songs===\nThe school songs were deliberately chosen to include both [[Urdu poetry]] and Hindu [[bhajan]]s as a way of emphasising Doon's secular ethos; similarly, the school prayers include a mix of Anglican hymns and Indian poetry.<ref>The Doon School prayer book p.02-26</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false |title=Constructing Post-Colonial India (p.93) |publisher=Routledge |accessdate=5 July 2012|isbn=9780415178563 |year=1998 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Introduction To Indian Social Anthropology (p.152)|first=Krishna|last=Rao|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xxNTbYeyJZUC&pg=PA209&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false|isbn=9788182200777|year=2005}}</ref> Attendance at the morning assembly is required of all pupils and teachers. It traditionally begins with a song from the school's Song Book, which includes: ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''Chisti Ne Jis Zamin Mein'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''Anand Loke'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]]; ''[[Saare Jahan Se Achcha]]'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''[[Lab Pe Aati Hai Dua]]'' by Muhammad Iqbal; ''Vandana Ke in Swaron Mein'' (a [[Bhajan|bhajan]]); ''Ghungat Ke Pat Khol Re'' (attributed to [[Meerabai]]); ''Pitu Matu Sahayak'' (a bhajan); ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' (from a poem by [[Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay]]). Although ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' is India's [[National anthem]], it is traditionally referred to as \"Song No. 1\" at Doon since it was adopted as the School Song in 1935, fifteen years before it was adopted as India's national anthem.<ref>Bathla, Sanjeev<''Chotta Hazri:A Dosco's yatra'' p.32</ref><ref name=\"srivastava\">{{cite book|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School (p.82)|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref>\n\n===Pupils===\nPupils are known as \"Doscos\", a contraction of \"Doon\" and \"school\". The vast majority of alumni are Indians, but a dwindling number are from Pakistan having studied at Doon before the [[Partition of India]] forced them to leave in 1947. Relations between Indian and Pakistani alumni have remained warm over the years, despite the long history of conflict between the two countries.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101024/dplus.htm#2 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HQCvgavbQjgC&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73&dq=pakistani+doon+school#v=onepage&q=pakistani%20doon%20school&f=false |title=Locating home: India's Hyderabadis abroad&nbsp;\u2013 Karen Isaksen Leonard&nbsp;\u2013 Google Books |accessdate=1 March 2012|isbn=9780804754422 |last1=Leonard |first1=Karen Isaksen |year=2007 }}</ref> Boys from Bangladesh and Nepal continue to study at Doon. Doon remains a boys-only school despite pressure from political leaders, including President Pratibha Patil, to become coeducational.<ref name=\"president\"/><ref name=\"telegraphindia1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1101025/jsp/frontpage/story_13097199.jsp |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|title=Dame dilemma for Doon&nbsp;\u2013 President's co-ed suggestion evokes mixed reaction |date=25 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1101031/jsp/7days/story_13121462.jsp |title=The Telegraph&nbsp;\u2013 Calcutta (Kolkata) &#124; Eye on England |work=The Telegraph|location=Kolka ta |date=31 October 2010 |accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\n{{Anchor|Athletics}}\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Cricket at Doon.jpg|thumb|left|A cricket game in progress on the Main Field.]]\n\nSports are compulsory at the school. It has over {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of playing fields, the largest of which are Skinner's Field and the Main Field. Cricket, hockey, athletics, boxing and association football are played seasonally. Tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, basketball, swimming and gymnastics tournaments are also available. Sport is dominated by cricket and hockey during the spring term and by football, athletics and boxing in the autumn term. Inter-house matches are played in cricket, hockey, football and basketball. Sports facilities include a 25-metre swimming pool, a boxing ring and a multi-purpose hall with a gymnasium and facilities for indoor badminton, basketball and table tennis. There are two [[artificial turf]] cricket pitches, five basketball courts, four tennis courts, four squash courts, eight cricket nets, seven fields for hockey and football (which can be converted to four cricket pitches to accommodate seasonal sports), a modern cricket pavilion and two 400-metre athletics tracks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/departments/sports/|title=Sports|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\nDoon hosts the annual Afzal Khan Memorial Basketball Tournament, an inter-school basketball tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/inside-the-hoop-dreams-of-21-boys-at-nbas-first-academy-in-india/articleshow/58979953.cms?from=mdr |title=NBA: Inside the hoop dreams of 21 boys at NBA\u2019s first academy in India - The Economic Times |date=2017-06-04 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020504/ncr3.htm |title=Tribune Online Edition, May 4, 2002 |work=The Tribune |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Clubs and societies===\n{{See|The Doon School Model United Nations}}\n[[File:The Doon School Weekly.jpg|thumb|''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication of Doon.]]\n\nExtracurricular activities are also a compulsory element of school life, and magazines are published in English and Hindi. There are around 23 clubs and societies, including politics, drama, photography, [[Model aircraft|aeromodelling]], first-aid, dramatics, painting, robotics, sculpture, carpentry, [[amateur radio]], music (including [[Trinity College, London|Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations), senior and junior English debating societies, [[The Doon School Model United Nations]], chess and astronomy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20110820/dplus.htm#6 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=20 August 2011|accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In many societies pupils come together to discuss a particular topic, presided over by a schoolmaster and often including a guest speaker. The school has often invited prominent figures to give speeches and talks to the students; these have included heads of state, politicians, ornithologists, naturalists, artists, writers, economists, diplomats and industrialists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/category/events/visiting-speakers/|title=Visiting Speakers Archives|website=Doon School}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/600-mn-to-be-enrolled-in-uidai-in-next-4-years-nilekani/714784 |title=600 Mn to be Enrolled in UIDAI in Next 4 Years: Nilekani |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'' is the official school newspaper, distributed every Saturday morning. It chronicles school activities and is a platform for creative and political writing. It was founded in 1936 and is edited by pupils.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The publication aims to represent the views of the School community as well as Old Boys, and satire and criticism of school policies have been published in the past. More subversive publications, far more critical of teachers and the school establishment, have occasionally been produced without official sponsorship. Other school magazines include ''The Yearbook'' and ''The Doon School Information Review''. Publications by academic departments include '' VIBGYOR'' (Art), ''Echo'' (Science), ''The Econocrat'' (Economics), ''Infinity'' (Mathematics), ''Grand Slam'' (Sports) and ''The Circle'' (History and Political Science).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/|title=Publications|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n===Mountaineering===\n{{Main|Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering}}\n\n[[File:Mt. Everest Base Camp Expedition - 2008, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|2008 expedition to the [[Mount Everest Base Camp]] and [[Kala Patthar]].]]\n\nHalfway through each term, the boys take a one-week \"midterm\"&nbsp;\u2013 a rugged trip, often through the [[Siwalik Hills]] or [[Himalayas]]. Senior boys make treks of up to five days, unaccompanied by teachers, camping out in tents, cooking their own food and hiking. They plan these trips themselves. Alumni have credited these midterms as being among their most formative and character-building experiences.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/how-the-playing-fields-of-doon-nurture-india-incs-best-leaders/articleshow/6872417.cms|title=How the playing fields of Doon nurture India Inc's best leaders |newspaper=The Times of India |date=5 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nDoon has been credited with pioneering mountaineering in India, due to the accomplishments of masters such as [[R.L. Holdsworth]], [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] and alumni such as [[Narendra Dhar Jayal|Nandu Jayal]].<ref name=\"Kohli\"> {{cite book |last1=Kohli |first1=M.S. |title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure and Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Mountains_of_India.html?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&redir_esc=y |date=2002 |publisher=Indus |location= |language= |isbn=9788173871351 |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |page=209 |quote= p.290, Much of the credit for early interest in mountaineering among Indians goes to the Doon School, largely because of some distinguished British mountaineers on its staff like J.A.K. Martyn, J.T.M. Gibson, R.L. Holdsworth...In 1951, Gurdial Singh of the Doon School climbed the 7,120 metres high Trisul. This was the first Indian summit.}}</ref> Notable climbs by staff and alumni include [[Bandarpunch]] (6,316&nbsp;m) in 1950, Kala Nag (6,387&nbsp;m) in 1956, [[Trisul]] (7,120&nbsp;m) in 1951, [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m) in 1955, [[Abi Gamin]] (7,355&nbsp;m) in 1953 and 1955, Mrigthuni (6,855&nbsp;m) in 1958 and Jaonli (6,632 metres) in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/62/16/early-years-of-indian-mountaineering/ |title=Early Years of Indian Mountaineering |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nSome of these expeditions have had their idiosyncrasies. After Gurdial Singh led a successful climb of Trisul, he performed a headstand [[asana]] on the summit as a tribute to the Hindu god [[Shiva]], who is said to abide there. Holdsworth has been claimed to hold the high-altitude record for smoking a pipe, which he did on the summit of [[Kamet]] after the first ascent in 1931.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.himalayanclub.org/journal/obituary/ |title=Obituary |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=30 March 2013}}</ref> Two Doon pupils climbed the [[Matterhorn]] in 1951 wearing cricket boots.<ref name=\"alpinejournal\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Richard|title=Climbing with the Doon School|journal=Alpine Journal|year=2001|pages=197\u2013201|url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2001_files/AJ%202001%20197-201%20Anderson%20Doon%20School.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and music===\n[[File:Waiting for Godot in Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' being staged in the Rose Bowl.]]\nAn [[amphitheatre]] known as the Rose Bowl was built largely by pupils in two years during the 1930s<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=130|quote=It took two years to complete the open air theatre. The first play staged on it was \"The Merchant of Venice prodcued by Jack Gibson, and he had all his actors dressed in Indian costumes.\"}}</ref> and underwent a major structural change in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Santayana|first=Vivek|title=Losing a Kidney|journal=The Doon School Weekly|date=24 October 2009|issue=2232|url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66UfGMuG8?url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It can seat up to 2,000 people and has been the setting for numerous [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays and other classics of western theatre, as well as musical performances and speeches during school ceremonies such as Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805061511/http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=Doon Online&nbsp;\u2013 Vikram Seth |publisher=Mtholyoke.edu |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Multi-Purpose Hall is a more modern indoor theatre that can accommodate approximately 2,000 people. Plays are regularly staged in [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]], with 8\u20139 productions each year including 2 major productions as part of the Founder's Day celebrations. The Inter House Once-Act Play competition is held each year, alternatively in English and Hindi. Many of the plays historically have been joint productions with the Welham Girls' School in [[Dehradun]].\n\nIn 2001 a new music school was built beside the Rose Bowl. It houses a [[music library]], a [[concert hall]] and several practice and teaching rooms where students learn various western and Indian instruments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/stas-and-activities/music/|title=Music Programme and Facilities at The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> Pupils of the school have an option to appear for the [[Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations, conducted by [[Trinity College London]], in [[piano]], [[violin]], drums and classical guitar. In 2002 the school choir raised {{Indian Rupee}} 2&nbsp;million for victims of the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] by organising a charity concert with the title ''Concerto 2000'', in which drummer [[Sivamani]] also took part.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/04/11/stories/2002041100070300.htm |title=Raga meets rhythm |newspaper=The Hindu |date=11 April 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/lf/2002/03/30/stories/2002033000930200.htm |title=Doon tunes |newspaper=The Hindu |date=30 March 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To commemorate its Platinum Jubilee, the school launched a music album called ''Spirit of Doon'' in collaboration with [[EMI]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-and-interviews/28261521_1_music-album-doscos-alumni |title=Doon goes musical|newspaper=The Times of India |date=14 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The school choir sang two songs (\"Lab pe Aati Hai Dua\" and \"Anand Loke\") for the project but only the former was included in the final recording. The tracks were written by the lyricist [[Gulzar]] and were sung by [[Sonu Nigam]], Shayan Italia and [[Bhajan Sopori]].<ref name=\"bare_url\" />\n\n==Affiliations==\n\n===Ties with other schools===\n\nFrom its foundation in 1937 until the early 1980s, [[Welham Boys' School]] was a [[feeder school]] for Doon School and Mayo College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/31886-welham-boys-school-to-celebrate-platinum-jubilee-year.html |title=Welham Boys' School to celebrate platinum jubilee year |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> This ended when Surendra Kandhari, an old boy and former housemaster at Doon, became Principal of Welham and transformed it into a high school. Several families who send their sons to Doon send their daughters to [[Welham Girls' School]], and many Doon alumni have married alumnae of Welham.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070121/ttlife1.htm |title=The Tribune Lifestyle |newspaper=The Tribune |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NorthIndia/Boys-will-be-boys/Article1-617029.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021022231/http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NorthIndia/Boys-will-be-boys/Article1-617029.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 October 2012 |title=Boys will be boys |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The two schools hold an annual \"dance social\", and their alumni sometimes collaborate in organising events. Pakistani ex-pupils from Doon established the [[Chand Bagh School]] 40&nbsp;km north of [[Lahore]], Pakistan, in 1998, modelling it on the general structure of Doon.<ref>{{cite web|author=Azhar M. A. Qureshi |url=http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611010826/http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2009 |title=Chand Bagh School |publisher=Chandbagh.edu.pk |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> Doon also has exchange programmes with a number of overseas schools, such as Eton College, Harrow School, [[St. Albans School (Washington, D.C.)|St. Albans School, Washington DC]], [[Millfield]], [[Schule Schloss Salem]], [[The Armidale School]], [[Bridge House School]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[King's Academy]], [[Stowe School]], [[Scotch College, Melbourne]], [[The Hutchins School]] and [[St. Mark's School (Texas)]]. In 2011 Doon twinned with [[The Thomas Hardye School]], Dorchester, [[England]], through a cultural exchange project organised by the [[BBC]] and [[British Council]] in light of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] held in the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9451296.stm|title=Schools Spotlight on Team Abhinav Bindra|publisher=BBC|date=8 April 2011|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Schools with similar names===\nAs private schools became more widespread in [[India]], several other schools used \"Doon\" as part of their names, causing some confusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-using-doon-in-their-names-to-cash-the-popularity-of-the-doon-school/articleshow/69224014.cms |title=Schools using Doon in their names to cash the popularity of The Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Among them are Doon Global School, Doon Presidency School, [[Doon International School (Palia Kalan)|Doon International School]], Doon Preparatory School, Doon Cambridge School, Doon Girls School, [[Doon Public School]] (in West Delhi, not the Doon Valley) and the Doon College of Spoken English. None of them are related to The Doon School.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-24/special-report/28263544_1_doon-school-ipsc-sainik-schools |title=Is the old school tie wearing thin?|newspaper=The Times of India |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Memberships===\nThe Doon School is a member of following organisations: [[G20 Schools]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gold |first=Adam |url=http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073515/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 October 2007 |title=Move over G8\u2014this is G20 > Harvard Westlake Chronicle Online |publisher=Students.hw.com |date=8 November 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Round Square]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925000935/http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 September 2012 |title=Doon School India |publisher=RoundSquare |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Interact Club|Rotary International's Interact Club]], [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/ |title=HMC Schools : International Members |publisher=Hmc.org.uk |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[International Boys' Schools Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theibsc.org/page.cfm?p=38&filter_data7=&filter_data10=INDIA&filter_data13=&filter_data15=&key=&submit=SEARCH |title=International Boys' Schools Coalition: Member Directory |publisher=Theibsc.org |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examinations]], [[International Baccalaureate|International Baccalaureate Organization (IBO)]],<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\"/> Indian Public Schools' Conference,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802223143/http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 August 2012 |title=Indian Public Schools' Conference |publisher=Ipsc.co.in |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Rashtriya Life Saving Society (India)]], [[International Award Association]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Pioneer |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/doon-school-becomes-first-indian-school-to-start-iayp-online.html |title=Doon School becomes first Indian school to start IAYP online |publisher=Dailypioneer.com |date=2014-08-06 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe school is the regional test centre for [[University of Cambridge ESOL Examinations]] and [[SAT]] Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivyzone.com/category/sat/test-centre/ |title=SAT l STUDY ABROAD l VISA I IvyZone.com &#124; Test-centre |publisher=Ivyzone.com |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n;Doon in films & television\n{{main|Dazed in Doon}}\n{{main|Indian Summer School}}\n\n* The film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'', which was commissioned by the School on the occasion of its 75th anniversary and produced by old boy Ashvin Kumar, was banned by the school authorities because it \"doesn't give the school a good name\".<ref name=\"dazed\" /><ref name=\"fallout\" /> The dispute remains unresolved.<ref name=ex-student-film />\n* In September 2010, [[BBC Sport]] made a documentary on the Doon School for the ''World Olympic Dreams'' Project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9075650.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 The school that breeds Indian medal winners |publisher=BBC News |date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The documentary was produced in association with the [[British Council]]. Its main purpose was to show the school where [[Abhinav Bindra]], the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, spent his formative years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 Abhinav Bindra, India |publisher=BBC News |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* In the 2010 Bollywood film [[Aisha (film)|Aisha]], the character Randhir Gambhir is a Doon School alumnus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/previews/12-aisha-movie-preview-061009.asp |title=Aisha movie preview |publisher=glamsham.com |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2017, [[Channel 4]] of UK commissioned a 3-part documentary, ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', where working-class boys from the UK were given a chance to study at Doon for a term to see if they would benefit from the all-round experience of an Indian residential school. The filming began in August 2017, and the programmes were broadcast in March\u2013April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/29/indian-summer-school-review-five-terrible-teens-are-sent-to-indias-equivalent-of-eton |title=Indian Summer School review \u2013 five terrible teens are sent to India\u2019s equivalent of Eton &#124; Television & radio |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n;Doon in literature\n* [[Vikram Seth]] used his own experiences of being bullied at Doon to model the character of Tapan in ''[[A Suitable Boy]]''.<ref name=\"suitablejoy\" /><ref name=\"nytimes1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book&nbsp;\u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1993 |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref>\n* In [[Salman Rushdie]]'s short-story anthology [[East, West]], the protagonists Zulu and Chekhov are Doscos.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theroundtable.ro/Current/Literary/Titus_Pop_Eastern_and_Western_Cultural_Commingling_in_Rushdie_s_Stories.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=5 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130619225420/http://www.theroundtable.ro/Current/Literary/Titus_Pop_Eastern_and_Western_Cultural_Commingling_in_Rushdie_s_Stories.pdf |archive-date=19 June 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlantisjournal.org/ARCHIVE/31.2/2009Ganapathy-Dore.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224003035/http://www.atlantisjournal.org/ARCHIVE/31.2/2009Ganapathy-Dore.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 December 2010 |title=Shakespeare in Rushdie/Shakespearean Rushdie |accessdate=30 March 2013}}</ref>\n* In [[Tenzing Norgay]]'s autobiography ''Man of Everest'', he refers to [[Bandarpunch]] as \"The Doon School mountain\" due to the fact that the mountain was frequented by two Doon School teachers [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John Martyn]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norgay |first1=Tenzing |title=Man of Everest \u2013 The Autobiography of Tenzing |url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=90IPAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=doon+school+mountain |date=1955 |publisher=[[George G. Harrap and Co.]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781447400288 |page=154 |quote= It was to Garhwal. Back to Bandar Punch, \"the Doon School mountain,\" with my old friend Mr Gibson. }}</ref>\n* In [[Ruskin Bond]]'s novella ''Strangers in the Night'', character Jai Shankar is from Doon.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JIZHr-st3cYC&pg=PA4&dq=%22doon+school%22#v=onepage&q=%22doon%20school%22&f=false |title=Strangers in the Nights: Two Novellas - Ruskin Bond - Google Books |accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9780140240658 |last1=Yadav |first1=Rajendra |last2=Bond |first2=Ruskin |year=1994 }}</ref>\n* [[Penguin Books|Penguin's]] ''The Great Speeches of Modern India'' (2011) included Vikram Seth's 1992 Founder's Day address, which being confessional surprised the school community, and [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]'s 2007 speech, which was noted for its wit and humour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7dCH_IYbt8C&q=doon+school#v=snippet&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=The Great Speeches of Modern India - Rudranghsu Mukherjee - Google Books |date= October 2011|accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9788184002348 |last1=Mukherjee |first1=Rudranghsu }}</ref>\n\n;Doon in research\n* ''Doon School Chronicles'' is the first of five [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] films called the ''Doon School Quintet'', made by David MacDougall between 1997 and 2000 about the culture of the School.<ref>{{cite video|first=David|last=MacDougall|url=http://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/526/doon-school-chronicles.html |title=DOON SCHOOL CHRONICLES|publisher=Ronin Films|accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/302112/Doon-School-Chronicles/overview |title=Doon School Chronicles|work=The New York Times |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220001143/http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 February 2006 |title=Berkeley Media LLC: Catalog: Doon School Chronicles |publisher=Berkeleymedia.com |accessdate=20 February 2012 }}</ref> Macdougall has written of a tendency of some alumni to idealise a ''[[Golden age (metaphor)|Golden Age]]'' set in the first decade of the school's life, which sometimes makes them resistant to change.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\"/>\n* ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School'' by Sanjay Srivastva is a detailed [[Sociology|sociological]] study of the school's culture and how it has influenced India's national character.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva}}</ref>\n* ''{{'}}Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools'', a 2005 report by the Institute of Social Studies Trust, discusses why the Doon School has no [[Reservation in India|reservations]] (quotas for specific social groups) in its admissions process. The post quotes an unnamed student who explains, \"passing the Doon School entrance exam means that you have proved yourself worthy of the school. Reserving seats for students seems to imply that the school must prove itself worthy of you.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Mallica |title='Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools |url=http://www.isst-india.org/PDF/Poor%20children%20in%20Rich%20school.pdf |publisher=Institute of Social Studies Trust |accessdate=30 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1969, [[Asian Survey]] (then Asian Review) - an Asian studies [[academic journal]] of [[University of California, Berkeley]] - produced a report on The Doon School as a part of their project which documented Indian history after the entry of [[East India Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sh4sAQAAIAAJ&q=doon+school&dq=doon+school |title=Asian review&nbsp;\u2014 Demetrius Charles Boulger, East India Association (London, England), Oriental Institute (Woking, England)  |accessdate=30 March 2013|last1=Boulger |first1=Demetrius Charles |year=1969 }}</ref>\n* In ''Indian Tales of the Raj'', Zareer Masani studies how Doon School's alumni affected the Indian political scene in the '60s.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Lm4FVb54_oUC&pg=PA152&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=Indian Tales of the Raj&nbsp;\u2014 Zareer Masani  |accessdate=30 March 2013|isbn=9780520071278 |last1=Masani |first1=Zareer |year=1988 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n\n\n{{Main|List of The Doon School alumni}}\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School alumni}}\n[[File:Rahul Gandhi at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Rahul Gandhi]] (Class of 1988), Indian politician, [[Member of Parliament, Lok Sabha]] speaking at The Doon School Model United Nations' Conference in August 2017.]]\nPupils of Doon have gone on to achieve prominence in politics, government service, the armed forces of India and Pakistan, commerce, journalism, the arts and literature.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-09-04/news/30112792_1_boys-clubs-doon-school-dosco |title=Old boys' clubs of Doon School, IITs, IIMs, Harvard and others mean more than just databases |newspaper=The Times of India|accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707070626/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Naveen Patnaik sets stage for GeNext Doscos |newspaper=The Times of India |date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/06/01/stories/2009060153270700.htm |title=Other States / Uttaranchal News : Seven Doon alumni in 15th Lok Sabha |newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> They include nine [[Union Cabinet of India|Cabinet Ministers]], two [[chief minister]]s, several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] and [[Legislative Assembly|state Legislative Assemblies]];,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/news/special-videos/kamal-naths-journeydoon-school-to-parliament_446626.html |title=If India has to grow, we have to bridge infra deficit: Nath |work=CNBC-TV18 |publisher=Moneycontrol.com |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> nineteen generals, two admirals, former heads of the Indian and Pakistani Air Forces and twenty-four ambassadors, including those from India, Pakistan, Nepal and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pubby |first=Vipin |url=http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/Badal-vs-Badal/697446/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120730012554/http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/Badal-vs-Badal/697446/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 July 2012 |title=Badal vs Badal |publisher=Express India |date=14 October 2010 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-04-18/india/28002685_1_sukhbir-badal-doscos-media-campaign |title=Old boys' network at work in war-zone Bathinda&nbsp;\u2013 Times of India |work=The Times of India |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The best-known alumnus is former Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]], who appointed many Doon friends to prominent positions. Although any alumnus seldom held public office for some time afterward, this changed with the political ascendance of Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia, Kamal Nath, Kalikesh Singh Deo and Rahul Gandhi.<ref name=\"telegraphindia1\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376408_1_doon-school-doscos-singh-and-vishvjeet-singh |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707125405/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376408_1_doon-school-doscos-singh-and-vishvjeet-singh |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Dooned if you do, damned if&nbsp;...|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> \n[[File:Sanjit Bunker Roy at Time 2010.jpg|thumb|left|160px|[[Bunker Roy]] (Class of 1962), Social activist and the founder of [[Barefoot College]], [[Tilonia]].]]\nNotable Doon alumni to have held senior positions in Indian and Pakistani politics include the former Indian diplomat turned politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]], currently a Rajya Sabha nominee, the former Defence Secretary of Pakistan [[Ghulam Jilani Khan]], [[Kamal Nath]] (Politician, class of 1964), [[Rahul Gandhi]] (Congress Politician, class of 1988), [[Sanjay Gandhi]] (Congress Politician, class of 1964),<ref>{{cite news|last=Bajpai |first=Kanti |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-24/news-interviews/29809510_1_amitabh-bachchan-teji-bachchan-rajiv-gandhi |title=Amitabh Bachchan in Doon School|newspaper=The Times of India |date=1 November 2008 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Koel Rinchet Poorie |url=http://blogs.intoday.in/index.php?option=com_myblog&contentid=61472&show=Inpoliticsbydefault.html&blogs=2 |title=Kamal Nath Makes It!|newspaper=Headlines Today |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Allana |first=Alia |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/doon-squad/464930/ |title=The Doon School Squad|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> [[Naveen Patnaik]] (Politician, class of 1964), [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] (Politician, class of 1989),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://india.gov.in/govt/loksabhampbiodata.php?mpcode=3958|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514143320/http://india.gov.in/govt/loksabhampbiodata.php?mpcode=3958|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 May 2011|title=Indian Government Profile}}</ref> [[Dr. Karan Singh]] (Politician, class of 1948)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://india.gov.in/govt/rajyasabhampbiodata.php?mpcode=82 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009004439/http://india.gov.in/govt/rajyasabhampbiodata.php?mpcode=82 |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 October 2012 |title=Minister Profile |publisher=The Government of India |date=31 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\nIn the field of Literature and Poetry, Doon alumni include [[Amitav Ghosh]] (class of 1972),<ref>{{cite web|author=Elisabeth Bumiller |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/29/books/a-novelist-beginning-with-a-bang.html |title=A Novelist Beginning With a Bang - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1997-07-29 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> [[Ramachandra Guha]] (class of 1973),<ref>{{cite journal|last=Naqvi |first=Saba |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?225730 |title=ARam Guha in Doon School|journal=Outlook Magazine |date=1 November 2007 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> [[Vikram Seth]] (class of 1970),<ref>{{cite news|author=Richard B. Woodward |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1993-05-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> [[Ardashir Vakil]].\n\nDoon alumni in journalism include [[Prannoy Roy]] (class of 1965), [[Aroon Purie]] (class of 1962),<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chandra |first=Ram |url=http://www.careers360.com/news/3632-Aroon-Purie-Editor-in-Chief-India-Today |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124094457/http://www.careers360.com/news/3632-Aroon-Purie-Editor-in-Chief-India-Today |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 November 2009 |title=Aroon Purie on Education |journal=Careers 360 News Magazine |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012 }}</ref> [[Karan Thapar]], [[Virendra Prabhakar]] and [[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]]. The first Indian [[Rhodes scholar]] was a Doon School alumni - [[Lovraj Kumar]].<ref>{{cite news|author=I. M. D. Little |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lovraj-kumar-1367199.html |title=Obituary: Lovraj Kumar|newspaper=The Independent |date=1 April 1994 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon is also the alma mater of the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, [[Abhinav Bindra]] (class of 1999) and the mountaineering pioneer [[Nandu Jayal]].<ref>{{cite news|author=BBC Sports Desk |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=Abhinav Bindra Indian Olympic Medallist|publisher=BBC |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Anish Kapoor at the Deutsche Guggenheim - Berlin.jpg|thumb|right|160px|[[Anish Kapoor]] (Class of 1970) is a sculptor whose designs include [[ArcelorMittal Orbit]], [[Olympic Park, London]].<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/>]]\nIn the field of Arts and Entertainment, Doon's alumni include [[Roshan Seth]] (Class of 1960),<ref>{{cite journal|last=Harper |first=Alan |url=http://www.harpritsan.com/DoonFutureArticle.html |title=The Doon Future|journal=Harpitsan Magazine (Outlook) |date=1 November 2008 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> [[Himani Shivpuri]] (class of 1971),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/article2890613.ece |title=A Renaissance Woman|newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> [[Chandrachur Singh]], [[Satyadeep Mishra]] (class of 1991) and [[Abhishek Poddar]], a prominent art collector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/features/The-Abhishek-and-Radhika-Poddar-collection-of-Indian-Modern-and-Contemporary-Art-7960-1.aspx |title=How Abhishek and Radhika Poddar built their collection of Indian art &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date=2016-12-18 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The sculptor [[Anish Kapoor]] (class of 1970) also attended Doon.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://forbesindia.com/article/recliner/anish-kapoor-making-it-big/19942/1|journal=Forbes India|title=Anish Kapoor Making it Big}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jun/07/anish-kapoor-sculpture-versailles-controversy |title=Anish Kapoor: superstar sculptor who loves to court scandal &#124; Observer profile &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn Business, the Doon alumni included [[Anil Kumar]], former senior partner at [[McKinsey & Company]] and co-founder of the [[Indian School of Business]], [[Gautam Thapar]], founder and chairman of the [[Avantha Group]], [[Malvinder Mohan Singh]] and [[Shivinder Mohan Singh]], former owners of [[Ranbaxy Laboratories]] and presently owning [[Fortis Healthcare]], [[Rohit Kapoor]], founder and CEO of EXL Service.com. \n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Faculty===\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School faculty}}\nPrevious teachers have included: [[Peter Lawrence (teacher)|Peter Lawrence]],<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4309213.stm|title=Eton, the Raj and modern India|date=9 March 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20041207/edit.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Opinions|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John A. K. Martyn]],<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> [[Sheel Vohra]],<ref name=\"tribuneindia1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101014/dplus.htm#3 |title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India&nbsp;\u2014 Dehradun Plus |work=The Tribune |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> [[R. L. Holdsworth]],<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/> [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]],<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/> [[Sudhir Khastgir]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?267708 |title=Bonfire of Vanities &#124; Vishvjit P. Singh |publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> [[Chetan Anand (director)|Chetan Anand]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8y8vN9A14nkC&pg=PT89&dq=taught+at+doon+school|title=Encyclopaedia of Hindi Cinema|first=Encyclopedia|last=Britannica|date=16 January 2019|publisher=Popular Prakashan|via=Google Books|isbn=9788179910665}}</ref> [[Simon Singh]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/there-s-math-in-simpsons-simon-says/story-czEcewcbqXaAuE38U6oF2K.html|title=There's math in Simpsons, Simon says|date=11 January 2014|work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref> [[Vikram Seth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://itv.in/index.php?option=com_sentiments&view=detail&sid=576&Itemid=3 |title=A reverie at a book-reading |work=Hindustan Times |date=5 March 1999 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> [[Satendra Nandan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/25/its-time-goodbye-comrades/|title=It's Time: Goodbye, COMRADES - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref> [[Ashok Roy]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Schools|Education}}\n* [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://archive.is/20121219012747/http://fullcirclebooks.in/content/chhota-hazri-days-doscos-yatra ''Chhota Hazri Days: A Dosco's Yatra''] by Sanjiv Bathla, [[Rupa & Co.]], 2010 {{ISBN|978-81-291-1694-9}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130323003553/http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/sahibs-who-loved-india ''Sahibs who Loved India''] by [[Khushwant Singh]], [[Penguin Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-14-341580-0}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&q=Doon+School&dq=the+doon+school+sixty+years+on+pushpinder&source=gbs_word_cloud_r&cad=5#v=snippet&q=Doon%20School&f=false ''The Corporeal Image''] by David McDougall, [[Princeton University Press]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-691-12156-7}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Trees of Chandbagh''] by K.C. Sinha, Konark Publishers, 1996, {{ISBN|978-81-220-0457-1}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=3sVlHQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''For Hills To Climb''] by Gurdial Singh and Nalni Dhar, The Doon School Old Boys' Society, 2001.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=NEdmQgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Doon, The Story of a School''], IPSS (1985) edited by Sumer Singh, published by the Indian Public Schools Society 1985. ASIN B0006ENF66\n* [http://dsobs.net/currentrb/current_rosebowl.php ''The Rose Bowl''],  a periodic newsletter by the Doon School Old Boys' Society\n* [https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School, ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School''] by Sanjay Srivastva, published by [[Routledge]] 1998 {{ISBN|0-203-98027-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=The Doon School |s=Category:The Doon School |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School }}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.doonschool.com/|name = Official website}}\n* [http://www.dsobs.net/ Website of the Doon School Old Boys' Society]\n* [http://store.doonschool.com/ The Doon School - Gift Store]\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School}}\n[[Category:The Doon School| ]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Round Square schools]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in India]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in India]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in India]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{in use}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|Boys' boarding school in Dehradun, India}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | image                   = The Doon School.jpg\n | caption                 = Main Building at The Doon School\n | image_size              = 300px\n | name                    = The Doon School\n | logo                    = The Doon School, Dehradun - logo.png\n | logo_size               = 150px\n | colours                 = Blue & White {{color box|#005293}} {{color box|white}}\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30.333|78.030|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n | pushpin_map             = India Uttarakhand#India\n | location                = The Doon School<br>Mall Road<br>[[Dehradun]]&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;248001<br>India<br>([https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/The+Doon+School/@30.3350253,78.0298105,17z Google Map], [https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/158385701 OpenStreetMap])\n | specialist              = \n | schooltype              = Independent [[boarding school]]\n | motto                   = '' Knowledge our Light''\n | sister_school           = [[Welham Girls' School]]\n | established             = \n | founded                 = {{Start date and age|1935|09|10}}\n | founder                 = [[Satish Ranjan Das]]\n | head_name               = Founder Headmaster\n | head                    = [[Arthur Foot|Arthur Edward Foot]]\n | gender                  = Boys\n | lower_age               = 12\n | upper_age               = 18\n | headmaster              = Post vacant \n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governors\n | chair                   = [[Sunil Kant Munjal]]\n | pupils                  = c. 600\n | faculty                 = 70\n | houses                  = 5 houses + 2 holding houses\n | campus                  = 72 acres (297,314&nbsp;m\u00b2)\n | ceeb                    = 671616\n | district                = [[Dehradun district|Dehradun District]]\n | student_union           = [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n | affiliation             = [[International Baccalaureate|IB]]<br>[[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examination|CISCE]]<br>[[International General Certificate of Secondary Education|IGCSE]]\n | publication             = ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]''\n | free_label2             = Annual fees\n | free_text2              = {{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1025000}} (home students)<br>{{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1281000}} (international)\n | free_label              = Former pupils\n | free_text               = [[List of The Doon School alumni|Doscos]]\n | website                 = [http://www.doonschool.com/ www.doonschool.com]\n}}\n\n'''The Doon School''' (informally '''Doon School''' or '''Doon''') is a boys-only private, [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]] [[Selective school|selective]] boarding school in Dehradun, Uttarakhand, India, established in 1935. It was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a [[Kolkata]] lawyer, who prevised a school modelled on the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]], but conscious of Indian ambitions and desires.<ref name=\"auto\">MacDougall2006-page100</ref> Although he died in 1928, he is considered the founder of the school. The school's first [[Head teacher|headmaster]] was an Englishman, [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], who had spent nine years as a science master at [[Eton College]], England.<ref>{{cite book|year=1979|chapter=FOOT, Arthur Edward|title=Who Was Who 1961\u20131970|location=London|publisher=A. & C. Black|isbn=0-7136-2008-0}}</ref> The last headmaster was [[Matthew Raggett]], who resigned in January 2020. He was the fourth British headmaster in Doon's history and a member of [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]], [[UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/|title=The Doon School|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nDoon houses roughly 500 pupils aged 13 to 18, and admission is based on a competitive entrance examination, a group discussion and an interview with the headmaster.<ref name=\"wsj\" /> Every year in January and April, the school admits pupils aged 13 in Grade 7 (known as D-form) and aged 14 in Grade 8 (C-form) respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kapoor |first=Jaskiran |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/class-apart/601507/0 |title=Class Apart |publisher=Indian Express |date=11 April 2010 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> Doon remains a boys-only school despite continued pressure from political leaders, including former [[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]], to become [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]].<ref name=\"president\">{{cite news |last=Chopra |first=Jaskiran |title=President leads assault on Doon School heritage |newspaper=[[The Pioneer (Indian newspaper)|The Pioneer]] |date=24 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nDoon has been consistently ranked the best all-boys residential school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite news |title=3 Bangalore schools among India's best |first=Neha |last=Pushkarna |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-10-09/bangalore/30259994_1_bangalore-schools-shri-ram-school-parental-involvement |newspaper=The Times of India|publisher=The Times Group|date=9 October 2011 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?218344 |title=India's Best Schools |newspaper=Outlook |publisher=Outlook Newsmagazine |date=16 December 2002 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref> Although the school has often been cited as 'Eton of India' by media outlets such as the ''[[BBC]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02c3zgq|title=BBC World Service - Witness, India's Eton|website=BBC}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|author=STEVEN R. WEISMAN, Special to the New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/12/world/india-s-old-school-tie-harrow-by-the-himalayas.html |title=India'S Old School Tie - Harrow By The Himalayas |location=Dehra Dun (India); India |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=12 November 1985 |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/aug/13/fiction.arundhatiroy|title=The lost sub-continent|first=William|last=Dalrymple|date=13 August 2005|website=the Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Spectator]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author=Read |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/03/its-a-spartan-life-at-the-eton-of-india/# |title=It's a spartan life at 'the Eton of India' |publisher=The Spectator |date= |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/alastair-sooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html|title=The rise & rise of Anish Kapoor Inc.|first=Alastair|last=Sooke|date=2 April 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> ''[[Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Remnick |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/10/20/rajiv-gandhi-and-the-mantle-unsought/779cee82-b666-4248-8116-278d6134a002/ |title=Rajiv Gandhi And The Mantle Unsought |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1987-10-20 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> and ''[[Forbes]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/10/28/the-doon-school-grooming-ground-for-indias-wealthy-kids/|title=The Doon School: Grooming Ground For India's Wealthy Kids|first=Forbes|last=Staff|website=Forbes}}</ref> it strongly eschews the label.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Doon-of-India-wants-to-conquer-the-globe/articleshow/6800690.cms |title=\u2018Doon of India\u2019 wants to conquer the globe - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> [[Old boy network|Old boys]] of the school are commonly known as ''Doscos''.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\">{{citation|last=MacDougall|first=David|title=The corporeal image: film, ethnography, and the senses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&pg=PA107|accessdate=31 March 2012|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12156-7|pages=107\u2013108}}</ref>  Although the total number of former pupils is relatively small (estimated at 5,000 since the school's founding), they include some of India's most prominent politicians, government officials and business leaders.<ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709213757/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=For wannabe Doons, don from hills is a boon |newspaper=Times of India |date=30 December 2002 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> The best known alumnus is the late Indian Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:The Doon School main building (then FRI) - 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|Main building of Doon in 1917, when it was part of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].]]\n[[File:Main Gate, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main gate of the Doon School.]]\nDoon was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a lawyer from Calcutta and advocate-general of Bengal, who in 1927 became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council]] of [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Irwin]] on the condition that he would use the prestige of this position to raise funds for a new type of school in [[India]].<ref>''The Indian Year Book'', vol. 29 (1942), p. 419: \"Doon School&nbsp;\u2013 This school which is established in the Chand Bagh and Skinner's Estates at Dehra Doon owes its origin to the initiative and enthusiasm of the late SR Das.\"</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Rudrangshu |last=Mukherjee |authorlink=Rudrangshu Mukherjee |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1020707/editoria.htm |title=Editorial > Remains of the Past |work=The Telegraph|location=Kolkata |date=21 May 1985 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref> He decided to name the new school \"Doon\", as it was situated in the [[Doon Valley]]. He travelled widely in [[India]] with the goal of collecting {{Indian Rupee}}4&nbsp;million, but at the time of his death had raised only {{Indian Rupee}}1 million in cash and a further {{Indian Rupee}}1&nbsp;million in promises. With the money, Das formed the Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which had the objective of founding new public schools in [[India]] that would admit students regardless of caste, creed or social status. Under the IPSS, a Board of Governors supervises all matters of Doon.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 41: \"...the body founded by Das for the purposes of establishing the Doon School, the Indian Public Schools Society\"</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Das in 1928, the IPSS accomplished little, and by 1934 some of the original lenders had begun to inquire about the return of their money. To solve this problem, Sir Joseph Bhore, then Railway Minister of [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|Lord Willingdon's]] Council, became IPSS chairman and, with [[Akbar Hydari|Sir Akbar Hydari]] as secretary, worked to obtain the former estate of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] in [[Dehra Dun]] on favourable terms. Sir Frank Noyce also joined the team. [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], then President of the British Board of Education, led a selection committee that nominated [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], a science teacher at [[Eton College]], to be the first headmaster.<ref name=\"excellence\">{{cite journal|title=Excellence personified |journal=Frontline |date=12 February 2011 |volume=28 |issue=4 |url=http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313163529/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> On 27 October 1935, the [[Viceroy]], [[Lord Willingdon]], presided over the formal opening of the school. Seventy boys enrolled in the first [[Academic term|term]], and 110 more signed up for the second.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 203 (Note 12): \"...from Willingdon's inaugural address on 27 October 1935\"</ref>\n\nThe [[House system|houses]] at the new school were originally named after their respective [[housemaster]]s, but later renamed in honour of the largest presenter to the IPSS: Hyderabad House was named after Sir [[Akbar Hydari]] secured a contribution of {{Indian Rupee}} 200,000 from the [[Nizam of Hyderabad]]'s government;. [[Kashmir House]], after [[Maharajah]] [[Hari Singh]], then ruler of [[Jammu and Kashmir]], promised a contribution of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000, which was delivered in 1935;. Tata House, after the [[Tata family|Tata]] and [[Wadia family|Wadia]] Trusts promised {{Indian Rupee}}150,000, half of which was delivered in 1935;. Jaipur House, after [[Rai Bahadur]] Amarnath Atal arranged for contributions of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000 from the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] of [[Jaipur]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 197 (Appendix 1): \"Donors to the Indian Public Schools' Society prior to 1936\"</ref> No building was named after [[Rai Bahadur]] Rameshwar Nathany, since his donation of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000 was initially anonymous.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/constructingpost0000sriv |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/constructingpost0000sriv/page/224 224] |quote=rai bahadur. |title=Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School|publisher=Psychology Press |first=Sanjay|last=Srivastava |accessdate=6 March 2012|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref>\n\n===Early years:1935\u20131970===\n\n[[Arthur Foot]] had never visited [[India]] before accepting the position of headmaster. He noted that the school appeared to be surrounded by forests and close to mountains, and the possibilities of outdoor recreation and mountaineering seem to have influenced his decision as much as the chance to create a completely new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"sixtyyears\">{{cite book|title=The Doon School Sixty Years On |publisher=Doon School Old Boys' Society|date=October 1996}}</ref> Foot's first action upon being offered the position was to recruit [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J.A.K. (John) Martyn]] from [[Harrow School]] as his deputy. Doon's ethos and guiding principles were determined early in its life by Foot, Martyn, [[R. L. Holdsworth|R.L. Holdsworth]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]], who went on to become Principal of [[Mayo College]]. While these masters all came from very traditional British schools,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnathersuch.com/op_website/op_owners_text.htm |title=Ottershaw Park |publisher=Johnathersuch.com |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> they were determined to create a uniquely Indian public school rather than a transplanted British institution, and they were soon joined in their efforts by equally influential Indians such as [[Sudhir Khastgir]] (the school's first art teacher, who had trained previously in [[Santiniketan]]) and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], a pioneering mountaineer who taught at Doon for several decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =...&nbsp;By 14 he should have learnt all the ordinary principles of social behaviour. He should know how to stand up and speak to a variety of different types of people&nbsp;\u2013 to his own mother, to someone else's mother, to his father, to his schoolmasters, to servants, to Mahatma Gandhi or to the Viceroy, and to do this without any self-consciousness&nbsp;...At 17 must come another quality, less instinctive and requiring a maturer mind: he must acquire a capacity of judgement.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" />&nbsp;...\n |source = <small>Arthur Foot, 1946, ''The Objects of Education''</small>\n |align  = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\n\nIn an essay entitled ''The Objects of Education'' published in the school magazine, Foot offered a template for a complete education for boys, which included teaching them to distinguish clearly between good and evil, form a habit of choosing good over evil, think logically, express their thoughts and views clearly, and maintain a healthy body.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" /> Martyn, who was involved with Doon for several decades and became its second headmaster, acknowledged the influence of German educator [[Kurt Hahn]] in the development of the school's ethos. Although Martyn had not visited India before, he immediately accepted Foot's offer because of the opportunity it afforded to implement Hahn's ideas, which he had not been able to do at Harrow.<ref>{{cite web|author=site admin |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19851115-book-review-sumer-singh-doon-the-story-of-a-school-mady-martyn-martyn-sahib-802174-2014-01-16 |title=Where East meets West - Society & The Arts News - Issue Date: Nov 15, 1985 |publisher=Indiatoday.in |date=1985-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Martyn acknowledged Foot's leadership in the development of the school, but added that they both had similar ideas: \"I would not have been as bold as he was in trying to eliminate punishments, but we were equally keen on providing as wide a range as possible of activities that were creative and challenging&nbsp;... The problem, as we saw it, was to create an atmosphere in which boys would learn the importance of public spirit at the same time as they acquired self-confidence and initiative.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=38|quote=When John wrote to Hahn to tell him we was going to India, Hahn replied that he had been waiting to be able to offer him a place at Gordonstoun...}}</ref>\n\nFoot and Martyn, the first two headmasters at Doon, were both from elite British institutions&nbsp;\u2013 Eton College and Harrow School. They were determined to model Doon on those two schools, but both agreed that it should cater primarily for Indian boys rather than the sons of British expatriates. The public school jargon introduced by these headmasters is still in use. For example, the weekly masters' meeting, started by Foot, is called ''Chambers'', a term taken from Eton, and evening \"prep\" (the boarding-school equivalent of homework) is called ''Toye-time'', a term taken from [[Winchester College]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Charles |last1=Stevens|first2=Christopher|last2=Stray|title=Winchester notions: the English dialect of Winchester College|publisher=Athlone Press|year=1998|page=294|quote=Toy-time, or toytime recorded from 1831 as the evening hours of preparation, called 'prep' elsewhere&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB917469665815143000 |title=Language Lessons: For India's Elite English Is the Past -- and the Future\n|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Though Foot modelled Doon on Eton and Harrow (and the school is often called the \"Eton of India\" by various press agencies), he did not want Doon to be considered elitist.<ref name=\"anish\">{{cite news|last=Botsman |first=John |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturecritics/alastairsooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html |title=The Rise of Anish Kapoor|newspaper=The Telegraph, U.K. |date=1 November 2009 |accessdate=2 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"suitablejoy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/mar/27/books.guardianreview1 |title=A suitable joy|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 March 1999 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jun/09/india.kashmir2 |title=Which way now for India?|newspaper=The Guardian|date=8 June 2002 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref> Foot once said, \"our boys will join an aristocracy, but it\u2019s an aristocracy of service, not one of wealth, privilege or position\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/interview_doon-school-is-popular-for-building-an-aristocracy-of-service_1392063 |title=Doon School is popular for building an 'aristocracy of service'&nbsp;\u2013 Academy|work=DNA |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> \n\n===1970\u2013End of 20th century===\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-right:1em; font-size:85%; background:#ffc; color:black; width:20em; max-width:25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Headmasters\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n* [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], 1935\u20131948\n* [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J. A. K. Martyn]], 1948\u20131966\n* [[C. J. Miller]], 1966\u20131970\n* [[Eric Simeon|Eric J. Simeon]], 1970\u20131979\n* [[Gulab Ramchandani]], 1979\u20131988\n* [[Shomie Das]], 1988\u20131996\n* [[John Mason (Schoolmaster)|John A. Mason]], 1996\u20132003\n* [[Kanti Bajpai]], 2003\u20132009\n* [[Peter McLaughlin]], 2009\u20132016\n* [[Matthew Raggett]], 2016\u20132020 \n|}\n\nThe school's first Indian headmaster was [[Eric Simeon]], appointed in 1970. He came from a military background and laid great emphasis on disciplined living.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/schooled-for-life/32471/|title=Schooled for life - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/05/16/stories/2007051615082000.htm |title=Lt. Col. Eric Joseph Simeon dead |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> During Simeon's tenure of nine years, the school faced financial difficulties. The estate suffered as the funds were not enough to maintain buildings and facilities.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/weekly/May%2019%202007.pdf</ref> In 1979, [[Gulab Ramchandani]] became the first alumnus to be appointed headmaster. In 1988, [[Shomie Das]], another alumnus and the grandson of school founder Satish Ranjan Das, became headmaster. Das's focus was to upgrade the school infrastructure and during his tenure the Oberoi house was added to the original four houses. The next headmaster, [[John Mason (schoolmaster)|John Mason]], appointed in 1996, planned on making Doon more affordable to school pupils; the school did not raise its fees during his tenure. \n\n====Criticism of Rajiv Gandhi administration====\n\nIn the 1980s, the then [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Rajiv Gandhi]], an alumnus, drew criticism from the media for appointing many old boys to his administration. His inner circle was labelled a \"Doon cabinet\" or \"Dosco Mafia\"<ref>''Indian Tales of the Raj'' by Zareer Masani, p.152</ref> and ''Washington Post'' reported, \"The catch phrase around Delhi these days is that the 'Doon School runs India,' but that is too simple an analysis for a complex, chaotic country with so many competing spheres of influence.\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\">{{cite web|last=Bumiller |first=Elisabeth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1985/11/24/where-indias-elite-were-boys-together/0579f3d9-1835-4441-b1b1-a55e3111bdc3/ |title=Where India's Elite Were Boys Together |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1985-11-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Steven R. Weisman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/20/magazine/the-rajiv-generation.html |title=THE RAJIV GENERATION - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1986-04-20 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gandhi's reliance on Doon alumni for political advice later led Prime Minister [[Morarji Desai]] to remark, \"If I had anything to do with this place, I'd close it down\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0724/eindia.html|title=Bootstrap steps for Gandhi|date=24 July 1987|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref>\n\n===2000-Present day===\nIn 2003, [[Kanti Bajpai]] became the third old boy to become headmaster, after Gulab Ramchandani and Shomie Das. He introduced numerous punishments, notably \"yellow cards\", to control an outburst of bullying at Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03cgg70 |title=BBC World Service - Path to Power, Educating India's Elite |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1994-10-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> In 2006, Bajpai found himself embroiled in a controversy when the parents of Hindu and Sikh students complained on discovering that the school's dining hall only serves [[halal]] meat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bad-blood-over-meat-served-at-Doon-School/articleshow/1516879.cms|title=Bad blood over meat served at Doon School &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The matter was brought to light after a visiting Pakistani delegation was assured of their meal's halal status. Later, the school's board of governors called for a status quo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/doon-debates-meaty-matters/story-mQ4y1Lt1fXLI3DiW2cV3XI.html|title=Doon debates meaty matters|date=3 May 2006|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> As of 2016, the school was serving both halal and non-halal (''jhatka'') meat varieties.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2434-FINAL.pdf</ref> In 2009, [[Peter McLaughlin]], an Irish academic, was chosen to lead the school, becoming the first non-Indian headmaster in almost four decades. Shortly before taking up his appointment he said, \"We will be adhering to the school credo of engaging individuals in socially productive work, at the same time delivering on quality education.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20090526/dplus.htm#3 |work=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India|title=Dehradun Plus |date=26 May 2009 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2010 Founder's Day celebrations====\n[[File:President of India speaking at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]] speaking at the Doon School's Platinum Jubilee in October 2010.]]\n\nIn 2010, Doon celebrated its 75th Founder's Day, a three-four day event in the Autumn Term, usually October, that marks the school's founding. <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/item/40943-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doonschool.com/founders-day-celebrations |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091019061244/http://www.doonschool.com/founders-day-celebrations |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 October 2009 |title=Founder's Day Celebrations 2009 |publisher=The Doon School |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> The Founder's Day draws many ex-pupils from all parts of the world and security on campus is tight, since alumni attending the event often include senior politicians and government officials. The chief guest is usually a prominent person.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/how-indias-renowned-doon-school-is-embracing-change-to-retain-its-exclusivity/articleshow/45006985.cms?from=mdr |title=How India's renowned Doon School is embracing change to retain its exclusivity - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-11-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The event includes productions of English dramas followed by an orchestral concert given by members of the school's Music Society.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Hill Post|url=http://hillpost.in/2011/10/28/doon-school-celebrates-76-th-founders-day/33352/latest-news/bhatt |title=Doon School celebrates 76 th founders day |date=28 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Datta |first=Sravasti |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523113538/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 May 2011 |title=Life & Style / Metroplus : All boarders on board |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 February 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe 75th Founder's Day was christened ''DS-75''.<ref name=\"Doon school\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-08/news/27591639_1_celebrations-doon-school-chief-guest |title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21 |publisher=[[The Times Group]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Back to School\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/KaranThapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104092100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/karanthapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2010 |last=Thapar|first=Karan|title=Back to School |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School\">{{cite news|title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/15930-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |newspaper=Daily Pioneer|date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Among the chief guests were the then President [[Pratibha Patil]] of India, King [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]] of Bhutan and [[Kapil Sibal]], (then [[Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)|Union Minister for Human Resource Development]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bhutanjournals.com/monarchy/hms-address-at-doon-school-dehradun-india/ |title=HM's Address at Doon School, Dehradun, India|newspaper=Bhutan Journals |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Pratibha Patil, in her address, urged the school authorities to make Doon a co-educational institution. One of the main events was a discussion, dubbed the \"Chandbagh Debate\", held between alumni including [[Vikram Seth]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Manpreet Singh Badal]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] and retired headmaster Kanti Bajpai, on the topic ''Can India lead?''. It was moderated by television commentator [[Karan Thapar]], an alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+matter+of+debate+at+Doon+School+platinum+jubilee.-a0240443417 |title=A matter of debate at Doon School platinum jubilee|newspaper=[[India Today]] |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Ashvin Kumar]] made the film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'' for the celebrations, using pupils for the cast and crew. Most of it was shot in June and July during the summer break, and those scenes which required the entire student body were filmed after the school reopened in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imaginox.co.uk/course/1718 |title=Making 'Dazed in Doon' |publisher=Imaginox |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Doon School, however, objected to the film and its distribution, obtaining a court order to delay its release and labelling it \"defamatory\".<ref name=dazed>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-interviews/28271042_1_film-doon-school-ashvin-kumar|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film|newspaper=The Times of India|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=fallout>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-18/news-interviews/28230561_1_doon-short-film-ashvin|title=Doon film fallout!|newspaper=The Times of India|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=Doon-film-banned>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-03/news-interviews/28366688_1_doon-school-doon-film-dehradun|title=Doon film banned in Dehradun|newspaper=The Times of India|date=3 February 2011|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=ex-student-film>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120701125916/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 July 2012|title=Ex-student's film celebrating Doon draws school's ire|newspaper=The Times of India|date=25 December 2010}}</ref> On 22 October 2010, a commemorative postage stamp depicting the school's main building was released by the [[Indian Postal Service]] to mark the occasion of the 75th Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101009/dplus.htm#5 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016 the school announced the appointment of Matthew Raggett, principal of the [[Leipzig International School]]'s secondary department, to succeed Peter McLaughlin from the end of the summer term. In recent years, boys from the [[North Indian]] states have dominated the student demographic. To make the school more diverse, Raggett continued McLaughlin's initiative by inviting more applications from boys in [[South Indian]] cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/doon-school-looks-for-more-boys-from-south/articleshow/57725021.cms|title=Doon School: Doon School looks for more boys from south &#124; Bengaluru News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/doons-bonds-with-hyderabad/article7072329.ece|title=Doon\u2019s bonds with Hyderabad|first=R. Ravikanth|last=Reddy|date=6 April 2015|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> He also introduced a group discussion as part of the admissions process to test for critical thinking and peer interaction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/dehradun/after-8-decades-doon-school-looks-to-south-east-for-students/story-4uYQRMF8qalW61HFHuB0xM.html|title=After 8 decades, Doon School looks to South, East for students|date=3 July 2017|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> In January 2020, Matthew Raggett stepped down as the tenth headmaster citing personal reasons. In March 2020, the school was shut down and boys were sent home due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]] and [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|Indian ockdown]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/three-city-based-boarding-schools-close/articleshow/74662334.cms|title=Coronavirus scare: Three city-based boarding schools close &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Online classes are being conducted for students through video conferencing apps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-launch-online-classes-to-complete-syllabus/articleshow/74781758.cms|title=Schools launch online classes to complete syllabus in parts of Uttarakhand &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:FC Barcelona camp at Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|Main Field of the school with Kashmir and Hyderabad houses in the background.]]\n\nThe school occupies a single campus covering approximately {{convert|72|acre|m2}} flanked by Chakrata Road and Mall Road in the [[Dehradun Cantonment]] area of Dehradun city, [[Uttarakhand]], India.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114929995090170584 |title=The Andover of India? |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Anita|last=Raghavan|date=24 June 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To house the school, the IPSS acquired Chandbagh Estate in Dehradun from the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] (FRI). Part of the estate was once a deer park. The IPSS also acquired an adjoining estate, now known as Skinner's Field, from the descendants of [[James Skinner (East India Company officer)|James Skinner]]. \n\n===Architecture===\nThe construction of the Main Building, then in FRI, was carried out by Imperial Public Works Department, and finished in 1911. Its Renaissance-style architecture was inspired by [[Basilica Palladiana]] in [[Vicenza]], Italy.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\" /> Many buildings on the campus have been designed by notable Indian architects or firms.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\" /> The library was designed by Romi Khosla, the Biology block by Ram Sharma, teachers' residences by Anagram Architects, and the new Arts and Media Centre, which was inaugurated in October 2010 and shortlisted for the 2010 World Architecture News Education Award, by alumnus Sandeep Khosla <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/5-schools-india-teach-lesson-design-architecture-pune-mumbai/|title=5 schools in India that offer a quick course in sensitive design and architecture|date=10 January 2020|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sandeep Khosla, Principal Architect , Khosla Associates |url=https://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/article/1507033/making-cut |title=Making the cut |publisher=Worldarchitecturenews.com |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Arts and Media Centre houses painting, ceramic, sculpture, and textile studios, along with a lecture hall, film and photography studio, publications' room and exhibition galleries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/86476/arts-and-media-centre-at-the-doon-school-khosla-associates/|title=Arts and Media Centre at the Doon School / Khosla Associates|date=4 November 2010|website=ArchDaily}}</ref> In 2016, the school's Main Building received an \"Honourable Mention\" under the [[UNESCO Asia Pacific Heritage Awards|UNESCO Asia-Pacific Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation]], following the conservation work carried out by Aishwarya Tipnis Architects on the more than a century-old building.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/doon-school-campus-extension-anagram-architects/|title=Take a tour of India\u2019s most elite private school, The Doon School campus|date=21 March 2018|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.one.un.org/page/restoration-of-prayer-hall-at-japan-shrine-wins-top-honor-in-unesco-asia-pacific-heritage-awards/ |title=Restoration of prayer hall at Japan shrine wins top honor in UNESCO Asia- Pacific Heritage Awards - UN India |publisher=In.one.un.org |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Natural environment===\nThe Chandbagh estate is located in a green part of [[Dehradun]] and a wide variety of [[flora]] and [[fauna]] are found on the estate, including many rare trees that date back to the days of the Forest Research Institute.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\">{{cite web|url=https://fountainink.in/essay/no-common-or-garden-affair |title=No common or garden affair &#124; Fountain Ink |publisher=Fountainink.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\" /> The school has over 150 species of trees on its campus, and the formal gardens attract a variety of birds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashant |first=Shishir |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/doon-schools-etp-may-be-trendsetter/428364/ |title=Doon school's ETP may be trendsetter |newspaper=[[Business Standard]] |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1996, a book titled ''Trees of Chandbagh'' was released which provided a comprehensive account of vegetation found on Doon's campus, known as Chandbagh.<ref name=\"TreesofChandbagh\">{{cite book|last=Sahni|first=K. C.|title=Trees of Chandbagh: Doon's national heritage|year=1996|publisher=Konark Publishers|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-220-0457-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> Along similar lines, the illustrated book ''Birds of Chandbagh: A Guide To Birding at The Doon School'' was released in 2019, featuring photographs, illustrations and [[QR codes]] documenting the [[bird calls]] of the species found on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.in/BIRDS-CHANDBAGH-guide-birding-School/dp/B084HG4R87 |title=Buy BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Book Online at Low Prices in India &#124; BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Reviews & Ratings |publisher=Amazon.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has devised an Architectural and Projects Committee, which ensures that any construction taking place on campus is done without disturbing the ecological balance of the wooded school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/7-days/studies-in-style/cid/598008 |title=Studies in style |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2017-10-30 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Houses===\n[[File:TataHouseQuadinDoon.jpg|thumb|right|East wing of Tata House and the quad.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:80%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | House name and Colours\n|-\n! House\n! Colour\n! Swatch\n|-\n|Kashmir || Yellow || {{colour box|#fecb00}}\n|-\n|Oberoi || Sky blue || {{colour box|#00add0}}\n|-\n|Tata || Red || {{colour box|#c60c30}}\n|-\n|Jaipur || Green || {{colour box|#007934}}\n|-\n|Hyderabad || Navy Blue || {{colour box|#003359}}\n|-\n|Martyn || || {{colour box|#496c60}}\n|-\n|Foot || ||{{colour box|#589199}}\n|}\n\nDoon follows the [[house system]]; there are five main houses (Hyderabad, Jaipur, Kashmir, Tata and Oberoi) and two 'holding houses' (Foot and Martyn, named after former headmasters), where new students live for a year before moving to one of the main houses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/pastoral-care/boarding-at-doon/|title=Boarding at Doon|website=Doon School}}</ref> Each house is run by a housemaster or a housemistress, along with a house captain and a team of [[School prefect|prefects]]. One senior boy serves as [[school captain]], chosen by teachers and students voting in a [[secret ballot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-lad-is-Doon-School-captain/articleshow/18424444.cms |title=Ludhiana lad is Doon School captain &#124; Ludhiana News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-02-10 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Boys are assigned to houses at the time of admission and develop great loyalty to them, since all [[intramural sports]] involve fierce competition between houses.\n\nEach housemaster and housemistress is assisted by a [[matron]] known as \"The Dame\", who provides [[pastoral care]] for pupils, some of whom take several weeks to adjust fully to life in a boarding school, particularly given Doon's monastic lifestyle and strict routine.<ref name=\"outlookindia2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230938 |title=Class Up At Doon &#124; Anjali Puri |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Futehally\"> {{cite book |last1=Futehally |first1=Laeeq |title=The Last Englishman: The Life and Times of Jack Gibson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iw1CgAAQBAJ&dq=the+last+englishman+jack+gibson&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2015 |publisher=Hachette UK |location=London |language= |isbn=9789350099698 |page= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= The food and linen was the responsibility of the Dame (Matron)}}</ref> The homes of housemasters and housemistresses are adjacent or physically attached to their houses to enable close supervision and support.\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main Building of the school which houses classrooms and offices.]]\nThe school practices a five-and-a-half-day week consisting of 40 periods (or \"schools\"), each of 40 minutes. The school day begins with \"first bell\" soon after 6:15&nbsp;am. The boys have [[chhota haazri]] before doing [[calisthenics]] outdoors on the playing fields, which is then followed by classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2004-07-04/special-report/27149351_1_education-system-elite-schools-vikram-seth |title=Chhota Hazri bell tolls for desi Etons|newspaper=The Times of India |date=4 July 2004 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon pupils take the [[International General Certificate of Secondary Education]] (IGCSE) exams in [[tenth grade]], which replaced [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] in 2017, and are thereafter offered two strands for the final two years: [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) or [[Indian School Certificate]] (ISC).<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibo.org/en/school/002603 |title=The Doon School - International Baccalaureate\u00ae |publisher=Ibo.org |date=2006-08-28 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year has three terms: Spring, Summer and Autumn. New pupils (\"D-Formers or 7th Graders\") join Doon at the beginning of April. The Autumn Term runs from August to the year-end examinations in November after which the boys are promoted to the new class beginning in February. These internal examinations are known as \"trials\", while examinations leading to certificates such as the [[Indian School Certificate]] are known as \"finals\". Discipline at the school has always been strict, and the school has expelled children from well-known families. In the 1950s, Martyn's suggestion that [[Sanjay Gandhi]] finish his senior year elsewhere was accepted without question by his mother, Indira Gandhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2008/20081202/dplus1.htm |title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India&nbsp;\u2014 Dehradun Plus |work=The Tribune |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> \n\nSocial work, known formally as \"Socially Useful Productive Work\", is also part of school life. All boys of the school must complete a mandatory quota of social service hours every term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/nation-education/article/doon-school-scouts-tamil-nadu-students |title=Doon School scouts for Tamil Nadu students |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon also oversees a Panchayat Ghar teaching impoverished children, and many building projects and workshops for the local community. Pupils and alumni have frequently helped local villages of organised efforts across India to assist people affected by natural disasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roundsquare.org/educational-insights/the-doon-school-a-village-service-partnership/ |title=The Doon School: A Village Service Partnership |publisher=Round Square |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> During the [[1991 Uttarkashi earthquake]] the school's amateur radio club was used by the government for communication purposes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gautam|first=Ashutosh|title=Earthquake: A Natural Disaster|year=2008|publisher=APH Publishing|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-313-0337-5|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSbTJDwMFgAC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=doon+school+uttarkashi+earthquake#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20uttarkashi%20earthquake&f=false}}</ref>  \n\n===School songs===\nThe school songs were deliberately chosen to include both [[Urdu poetry]] and Hindu [[bhajan]]s as a way of emphasising Doon's secular ethos; similarly, the school prayers include a mix of Anglican hymns and Indian poetry.<ref>The Doon School prayer book p.02-26</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false |title=Constructing Post-Colonial India (p.93) |publisher=Routledge |accessdate=5 July 2012|isbn=9780415178563 |year=1998 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Introduction To Indian Social Anthropology (p.152)|first=Krishna|last=Rao|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xxNTbYeyJZUC&pg=PA209&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false|isbn=9788182200777|year=2005}}</ref> Attendance at the morning assembly is required of all pupils and teachers. It traditionally begins with a song from the school's Song Book, which includes: ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''Chisti Ne Jis Zamin Mein'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''Anand Loke'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]]; ''[[Saare Jahan Se Achcha]]'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''[[Lab Pe Aati Hai Dua]]'' by Muhammad Iqbal; ''Vandana Ke in Swaron Mein'' (a [[Bhajan|bhajan]]); ''Ghungat Ke Pat Khol Re'' (attributed to [[Meerabai]]); ''Pitu Matu Sahayak'' (a bhajan); ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' (from a poem by [[Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay]]). Although ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' is India's [[National anthem]], it is traditionally referred to as \"Song No. 1\" at Doon since it was adopted as the School Song in 1935, fifteen years before it was adopted as India's national anthem.<ref>Bathla, Sanjeev<''Chotta Hazri:A Dosco's yatra'' p.32</ref><ref name=\"srivastava\">{{cite book|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School (p.82)|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref>\n\n===Pupils===\nPupils are known as \"Doscos\", a contraction of \"Doon\" and \"school\". The vast majority of alumni are Indians, but a dwindling number are from Pakistan having studied at Doon before the [[Partition of India]] forced them to leave in 1947. Relations between Indian and Pakistani alumni have remained warm over the years, despite the long history of conflict between the two countries.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101024/dplus.htm#2 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HQCvgavbQjgC&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73&dq=pakistani+doon+school#v=onepage&q=pakistani%20doon%20school&f=false |title=Locating home: India's Hyderabadis abroad&nbsp;\u2013 Karen Isaksen Leonard&nbsp;\u2013 Google Books |accessdate=1 March 2012|isbn=9780804754422 |last1=Leonard |first1=Karen Isaksen |year=2007 }}</ref> Boys from Bangladesh and Nepal continue to study at Doon. Doon remains a boys-only school despite pressure from political leaders, including President Pratibha Patil, to become coeducational.<ref name=\"president\"/><ref name=\"telegraphindia1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1101025/jsp/frontpage/story_13097199.jsp |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|title=Dame dilemma for Doon&nbsp;\u2013 President's co-ed suggestion evokes mixed reaction |date=25 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1101031/jsp/7days/story_13121462.jsp |title=The Telegraph&nbsp;\u2013 Calcutta (Kolkata) &#124; Eye on England |work=The Telegraph|location=Kolka ta |date=31 October 2010 |accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\n{{Anchor|Athletics}}\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Cricket at Doon.jpg|thumb|left|A cricket game in progress on the Main Field.]]\n\nSports are compulsory at the school. It has over {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of playing fields, the largest of which are Skinner's Field and the Main Field. Cricket, hockey, athletics, boxing and association football are played seasonally. Tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, basketball, swimming and gymnastics tournaments are also available. Sport is dominated by cricket and hockey during the spring term and by football, athletics and boxing in the autumn term. Inter-house matches are played in cricket, hockey, football and basketball. Sports facilities include a 25-metre swimming pool, a boxing ring and a multi-purpose hall with a gymnasium and facilities for indoor badminton, basketball and table tennis. There are two [[artificial turf]] cricket pitches, five basketball courts, four tennis courts, four squash courts, eight cricket nets, seven fields for hockey and football (which can be converted to four cricket pitches to accommodate seasonal sports), a modern cricket pavilion and two 400-metre athletics tracks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/departments/sports/|title=Sports|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\nDoon hosts the annual Afzal Khan Memorial Basketball Tournament, an inter-school basketball tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/inside-the-hoop-dreams-of-21-boys-at-nbas-first-academy-in-india/articleshow/58979953.cms?from=mdr |title=NBA: Inside the hoop dreams of 21 boys at NBA\u2019s first academy in India - The Economic Times |date=2017-06-04 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020504/ncr3.htm |title=Tribune Online Edition, May 4, 2002 |work=The Tribune |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Clubs and societies===\n{{See|The Doon School Model United Nations}}\n[[File:The Doon School Weekly.jpg|thumb|''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication of Doon.]]\n\nExtracurricular activities are also a compulsory element of school life, and magazines are published in English and Hindi. There are around 23 clubs and societies, including politics, drama, photography, [[Model aircraft|aeromodelling]], first-aid, dramatics, painting, robotics, sculpture, carpentry, [[amateur radio]], music (including [[Trinity College, London|Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations), senior and junior English debating societies, [[The Doon School Model United Nations]], chess and astronomy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20110820/dplus.htm#6 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=20 August 2011|accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In many societies pupils come together to discuss a particular topic, presided over by a schoolmaster and often including a guest speaker. The school has often invited prominent figures to give speeches and talks to the students; these have included heads of state, politicians, ornithologists, naturalists, artists, writers, economists, diplomats and industrialists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/category/events/visiting-speakers/|title=Visiting Speakers Archives|website=Doon School}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/600-mn-to-be-enrolled-in-uidai-in-next-4-years-nilekani/714784 |title=600 Mn to be Enrolled in UIDAI in Next 4 Years: Nilekani |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'' is the official school newspaper, distributed every Saturday morning. It chronicles school activities and is a platform for creative and political writing. It was founded in 1936 and is edited by pupils.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The publication aims to represent the views of the School community as well as Old Boys, and satire and criticism of school policies have been published in the past. More subversive publications, far more critical of teachers and the school establishment, have occasionally been produced without official sponsorship. Other school magazines include ''The Yearbook'' and ''The Doon School Information Review''. Publications by academic departments include '' VIBGYOR'' (Art), ''Echo'' (Science), ''The Econocrat'' (Economics), ''Infinity'' (Mathematics), ''Grand Slam'' (Sports) and ''The Circle'' (History and Political Science).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/|title=Publications|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n===Mountaineering===\n{{Main|Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering}}\n\n[[File:Mt. Everest Base Camp Expedition - 2008, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|2008 expedition to the [[Mount Everest Base Camp]] and [[Kala Patthar]].]]\n\nHalfway through each term, the boys take a one-week \"midterm\"&nbsp;\u2013 a rugged trip, often through the [[Siwalik Hills]] or [[Himalayas]]. Senior boys make treks of up to five days, unaccompanied by teachers, camping out in tents, cooking their own food and hiking. They plan these trips themselves. Alumni have credited these midterms as being among their most formative and character-building experiences.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/how-the-playing-fields-of-doon-nurture-india-incs-best-leaders/articleshow/6872417.cms|title=How the playing fields of Doon nurture India Inc's best leaders |newspaper=The Times of India |date=5 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nDoon has been credited with pioneering mountaineering in India, due to the accomplishments of masters such as [[R.L. Holdsworth]], [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] and alumni such as [[Narendra Dhar Jayal|Nandu Jayal]].<ref name=\"Kohli\"> {{cite book |last1=Kohli |first1=M.S. |title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure and Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Mountains_of_India.html?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&redir_esc=y |date=2002 |publisher=Indus |location= |language= |isbn=9788173871351 |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |page=209 |quote= p.290, Much of the credit for early interest in mountaineering among Indians goes to the Doon School, largely because of some distinguished British mountaineers on its staff like J.A.K. Martyn, J.T.M. Gibson, R.L. Holdsworth...In 1951, Gurdial Singh of the Doon School climbed the 7,120 metres high Trisul. This was the first Indian summit.}}</ref> Notable climbs by staff and alumni include [[Bandarpunch]] (6,316&nbsp;m) in 1950, Kala Nag (6,387&nbsp;m) in 1956, [[Trisul]] (7,120&nbsp;m) in 1951, [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m) in 1955, [[Abi Gamin]] (7,355&nbsp;m) in 1953 and 1955, Mrigthuni (6,855&nbsp;m) in 1958 and Jaonli (6,632 metres) in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/62/16/early-years-of-indian-mountaineering/ |title=Early Years of Indian Mountaineering |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nSome of these expeditions have had their idiosyncrasies. After Gurdial Singh led a successful climb of Trisul, he performed a headstand [[asana]] on the summit as a tribute to the Hindu god [[Shiva]], who is said to abide there. Holdsworth has been claimed to hold the high-altitude record for smoking a pipe, which he did on the summit of [[Kamet]] after the first ascent in 1931.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.himalayanclub.org/journal/obituary/ |title=Obituary |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=30 March 2013}}</ref> Two Doon pupils climbed the [[Matterhorn]] in 1951 wearing cricket boots.<ref name=\"alpinejournal\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Richard|title=Climbing with the Doon School|journal=Alpine Journal|year=2001|pages=197\u2013201|url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2001_files/AJ%202001%20197-201%20Anderson%20Doon%20School.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and music===\n[[File:Waiting for Godot in Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' being staged in the Rose Bowl.]]\nAn [[amphitheatre]] known as the Rose Bowl was built largely by pupils in two years during the 1930s<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=130|quote=It took two years to complete the open air theatre. The first play staged on it was \"The Merchant of Venice prodcued by Jack Gibson, and he had all his actors dressed in Indian costumes.\"}}</ref> and underwent a major structural change in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Santayana|first=Vivek|title=Losing a Kidney|journal=The Doon School Weekly|date=24 October 2009|issue=2232|url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66UfGMuG8?url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It can seat up to 2,000 people and has been the setting for numerous [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays and other classics of western theatre, as well as musical performances and speeches during school ceremonies such as Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805061511/http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=Doon Online&nbsp;\u2013 Vikram Seth |publisher=Mtholyoke.edu |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Multi-Purpose Hall is a more modern indoor theatre that can accommodate approximately 2,000 people. Plays are regularly staged in [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]], with 8\u20139 productions each year including 2 major productions as part of the Founder's Day celebrations. The Inter House Once-Act Play competition is held each year, alternatively in English and Hindi. Many of the plays historically have been joint productions with the Welham Girls' School in [[Dehradun]].\n\nIn 2001 a new music school was built beside the Rose Bowl. It houses a [[music library]], a [[concert hall]] and several practice and teaching rooms where students learn various western and Indian instruments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/stas-and-activities/music/|title=Music Programme and Facilities at The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> Pupils of the school have an option to appear for the [[Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations, conducted by [[Trinity College London]], in [[piano]], [[violin]], drums and classical guitar. In 2002 the school choir raised {{Indian Rupee}} 2&nbsp;million for victims of the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] by organising a charity concert with the title ''Concerto 2000'', in which drummer [[Sivamani]] also took part.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/04/11/stories/2002041100070300.htm |title=Raga meets rhythm |newspaper=The Hindu |date=11 April 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/lf/2002/03/30/stories/2002033000930200.htm |title=Doon tunes |newspaper=The Hindu |date=30 March 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To commemorate its Platinum Jubilee, the school launched a music album called ''Spirit of Doon'' in collaboration with [[EMI]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-and-interviews/28261521_1_music-album-doscos-alumni |title=Doon goes musical|newspaper=The Times of India |date=14 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The school choir sang two songs (\"Lab pe Aati Hai Dua\" and \"Anand Loke\") for the project but only the former was included in the final recording. The tracks were written by the lyricist [[Gulzar]] and were sung by [[Sonu Nigam]], Shayan Italia and [[Bhajan Sopori]].<ref name=\"bare_url\" />\n\n==Affiliations==\n\n===Ties with other schools===\n\nFrom its foundation in 1937 until the early 1980s, [[Welham Boys' School]] was a [[feeder school]] for Doon School and Mayo College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/31886-welham-boys-school-to-celebrate-platinum-jubilee-year.html |title=Welham Boys' School to celebrate platinum jubilee year |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> This ended when Surendra Kandhari, an old boy and former housemaster at Doon, became Principal of Welham and transformed it into a high school. Several families who send their sons to Doon send their daughters to [[Welham Girls' School]], and many Doon alumni have married alumnae of Welham.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070121/ttlife1.htm |title=The Tribune Lifestyle |newspaper=The Tribune |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NorthIndia/Boys-will-be-boys/Article1-617029.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021022231/http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NorthIndia/Boys-will-be-boys/Article1-617029.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 October 2012 |title=Boys will be boys |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The two schools hold an annual \"dance social\", and their alumni sometimes collaborate in organising events. Pakistani ex-pupils from Doon established the [[Chand Bagh School]] 40&nbsp;km north of [[Lahore]], Pakistan, in 1998, modelling it on the general structure of Doon.<ref>{{cite web|author=Azhar M. A. Qureshi |url=http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611010826/http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2009 |title=Chand Bagh School |publisher=Chandbagh.edu.pk |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> Doon also has exchange programmes with a number of overseas schools, such as Eton College, Harrow School, [[St. Albans School (Washington, D.C.)|St. Albans School, Washington DC]], [[Millfield]], [[Schule Schloss Salem]], [[The Armidale School]], [[Bridge House School]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[King's Academy]], [[Stowe School]], [[Scotch College, Melbourne]], [[The Hutchins School]] and [[St. Mark's School (Texas)]]. In 2011 Doon twinned with [[The Thomas Hardye School]], Dorchester, [[England]], through a cultural exchange project organised by the [[BBC]] and [[British Council]] in light of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] held in the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9451296.stm|title=Schools Spotlight on Team Abhinav Bindra|publisher=BBC|date=8 April 2011|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Schools with similar names===\nAs private schools became more widespread in [[India]], several other schools used \"Doon\" as part of their names, causing some confusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-using-doon-in-their-names-to-cash-the-popularity-of-the-doon-school/articleshow/69224014.cms |title=Schools using Doon in their names to cash the popularity of The Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Among them are Doon Global School, Doon Presidency School, [[Doon International School (Palia Kalan)|Doon International School]], Doon Preparatory School, Doon Cambridge School, Doon Girls School, [[Doon Public School]] (in West Delhi, not the Doon Valley) and the Doon College of Spoken English. None of them are related to The Doon School.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-24/special-report/28263544_1_doon-school-ipsc-sainik-schools |title=Is the old school tie wearing thin?|newspaper=The Times of India |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Memberships===\nThe Doon School is a member of following organisations: [[G20 Schools]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gold |first=Adam |url=http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073515/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 October 2007 |title=Move over G8\u2014this is G20 > Harvard Westlake Chronicle Online |publisher=Students.hw.com |date=8 November 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Round Square]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925000935/http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 September 2012 |title=Doon School India |publisher=RoundSquare |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Interact Club|Rotary International's Interact Club]], [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/ |title=HMC Schools : International Members |publisher=Hmc.org.uk |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[International Boys' Schools Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theibsc.org/page.cfm?p=38&filter_data7=&filter_data10=INDIA&filter_data13=&filter_data15=&key=&submit=SEARCH |title=International Boys' Schools Coalition: Member Directory |publisher=Theibsc.org |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examinations]], [[International Baccalaureate|International Baccalaureate Organization (IBO)]],<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\"/> Indian Public Schools' Conference,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802223143/http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 August 2012 |title=Indian Public Schools' Conference |publisher=Ipsc.co.in |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Rashtriya Life Saving Society (India)]], [[International Award Association]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Pioneer |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/doon-school-becomes-first-indian-school-to-start-iayp-online.html |title=Doon School becomes first Indian school to start IAYP online |publisher=Dailypioneer.com |date=2014-08-06 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe school is the regional test centre for [[University of Cambridge ESOL Examinations]] and [[SAT]] Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivyzone.com/category/sat/test-centre/ |title=SAT l STUDY ABROAD l VISA I IvyZone.com &#124; Test-centre |publisher=Ivyzone.com |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n;Doon in films & television\n{{main|Dazed in Doon}}\n{{main|Indian Summer School}}\n\n* The film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'', which was commissioned by the School on the occasion of its 75th anniversary and produced by old boy Ashvin Kumar, was banned by the school authorities because it \"doesn't give the school a good name\".<ref name=\"dazed\" /><ref name=\"fallout\" /> The dispute remains unresolved.<ref name=ex-student-film />\n* In September 2010, [[BBC Sport]] made a documentary on the Doon School for the ''World Olympic Dreams'' Project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9075650.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 The school that breeds Indian medal winners |publisher=BBC News |date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The documentary was produced in association with the [[British Council]]. Its main purpose was to show the school where [[Abhinav Bindra]], the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, spent his formative years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 Abhinav Bindra, India |publisher=BBC News |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* In the 2010 Bollywood film [[Aisha (film)|Aisha]], the character Randhir Gambhir is a Doon School alumnus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/previews/12-aisha-movie-preview-061009.asp |title=Aisha movie preview |publisher=glamsham.com |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2017, [[Channel 4]] of UK commissioned a 3-part documentary, ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', where working-class boys from the UK were given a chance to study at Doon for a term to see if they would benefit from the all-round experience of an Indian residential school. The filming began in August 2017, and the programmes were broadcast in March\u2013April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/29/indian-summer-school-review-five-terrible-teens-are-sent-to-indias-equivalent-of-eton |title=Indian Summer School review \u2013 five terrible teens are sent to India\u2019s equivalent of Eton &#124; Television & radio |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n;Doon in literature\n* [[Vikram Seth]] used his own experiences of being bullied at Doon to model the character of Tapan in ''[[A Suitable Boy]]''.<ref name=\"suitablejoy\" /><ref name=\"nytimes1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book&nbsp;\u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1993 |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref>\n* In [[Salman Rushdie]]'s short-story anthology [[East, West]], the protagonists Zulu and Chekhov are Doscos.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theroundtable.ro/Current/Literary/Titus_Pop_Eastern_and_Western_Cultural_Commingling_in_Rushdie_s_Stories.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=5 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130619225420/http://www.theroundtable.ro/Current/Literary/Titus_Pop_Eastern_and_Western_Cultural_Commingling_in_Rushdie_s_Stories.pdf |archive-date=19 June 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlantisjournal.org/ARCHIVE/31.2/2009Ganapathy-Dore.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224003035/http://www.atlantisjournal.org/ARCHIVE/31.2/2009Ganapathy-Dore.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 December 2010 |title=Shakespeare in Rushdie/Shakespearean Rushdie |accessdate=30 March 2013}}</ref>\n* In [[Tenzing Norgay]]'s autobiography ''Man of Everest'', he refers to [[Bandarpunch]] as \"The Doon School mountain\" due to the fact that the mountain was frequented by two Doon School teachers [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John Martyn]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norgay |first1=Tenzing |title=Man of Everest \u2013 The Autobiography of Tenzing |url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=90IPAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=doon+school+mountain |date=1955 |publisher=[[George G. Harrap and Co.]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781447400288 |page=154 |quote= It was to Garhwal. Back to Bandar Punch, \"the Doon School mountain,\" with my old friend Mr Gibson. }}</ref>\n* In [[Ruskin Bond]]'s novella ''Strangers in the Night'', character Jai Shankar is from Doon.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JIZHr-st3cYC&pg=PA4&dq=%22doon+school%22#v=onepage&q=%22doon%20school%22&f=false |title=Strangers in the Nights: Two Novellas - Ruskin Bond - Google Books |accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9780140240658 |last1=Yadav |first1=Rajendra |last2=Bond |first2=Ruskin |year=1994 }}</ref>\n* [[Penguin Books|Penguin's]] ''The Great Speeches of Modern India'' (2011) included Vikram Seth's 1992 Founder's Day address, which being confessional surprised the school community, and [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]'s 2007 speech, which was noted for its wit and humour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7dCH_IYbt8C&q=doon+school#v=snippet&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=The Great Speeches of Modern India - Rudranghsu Mukherjee - Google Books |date= October 2011|accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9788184002348 |last1=Mukherjee |first1=Rudranghsu }}</ref>\n\n;Doon in research\n* ''Doon School Chronicles'' is the first of five [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] films called the ''Doon School Quintet'', made by David MacDougall between 1997 and 2000 about the culture of the School.<ref>{{cite video|first=David|last=MacDougall|url=http://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/526/doon-school-chronicles.html |title=DOON SCHOOL CHRONICLES|publisher=Ronin Films|accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/302112/Doon-School-Chronicles/overview |title=Doon School Chronicles|work=The New York Times |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220001143/http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 February 2006 |title=Berkeley Media LLC: Catalog: Doon School Chronicles |publisher=Berkeleymedia.com |accessdate=20 February 2012 }}</ref> Macdougall has written of a tendency of some alumni to idealise a ''[[Golden age (metaphor)|Golden Age]]'' set in the first decade of the school's life, which sometimes makes them resistant to change.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\"/>\n* ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School'' by Sanjay Srivastva is a detailed [[Sociology|sociological]] study of the school's culture and how it has influenced India's national character.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva}}</ref>\n* ''{{'}}Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools'', a 2005 report by the Institute of Social Studies Trust, discusses why the Doon School has no [[Reservation in India|reservations]] (quotas for specific social groups) in its admissions process. The post quotes an unnamed student who explains, \"passing the Doon School entrance exam means that you have proved yourself worthy of the school. Reserving seats for students seems to imply that the school must prove itself worthy of you.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Mallica |title='Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools |url=http://www.isst-india.org/PDF/Poor%20children%20in%20Rich%20school.pdf |publisher=Institute of Social Studies Trust |accessdate=30 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1969, [[Asian Survey]] (then Asian Review) - an Asian studies [[academic journal]] of [[University of California, Berkeley]] - produced a report on The Doon School as a part of their project which documented Indian history after the entry of [[East India Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sh4sAQAAIAAJ&q=doon+school&dq=doon+school |title=Asian review&nbsp;\u2014 Demetrius Charles Boulger, East India Association (London, England), Oriental Institute (Woking, England)  |accessdate=30 March 2013|last1=Boulger |first1=Demetrius Charles |year=1969 }}</ref>\n* In ''Indian Tales of the Raj'', Zareer Masani studies how Doon School's alumni affected the Indian political scene in the '60s.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Lm4FVb54_oUC&pg=PA152&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=Indian Tales of the Raj&nbsp;\u2014 Zareer Masani  |accessdate=30 March 2013|isbn=9780520071278 |last1=Masani |first1=Zareer |year=1988 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n\n\n{{Main|List of The Doon School alumni}}\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School alumni}}\n[[File:Rahul Gandhi at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Rahul Gandhi]] (Class of 1988), Indian politician, [[Member of Parliament, Lok Sabha]] speaking at The Doon School Model United Nations' Conference in August 2017.]]\nPupils of Doon have gone on to achieve prominence in politics, government service, the armed forces of India and Pakistan, commerce, journalism, the arts and literature.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-09-04/news/30112792_1_boys-clubs-doon-school-dosco |title=Old boys' clubs of Doon School, IITs, IIMs, Harvard and others mean more than just databases |newspaper=The Times of India|accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707070626/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Naveen Patnaik sets stage for GeNext Doscos |newspaper=The Times of India |date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/06/01/stories/2009060153270700.htm |title=Other States / Uttaranchal News : Seven Doon alumni in 15th Lok Sabha |newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> They include nine [[Union Cabinet of India|Cabinet Ministers]], two [[chief minister]]s, several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] and [[Legislative Assembly|state Legislative Assemblies]];,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/news/special-videos/kamal-naths-journeydoon-school-to-parliament_446626.html |title=If India has to grow, we have to bridge infra deficit: Nath |work=CNBC-TV18 |publisher=Moneycontrol.com |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> nineteen generals, two admirals, former heads of the Indian and Pakistani Air Forces and twenty-four ambassadors, including those from India, Pakistan, Nepal and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pubby |first=Vipin |url=http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/Badal-vs-Badal/697446/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120730012554/http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/Badal-vs-Badal/697446/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 July 2012 |title=Badal vs Badal |publisher=Express India |date=14 October 2010 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-04-18/india/28002685_1_sukhbir-badal-doscos-media-campaign |title=Old boys' network at work in war-zone Bathinda&nbsp;\u2013 Times of India |work=The Times of India |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The best-known alumnus is former Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]], who appointed many Doon friends to prominent positions. Although any alumnus seldom held public office for some time afterward, this changed with the political ascendance of Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia, Kamal Nath, Kalikesh Singh Deo and Rahul Gandhi.<ref name=\"telegraphindia1\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376408_1_doon-school-doscos-singh-and-vishvjeet-singh |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707125405/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376408_1_doon-school-doscos-singh-and-vishvjeet-singh |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Dooned if you do, damned if&nbsp;...|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> \n[[File:Sanjit Bunker Roy at Time 2010.jpg|thumb|left|160px|[[Bunker Roy]] (Class of 1962), Social activist and the founder of [[Barefoot College]], [[Tilonia]].]]\nNotable Doon alumni to have held senior positions in Indian and Pakistani politics include the former Indian diplomat turned politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]], currently a Rajya Sabha nominee, the former Defence Secretary of Pakistan [[Ghulam Jilani Khan]], [[Kamal Nath]] (Politician, class of 1964), [[Rahul Gandhi]] (Congress Politician, class of 1988), [[Sanjay Gandhi]] (Congress Politician, class of 1964),<ref>{{cite news|last=Bajpai |first=Kanti |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-24/news-interviews/29809510_1_amitabh-bachchan-teji-bachchan-rajiv-gandhi |title=Amitabh Bachchan in Doon School|newspaper=The Times of India |date=1 November 2008 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Koel Rinchet Poorie |url=http://blogs.intoday.in/index.php?option=com_myblog&contentid=61472&show=Inpoliticsbydefault.html&blogs=2 |title=Kamal Nath Makes It!|newspaper=Headlines Today |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Allana |first=Alia |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/doon-squad/464930/ |title=The Doon School Squad|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> [[Naveen Patnaik]] (Politician, class of 1964), [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] (Politician, class of 1989),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://india.gov.in/govt/loksabhampbiodata.php?mpcode=3958|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514143320/http://india.gov.in/govt/loksabhampbiodata.php?mpcode=3958|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 May 2011|title=Indian Government Profile}}</ref> [[Dr. Karan Singh]] (Politician, class of 1948)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://india.gov.in/govt/rajyasabhampbiodata.php?mpcode=82 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009004439/http://india.gov.in/govt/rajyasabhampbiodata.php?mpcode=82 |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 October 2012 |title=Minister Profile |publisher=The Government of India |date=31 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\nIn the field of Literature and Poetry, Doon alumni include [[Amitav Ghosh]] (class of 1972),<ref>{{cite web|author=Elisabeth Bumiller |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/29/books/a-novelist-beginning-with-a-bang.html |title=A Novelist Beginning With a Bang - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1997-07-29 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> [[Ramachandra Guha]] (class of 1973),<ref>{{cite journal|last=Naqvi |first=Saba |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?225730 |title=ARam Guha in Doon School|journal=Outlook Magazine |date=1 November 2007 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> [[Vikram Seth]] (class of 1970),<ref>{{cite news|author=Richard B. Woodward |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1993-05-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> [[Ardashir Vakil]].\n\nDoon alumni in journalism include [[Prannoy Roy]] (class of 1965), [[Aroon Purie]] (class of 1962),<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chandra |first=Ram |url=http://www.careers360.com/news/3632-Aroon-Purie-Editor-in-Chief-India-Today |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124094457/http://www.careers360.com/news/3632-Aroon-Purie-Editor-in-Chief-India-Today |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 November 2009 |title=Aroon Purie on Education |journal=Careers 360 News Magazine |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012 }}</ref> [[Karan Thapar]], [[Virendra Prabhakar]] and [[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]]. The first Indian [[Rhodes scholar]] was a Doon School alumni - [[Lovraj Kumar]].<ref>{{cite news|author=I. M. D. Little |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lovraj-kumar-1367199.html |title=Obituary: Lovraj Kumar|newspaper=The Independent |date=1 April 1994 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon is also the alma mater of the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, [[Abhinav Bindra]] (class of 1999) and the mountaineering pioneer [[Nandu Jayal]].<ref>{{cite news|author=BBC Sports Desk |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=Abhinav Bindra Indian Olympic Medallist|publisher=BBC |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Anish Kapoor at the Deutsche Guggenheim - Berlin.jpg|thumb|right|160px|[[Anish Kapoor]] (Class of 1970) is a sculptor whose designs include [[ArcelorMittal Orbit]], [[Olympic Park, London]].<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/>]]\nIn the field of Arts and Entertainment, Doon's alumni include [[Roshan Seth]] (Class of 1960),<ref>{{cite journal|last=Harper |first=Alan |url=http://www.harpritsan.com/DoonFutureArticle.html |title=The Doon Future|journal=Harpitsan Magazine (Outlook) |date=1 November 2008 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> [[Himani Shivpuri]] (class of 1971),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/article2890613.ece |title=A Renaissance Woman|newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> [[Chandrachur Singh]], [[Satyadeep Mishra]] (class of 1991) and [[Abhishek Poddar]], a prominent art collector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/features/The-Abhishek-and-Radhika-Poddar-collection-of-Indian-Modern-and-Contemporary-Art-7960-1.aspx |title=How Abhishek and Radhika Poddar built their collection of Indian art &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date=2016-12-18 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The sculptor [[Anish Kapoor]] (class of 1970) also attended Doon.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://forbesindia.com/article/recliner/anish-kapoor-making-it-big/19942/1|journal=Forbes India|title=Anish Kapoor Making it Big}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jun/07/anish-kapoor-sculpture-versailles-controversy |title=Anish Kapoor: superstar sculptor who loves to court scandal &#124; Observer profile &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn Business, the Doon alumni included [[Anil Kumar]], former senior partner at [[McKinsey & Company]] and co-founder of the [[Indian School of Business]], [[Gautam Thapar]], founder and chairman of the [[Avantha Group]], [[Malvinder Mohan Singh]] and [[Shivinder Mohan Singh]], former owners of [[Ranbaxy Laboratories]] and presently owning [[Fortis Healthcare]], [[Rohit Kapoor]], founder and CEO of EXL Service.com. \n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Faculty===\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School faculty}}\nPrevious teachers have included: [[Peter Lawrence (teacher)|Peter Lawrence]],<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4309213.stm|title=Eton, the Raj and modern India|date=9 March 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20041207/edit.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Opinions|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John A. K. Martyn]],<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> [[Sheel Vohra]],<ref name=\"tribuneindia1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101014/dplus.htm#3 |title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India&nbsp;\u2014 Dehradun Plus |work=The Tribune |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> [[R. L. Holdsworth]],<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/> [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]],<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/> [[Sudhir Khastgir]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?267708 |title=Bonfire of Vanities &#124; Vishvjit P. Singh |publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> [[Chetan Anand (director)|Chetan Anand]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8y8vN9A14nkC&pg=PT89&dq=taught+at+doon+school|title=Encyclopaedia of Hindi Cinema|first=Encyclopedia|last=Britannica|date=16 January 2019|publisher=Popular Prakashan|via=Google Books|isbn=9788179910665}}</ref> [[Simon Singh]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/there-s-math-in-simpsons-simon-says/story-czEcewcbqXaAuE38U6oF2K.html|title=There's math in Simpsons, Simon says|date=11 January 2014|work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref> [[Vikram Seth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://itv.in/index.php?option=com_sentiments&view=detail&sid=576&Itemid=3 |title=A reverie at a book-reading |work=Hindustan Times |date=5 March 1999 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> [[Satendra Nandan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/25/its-time-goodbye-comrades/|title=It's Time: Goodbye, COMRADES - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref> [[Ashok Roy]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Schools|Education}}\n* [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://archive.is/20121219012747/http://fullcirclebooks.in/content/chhota-hazri-days-doscos-yatra ''Chhota Hazri Days: A Dosco's Yatra''] by Sanjiv Bathla, [[Rupa & Co.]], 2010 {{ISBN|978-81-291-1694-9}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130323003553/http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/sahibs-who-loved-india ''Sahibs who Loved India''] by [[Khushwant Singh]], [[Penguin Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-14-341580-0}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&q=Doon+School&dq=the+doon+school+sixty+years+on+pushpinder&source=gbs_word_cloud_r&cad=5#v=snippet&q=Doon%20School&f=false ''The Corporeal Image''] by David McDougall, [[Princeton University Press]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-691-12156-7}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Trees of Chandbagh''] by K.C. Sinha, Konark Publishers, 1996, {{ISBN|978-81-220-0457-1}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=3sVlHQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''For Hills To Climb''] by Gurdial Singh and Nalni Dhar, The Doon School Old Boys' Society, 2001.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=NEdmQgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Doon, The Story of a School''], IPSS (1985) edited by Sumer Singh, published by the Indian Public Schools Society 1985. ASIN B0006ENF66\n* [http://dsobs.net/currentrb/current_rosebowl.php ''The Rose Bowl''],  a periodic newsletter by the Doon School Old Boys' Society\n* [https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School, ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School''] by Sanjay Srivastva, published by [[Routledge]] 1998 {{ISBN|0-203-98027-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=The Doon School |s=Category:The Doon School |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School }}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.doonschool.com/|name = Official website}}\n* [http://www.dsobs.net/ Website of the Doon School Old Boys' Society]\n* [http://store.doonschool.com/ The Doon School - Gift Store]\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School}}\n[[Category:The Doon School| ]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Round Square schools]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in India]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in India]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in India]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "CallMeByYourMane", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2010 Founder's Day celebrations:fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Doon_School"}
{"title_page": "Cadillac Cimarron", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image = Cadillac_Cimarron_2_--_07-01-2009.jpg\n| name = Cadillac Cimarron\n| caption = ''1987-1988 Cadillac Cimarron''\n| manufacturer = [[General Motors]]\n| production = 1981\u20131988\n| model_years = 1982\u20131988\n| class = [[Compact executive car]]\n| length = {{convert|177.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|66.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|54.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]\n| platform = [[GM J platform|J-body]]\n| wheelbase = 101.2 in (2570 mm)\n| transmission = 4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]<br>5-speed manual<br>3-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|Transverse front-engine, front-wheel drive]]\n| engine = 1.8 L ''[[GM 122 engine#L46|L46]]'' [[Straight-4|I4]] (gasoline)<br>2.0 L ''[[GM 122 engine#LQ5|LQ5]]'' [[Straight-4|I4]] (gasoline)<br>2.8&nbsp;L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#LB6|LB6]]'' [[V6]] (gasoline)\n| related = [[Buick Skyhawk]]<br>[[Chevrolet Cavalier]]<br>[[Oldsmobile Firenza]]<br>[[Pontiac Sunbird|Pontiac J2000/2000/Sunbird]]\n| successor = [[Cadillac BLS]] (FWD) <br> [[Cadillac Catera]] (RWD)\n| assembly = United States: [[Janesville, Wisconsin]], ([[Janesville GM Assembly Plant]])<br>[[South Gate, California]], ([[South Gate Assembly]])\n}}\nThe '''Cadillac Cimarron''' is an [[Compact executive car#History in the United States|entry-level luxury car]] manufactured and marketed by the [[Cadillac]] division of [[General Motors]] from 1981 to 1988 as a four-door sedan across a single generation.  \n\nMarking Cadillac's entry into the compact segment<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ewAAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA71&dq=Cadillac+Cimarron+compact#v=onepage&q=Cadillac%20Cimarron%20compact&f=false|title=Popular Science|last=Corporation|first=Bonnier|date=August 1985|publisher=Bonnier Corporation}}</ref> and using the [[GM J platform]], the Cimarron was introduced and marketed concurrently with  [[badge engineering|rebadged]] J-platform variants from each of its divisions, and was manufactured at [[South Gate Assembly]] and [[Janesville Assembly Plant|Janesville Assembly]].  Following South Gate's closure in 1982, assembly continued in Janesville.\n\nThe Cimarron is noted as a [[wikt:nadir|nadir]] of GM's product planning for its low sales, poor performance and ill-conceived badge engineering.\n\n== Background ==\nAs General Motors prepared for the 1980s, Cadillac product planners considered a sedan smaller than the [[Cadillac Seville|Seville]].  While the Seville had sold well, in its research of buyers, Cadillac learned that in place of import buyers, many Sevilles were purchased by traditional luxury-car buyers wanting a smaller car.  To diversify and modernize their product range, and complement the Seville which competed with premium European luxury sedans, Cadillac dealers requested a smaller car that could compete with compact European sedans.<ref name=\"Yates, page 71\">Yates, p. 71.</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ySZhMJrzhw4C&lpg=PT83&dq=Cadillac%20Cimarron&pg=PT83#v=onepage&q=Cadillac%20Cimarron&f=false |title=GM Designs for the '80s |work=Popular Science |last=Dunne |first=Jim |page=88 |date=January 1981 |publisher=Bonnier Corporation }}</ref>\n\nIn one of the shortest development programs undertaken by General Motors, development of the Cimarron began in early 1980,<ref name=\"RD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rideanddrive.com/disasters/cimarron.html|title=Trouble In Paradise: The Story of the Cadillac Cimarron|author=Bonsall, Thomas E.|year=1997|work=RideAndDrive.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010118205200/http://www.rideanddrive.com/disasters/cimarron.html|archivedate=January 18, 2001|url-status=dead|accessdate=2009-10-04|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />  even though other vehicles of the GM J-platform had been in development since 1976.<ref>[[Brock Yates|Yates, Brock]]: ''The Decline and Fall of the American Automobile Industry'', p. 24. Empire Books, 1983.</ref>  While General Motors wanted Cadillac to better compete with other luxury brands, the use of the J-platform to do so was met with heavy resistance.  [[Pete Estes]], GM's president at the time, warned Ed Kennard, Cadillac's general manager: \"Ed, you don't have time to turn the J-car into a Cadillac.\"<ref name=\"RD\" />\n\nOriginally scheduled for mid-1980s release,<ref name=\"Yates, page 71\" /> the Cimarron was released in early 1981 along with the Chevrolet Cavalier, Buick Skyhawk, Oldsmobile Firenza, and Pontiac J2000 (later marketed as the Sunbird).  With the Seville competing with mid-size/large European luxury sedans, the Cimarron was marketed as a sportier sedan, competing with the [[Audi 80#4000 (1980\u20131987) & 4000 5+5|Audi 4000]], [[BMW 3 Series (E21)#North American models|BMW 320i]], [[Saab 900#Saab 900 \"Classic\"|Saab 900]], and [[Volvo 200 Series|Volvo 240]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Cadillac/1982_Cadillac/1982%20Cadillac%20Cimarron%20Brochure/image9.html|title=1982 Cadillac Cimarron Brochure|last=Ristic-Petrovic|first=Dusan|website=www.oldcarbrochures.com|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref>\n\n== Model name ==\nAt its 1981 introduction, the copy text of original sales brochures associated the Cimarron nameplate with \"fortitude, adventure and pioneering\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Cadillac/1982_Cadillac/1982%20Cadillac%20Cimarron%20Brochure/image2.html|title=1982 Cadillac Cimarron Brochure|last=Ristic-Petrovic|first=Dusan|website=www.oldcarbrochures.com|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref> The nameplate was chosen from a list that included J2000 (used on predecessor of [[Pontiac Sunbird]]); Carmel; Cascade; Caville ([[portmanteau]] of Cadillac and [[Cadillac de Ville series|De Ville]]); Envoy; and [[Cadillac Series 62|Series 62]] (predecessor of [[Cadillac Calais]]).<ref>Witzenburg, Gary. \"The Name Game\", ''Motor Trend'', 4/84, p. 86.</ref><ref>Witzenburg, p. 86.</ref>  For 1982, the brand nomenclature was \"Cimarron by Cadillac\", although initially the Cadillac name did not appear on the car.  <ref name=\"RD\" /><ref name=\"buzz1\" />  For 1983, the nameplate was simply \"Cadillac Cimarron\".<ref name=\"RD\" />\n\n==Design==\nThe Cimarron was built using the front-wheel drive [[GM J platform]], using a {{Convert|101.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} wheelbase.  Using [[Vehicle frame|unibody]] construction, the front suspension consists of a [[MacPherson strut]] configuration (mounted to a front subframe), with a rear suspension using [[torsion beam]] axle, along with front and rear stabilizer bars.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Cadillac/1983_Cadillac/1983_Cadillac_Cimarron_Brochure/1983%20Cadillac%20Cimarron-15.html|title=Cimarron '83|publisher=Cadillac Devison of General Motors|accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor 1982, the Cimarron was equipped with a 1.8&nbsp;L four-cylinder engine, producing {{convert|88|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} (the first four-cylinder Cadillac since 1914 and the first engine below 2.0&nbsp;L displacement since 1908).  For 1983, the engine was enlarged to 2.0&nbsp;L and given fuel injection, though engine tuning would drop peak output to {{convert|86|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}.  For 1985, a 2.8&nbsp;L V6 (shared with the Chevrolet Cavalier and Oldsmobile Firenza) was added as an option, producing {{convert|130|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}; for 1987, the V6 became standard.  The four-cylinder engines were paired with a 4-speed manual (later a 5-speed), with a 3-speed automatic as an option; the 3-speed automatic was the sole transmission with the V6.\n\nTo distinguish the Cimarron from the Chevrolet Cavalier and its Buick, Oldsmobile, and Pontiac counterparts, Cadillac standardized many of the available features offered on J-platform cars at the time, including air conditioning, leather seats, alloy wheels, power mirrors, full instrumentation (including tachometer; the only Cadillac to do so at the time), courtesy lights, intermittent wipers, rear window defogger, and AM/FM stereo.<ref name=\":0\" />  Its interior featured simulated aluminum trim, notably foregoing simulated wood trim.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Cadillac/1982_Cadillac/1982%20Cadillac%20Cimarron%20Brochure/image6.html|title=1982 Cadillac Cimarron Brochure|last=Ristic-Petrovic|first=Dusan|website=www.oldcarbrochures.com|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Cadillac/1983_Cadillac/1983_Cadillac_Cimarron_Brochure/1983%20Cadillac%20Cimarron-13.html|title=Directory Index: Cadillac/1983_Cadillac/1983_Cadillac_Cimarron_Brochure|website=www.oldcarbrochures.com|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nAvailable options included automatic transmission, cruise control, tilt steering wheel, power windows, power door locks, power driver and passenger seats, sunroof, and a cassette player.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />  With the exception of its upholstery and model-specific special suspension tuning, other J-platform models could be optioned nearly identically to a Cimarron though doing so would raise prices close to the $12,131 base price of the Cadillac in 1982.<ref name=\"RD\" /><ref name=\"buzz1\" />    \n<gallery mode=\"packed\" caption=\"1982-1988 Cimarron\">\nFile:1981 cimarron 1.jpg|1982 Cimarron\nFile:1981 cimarron 2.jpg|1982 Cimarron, rear\nFile:Cadillac Cimarron (5810874724).jpg|1985 Cimarron D'Oro\nFile:1988 Cadillac Cimarron.jpg|1988 Cimarron\n</gallery>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\nThe Cimarron's market failure is one in a series of events throughout the 1980s and 1990s which caused Cadillac's share of the US market  to decline from 3.8% in 1979 to 2.2% in 1997;<ref>Flammang and Kowalke, pp. 149-189</ref> it is routinely cited as the nadir of GM's product planning:\n\n:*Noted automotive journalist [[Dan Neil]] included the Cimarron in his 2007 list of ''Worst Cars of all Time'', saying \"everything that was wrong, venal, lazy, and mendacious about GM in the 1980s was crystallized in this flagrant insult to the good name and fine customers of Cadillac.\"<ref name=\"time\">{{cite web\n  | title = The 50 Worst Cars of All Time\n  | publisher = Time Magazine\n  | author = Dan Neil\n  | url = http://content.time.com/time/specials/2007/0,28757,1658545,00.html}}</ref> He added that the Cimarron \"nearly killed Cadillac and remains its biggest shame.\"<ref name=time/>\n\n:*''[[Forbes]]'' placed the Cimarron on its list of \"Legendary Car Flops,\" citing low sales, poor performance and the fact the car \"didn't work, coming from a luxury brand.\"<ref name=\"buzz1\">{{cite web\n  | title = Rebadged Disasters: Cadillac Cimarron\n  | publisher = Carbuzz.com\n  | author =\n  | date = November 11, 2012\n  | url = http://www.carbuzz.com/news/2012/11/11/Rebadged-Disasters-Cadillac-Cimarron-7711547/}}</ref>\n\n:*CarBuzz called the Cimarron a \"textbook example of what goes wrong when a carmaker tries to badge engineer an economy car into a luxury car.\"<ref name=\"buzz2\">{{cite web\n  | title = Rebadged Disasters\n  | publisher = Carbuzz.com\n  | url = http://www.carbuzz.com/news/2012/11/11/Rebadged-Disasters-Cadillac-Cimarron-7711547/}}</ref>\n\n:*Author Hannah Elliott said the Cimarron \"appealed neither to Cadillac's loyal followers, who appreciated powerful V8s and Cadillac's domestic luxury edge, nor to buyers who favored Europe's luxury brands, whose cars out-handled and out-classed the Cimarron in every way.\"<ref name=\"autos.yahoo.com\">{{cite news\n|title=Legendary Car Flops\n|work=Forbes\n|url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/04/21/car-flops-toyota-forbeslife-vehicles-edsel-ford-gm.html\n|date=May 2010\n|accessdate=Jan 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n:*[[CNNMoney.com|CNN Money]] described the Cimarron as \"in all important respects, a Chevrolet Cavalier. It also added thousands to the price tag. In all, it was neither a good Cadillac nor a good value. Today, GM executives will readily admit that this was a bad idea.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|title=GM's Junk Heap: Cadillac Cimarron\n|work=CNN Money\n|url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2009/autos/0905/gallery.gm_problem_cars/3.html\n|date=May 2009\n|accessdate=2009-06-02}}</ref>\n\n:*''[[Car and Driver]]'' said a subsequent Cadillac product director, John Howell, kept a picture of the Cimarron on his wall captioned, \"Lest we forget.\"<ref>Hutton, Ray, [http://www.caranddriver.com/carnews/11058/upfront-news-2006-cadillac-bls.html 2006 Cadillac BLS], Car and Driver, June 2006.</ref> \n\nCadillac would again offer a compact sedan developed through the badge engineering of vehicles designed by other GM subsidiaries, firstly in [[1996]] with the [[Cadillac Catera]] which was essentially a lightly reworked [[Opel Omega|Opel/Vauxhall Omega]] produced in Germany. The Catera met with a lukewarm reception (being branded the \"Cimarron Ii\" by the press at its launch but sold a reasonable 95,000 units. Cadillac tried yet again between 2005-2009 by introducing the [[Cadillac BLS]] as its smallest model line.  Derived from the [[Saab 9-3]], the BLS was manufactured by Saab in Sweden as a four-door sedan and as a station wagon.  While Cadillac used \"Art and Science\" design language to style unique front and rear fascias and elements of its roofline, the BLS visibly shared all four doors with the 9-3.\n\nSized slightly smaller than the CTS, the BLS was never offered in the United States and Canada and was sold in Europe, the Middle East, South Africa, South Korea, and Mexico.\n\n==Yearly American sales==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Model Year\n!Total sales\n|-\n|1982\n|25,968\n|-\n|1983\n|19,194\n|-\n|1984\n|21,898\n|-\n|1985\n|19,890\n|-\n|1986\n|24,534\n|-\n|1987\n|14,561\n|-\n|1988\n|6,454\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.autoblog.com/2007/01/30/future-classic-cadillac-cimarron/ Derek Kreindler's Autoblog article on the Cimarron]\n\n{{Cadillac}}\n\n[[Category:Cadillac vehicles|Cimarron]]\n[[Category:Compact cars]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicles manufactured in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1982]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image = Cadillac_Cimarron_2_--_07-01-2009.jpg\n| name = Cadillac Cimarron\n| caption = ''1987-1988 Cadillac Cimarron''\n| manufacturer = [[General Motors]]\n| production = 1981\u20131988\n| model_years = 1982\u20131988\n| class = [[Compact executive car]]\n| length = {{convert|177.8|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|66.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|54.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]\n| platform = [[GM J platform|J-body]]\n| wheelbase = 101.2 in (2570 mm)\n| transmission = 4-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]<br>5-speed manual<br>3-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|Transverse front-engine, front-wheel drive]]\n| engine = 1.8 L ''[[GM 122 engine#L46|L46]]'' [[Straight-4|I4]] (gasoline)<br>2.0 L ''[[GM 122 engine#LQ5|LQ5]]'' [[Straight-4|I4]] (gasoline)<br>2.8&nbsp;L ''[[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#LB6|LB6]]'' [[V6]] (gasoline)\n| related = [[Buick Skyhawk]]<br>[[Chevrolet Cavalier]]<br>[[Oldsmobile Firenza]]<br>[[Pontiac Sunbird|Pontiac J2000/2000/Sunbird]]\n| successor = [[Cadillac BLS]] (FWD) <br> [[Cadillac Catera]] (RWD)\n| assembly = United States: [[Janesville, Wisconsin]], ([[Janesville GM Assembly Plant]])<br>[[South Gate, California]], ([[South Gate Assembly]])\n}}\nThe '''Cadillac Cimarron''' is an [[Compact executive car#History in the United States|entry-level luxury car]] manufactured and marketed by the [[Cadillac]] division of [[General Motors]] from 1981 to 1988 as a four-door sedan across a single generation.  \n\nMarking Cadillac's entry into the compact segment<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ewAAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA71&dq=Cadillac+Cimarron+compact#v=onepage&q=Cadillac%20Cimarron%20compact&f=false|title=Popular Science|last=Corporation|first=Bonnier|date=August 1985|publisher=Bonnier Corporation}}</ref> and using the [[GM J platform]], the Cimarron was introduced and marketed concurrently with  [[badge engineering|rebadged]] J-platform variants from each of its divisions, and was manufactured at [[South Gate Assembly]] and [[Janesville Assembly Plant|Janesville Assembly]].  Following South Gate's closure in 1982, assembly continued in Janesville.\n\nThe Cimarron is noted as a [[wikt:nadir|nadir]] of GM's product planning for its low sales, poor performance and ill-conceived badge engineering.\n\n== Background ==\nAs General Motors prepared for the 1980s, Cadillac product planners considered a sedan smaller than the [[Cadillac Seville|Seville]].  While the Seville had sold well, in its research of buyers, Cadillac learned that in place of import buyers, many Sevilles were purchased by traditional luxury-car buyers wanting a smaller car.  To diversify and modernize their product range, and complement the Seville which competed with premium European luxury sedans, Cadillac dealers requested a smaller car that could compete with compact European sedans.<ref name=\"Yates, page 71\">Yates, p. 71.</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ySZhMJrzhw4C&lpg=PT83&dq=Cadillac%20Cimarron&pg=PT83#v=onepage&q=Cadillac%20Cimarron&f=false |title=GM Designs for the '80s |work=Popular Science |last=Dunne |first=Jim |page=88 |date=January 1981 |publisher=Bonnier Corporation }}</ref>\n\nIn one of the shortest development programs undertaken by General Motors, development of the Cimarron began in early 1980,<ref name=\"RD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rideanddrive.com/disasters/cimarron.html|title=Trouble In Paradise: The Story of the Cadillac Cimarron|author=Bonsall, Thomas E.|year=1997|work=RideAndDrive.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010118205200/http://www.rideanddrive.com/disasters/cimarron.html|archivedate=January 18, 2001|url-status=dead|accessdate=2009-10-04|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />  even though other vehicles of the GM J-platform had been in development since 1976.<ref>[[Brock Yates|Yates, Brock]]: ''The Decline and Fall of the American Automobile Industry'', p. 24. Empire Books, 1983.</ref>  While General Motors wanted Cadillac to better compete with other luxury brands, the use of the J-platform to do so was met with heavy resistance.  [[Pete Estes]], GM's president at the time, warned Ed Kennard, Cadillac's general manager: \"Ed, you don't have time to turn the J-car into a Cadillac.\"<ref name=\"RD\" />\n\nOriginally scheduled for mid-1980s release,<ref name=\"Yates, page 71\" /> the Cimarron was released in early 1981 along with the Chevrolet Cavalier, Buick Skyhawk, Oldsmobile Firenza, and Pontiac J2000 (later marketed as the Sunbird).  With the Seville competing with mid-size/large European luxury sedans, the Cimarron was marketed as a sportier sedan, competing with the [[Audi 80#4000 (1980\u20131987) & 4000 5+5|Audi 4000]], [[BMW 3 Series (E21)#North American models|BMW 320i]], [[Saab 900#Saab 900 \"Classic\"|Saab 900]], and [[Volvo 200 Series|Volvo 240]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Cadillac/1982_Cadillac/1982%20Cadillac%20Cimarron%20Brochure/image9.html|title=1982 Cadillac Cimarron Brochure|last=Ristic-Petrovic|first=Dusan|website=www.oldcarbrochures.com|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref>\n\n== Model name ==\nAt its 1981 introduction, the copy text of original sales brochures associated the Cimarron nameplate with \"fortitude, adventure and pioneering\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Cadillac/1982_Cadillac/1982%20Cadillac%20Cimarron%20Brochure/image2.html|title=1982 Cadillac Cimarron Brochure|last=Ristic-Petrovic|first=Dusan|website=www.oldcarbrochures.com|access-date=2018-08-30}}</ref> The nameplate was chosen from a list that included J2000 (used on predecessor of [[Pontiac Sunbird]]); Carmel; Cascade; Caville (blend of Cadillac and [[Cadillac de Ville series|De Ville]]); Envoy; and [[Cadillac Series 62|Series 62]] (predecessor of [[Cadillac Calais]]).<ref>Witzenburg, Gary. \"The Name Game\", ''Motor Trend'', 4/84, p. 86.</ref><ref>Witzenburg, p. 86.</ref>  For 1982, the brand nomenclature was \"Cimarron by Cadillac\", although initially the Cadillac name did not appear on the car.  <ref name=\"RD\" /><ref name=\"buzz1\" />  For 1983, the nameplate was simply \"Cadillac Cimarron\".<ref name=\"RD\" />\n\n==Design==\nThe Cimarron was built using the front-wheel drive [[GM J platform]], using a {{Convert|101.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} wheelbase.  Using [[Vehicle frame|unibody]] construction, the front suspension consists of a [[MacPherson strut]] configuration (mounted to a front subframe), with a rear suspension using [[torsion beam]] axle, along with front and rear stabilizer bars.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Cadillac/1983_Cadillac/1983_Cadillac_Cimarron_Brochure/1983%20Cadillac%20Cimarron-15.html|title=Cimarron '83|publisher=Cadillac Devison of General Motors|accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor 1982, the Cimarron was equipped with a 1.8&nbsp;L four-cylinder engine, producing {{convert|88|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} (the first four-cylinder Cadillac since 1914 and the first engine below 2.0&nbsp;L displacement since 1908).  For 1983, the engine was enlarged to 2.0&nbsp;L and given fuel injection, though engine tuning would drop peak output to {{convert|86|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}.  For 1985, a 2.8&nbsp;L V6 (shared with the Chevrolet Cavalier and Oldsmobile Firenza) was added as an option, producing {{convert|130|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}; for 1987, the V6 became standard.  The four-cylinder engines were paired with a 4-speed manual (later a 5-speed), with a 3-speed automatic as an option; the 3-speed automatic was the sole transmission with the V6.\n\nTo distinguish the Cimarron from the Chevrolet Cavalier and its Buick, Oldsmobile, and Pontiac counterparts, Cadillac standardized many of the available features offered on J-platform cars at the time, including air conditioning, leather seats, alloy wheels, power mirrors, full instrumentation (including tachometer; the only Cadillac to do so at the time), courtesy lights, intermittent wipers, rear window defogger, and AM/FM stereo.<ref name=\":0\" />  Its interior featured simulated aluminum trim, notably foregoing simulated wood trim.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Cadillac/1982_Cadillac/1982%20Cadillac%20Cimarron%20Brochure/image6.html|title=1982 Cadillac Cimarron Brochure|last=Ristic-Petrovic|first=Dusan|website=www.oldcarbrochures.com|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Cadillac/1983_Cadillac/1983_Cadillac_Cimarron_Brochure/1983%20Cadillac%20Cimarron-13.html|title=Directory Index: Cadillac/1983_Cadillac/1983_Cadillac_Cimarron_Brochure|website=www.oldcarbrochures.com|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nAvailable options included automatic transmission, cruise control, tilt steering wheel, power windows, power door locks, power driver and passenger seats, sunroof, and a cassette player.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />  With the exception of its upholstery and model-specific special suspension tuning, other J-platform models could be optioned nearly identically to a Cimarron though doing so would raise prices close to the $12,131 base price of the Cadillac in 1982.<ref name=\"RD\" /><ref name=\"buzz1\" />    \n<gallery mode=\"packed\" caption=\"1982-1988 Cimarron\">\nFile:1981 cimarron 1.jpg|1982 Cimarron\nFile:1981 cimarron 2.jpg|1982 Cimarron, rear\nFile:Cadillac Cimarron (5810874724).jpg|1985 Cimarron D'Oro\nFile:1988 Cadillac Cimarron.jpg|1988 Cimarron\n</gallery>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\nThe Cimarron's market failure is one in a series of events throughout the 1980s and 1990s which caused Cadillac's share of the US market  to decline from 3.8% in 1979 to 2.2% in 1997;<ref>Flammang and Kowalke, pp. 149-189</ref> it is routinely cited as the nadir of GM's product planning:\n\n:*Noted automotive journalist [[Dan Neil]] included the Cimarron in his 2007 list of ''Worst Cars of all Time'', saying \"everything that was wrong, venal, lazy, and mendacious about GM in the 1980s was crystallized in this flagrant insult to the good name and fine customers of Cadillac.\"<ref name=\"time\">{{cite web\n  | title = The 50 Worst Cars of All Time\n  | publisher = Time Magazine\n  | author = Dan Neil\n  | url = http://content.time.com/time/specials/2007/0,28757,1658545,00.html}}</ref> He added that the Cimarron \"nearly killed Cadillac and remains its biggest shame.\"<ref name=time/>\n\n:*''[[Forbes]]'' placed the Cimarron on its list of \"Legendary Car Flops,\" citing low sales, poor performance and the fact the car \"didn't work, coming from a luxury brand.\"<ref name=\"buzz1\">{{cite web\n  | title = Rebadged Disasters: Cadillac Cimarron\n  | publisher = Carbuzz.com\n  | author =\n  | date = November 11, 2012\n  | url = http://www.carbuzz.com/news/2012/11/11/Rebadged-Disasters-Cadillac-Cimarron-7711547/}}</ref>\n\n:*CarBuzz called the Cimarron a \"textbook example of what goes wrong when a carmaker tries to badge engineer an economy car into a luxury car.\"<ref name=\"buzz2\">{{cite web\n  | title = Rebadged Disasters\n  | publisher = Carbuzz.com\n  | url = http://www.carbuzz.com/news/2012/11/11/Rebadged-Disasters-Cadillac-Cimarron-7711547/}}</ref>\n\n:*Author Hannah Elliott said the Cimarron \"appealed neither to Cadillac's loyal followers, who appreciated powerful V8s and Cadillac's domestic luxury edge, nor to buyers who favored Europe's luxury brands, whose cars out-handled and out-classed the Cimarron in every way.\"<ref name=\"autos.yahoo.com\">{{cite news\n|title=Legendary Car Flops\n|work=Forbes\n|url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/04/21/car-flops-toyota-forbeslife-vehicles-edsel-ford-gm.html\n|date=May 2010\n|accessdate=Jan 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n:*[[CNNMoney.com|CNN Money]] described the Cimarron as \"in all important respects, a Chevrolet Cavalier. It also added thousands to the price tag. In all, it was neither a good Cadillac nor a good value. Today, GM executives will readily admit that this was a bad idea.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|title=GM's Junk Heap: Cadillac Cimarron\n|work=CNN Money\n|url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2009/autos/0905/gallery.gm_problem_cars/3.html\n|date=May 2009\n|accessdate=2009-06-02}}</ref>\n\n:*''[[Car and Driver]]'' said a subsequent Cadillac product director, John Howell, kept a picture of the Cimarron on his wall captioned, \"Lest we forget.\"<ref>Hutton, Ray, [http://www.caranddriver.com/carnews/11058/upfront-news-2006-cadillac-bls.html 2006 Cadillac BLS], Car and Driver, June 2006.</ref> \n\nCadillac would again offer a compact sedan developed through the badge engineering of vehicles designed by other GM subsidiaries, firstly in [[1996]] with the [[Cadillac Catera]] which was essentially a lightly reworked [[Opel Omega|Opel/Vauxhall Omega]] produced in Germany. The Catera met with a lukewarm reception (being branded the \"Cimarron Ii\" by the press at its launch but sold a reasonable 95,000 units. Cadillac tried yet again between 2005-2009 by introducing the [[Cadillac BLS]] as its smallest model line.  Derived from the [[Saab 9-3]], the BLS was manufactured by Saab in Sweden as a four-door sedan and as a station wagon.  While Cadillac used \"Art and Science\" design language to style unique front and rear fascias and elements of its roofline, the BLS visibly shared all four doors with the 9-3.\n\nSized slightly smaller than the CTS, the BLS was never offered in the United States and Canada and was sold in Europe, the Middle East, South Africa, South Korea, and Mexico.\n\n==Yearly American sales==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Model Year\n!Total sales\n|-\n|1982\n|25,968\n|-\n|1983\n|19,194\n|-\n|1984\n|21,898\n|-\n|1985\n|19,890\n|-\n|1986\n|24,534\n|-\n|1987\n|14,561\n|-\n|1988\n|6,454\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.autoblog.com/2007/01/30/future-classic-cadillac-cimarron/ Derek Kreindler's Autoblog article on the Cimarron]\n\n{{Cadillac}}\n\n[[Category:Cadillac vehicles|Cimarron]]\n[[Category:Compact cars]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicles manufactured in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1982]]\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eModel name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cadillac_Cimarron"}
{"title_page": "Operation Barkhane", "text_new": "{{Expand French|Op\u00e9ration Barkhane|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Operation Barkhane\n| partof      = the [[Mali War]], the [[Insurgency in the Maghreb (2002\u2013present)|Insurgency in the Maghreb]] and the [[War on Terror]]\n| image       = Op\u00e9ration Barkhane.jpg\n| image_size  = 250px\n| caption     = French soldiers of the [[126th Infantry Regiment (France)|126th Infantry Regiment]] and Malian soldiers, March 17, 2016.\n| date        = 1 August 2014 \u2013 present\n| place       = [[Sahel]]: [[Mauritania]], [[Mali]], [[Burkina Faso]], [[Niger]] and [[Chad]]\n| territory   =\n| result      =\n| status      = Ongoing\n| combatant1  = {{flag|France}} <br> [[G5 Sahel]]\n* {{flag|Burkina Faso}}\n* {{flag|Chad}}\n* {{flag|Mali}}\n* {{flag|Mauritania}}\n* {{flag|Niger}}\n{{flag|Estonia}} <br> \n'''Supported by:'''<br>\n* {{flag|United Kingdom}}<ref name=\"UKSupport\" /><ref name=\"UKAirliftSupport\" />\n* {{flag|Canada}}<ref name=\"CanadaSupport\">{{cite web|title=Operation FREQUENCE|url=http://www.forces.gc.ca/en/operations-abroad-current/op-frequence.page|website=Forces.gc.ca|publisher=National Defence and the Canadian Armed Forces|accessdate=10 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GOC\">{{cite news|title=The CAF conduct airlift operations in support of French operations in West Africa and the Sahel region|url=http://news.gc.ca/web/article-en.do?mthd=index&crtr.page=1&nid=1158509&_ga=1.144435708.876596763.1479831559&wbdisable=true|accessdate=10 February 2017|agency=National Defence / Canadian Armed Forces|publisher=Government of Canada|date=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|United States}}<ref name=\"USSupport\">{{cite web|title=Operation FREQUENCE|url=https://www.army.mil/article/217360/us_gives_lift_to_french_forces|website=army.mil|publisher=US Army|accessdate=7 November 2019}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Denmark}}<ref>https://fmn.dk/eng/allabout/Pages/TheeffortinMali.aspx</ref>\n\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Jama'at Nasr al-Islam wal Muslimin|Nusrat al-Islam]] (2017\u2013present) <br> {{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Al-Qaeda in Islamic Maghreb|AQIM]] (2014\u2013present) <br> {{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Al-Mourabitoun (jihadist group)|Al-Mourabitoun]] (2014\u201317) <br> {{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Ansar Dine]] (2014\u201317)\n| commander1  = {{flagdeco|France}} [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] (2014\u201317)<br>\n{{flagdeco|France}} [[Emmanuel Macron]] (2017\u2013present)<br>\n{{flagdeco|Mali}} [[Ibrahim Boubacar Ke\u00efta]]<br>\n{{flagdeco|Niger}} [[Mahamadou Issoufou]]<br>\n{{flagdeco|Burkina Faso}} [[Michel Kafando]]<br>\n{{flagdeco|Mauritania}} [[Mohamed Ould Abdel Aziz]] (2014\u201319)<br>\n{{flagdeco|Mauritania}} [[Mohamed Ould Ghazouani]] (2019\u2013present)<br>\n{{flagdeco|Chad}} [[Idriss D\u00e9by]]<br>\n{{flagdeco|Estonia}} [[Kersti Kaljulaid]]\n| commander2  = {{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Iyad Ag Ghaly]]<br>\n{{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Djamel Okacha]]<br>\n{{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Mokhtar Belmokhtar]]\n| units1      =\n| units2      =\n| strength1   = 5,100 French troops<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mali-security-france-widerimage/french-troops-in-mali-anti-jihadist-campaign-mired-in-mud-and-mistrust-idUSKCN1V304Y | title=French troops in Mali anti-jihadist campaign mired in mud and mistrust | date= 13 August 2019| publisher=Reuters | accessdate=13 November 2019}}</ref><br>95 Estonian troops\n70 danish troops with two heavy lift helicopters\n| strength2   = 3,000 fighters (all groups)<ref>{{cite web| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/09/26/opinion/bergen-schneider-how-many-jihadists/ | title=Jihadist threat not as big as you think | date= 29 September 2014| publisher=CNN | accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref> \n| casualties1 = \n*{{flagdeco|France}} 35 deaths, 60 wounded<ref>[https://www.defense.gouv.fr/operations/sahel/in-memoriam/in-memoriam In memoriam], Minist\u00e8re de la D\u00e9fense.</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|Estonia}} 6 wounded <ref>Malis r\u00fcndasid terroristid Gao s\u00f5jav\u00e4ebaasi, [http://www.mil.ee/et/uudised/10785/malis-r%C3%BCndasid-terroristid-gao-s%C3%B5jav%C3%A4ebaasi, Estonian Defence Forces]</ref><ref>Six Estonian Defence Forces members injured in Mali terrorist attack, [https://news.err.ee/963913/six-estonian-defence-forces-members-injured-in-mali-terrorist-attack], Estonian Public Broadcasting</ref>\n| casualties2 = 600 killed or captured.<ref name=\"ExpAFP280219\">[https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/afrique/sahel-plus-de-600-djihadistes-neutralises-par-l-armee-francaise-depuis-2015_2064409.html Sahel : plus de 600 djihadistes \"neutralis\u00e9s\" par l'arm\u00e9e fran\u00e7aise depuis 2015], ''L'Express avec AFP'', 28 f\u00e9vrier 2019.</ref>\n| casualties3 =\n| notes       =\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Algeria 2002-present}}\n}}\n\n'''Operation Barkhane''' is an ongoing anti-insurgent operation started on August 1, 2014 and is lead by the French military against Islamist groups in Africa's [[Sahel]] region.<ref name=bbc>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28298230 France sets up anti-Islamist force in Africa's Sahel], bbc.co.uk.</ref> It consists of a 4,500-strong [[Military of France|French force]], which is permanently headquartered in [[N\u2019Djamena]], the capital of [[Chad]].<ref name=Africanadventures/> The operation has been designed with five countries, and former French colonies, that span the Sahel: [[Burkina Faso]], [[Chad]], [[Mali]], [[Mauritania]] and [[Niger]].<ref name=Africanadventures/> These countries are collectively referred to as the \"[[G5 Sahel]]\".<ref name=\":0\" />\nThe operation is named after a [[Barchan|crescent-shaped dune]] in the [[Sahara desert]].<ref name=france24>[http://www.france24.com/en/20140719-hollande-announces-new-military-operation-west-africa/ Hollande announces new military operation in West Africa], france24.com.</ref>\n\nThe French military initially intervened in Mali in early 2013 as part of [[Operation Serval]] which successfully regained the northern half of the country from Islamist groups. Operation Barkhane is intended to act as a follow up to this success and has expanded the French military's operations over a vast area of the Sahel region with the stated aim of helping these countries' governments to maintain control of their territory while also preventing the region from becoming a safe haven for Islamist terrorist groups planning to attack France and Europe.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mali-security-france-widerimage/french-troops-in-mali-anti-jihadist-campaign-mired-in-mud-and-mistrust-idUSKCN1V304Y | title=French troops in Mali anti-jihadist campaign mired in mud and mistrust | date= 13 August 2019| publisher=Reuters | accessdate=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nAs part of the fallout from the [[Libyan Civil War]], instability in northern Mali caused by a [[Tuareg]] rebellion against the central Malian government was exploited by [[Islamist]] groups who gained control over the northern half of the country. In response, France launched a military operation in January 2013 to stop the Islamist offensive from toppling the Malian government and to re-capture northern Mali.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-21002918 |title=BBC News - France Rafale jets target Gao in eastern Mali|publisher=BBC|date=13 January 2013|accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref> The operation, codenamed [[Operation Serval]], ended in the complete re-capture of all Islamist held territory by the operations conclusion on the 15 July 2014.\n\n[[File:Soldats fran\u00e7ais \u00e0 Gao2.PNG|thumb|left|French soldiers and VBCIs patrolling near [[Gao]], Mali as part of Operation Serval, in March 2013.]]\nFollowing the end of Operation Serval, France recognised the need to provide stability in the wider Sahel region by helping the region's various governments combat terrorism. The Former French Defense Minister, [[Jean-Yves Le Drian]], said that France recognised that \u201cthere still is a major risk that jihadists develop in the area that runs from the [[Horn of Africa]] to [[Guinea-Bissau]].\u201d Therefore Operation Barkhane was launched in order to assure the Sahel nations' security, and in effect France's security.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://nationalinterest.org/feature/welcome-frances-new-war-terror-africa-operation-barkhane-11029|title=Welcome to France's New War on Terror in Africa: Operation Barkhane|first=Maxime H.A.|last=Lariv\u00e9|date=|work=nationalinterest.org}}</ref> The operation is the successor of Operation Serval, the French military mission in Mali,<ref name=france24/> and [[Operation Epervier]], the mission in Chad.<ref>[http://www.defense.gouv.fr/operations/barkhane/dossier/operation-barkhane Op\u00e9ration Barkhane], French Ministry of Defense.</ref>\n\n== Aim ==\nThe operation is \"to become the French pillar of counterterrorism in the Sahel region.\"<ref name=\":0\"/>  According to French Defence Minister, Jean-Yves Le Drian, the main objective of Operation Barkhane is counter-terrorism:<ref name=bbc/> \"The aim is to prevent what I call the highway of all forms of traffics to become a place of permanent passage, where jihadist groups between Libya and the Atlantic Ocean can rebuild themselves, which would lead to serious consequences for our security.\"<ref>[http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/france-launches-new-sahel-counter-terrorism-operation-barkhane-1456646 France Launches New Sahel Counter-Terrorism Operation Barkhane], ibtimes.co.uk.</ref> Former French President, [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]], has said the Barkhane force will allow for a \"rapid and efficient intervention in the event of a crisis\" in the region.<ref name=france24/>\nThe operation will target Islamist extremists in Mali, Chad and Niger,<ref name=bbc/> and will have a mandate to operate across borders.<ref name=bbc/>\n\n== Forces committed ==\n=== French Forces ===\nThe French force is a 3,000-strong counter-terrorism force,<ref name=Africanadventures>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21607847-french-are-reorganising-security-increasingly-troubled-region-fran-ois-hollandes|title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande\u2019s African adventures: The French are reorganising security in an increasingly troubled region|work= Economist}}</ref> with 1,000 soldiers to be deployed indefinitely in Mali. These soldiers will be focused on counter-terrorism operations in northern Mali, with another 1,200 soldiers stationed in Chad, and the remaining soldiers split between a surveillance base in Niger, a bigger permanent base in Ivory Coast, and some [[special forces]] in Burkina Faso.<ref name=Africanadventures/>\nAccording to original plans, the French forces will be supplied with 20 helicopters, 200 armored vehicles, 10 transport aircraft, 6 fighter planes, and 3 drones.<ref name=Africanadventures/> French Army Aviation currently have two [[A\u00e9rospatiale SA 330 Puma]]'s in Chad.<ref name=\"AFMNOV15\">{{cite book|title=[[AirForces Monthly]]|year=November 2015|publisher=[[Key Publishing|Key Publishing Ltd]]|location=[[Stamford, Lincolnshire|Stamford]], [[Lincolnshire]], [[England]]|page=23}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sahel Map-Africa rough.png|thumb|left|upright=1.35|The Sahel region.]]\nThe division of labor between France and the G5 Sahel has been established by four permanent military bases:<ref name=\":0\" /> (1) headquarters and an air force base in the Chadian capital of N'Djamena (under the leadership of French G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Palasset); (2) a regional base in Gao, north Mali, with at least 1,000 men; (3) a special-forces base in Burkina Faso's capital, [[Ouagadougou]]; (4) an intelligence base in Niger\u2019s capital, [[Niamey]], with over 300 men.\nThe Niamey airbase is strategically important because it hosts drones in charge of gathering intelligence across the entire Sahel-Saharan region.<ref name=\":0\" /> From Niamey, France's troops are supported by two German [[Transall C-160]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.einsatz.bundeswehr.de/portal/a/einsatzbw/!ut/p/c4/LYvBCsIwEET_KJuAWPXW0IvgQbxovci2WcpimpS4tVD8eBPoDAzMPAaekB3wywMKx4AeHtD2fOoW1S2OXsThg7Lmim-ZyfttIlkJ7uXsSPUxkJQUCsI5h4QSk5piEl_InFImih202jTWVDu9yfxqezkerrraN2d7g2kc6z_vkPJS/ |title=Aktuelle Eins\u00e4tze der Bundeswehr |language=de |publisher=Einsatz.bundeswehr.de |date=2018-02-17 |accessdate=2018-02-21}}</ref> In 2020, France stated that it will deploy 600 soldiers in addition to the existing force to fight the Islamists militants in Africa\u2019s Sahel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-sahel-idUSKBN1ZW0A4|title=French defense ministry to send 600 more troops to Africa's Sahel|date=2020-02-02|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== British support ===\nIn March 2016, during the UK-France Summit in Paris, the British government announced that it would consider providing support to Operation Barkhane.<ref name=\"UKSupport\">{{cite news|title=UK-France Summit 3 rd March 2016 - Annex on security and defence|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/505177/UKFRS_security_and_defence_final_2_March.pdf|accessdate=24 March 2016|agency=Ministry of Defence|date=3 March 2016}}</ref> British Defence Secretary [[Michael Fallon]] then announced that the UK would provide monthly strategic airlift support to French forces in Africa.<ref name=\"UKAirliftSupport\">{{cite news|title=Defence Secretary secures progress on Brimstone sales as unmanned aircraft project moves forward|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/defence-secretary-secures-progress-on-brimstone-sales-as-unmanned-aircraft-project-moves-forward|accessdate=24 March 2016|agency=Ministry of Defence|date=3 March 2016|quote=And he committed the UK to providing one strategic airlift flight a month to support French forces in their operations against terrorists in Africa.}}</ref> In July 2018, three [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] [[Chinook helicopter]]s arrived in Mali to provide logistical and troop movement support to French and other military forces operating in the area. This deployment is in addition to the 90 British troops already deployed in the region.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://ukdefencejournal.org.uk/3-raf-chinooks-arrive-in-mali/ | title= Three Royal Air Force Chinooks arrive in Mali| date= 19 July 2018| publisher= UK Defence Journal | accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref> In September 2018, ''Forces.net'' reported that to date the RAF Chinooks Mk5s have made 30 sorties, transporting over 700 French troops, supplies and 70 tons of equipment across Mali.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forces.net/services/raf/raf-chinooks-begin-mali-deployment-french-military | title= RAF Chinooks Begin Mali Deployment With French Military| date= 28 September 2018| publisher= Forces.net | accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Estonia===\nOn March 22, 2018, the [[Ministry of Defence (Estonia)|Ministry of Defence of Estonia]] announced its intention to commit up to 50 troops and [[Patria Pasi|5 Pasi XA-188 armoured vehicles]] to Mali as part of Operation Barkhane, to be based in [[Gao]], pending approval by the [[Riigikogu]].<ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[Jane's Information Group]] |title=Estonia pledges troops for France's Sahel mission |first=Erwan |last=de Cherisey |date=March 28, 2018 |url=http://www.janes.com/article/78919/estonia-pledges-troops-for-france-s-sahel-mission?from_rss=1}}</ref><ref>https://news.err.ee/849604/estonian-infantry-unit-to-deploy-to-mali-in-august</ref> The unit, named ESTPLA-26 and headed by Maj. Kristjan Karist, was detached from the C Infantry Company of the [[Scouts Battalion]] on August 6, and arrived in Mali that same week to be stationed at the French military base in Gao.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.err.ee/852919/gallery-estonian-platoon-enters-service-in-mali | title=Gallery: Estonian platoon enters service in Mali | publisher=Eesti Rahvusringh\u00e4\u00e4ling | date=10 August 2018 | accessdate=8 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://estonianworld.com/security/an-estonian-infantry-unit-arrives-in-mali-to-fight-terrorists/ | title=An Estonian infantry unit arrives in Mali to fight terrorists | publisher=Estonian World.com | date=11 August 2018 | accessdate=8 October 2018 | author=Hankewitz, Sten}}</ref> In November of 2019, Estonia increased its Operation Barkhane troop deployment to 95 soldiers.<ref>https://thedefensepost.com/2019/11/08/estonia-troops-mali-operation-barkhane/</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n\n===2014===\n[[File:Af Ner 116 Fort de Madama.jpg|thumb|A French military helicopter over the Nigerien town [[Madama]], which serves as a [[forward operating base]] for the French, Niger and Chad armies|300px]]\nOperations commenced 1 August 2014. French Forces sustained their first casualty during a battle in early November 2014, which also resulted in 24 [[Jihadism|jihadists]] dead.<ref name=\"ABC News\">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/french-military-24-jihadists-killed-mali-26776182|title=French Military Says 24 Jihadists Killed in Mali|work=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref>  On 24 November, a French special forces soldier was killed in a [[Eurocopter EC725 Caracal|Caracal]] helicopter crash in Burkina Faso.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.lemonde.fr/defense/article/2014/11/30/un-soldat-francais-tue-dans-un-accident-d-helicoptere-au-burkina-faso_4531683_1724895.html| title= Un soldat fran\u00e7ais tu\u00e9 dans un accident d'h\u00e9licopt\u00e8re au Burkina Faso| date= 30 November 2014| newspaper= [[Le Monde]] | accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> French forces experienced their first major success of Barkhane in December 2014 with the killing of Ahmed al-Tilemsi, the leader of the Al-Mourabitoun jihadist group, by French special forces during a raid in the deserts of northern Mali.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/12/world/africa/french-forces-kill-jihadi-ahmed-tilemsi-mali.html| title= French Forces Kill a Leader of Jihadists in Mali Raid| date= 11 December 2014| newspaper= [[New York Times]] | accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nFrom 7 to 14 April 2015, French and Nigerien forces carried out an airborne operation in the far north of Niger to search for Jihadists. As part of the operation, 90 [[French Foreign Legion]] paratroopers of the [[2nd Foreign Parachute Regiment|2e REP]] jumped near the Salvador pass. Two legionnaires were injured during the jump before they were joined by a joint force of Nigerien and French soldiers from the [[1st Parachute Hussar Regiment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20150416-niger-mali-algerie-passe-salvador-arrestations-barkhane-/?aef_campaign_date=2015-04 | title= Niger: des arrestations lors d\u2019une op\u00e9ration militaire franco-nig\u00e9rienne| date= 16 April 2015| publisher= [[Radio France Internationale]] | accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2015, a French Air Parachute Commando died in hospital in France as a result of his injuries after being hit by an anti-tank mine on 13 October near [[Tessalit]] during a reconnaissance mission.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lepoint.fr/societe/mali-deces-d-un-soldat-des-forces-speciales-blesse-en-octobre-26-11-2015-1984914_23.php | title= D\u00e9c\u00e8s d'un soldat des forces sp\u00e9ciales bless\u00e9 en octobre au Mali| date= 26 November 2015| publisher= AFP | accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nOn 12 April 2016, three French soldiers were killed when their armored personnel carrier struck a land mine. The convoy of about 60 vehicles was travelling to the northern desert town of Tessalit when it hit the mine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/13/three-french-soldiers-killed-mali-mine-blast-operation-barkhane|title=Three French soldiers killed in Mali mine blast|last=France-Presse|first=Agence|date=2016-04-13|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref> Another French soldier was killed on 4 November 2016 following the explosion of a mine near the town of [[Abe\u00efbara]], making 2016 the deadliest year for French forces participating in Barkhane.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lepoint.fr/monde/mali-mort-d-un-soldat-francais-dans-l-explosion-d-une-mine-05-11-2016-2080926_24.php | title= Mali : un soldat fran\u00e7ais tu\u00e9, le groupe Ansar Dine revendique| date= 5 November 2016| publisher= AFP | accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\n[[File:BarkhaneGao2017(13).jpg|thumb|French soldiers from the [[27th Mountain Infantry Brigade (France)|Mountain Commando Group]] inspecting Malian travelers northeast of Gao in June 2017.|300px]]\nOn 15 March 2017, French forces arrested eight jihadists in the desert north of Timbuktu.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.startribune.com/french-forces-arrest-8-jihadists-in-northern-mali-official/416248964/?section=world|title=French forces arrest 8 jihadists in northern Mali: Official|newspaper=Star Tribune|author=Baba Ahmed|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317054741/http://m.startribune.com/french-forces-arrest-8-jihadists-in-northern-mali-official/416248964/?section=world|archivedate=2017-03-17}}</ref>\nOn 5 April 2017, master corporal Julien Barb\u00e9,<ref name=\"angersunhommageemouvant\">{{cite news|title=Angers Un hommage \u00e9mouvant au soldat Julien Barb\u00e9 tu\u00e9 au Mali|url=http://www.courrierdelouest.fr/actualite/angers-un-hommage-emouvant-au-soldat-julien-barbe-tue-au-mali-13-04-2017-310915|accessdate=7 May 2017|work=Le Courrier de l'ouest|date=13 April 2017}}</ref> was killed in action near [[Hombori]] after an explosive device blew up an armoured vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.france24.com/en/20170406-french-soldier-killed-clash-with-terrorists-mali-barkhane-jihadists|publisher=France 24|title=French soldier killed in 'clash with terrorists' in Mali|date=6 April 2017}}</ref> He was posthumously made a knight of the [[Legion of Honour]].<ref name=\"angersunhommageemouvant\"/> Heavy fighting between French forces and Jihadist groups continued into the summer of 2017, with 8 French soldiers being wounded by a mortar attack on their base in [[Timbuktu]] on 1 June.<ref>[http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20170601-mali-attaque-tombouctou-contre-casques-bleus-force-barkhane?ref=tw_i Mali: attaque \u00e0 Tombouctou contre les casques bleus et la force Barkhane], ''RFI'', 1 June 2017.</ref> On the night of 17 June, France suffered its tenth soldier killed during an airborne operation in the north-east of Mali.<ref>[https://www.lemonde.fr/afrique/article/2017/06/18/l-elysee-annonce-la-mort-accidentelle-d-un-soldat-francais-au-mali_5146739_3212.html L\u2019Elys\u00e9e annonce la mort accidentelle d\u2019un soldat fran\u00e7ais au Mali], ''Le Monde avec AFP'', 18 June 2017.</ref>\n\nOn 4 October 2017, French forces operating as part of Barkhane were the first to respond to [[Tongo Tongo ambush|the ambush]] of American soldiers searching for an [[Islamic State of Azawad|Islamic State]] commander on the Niger-Mali border. French air support was requested by the Americans and two hours later [[Dassault Mirage 2000|Mirage]] fighter jets arrived from [[Niamey]]. Despite the French pilots being unable to engage ground targets due to the proximity of friendly forces, the jets deterrence was enough to end the ambush.<ref name=\"Lamothe\">{{cite news|last1=Lamothe|first1=Dan |title=Caught in a deadly ambush, US troops in Niger waited an hour for French air power to arrive |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/caught-in-a-deadly-ambush-us-troops-in-niger-waited-an-hour-for-french-air-power-to-arrive/2017/10/23/0db1cea6-b834-11e7-be94-fabb0f1e9ffb_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=24 October 2017|date=23 October 2017}}</ref> A French special forces team were the first ground forces to reach the scene of the ambush, 3\u20134 hours after the firefight which resulted in the death of 4 American [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Green Berets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/niger-ambush-pentagon-acknowledges-second-team-on-ground/|publisher=[[CBS News]]|title=Pentagon acknowledges a second team was on the ground in Niger|date=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 October 2017, an [[Antonov An-26]] aircraft operating in support of Operation Barkhane [[2017 Valan International Antonov An-26 crash|crashed shortly before landing]] at [[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt Boigny International Airport]], [[Abidjan]], Ivory Coast.<ref name=ASN141017>{{cite web |url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20171014-0 |title=ER-APV Accident description |website=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=14 October 2017}}</ref> Four Moldovan flight crew were killed. Two Moldovan flight crew and four French Army soldiers were injured.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=intelNews |url=https://intelnews.org/2017/10/16/01-2196/ |title=French Special Forces were on plane that crashed in Ivory Coast, killing 4 |first=Ian |last=Allen |date=October 16, 2017 |access-date=October 17, 2017 |quote=Of the ten people that were on board, four are reportedly dead; six others are seriously hurt. Reports said that the four dead passengers were all Moldovan nationals. Two other Moldovans and four French nationals were injured.}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n[[File:Burning VBCI in Gao.jpg|left|thumb|A heavily damaged French [[VBCI]] armoured vehicle burns after an attack on a French patrol in the city of [[Gao]] |300px]]\nA French Army convoy was attacked on January 11 by a suicide car bomb while driving between the towns of Idelimane and Menaka. Three French soldiers were wounded, one seriously, in the attack which was later claimed by [[Islamic State in the Greater Sahara]].<ref>[http://www.lepoint.fr/monde/mali-3-soldats-francais-blesses-dans-un-attentat-12-01-2018-2186087_24.php Mali : 3 soldats fran\u00e7ais bless\u00e9s dans un attentat], ''Le Point avec AFP'', 12 janvier 2018.</ref> On 14 February, a French airstrike killed at least 10 Jihadists at the border between Algeria and Mali.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.modernghana.com/news/835146/french-forces-kill-at-least-10-jihadists-in-mali-military-s.html|title=French forces kill at least 10 jihadists in Mali: military sources|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/Africa/News/french-forces-kill-at-least-10-jihadists-in-mali-military-sources-20180214|title=French forces kill at least 10 jihadists in Mali: military sources|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref> Two French soldiers from the [[1st Spahi Regiment]] were killed and the Colonel-in-chief was wounded on 21 February when the armoured vehicle they were travelling in struck a mine between the towns of Gao and Menaka.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.france24.com/en/20180221-mali-french-soldiers-killed-explosive-device-sahel | title= Two French soldiers were killed after their armoured vehicle was hit by an explosive device in Mali, the French president's office said on Wednesday. | date= 3 March 2018| publisher=France 24 | accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April 2018, [[Jama'at Nasr al-Islam wal Muslimin|JNIM]] militants launched [[MINUSMA super camp attack|an attack]] on a [[UN]] base in Timbuktu, wounding several French soldiers before being repelled by French, Malian and American troops.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/militants-disguised-as-peacekeepers-attack-french-and-un-bases-in-mali/news-story/02e7fedc0e0588b064445b667a72df8a|website=news.com.au|title=Mali: 15 militants killed in Timbuktu attack|accessdate=2018-04-17}}</ref> Four French soldiers were seriously wounded by a suicide car bomb attack against a joint French-Malian patrol in [[Gao]] on 1 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/french-army-patrol-attacked-mali-141918305--spt.html?guccounter=1 | title= French army patrol attacked in Mali| date= 1 July 2018| publisher=Australian Associated Press | accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref> The attack, which heavily damaged a number of French [[VBCI|VBCI's]], also killed 4 civilians and seriously wounded 27 others.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/mali-french-soldiers-car-bomb-attack-1.4730322 | title= Mali car bombing kills 4 civilians, wounds 31 others, including soldiers| date= 1 July 2018| publisher=Australian Associated Press | accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nOn 22 February, French forces backed by an armed reaper drone and a helicopter attacked a JNIM convoy killing 11 militants including senior leader Yahia Abou el Hamman in the [[Tombouctou Region]] of [[Mali]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-02/23/c_137843317.htm|title=French forces kill senior jihadist leader in Mali - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=[[xinhuanet.com]]|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thedefensepost.com/2019/02/22/al-qaeda-jnim-deputy-leader-el-hamame-killed-mali-parly/|title=French forces kill JNIM deputy leader El Hamame in Mali, Parly says|date=2019-02-22|website=The Defense Post|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref> A militant improvised explosive device struck a French armoured vehicle carrying out an anti-terrorist operation in the [[Mopti Region]] on 2 April, killing one French soldier and seriously wounding another.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.yahoo.com/news/french-military-doctor-killed-mali-215421082.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAGiehEeSNJo-j_M5g4w3h7iipxCA6CSuvHDszE_nXOdOOYz0RVh_CXHYVG8-mc3iScJSFF709_xUALNRQ-liEz0AKDK0tni5gCy9445XYzT4h9n0JhZbg7tor4-NaZc1pf5esyYrMFLtYedJl9H0IRljsNi0hCBbKwzlLBJWhLRJ | title= French military doctor killed in Mali| date= 2 April 2019 | publisher=Associated Press | accessdate= 4 April 2019}}</ref> Two French commandos of the [[Commandos Marine]] were killed on 9 May in the North of Burkina Faso during a [[May 2019 Burkina Faso hostage rescue|rescue mission]] which successfully rescued four hostages, included two Frenchmen, and an  American and South Korean woman, who had been kidnapped by Islamists.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-48228353 | title= French troops free hostages in Burkina Faso| date= 10 May 2019 | publisher=BBC | accessdate= 10 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-June, a French Army Light Aviation [[A\u00e9rospatiale Gazelle|Gazelle]] helicopter crashed in the border region between Mali and Niger after being fired upon by insurgent small arms fire. The two pilots and a special forces sniper were subsequently rescued by another helicopter after destroying the damaged helicopter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.janes.com/article/89508/french-gazelle-down-in-north-africa-crew-rescued|title=French Gazelle down in North Africa, crew rescued|work=[[Jane's Defence Weekly]]|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> The French military base in Gao was assaulted by suicide bombers on 22 July in an attack that wounded 6 Estonian soldiers and a similar number of French personnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.err.ee/963913/six-estonian-defence-forces-members-injured-in-mali-terrorist-attack|title=Six Estonian Defence Forces members injured in Mali terrorist attack|work=ERR News|accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref> A French soldier was killed on 2 November when his vehicle was struck by an improvised explosive device during a patrol near [[Menaka]] in eastern Mali.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.france24.com/en/20191102-french-soldier-killed-in-mali-by-roadside-bomb | title= French soldier killed in Mali by roadside bomb in attack claimed by IS group | date= 2 November 2019| publisher=France 24 | accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref> French commandos launched a heli-borne raid on an insurgent camp in Mali's eastern regions on November 16, which resulted in five insurgents killed and one French soldier being seriously injured.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://thedefensepost.com/2019/11/18/mali-5-isis-terrorists-killed-france-soldier-injured-indelimane-barkhane/ | title= French commando seriously injured in Mali counter-ISIS operation that killed 5 \u2018terrorists\u2019 near Indelimane | date= 18 November 2019| publisher=The Defence Post | accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 November, 13 French soldiers were killed in northern Mali when two French helicopters, a '[[Eurocopter Tiger|Tigre]]' and a '[[Eurocopter AS532 Cougar|Cougar]]', collided in mid-air while flying to reinforce soldiers engaged in combat with insurgents.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-mali/thirteen-french-helicopter-troops-killed-in-mali-combat-operation-idUSKBN1Y00VR | title= Thirteen French helicopter troops killed in Mali combat operation | date= 26 November 2019| publisher= Reuters | accessdate= 26 November 2019}}</ref> The loss of 13 soldiers was the heaviest loss of life for the French military since the [[1983 Beirut barracks bombings]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.france24.com/en/20191126-thirteen-french-soldiers-killed-in-mali-helicopter-accident | title= Thirteen French soldiers killed in Mali helicopter accident | date= 26 November 2019| publisher= France24 | accessdate= 26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 December, the French military killed 40 militants in an operation in the [[Mopti Region]] of Mali. The area where the operation took place was controlled by [[Macina Liberation Front]] and it involved France's first ever use of a drone strike which killed 33 of the 40.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191223-french-army-carries-out-first-ever-drone-strike-during-mali-op|title=French army carries out first-ever drone strike during Mali op|date=2019-12-23|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nThe French Defense Minister [[Florence Parly]] announced in February 2020 that France would send an additional 600 troops to the Sahel region, bolstering Operation Barkhanes' force to 5,100 troops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200202-france-sahel-africa-parly-troops-army-soldiers-defence-minister-florence-mali-burkina-faso-niger|title=France to send 600 more troops to Africa's Sahel|date=2020-02-21|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2019-02-21}}</ref> The first contingent of these reinforcements was 200 [[French Foreign Legion]] paratroopers from the [[2nd Foreign Parachute Regiment|2e REP]] who were transported to Niger and formed a battle group called Desert Tactical Grouping (GTD) \"Altor\". This battle group operated autonomously and without a base on the ground for over a month, receiving supplies only by airdrop. GTD Altor killed over a dozen insurgents and disrupted their logistics throughout their initial month-long operation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.opex360.com/2020/03/06/niger-deployes-durant-un-mois-dans-le-liptako-les-legionnaires-du-2e-rep-ont-mene-la-vie-dure-aux-jihadistes/|title=Niger : D\u00e9ploy\u00e9s durant un mois dans le Liptako, les l\u00e9gionnaires du 2e REP ont men\u00e9 la vie dure aux jihadistes|date=2020-03-06|website=opex360.com|language=fra|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n== Intervention assessment ==\nIn late 2015, French army representatives indicated that over 150 [[ammunition]] and [[explosive]] depositories had been discovered and 25 vehicles and 80 electronic device ([[GPS]], [[computers]], [[satellite phones]] and radio stations) had been destroyed. This represented 20 tons of ammunition, including 2,000 [[shell (projectile)|shells]], 680 [[grenades]], [[guided missiles]], 25 [[Improvised explosive device|IED]]s and [[Land mine|mines]], 210 detonators, 30 [[mortar (weapon)|mortars]], [[machine gun]]s and [[rocket launcher]]s. The army also seized 3,500 kg of various [[drugs]].\n\nOn February 2018, French [[Defense Minister]], Ms. [[Florence Parly]], indicated that 450 [[jihadists]] have been neutralized, amongst which 120 have been killed and 150 held as prisoners by Malian authorities. In July 2018, General Bruno Guibert, head of the Barkhane force, confirmed that 120 terrorists had been killed since the beginning of the year. \n\nOn February 2019, Ms. Parly announced that over 600 [[jihadists]] had been \"neutralized\" since the beginning of the operation. [[Intelligence services]] estimate that at least 2,000 to 3,000 jihadists are operating in [[Mauritania]], [[Mali]], [[Niger]] and [[Burkina Faso]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of battles involving France in modern history]]\n* [[United Nations Multidimensional Integrated Stabilization Mission in Mali]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Erforth, Benedikt. (2020) \"[[doi:10.1080/01402390.2020.1733986|Multilateralism as a tool: Exploring French military cooperation in the Sahel.]]\" Journal of Strategic Studies\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barkhane, Operation}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2014]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2015]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2016]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2017]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2018]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2019]]\n[[Category:Counter-insurgency]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving France]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving Chad]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving Niger]]\n[[Category:Sahel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand French|Op\u00e9ration Barkhane|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Operation Barkhane\n| partof      = the [[Mali War]], the [[Insurgency in the Maghreb (2002\u2013present)|Insurgency in the Maghreb]] and the [[War on Terror]]\n| image       = Op\u00e9ration Barkhane.jpg\n| image_size  = 250px\n| caption     = French soldiers of the [[126th Infantry Regiment (France)|126th Infantry Regiment]] and Malian soldiers, March 17, 2016.\n| date        = 1 August 2014 \u2013 present\n| place       = [[Sahel]]: [[Mauritania]], [[Mali]], [[Burkina Faso]], [[Niger]] and [[Chad]]\n| territory   =\n| result      =\n| status      = Ongoing\n| combatant1  = {{flag|France}} <br> [[G5 Sahel]]\n* {{flag|Burkina Faso}}\n* {{flag|Chad}}\n* {{flag|Mali}}\n* {{flag|Mauritania}}\n* {{flag|Niger}}\n{{flag|Estonia}} <br> \n'''Supported by:'''<br>\n* {{flag|United Kingdom}}<ref name=\"UKSupport\" /><ref name=\"UKAirliftSupport\" />\n* {{flag|Canada}}<ref name=\"CanadaSupport\">{{cite web|title=Operation FREQUENCE|url=http://www.forces.gc.ca/en/operations-abroad-current/op-frequence.page|website=Forces.gc.ca|publisher=National Defence and the Canadian Armed Forces|accessdate=10 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GOC\">{{cite news|title=The CAF conduct airlift operations in support of French operations in West Africa and the Sahel region|url=http://news.gc.ca/web/article-en.do?mthd=index&crtr.page=1&nid=1158509&_ga=1.144435708.876596763.1479831559&wbdisable=true|accessdate=10 February 2017|agency=National Defence / Canadian Armed Forces|publisher=Government of Canada|date=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|United States}}<ref name=\"USSupport\">{{cite web|title=Operation FREQUENCE|url=https://www.army.mil/article/217360/us_gives_lift_to_french_forces|website=army.mil|publisher=US Army|accessdate=7 November 2019}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Denmark}}<ref>https://fmn.dk/eng/allabout/Pages/TheeffortinMali.aspx</ref>\n\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Jama'at Nasr al-Islam wal Muslimin|Nusrat al-Islam]] (2017\u2013present) <br> {{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Al-Qaeda in Islamic Maghreb|AQIM]] (2014\u2013present) <br> {{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Al-Mourabitoun (jihadist group)|Al-Mourabitoun]] (2014\u201317) <br> {{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Ansar Dine]] (2014\u201317)\n| commander1  = {{flagdeco|France}} [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] (2014\u201317)<br>\n{{flagdeco|France}} [[Emmanuel Macron]] (2017\u2013present)<br>\n{{flagdeco|Mali}} [[Ibrahim Boubacar Ke\u00efta]]<br>\n{{flagdeco|Niger}} [[Mahamadou Issoufou]]<br>\n{{flagdeco|Burkina Faso}} [[Michel Kafando]]<br>\n{{flagdeco|Mauritania}} [[Mohamed Ould Abdel Aziz]] (2014\u201319)<br>\n{{flagdeco|Mauritania}} [[Mohamed Ould Ghazouani]] (2019\u2013present)<br>\n{{flagdeco|Chad}} [[Idriss D\u00e9by]]<br>\n{{flagdeco|Estonia}} [[Kersti Kaljulaid]]\n| commander2  = {{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Iyad Ag Ghaly]]<br>\n{{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Djamel Okacha]]<br>\n{{flagicon image|AQMI Flag.svg}} [[Mokhtar Belmokhtar]]\n| units1      =\n| units2      =\n| strength1   = 5,100 French troops<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mali-security-france-widerimage/french-troops-in-mali-anti-jihadist-campaign-mired-in-mud-and-mistrust-idUSKCN1V304Y | title=French troops in Mali anti-jihadist campaign mired in mud and mistrust | date= 13 August 2019| publisher=Reuters | accessdate=13 November 2019}}</ref><br>95 Estonian troops\n70 danish troops with two heavy lift helicopters\n| strength2   = 3,000 fighters (all groups)<ref>{{cite web| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/09/26/opinion/bergen-schneider-how-many-jihadists/ | title=Jihadist threat not as big as you think | date= 29 September 2014| publisher=CNN | accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref> \n| casualties1 = \n*{{flagdeco|France}} 35 deaths, 60 wounded<ref>[https://www.defense.gouv.fr/operations/sahel/in-memoriam/in-memoriam In memoriam], Minist\u00e8re de la D\u00e9fense.</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|Estonia}} 6 wounded <ref>Malis r\u00fcndasid terroristid Gao s\u00f5jav\u00e4ebaasi, [http://www.mil.ee/et/uudised/10785/malis-r%C3%BCndasid-terroristid-gao-s%C3%B5jav%C3%A4ebaasi, Estonian Defence Forces]</ref><ref>Six Estonian Defence Forces members injured in Mali terrorist attack, [https://news.err.ee/963913/six-estonian-defence-forces-members-injured-in-mali-terrorist-attack], Estonian Public Broadcasting</ref>\n| casualties2 = 600 killed or captured.<ref name=\"ExpAFP280219\">[https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/afrique/sahel-plus-de-600-djihadistes-neutralises-par-l-armee-francaise-depuis-2015_2064409.html Sahel : plus de 600 djihadistes \"neutralis\u00e9s\" par l'arm\u00e9e fran\u00e7aise depuis 2015], ''L'Express avec AFP'', 28 f\u00e9vrier 2019.</ref>\n| casualties3 =\n| notes       =\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Algeria 2002-present}}\n}}\n\n'''Operation Barkhane''' is an ongoing anti-insurgent operation started on August 1, 2014 and is lead by the French military against Islamist groups in Africa's [[Sahel]] region.<ref name=bbc>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28298230 France sets up anti-Islamist force in Africa's Sahel], bbc.co.uk.</ref> It consists of a 4,500-strong [[Military of France|French force]], which is permanently headquartered in [[N\u2019Djamena]], the capital of [[Chad]].<ref name=Africanadventures/> The operation has been designed with five countries, and former French colonies, that span the Sahel: [[Burkina Faso]], [[Chad]], [[Mali]], [[Mauritania]] and [[Niger]].<ref name=Africanadventures/> These countries are collectively referred to as the \"[[G5 Sahel]]\".<ref name=\":0\" />\nThe operation is named after a [[Barchan|crescent-shaped dune]] in the [[Sahara desert]].<ref name=france24>[http://www.france24.com/en/20140719-hollande-announces-new-military-operation-west-africa/ Hollande announces new military operation in West Africa], france24.com.</ref>\n\nThe French military initially intervened in Mali in early 2013 as part of [[Operation Serval]] which successfully regained the northern half of the country from Islamist groups. Operation Barkhane is intended to act as a follow up to this success and has expanded the French military's operations over a vast area of the Sahel region with the stated aim of helping these countries' governments to maintain control of their territory while also preventing the region from becoming a safe haven for Islamist terrorist groups planning to attack France and Europe.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mali-security-france-widerimage/french-troops-in-mali-anti-jihadist-campaign-mired-in-mud-and-mistrust-idUSKCN1V304Y | title=French troops in Mali anti-jihadist campaign mired in mud and mistrust | date= 13 August 2019| publisher=Reuters | accessdate=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nAs part of the fallout from the [[Libyan Civil War]], instability in northern Mali caused by a [[Tuareg]] rebellion against the central Malian government was exploited by [[Islamist]] groups who gained control over the northern half of the country. In response, France launched a military operation in January 2013 to stop the Islamist offensive from toppling the Malian government and to re-capture northern Mali.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-21002918 |title=BBC News - France Rafale jets target Gao in eastern Mali|publisher=BBC|date=13 January 2013|accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref> The operation, codenamed [[Operation Serval]], ended in the complete re-capture of all Islamist held territory by the operations conclusion on the 15 July 2014.\n\n[[File:Soldats fran\u00e7ais \u00e0 Gao2.PNG|thumb|left|French soldiers and VBCIs patrolling near [[Gao]], Mali as part of Operation Serval, in March 2013.]]\nFollowing the end of Operation Serval, France recognised the need to provide stability in the wider Sahel region by helping the region's various governments combat terrorism. The Former French Defense Minister, [[Jean-Yves Le Drian]], said that France recognised that \u201cthere still is a major risk that jihadists develop in the area that runs from the [[Horn of Africa]] to [[Guinea-Bissau]].\u201d Therefore Operation Barkhane was launched in order to assure the Sahel nations' security, and in effect France's security.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://nationalinterest.org/feature/welcome-frances-new-war-terror-africa-operation-barkhane-11029|title=Welcome to France's New War on Terror in Africa: Operation Barkhane|first=Maxime H.A.|last=Lariv\u00e9|date=|work=nationalinterest.org}}</ref> The operation is the successor of Operation Serval, the French military mission in Mali,<ref name=france24/> and [[Operation Epervier]], the mission in Chad.<ref>[http://www.defense.gouv.fr/operations/barkhane/dossier/operation-barkhane Op\u00e9ration Barkhane], French Ministry of Defense.</ref>\n\n== Aim ==\nThe operation is \"to become the French pillar of counterterrorism in the Sahel region.\"<ref name=\":0\"/>  According to French Defence Minister, Jean-Yves Le Drian, the main objective of Operation Barkhane is counter-terrorism:<ref name=bbc/> \"The aim is to prevent what I call the highway of all forms of traffics to become a place of permanent passage, where jihadist groups between Libya and the Atlantic Ocean can rebuild themselves, which would lead to serious consequences for our security.\"<ref>[http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/france-launches-new-sahel-counter-terrorism-operation-barkhane-1456646 France Launches New Sahel Counter-Terrorism Operation Barkhane], ibtimes.co.uk.</ref> Former French President, [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]], has said the Barkhane force will allow for a \"rapid and efficient intervention in the event of a crisis\" in the region.<ref name=france24/>\nThe operation will target Islamist extremists in Mali, Chad and Niger,<ref name=bbc/> and will have a mandate to operate across borders.<ref name=bbc/>\n\n== Forces committed ==\n=== French Forces ===\nThe French force is a 3,000-strong counter-terrorism force,<ref name=Africanadventures>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21607847-french-are-reorganising-security-increasingly-troubled-region-fran-ois-hollandes|title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande\u2019s African adventures: The French are reorganising security in an increasingly troubled region|work= Economist}}</ref> with 1,000 soldiers to be deployed indefinitely in Mali. These soldiers will be focused on counter-terrorism operations in northern Mali, with another 1,200 soldiers stationed in Chad, and the remaining soldiers split between a surveillance base in Niger, a bigger permanent base in Ivory Coast, and some [[special forces]] in Burkina Faso.<ref name=Africanadventures/>\nAccording to original plans, the French forces will be supplied with 20 helicopters, 200 armored vehicles, 10 transport aircraft, 6 fighter planes, and 3 drones.<ref name=Africanadventures/> French Army Aviation currently have two [[A\u00e9rospatiale SA 330 Puma]]'s in Chad.<ref name=\"AFMNOV15\">{{cite book|title=[[AirForces Monthly]]|year=November 2015|publisher=[[Key Publishing|Key Publishing Ltd]]|location=[[Stamford, Lincolnshire|Stamford]], [[Lincolnshire]], [[England]]|page=23}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sahel Map-Africa rough.png|thumb|left|upright=1.35|The Sahel region.]]\nThe division of labor between France and the G5 Sahel has been established by four permanent military bases:<ref name=\":0\" /> (1) headquarters and an air force base in the Chadian capital of N'Djamena (under the leadership of French G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Palasset); (2) a regional base in Gao, north Mali, with at least 1,000 men; (3) a special-forces base in Burkina Faso's capital, [[Ouagadougou]]; (4) an intelligence base in Niger\u2019s capital, [[Niamey]], with over 300 men.\nThe Niamey airbase is strategically important because it hosts drones in charge of gathering intelligence across the entire Sahel-Saharan region.<ref name=\":0\" /> From Niamey, France's troops are supported by two German [[Transall C-160]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.einsatz.bundeswehr.de/portal/a/einsatzbw/!ut/p/c4/LYvBCsIwEET_KJuAWPXW0IvgQbxovci2WcpimpS4tVD8eBPoDAzMPAaekB3wywMKx4AeHtD2fOoW1S2OXsThg7Lmim-ZyfttIlkJ7uXsSPUxkJQUCsI5h4QSk5piEl_InFImih202jTWVDu9yfxqezkerrraN2d7g2kc6z_vkPJS/ |title=Aktuelle Eins\u00e4tze der Bundeswehr |language=de |publisher=Einsatz.bundeswehr.de |date=2018-02-17 |accessdate=2018-02-21}}</ref> In 2020, France stated that it will deploy 600 soldiers in addition to the existing force to fight the Islamists militants in Africa\u2019s Sahel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-sahel-idUSKBN1ZW0A4|title=French defense ministry to send 600 more troops to Africa's Sahel|date=2020-02-02|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== British support ===\nIn March 2016, during the UK-France Summit in Paris, the British government announced that it would consider providing support to Operation Barkhane.<ref name=\"UKSupport\">{{cite news|title=UK-France Summit 3 rd March 2016 - Annex on security and defence|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/505177/UKFRS_security_and_defence_final_2_March.pdf|accessdate=24 March 2016|agency=Ministry of Defence|date=3 March 2016}}</ref> British Defence Secretary [[Michael Fallon]] then announced that the UK would provide monthly strategic airlift support to French forces in Africa.<ref name=\"UKAirliftSupport\">{{cite news|title=Defence Secretary secures progress on Brimstone sales as unmanned aircraft project moves forward|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/defence-secretary-secures-progress-on-brimstone-sales-as-unmanned-aircraft-project-moves-forward|accessdate=24 March 2016|agency=Ministry of Defence|date=3 March 2016|quote=And he committed the UK to providing one strategic airlift flight a month to support French forces in their operations against terrorists in Africa.}}</ref> In July 2018, three [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] [[Chinook helicopter]]s arrived in Mali to provide logistical and troop movement support to French and other military forces operating in the area. This deployment is in addition to the 90 British troops already deployed in the region.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://ukdefencejournal.org.uk/3-raf-chinooks-arrive-in-mali/ | title= Three Royal Air Force Chinooks arrive in Mali| date= 19 July 2018| publisher= UK Defence Journal | accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref> In September 2018, ''Forces.net'' reported that to date the RAF Chinooks Mk5s have made 30 sorties, transporting over 700 French troops, supplies and 70 tons of equipment across Mali.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forces.net/services/raf/raf-chinooks-begin-mali-deployment-french-military | title= RAF Chinooks Begin Mali Deployment With French Military| date= 28 September 2018| publisher= Forces.net | accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Estonia===\nOn March 22, 2018, the [[Ministry of Defence (Estonia)|Ministry of Defence of Estonia]] announced its intention to commit up to 50 troops and [[Patria Pasi|5 Pasi XA-188 armoured vehicles]] to Mali as part of Operation Barkhane, to be based in [[Gao]], pending approval by the [[Riigikogu]].<ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[Jane's Information Group]] |title=Estonia pledges troops for France's Sahel mission |first=Erwan |last=de Cherisey |date=March 28, 2018 |url=http://www.janes.com/article/78919/estonia-pledges-troops-for-france-s-sahel-mission?from_rss=1}}</ref><ref>https://news.err.ee/849604/estonian-infantry-unit-to-deploy-to-mali-in-august</ref> The unit, named ESTPLA-26 and headed by Maj. Kristjan Karist, was detached from the C Infantry Company of the [[Scouts Battalion]] on August 6, and arrived in Mali that same week to be stationed at the French military base in Gao.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.err.ee/852919/gallery-estonian-platoon-enters-service-in-mali | title=Gallery: Estonian platoon enters service in Mali | publisher=Eesti Rahvusringh\u00e4\u00e4ling | date=10 August 2018 | accessdate=8 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://estonianworld.com/security/an-estonian-infantry-unit-arrives-in-mali-to-fight-terrorists/ | title=An Estonian infantry unit arrives in Mali to fight terrorists | publisher=Estonian World.com | date=11 August 2018 | accessdate=8 October 2018 | author=Hankewitz, Sten}}</ref> In November of 2019, Estonia increased its Operation Barkhane troop deployment to 95 soldiers.<ref>https://thedefensepost.com/2019/11/08/estonia-troops-mali-operation-barkhane/</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n\n===2014===\n[[File:Af Ner 116 Fort de Madama.jpg|thumb|A French military helicopter over the Nigerien town [[Madama]], which serves as a [[forward operating base]] for the French, Niger and Chad armies|300px]]\nOperations commenced 1 August 2014. French Forces sustained their first casualty during a battle in early November 2014, which also resulted in 24 [[Jihadism|jihadists]] dead.<ref name=\"ABC News\">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/french-military-24-jihadists-killed-mali-26776182|title=French Military Says 24 Jihadists Killed in Mali|work=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref>  On 24 November, a French special forces soldier was killed in a [[Eurocopter EC725 Caracal|Caracal]] helicopter crash in Burkina Faso.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.lemonde.fr/defense/article/2014/11/30/un-soldat-francais-tue-dans-un-accident-d-helicoptere-au-burkina-faso_4531683_1724895.html| title= Un soldat fran\u00e7ais tu\u00e9 dans un accident d'h\u00e9licopt\u00e8re au Burkina Faso| date= 30 November 2014| newspaper= [[Le Monde]] | accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> French forces experienced their first major success of Barkhane in December 2014 with the killing of Ahmed al-Tilemsi, the leader of the Al-Mourabitoun jihadist group, by French special forces during a raid in the deserts of northern Mali.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/12/world/africa/french-forces-kill-jihadi-ahmed-tilemsi-mali.html| title= French Forces Kill a Leader of Jihadists in Mali Raid| date= 11 December 2014| newspaper= [[New York Times]] | accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nFrom 7 to 14 April 2015, French and Nigerien forces carried out an airborne operation in the far north of Niger to search for Jihadists. As part of the operation, 90 [[French Foreign Legion]] paratroopers of the [[2nd Foreign Parachute Regiment|2e REP]] jumped near the Salvador pass. Two legionnaires were injured during the jump before they were joined by a joint force of Nigerien and French soldiers from the [[1st Parachute Hussar Regiment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20150416-niger-mali-algerie-passe-salvador-arrestations-barkhane-/?aef_campaign_date=2015-04 | title= Niger: des arrestations lors d\u2019une op\u00e9ration militaire franco-nig\u00e9rienne| date= 16 April 2015| publisher= [[Radio France Internationale]] | accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2015, a French Air Parachute Commando died in hospital in France as a result of his injuries after being hit by an anti-tank mine on 13 October near [[Tessalit]] during a reconnaissance mission.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lepoint.fr/societe/mali-deces-d-un-soldat-des-forces-speciales-blesse-en-octobre-26-11-2015-1984914_23.php | title= D\u00e9c\u00e8s d'un soldat des forces sp\u00e9ciales bless\u00e9 en octobre au Mali| date= 26 November 2015| publisher= AFP | accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nOn 12 April 2016, three French soldiers were killed when their armored personnel carrier struck a land mine. The convoy of about 60 vehicles was travelling to the northern desert town of Tessalit when it hit the mine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/13/three-french-soldiers-killed-mali-mine-blast-operation-barkhane|title=Three French soldiers killed in Mali mine blast|last=France-Presse|first=Agence|date=2016-04-13|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref> Another French soldier was killed on 4 November 2016 following the explosion of a mine near the town of [[Abe\u00efbara]], making 2016 the deadliest year for French forces participating in Barkhane.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lepoint.fr/monde/mali-mort-d-un-soldat-francais-dans-l-explosion-d-une-mine-05-11-2016-2080926_24.php | title= Mali : un soldat fran\u00e7ais tu\u00e9, le groupe Ansar Dine revendique| date= 5 November 2016| publisher= AFP | accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\n[[File:BarkhaneGao2017(13).jpg|thumb|French soldiers from the [[27th Mountain Infantry Brigade (France)|Mountain Commando Group]] inspecting Malian travelers northeast of Gao in June 2017.|300px]]\nOn 15 March 2017, French forces arrested eight jihadists in the desert north of Timbuktu.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.startribune.com/french-forces-arrest-8-jihadists-in-northern-mali-official/416248964/?section=world|title=French forces arrest 8 jihadists in northern Mali: Official|newspaper=Star Tribune|author=Baba Ahmed|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317054741/http://m.startribune.com/french-forces-arrest-8-jihadists-in-northern-mali-official/416248964/?section=world|archivedate=2017-03-17}}</ref>\nOn 5 April 2017, master corporal Julien Barb\u00e9,<ref name=\"angersunhommageemouvant\">{{cite news|title=Angers Un hommage \u00e9mouvant au soldat Julien Barb\u00e9 tu\u00e9 au Mali|url=http://www.courrierdelouest.fr/actualite/angers-un-hommage-emouvant-au-soldat-julien-barbe-tue-au-mali-13-04-2017-310915|accessdate=7 May 2017|work=Le Courrier de l'ouest|date=13 April 2017}}</ref> was killed in action near [[Hombori]] after an explosive device blew up an armoured vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.france24.com/en/20170406-french-soldier-killed-clash-with-terrorists-mali-barkhane-jihadists|publisher=France 24|title=French soldier killed in 'clash with terrorists' in Mali|date=6 April 2017}}</ref> He was posthumously made a knight of the [[Legion of Honour]].<ref name=\"angersunhommageemouvant\"/> Heavy fighting between French forces and Jihadist groups continued into the summer of 2017, with 8 French soldiers being wounded by a mortar attack on their base in [[Timbuktu]] on 1 June.<ref>[http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20170601-mali-attaque-tombouctou-contre-casques-bleus-force-barkhane?ref=tw_i Mali: attaque \u00e0 Tombouctou contre les casques bleus et la force Barkhane], ''RFI'', 1 June 2017.</ref> On the night of 17 June, France suffered its tenth soldier killed during an airborne operation in the north-east of Mali.<ref>[https://www.lemonde.fr/afrique/article/2017/06/18/l-elysee-annonce-la-mort-accidentelle-d-un-soldat-francais-au-mali_5146739_3212.html L\u2019Elys\u00e9e annonce la mort accidentelle d\u2019un soldat fran\u00e7ais au Mali], ''Le Monde avec AFP'', 18 June 2017.</ref>\n\nOn 4 October 2017, French forces operating as part of Barkhane were the first to respond to [[Tongo Tongo ambush|the ambush]] of American soldiers searching for an [[Islamic State of Azawad|Islamic State]] commander on the Niger-Mali border. French air support was requested by the Americans and two hours later [[Dassault Mirage 2000|Mirage]] fighter jets arrived from [[Niamey]]. Despite the French pilots being unable to engage ground targets due to the proximity of friendly forces, the jets deterrence was enough to end the ambush.<ref name=\"Lamothe\">{{cite news|last1=Lamothe|first1=Dan |title=Caught in a deadly ambush, US troops in Niger waited an hour for French air power to arrive |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/caught-in-a-deadly-ambush-us-troops-in-niger-waited-an-hour-for-french-air-power-to-arrive/2017/10/23/0db1cea6-b834-11e7-be94-fabb0f1e9ffb_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=24 October 2017|date=23 October 2017}}</ref> A French special forces team were the first ground forces to reach the scene of the ambush, 3\u20134 hours after the firefight which resulted in the death of 4 American [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Green Berets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/niger-ambush-pentagon-acknowledges-second-team-on-ground/|publisher=[[CBS News]]|title=Pentagon acknowledges a second team was on the ground in Niger|date=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 October 2017, an [[Antonov An-26]] aircraft operating in support of Operation Barkhane [[2017 Valan International Antonov An-26 crash|crashed shortly before landing]] at [[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt Boigny International Airport]], [[Abidjan]], Ivory Coast.<ref name=ASN141017>{{cite web |url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20171014-0 |title=ER-APV Accident description |website=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=14 October 2017}}</ref> Four Moldovan flight crew were killed. Two Moldovan flight crew and four French Army soldiers were injured.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=intelNews |url=https://intelnews.org/2017/10/16/01-2196/ |title=French Special Forces were on plane that crashed in Ivory Coast, killing 4 |first=Ian |last=Allen |date=October 16, 2017 |access-date=October 17, 2017 |quote=Of the ten people that were on board, four are reportedly dead; six others are seriously hurt. Reports said that the four dead passengers were all Moldovan nationals. Two other Moldovans and four French nationals were injured.}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n[[File:Burning VBCI in Gao.jpg|left|thumb|A heavily damaged French [[VBCI]] armoured vehicle burns after an attack on a French patrol in the city of [[Gao]] |300px]]\nA French Army convoy was attacked on January 11 by a suicide car bomb while driving between the towns of Idelimane and Menaka. Three French soldiers were wounded, one seriously, in the attack which was later claimed by [[Islamic State in the Greater Sahara]].<ref>[http://www.lepoint.fr/monde/mali-3-soldats-francais-blesses-dans-un-attentat-12-01-2018-2186087_24.php Mali : 3 soldats fran\u00e7ais bless\u00e9s dans un attentat], ''Le Point avec AFP'', 12 janvier 2018.</ref> On 14 February, a French airstrike killed at least 10 Jihadists at the border between Algeria and Mali.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.modernghana.com/news/835146/french-forces-kill-at-least-10-jihadists-in-mali-military-s.html|title=French forces kill at least 10 jihadists in Mali: military sources|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/Africa/News/french-forces-kill-at-least-10-jihadists-in-mali-military-sources-20180214|title=French forces kill at least 10 jihadists in Mali: military sources|publisher=|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref> Two French soldiers from the [[1st Spahi Regiment]] were killed and the Colonel-in-chief was wounded on 21 February when the armoured vehicle they were travelling in struck a mine between the towns of Gao and Menaka.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.france24.com/en/20180221-mali-french-soldiers-killed-explosive-device-sahel | title= Two French soldiers were killed after their armoured vehicle was hit by an explosive device in Mali, the French president's office said on Wednesday. | date= 3 March 2018| publisher=France 24 | accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April 2018, [[Jama'at Nasr al-Islam wal Muslimin|JNIM]] militants launched [[MINUSMA super camp attack|an attack]] on a [[UN]] base in Timbuktu, wounding several French soldiers before being repelled by French, Malian and American troops.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/militants-disguised-as-peacekeepers-attack-french-and-un-bases-in-mali/news-story/02e7fedc0e0588b064445b667a72df8a|website=news.com.au|title=Mali: 15 militants killed in Timbuktu attack|accessdate=2018-04-17}}</ref> Four French soldiers were seriously wounded by a suicide car bomb attack against a joint French-Malian patrol in [[Gao]] on 1 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/french-army-patrol-attacked-mali-141918305--spt.html?guccounter=1 | title= French army patrol attacked in Mali| date= 1 July 2018| publisher=Australian Associated Press | accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref> The attack, which heavily damaged a number of French [[VBCI|VBCI's]], also killed 4 civilians and seriously wounded 27 others.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/mali-french-soldiers-car-bomb-attack-1.4730322 | title= Mali car bombing kills 4 civilians, wounds 31 others, including soldiers| date= 1 July 2018| publisher=Australian Associated Press | accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nOn 22 February, French forces backed by an armed reaper drone and a helicopter attacked a JNIM convoy killing 11 militants including senior leader Yahia Abou el Hamman in the [[Tombouctou Region]] of [[Mali]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-02/23/c_137843317.htm|title=French forces kill senior jihadist leader in Mali - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=[[xinhuanet.com]]|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thedefensepost.com/2019/02/22/al-qaeda-jnim-deputy-leader-el-hamame-killed-mali-parly/|title=French forces kill JNIM deputy leader El Hamame in Mali, Parly says|date=2019-02-22|website=The Defense Post|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref> A militant improvised explosive device struck a French armoured vehicle carrying out an anti-terrorist operation in the [[Mopti Region]] on 2 April, killing one French soldier and seriously wounding another.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.yahoo.com/news/french-military-doctor-killed-mali-215421082.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAGiehEeSNJo-j_M5g4w3h7iipxCA6CSuvHDszE_nXOdOOYz0RVh_CXHYVG8-mc3iScJSFF709_xUALNRQ-liEz0AKDK0tni5gCy9445XYzT4h9n0JhZbg7tor4-NaZc1pf5esyYrMFLtYedJl9H0IRljsNi0hCBbKwzlLBJWhLRJ | title= French military doctor killed in Mali| date= 2 April 2019 | publisher=Associated Press | accessdate= 4 April 2019}}</ref> Two French commandos of the [[Commandos Marine]] were killed on 9 May in the North of Burkina Faso during a [[May 2019 Burkina Faso hostage rescue|rescue mission]] which successfully rescued four hostages, included two Frenchmen, and an  American and South Korean woman, who had been kidnapped by Islamists.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-48228353 | title= French troops free hostages in Burkina Faso| date= 10 May 2019 | publisher=BBC | accessdate= 10 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-June, a French Army Light Aviation [[A\u00e9rospatiale Gazelle|Gazelle]] helicopter crashed in the border region between Mali and Niger after being fired upon by insurgent small arms fire. The two pilots and a special forces sniper were subsequently rescued by another helicopter after destroying the damaged helicopter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.janes.com/article/89508/french-gazelle-down-in-north-africa-crew-rescued|title=French Gazelle down in North Africa, crew rescued|work=[[Jane's Defence Weekly]]|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> The French military base in Gao was assaulted by suicide bombers on 22 July in an attack that wounded 6 Estonian soldiers and a similar number of French personnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.err.ee/963913/six-estonian-defence-forces-members-injured-in-mali-terrorist-attack|title=Six Estonian Defence Forces members injured in Mali terrorist attack|work=ERR News|accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref> A French soldier was killed on 2 November when his vehicle was struck by an improvised explosive device during a patrol near [[Menaka]] in eastern Mali.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.france24.com/en/20191102-french-soldier-killed-in-mali-by-roadside-bomb | title= French soldier killed in Mali by roadside bomb in attack claimed by IS group | date= 2 November 2019| publisher=France 24 | accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref> French commandos launched a heli-borne raid on an insurgent camp in Mali's eastern regions on November 16, which resulted in five insurgents killed and one French soldier being seriously injured.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://thedefensepost.com/2019/11/18/mali-5-isis-terrorists-killed-france-soldier-injured-indelimane-barkhane/ | title= French commando seriously injured in Mali counter-ISIS operation that killed 5 \u2018terrorists\u2019 near Indelimane | date= 18 November 2019| publisher=The Defence Post | accessdate=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 November, 13 French soldiers were killed in northern Mali when a '[[Eurocopter Tiger|Tigre]]' and '[[Eurocopter AS532 Cougar|Cougar]]' helicopter collided in mid-air while flying to reinforce soldiers engaged in combat with insurgents.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-mali/thirteen-french-helicopter-troops-killed-in-mali-combat-operation-idUSKBN1Y00VR | title= Thirteen French helicopter troops killed in Mali combat operation | date= 26 November 2019| publisher= Reuters | accessdate= 26 November 2019}}</ref> The loss of 13 soldiers was the heaviest loss of life for the French military since the [[1983 Beirut barracks bombings]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.france24.com/en/20191126-thirteen-french-soldiers-killed-in-mali-helicopter-accident | title= Thirteen French soldiers killed in Mali helicopter accident | date= 26 November 2019| publisher= France24 | accessdate= 26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 December, the French military killed 40 militants in an operation in the [[Mopti Region]] of Mali. The area where the operation took place was controlled by [[Macina Liberation Front]] and it involved France's first ever use of a drone strike which killed 33 of the 40.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191223-french-army-carries-out-first-ever-drone-strike-during-mali-op|title=French army carries out first-ever drone strike during Mali op|date=2019-12-23|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nThe French Defense Minister [[Florence Parly]] announced in February 2020 that France would send an additional 600 troops to the Sahel region, bolstering Operation Barkhanes' force to 5,100 troops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200202-france-sahel-africa-parly-troops-army-soldiers-defence-minister-florence-mali-burkina-faso-niger|title=France to send 600 more troops to Africa's Sahel|date=2020-02-21|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2019-02-21}}</ref> The first contingent of these reinforcements was 200 [[French Foreign Legion]] paratroopers from the [[2nd Foreign Parachute Regiment|2e REP]] who were transported to Niger and formed a battle group called Desert Tactical Grouping (GTD) \"Altor\". This battle group operated autonomously and without a base on the ground for over a month, receiving supplies only by airdrop. GTD Altor killed over a dozen insurgents and disrupted their logistics throughout their initial month-long operation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.opex360.com/2020/03/06/niger-deployes-durant-un-mois-dans-le-liptako-les-legionnaires-du-2e-rep-ont-mene-la-vie-dure-aux-jihadistes/|title=Niger : D\u00e9ploy\u00e9s durant un mois dans le Liptako, les l\u00e9gionnaires du 2e REP ont men\u00e9 la vie dure aux jihadistes|date=2020-03-06|website=opex360.com|language=fra|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n== Intervention assessment ==\nIn late 2015, French army representatives indicated that over 150 [[ammunition]] and [[explosive]] depositories had been discovered and 25 vehicles and 80 electronic device ([[GPS]], [[computers]], [[satellite phones]] and radio stations) had been destroyed. This represented 20 tons of ammunition, including 2,000 [[shell (projectile)|shells]], 680 [[grenades]], [[guided missiles]], 25 [[Improvised explosive device|IED]]s and [[Land mine|mines]], 210 detonators, 30 [[mortar (weapon)|mortars]], [[machine gun]]s and [[rocket launcher]]s. The army also seized 3,500 kg of various [[drugs]].\n\nOn February 2018, French [[Defense Minister]], Ms. [[Florence Parly]], indicated that 450 [[jihadists]] have been neutralized, amongst which 120 have been killed and 150 held as prisoners by Malian authorities. In July 2018, General Bruno Guibert, head of the Barkhane force, confirmed that 120 terrorists had been killed since the beginning of the year. \n\nOn February 2019, Ms. Parly announced that over 600 [[jihadists]] had been \"neutralized\" since the beginning of the operation. [[Intelligence services]] estimate that at least 2,000 to 3,000 jihadists are operating in [[Mauritania]], [[Mali]], [[Niger]] and [[Burkina Faso]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of battles involving France in modern history]]\n* [[United Nations Multidimensional Integrated Stabilization Mission in Mali]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Erforth, Benedikt. (2020) \"[[doi:10.1080/01402390.2020.1733986|Multilateralism as a tool: Exploring French military cooperation in the Sahel.]]\" Journal of Strategic Studies\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barkhane, Operation}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2014]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2015]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2016]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2017]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2018]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2019]]\n[[Category:Counter-insurgency]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving France]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving Chad]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving Niger]]\n[[Category:Sahel]]\n", "name_user": "JeanJacquesMoldu", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_Barkhane"}
{"title_page": "Laminated bow", "text_new": "A '''laminated bow''' is an archery [[Bow (weapon)|bow]] in which different materials are [[laminated]] together to form the bow stave itself. Traditional [[composite bow]]s are normally not included, although their construction with horn, wood, and sinew might bring them within the above definition. \n\n==History==\n\nThe [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptian]], [[Scythian]] and [[Assyria]]n people had been making laminate bows out of combinations of wood, horn and sinew as early as the [[2nd millennium BCE]].\n\nThe oldest-known laminate bows (made entirely of wood) belong to the [[Scythian]] cultures. A Scythian wood-laminate bow was discovered in the 19th century in [[Ukraine]], and is currently held at the Institute of Archaeology.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Insulander |first1=Ragnar |title=The two-wood bow |journal=Acta Borealia |date=2002 |volume=19 |issue=1}}</ref> It was constructed by laminating several fine strips of [[willow]] and [[alder]] wood, bound with fish glue and wrapped in birch bark. It had a double-curved shape, was just 32 inches (813mm) long and may have been capable of firing arrows at distances of over 500 yards (457m).<ref>{{cite book |title=The National Geographic Magazine, Volume 190 |date=1996 |publisher=National Geographic Society |page=66 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VPmAAAAAMAAJ&q=scythian+bow+%22willow%22+laminated&dq=scythian+bow+%22willow%22+laminated&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjukeC1gNroAhVGd6wKHaEEAzQQ6AEILDAB}}</ref> \n\nIn 2006, an international expedition to the [[Govi-Altai Province|Altai]] mountain region in Western [[Mongolia]] uncovered a laminate bow, associated with the [[Scythian]] [[Pazyryk culture|Pazyryk]] culture. It is of a complicated construction, with many fine strips of wood glued side-by-side, and a wooden reinforcement plate glued to the handle. The entire bow was wrapped in spiral form with rawhide and birch bark; in addition to reinforcing the construction this also made the bow resistant to water and humidity.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Molodin |first1=Vjaceslav |last2=Parsinger |first2=Hermann |last3=Ceveemdorz |first3=Durensuren |last4=Garkusa |first4=Jurij |last5=Grisin |first5=Artem |title=Das skythenzeitliche kriegergrab aus Olon-Kurin-Gol Neue Entdechungen in der Permafrostzone des mongolischen Altaj |journal=Eurasia Antiqua |date=2008 |pages=241-265 |url=https://dialnet.unirioja.es/servlet/articulo?codigo=4023894}}</ref> The bow is dated to the [[3rd century BCE]].\n\nThe modern Japanese [[yumi|bow]] is a laminated bow. Laminated bows in Japan first appeared around [[1000 AD]], during the late Heihan or Kamakura period. They were made of wood and bamboo laminated with glue, evolving from simple bamboo-backed bows to complex bows of 5 piece construction (''higo yumi'') by the 1600s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Green |first1=Thomas |last2=Svinth |first2=Joseph |title=Martial Arts of the World: An Encyclopedia of History and Innovation |date=2010 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=1598842447 |page=Q53 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P-Nv_LUi6KgC&pg=PA153}}</ref> The Saami and their neighbours<ref name=\"Insulander\">[http://taylorandfrancis.metapress.com/content/ct07yrml6fcbanuj/ Ragnar Insulander. The Two-Wood Bow. [[Acta Borealia]] 2002; 19: 49-73]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> across Northern Eurasia<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/1005699 The Neolithic Age in Eastern Siberia. Henry N. Michael. Transactions of the American Philosophical Society, New Ser., Vol. 48, No. 2 (1958), pp. 1-108. ] {{doi|10.2307/1005699}}</ref> also made laminated bows for centuries. Hij\u0101zi Arabs may also have used a laminated bow.<ref>Arab Archery. An Arabic manuscript of about A.D. 1500 \"A book on the excellence of the bow & arrow\" and the description thereof. Translated and edited by Nabih Amin Faris and Robert Potter Elmer. Princeton University Press, 1945.</ref>\n\n[[Reading Museum]] is in the posession of an [[Inuit]] laminate bow. It was made in [[Pelly Bay]] and consists of three shims of bone laminated near the handle region, and reinforced at the joints with rawhide. It has two short driftwood arrows with bone points.<ref>{{cite web |title=Inuit bow and arrows |url=http://collections.readingmuseum.org.uk/index.asp?page=record&mwsquery={totopic}={World%20Collection:%20War%20and%20Hunting}&filename=REDMG&hitsStart=95 |website=Reading Museum}}</ref> They reflect the shortage of wood in the Arctic region and the improvisation of pre-contact aboriginal [[Inuit]] people.\n\n==Further reading==\n* (1992) ''The Traditional Bowyers Bible Volume 1''. The Lyons Press. {{ISBN|1-58574-085-3}}\n* (1992) ''The Traditional Bowyers Bible Volume 2''. The Lyons Press. {{ISBN|1-58574-086-1}}\n* (1994) ''The Traditional Bowyers Bible Volume 3''. The Lyons Press. {{ISBN|1-58574-087-X}}\n* ''How to make fiberglass-laminated modern bows'' by John Clark, available from [https://web.archive.org/web/20070407012934/http://ausbow.com.au/books.html Ausbow Industries]\n* ''The Design and Construction of Composite Long (Flat) Bows'' by John Clark\n* ''The Design and Construction of Composite Recurve Bows'' by John Clark (2002)\n* ''Design and Construction of Flight Bows'', a supplement to ''The Design and Construction of Composite Recurve Bows'' by John Clark\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Archery}}\n\n[[Category:Bows (archery)]]\n", "text_old": "A '''laminated bow''' is an archery [[Bow (weapon)|bow]] in which different materials are [[laminated]] together to form the bow stave itself. Traditional [[composite bow]]s are normally not included, although their construction with horn, wood, and sinew might bring them within the above definition. \n\n==History==\n\nThe [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptian]], [[Scythian]] and [[Assyrian]] people had been making laminate bows out of combinations of wood, horn and sinew as early as the [[2nd millennium BCE]].\n\nThe oldest-known laminate bows (made entirely of wood) belong to the [[Scythian]] cultures. A Scythian wood-laminate bow was discovered in the 19th century in [[Ukraine]], and is currently held at the Institute of Archaeology.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Insulander |first1=Ragnar |title=The two-wood bow |journal=Acta Borealia |date=2002 |volume=19 |issue=1}}</ref> It was constructed by laminating several fine strips of [[willow]] and [[alder]] wood, bound with fish glue and wrapped in birch bark. It had a double-curved shape, was just 32 inches (813mm) long and may have been capable of firing arrows at distances of over 500 yards (457m).<ref>{{cite book |title=The National Geographic Magazine, Volume 190 |date=1996 |publisher=National Geographic Society |page=66 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VPmAAAAAMAAJ&q=scythian+bow+%22willow%22+laminated&dq=scythian+bow+%22willow%22+laminated&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjukeC1gNroAhVGd6wKHaEEAzQQ6AEILDAB}}</ref> \n\nIn 2006, an international expedition to the [[Altai]] mountain region in Western [[Mongolia]] uncovered a laminate bow, associated with the [[Scythian]] [[Pazyryk]] culture. It is of a complicated construction, with many fine strips of wood glued side-by-side, and a wooden reinforcement plate glued to the handle. The entire bow was wrapped in spiral form with rawhide and birch bark; in addition to reinforcing the construction this also made the bow resistant to water and humidity.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Molodin |first1=Vjaceslav |last2=Parsinger |first2=Hermann |last3=Ceveemdorz |first3=Durensuren |last4=Garkusa |first4=Jurij |last5=Grisin |first5=Artem |title=Das skythenzeitliche kriegergrab aus Olon-Kurin-Gol Neue Entdechungen in der Permafrostzone des mongolischen Altaj |journal=Eurasia Antiqua |date=2008 |pages=241-265 |url=https://dialnet.unirioja.es/servlet/articulo?codigo=4023894}}</ref> The bow is dated to the [[3rd century BCE]].\n\nThe modern Japanese [[yumi|bow]] is a laminated bow. Laminated bows in Japan first appeared around [[1000 AD]], during the late Heihan or Kamakura period. They were made of wood and bamboo laminated with glue, evolving from simple bamboo-backed bows to complex bows of 5 piece construction (''higo yumi'') by the 1600s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Green |first1=Thomas |last2=Svinth |first2=Joseph |title=Martial Arts of the World: An Encyclopedia of History and Innovation |date=2010 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=1598842447 |page=Q53 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P-Nv_LUi6KgC&pg=PA153}}</ref> The Saami and their neighbours<ref name=\"Insulander\">[http://taylorandfrancis.metapress.com/content/ct07yrml6fcbanuj/ Ragnar Insulander. The Two-Wood Bow. [[Acta Borealia]] 2002; 19: 49-73]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> across Northern Eurasia<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/1005699 The Neolithic Age in Eastern Siberia. Henry N. Michael. Transactions of the American Philosophical Society, New Ser., Vol. 48, No. 2 (1958), pp. 1-108. ] {{doi|10.2307/1005699}}</ref> also made laminated bows for centuries. Hij\u0101zi Arabs may also have used a laminated bow.<ref>Arab Archery. An Arabic manuscript of about A.D. 1500 \"A book on the excellence of the bow & arrow\" and the description thereof. Translated and edited by Nabih Amin Faris and Robert Potter Elmer. Princeton University Press, 1945.</ref>\n\n[[Reading Museum]] is in the posession of an [[Inuit]] laminate bow. It was made in [[Pelly Bay]] and consists of three shims of bone laminated near the handle region, and reinforced at the joints with rawhide. It has two short driftwood arrows with bone points.<ref>{{cite web |title=Inuit bow and arrows |url=http://collections.readingmuseum.org.uk/index.asp?page=record&mwsquery={totopic}={World%20Collection:%20War%20and%20Hunting}&filename=REDMG&hitsStart=95 |website=Reading Museum}}</ref> They reflect the shortage of wood in the Arctic region and the improvisation of pre-contact aboriginal [[Inuit]] people.\n\n==Further reading==\n*